The New York Times 	January 22, 2009 Thursday   Late Edition - Final	INSIDE THE TIMES: January 22, 2009  	Section A; Column 0; Metropolitan Desk; Pg. 2  	2334 words  	InternationalLiNeBrEaK  WHILE MIDEAST IS IN CONSTANT FLUX,LiNeBrEaK  A Quick Choice Looms for ObamaLiNeBrEaK  President Obama faces a tough policy choice in what to do about Gaza and the West Bank, continue to isolate Hamas or support a unified Palestinian government as other Arab nations have suggested. He has to decide quickly, before Hamas solidifies itself by taking any credit for Gaza's reconstruction. But how to support a unified government in a place so divided?  Page A6 LiNeBrEaK  FROM RUSSIA FOR A NEWSPAPERLiNeBrEaK  Once a Soviet-era Russian spy, Aleksandr Y. Lebedev made millions after the Soviet Union collapsed and the newly born Russia embraced capitalism. He owns a major bank, large chunks of an airline and a newspaper in Moscow. Now he heads to London with a new identity: media baron. Mr. Lebedev is buying a majority stake in The Evening Standard.  Page A6  LiNeBrEaK  ASSASSINATION IN IRAQ FAILSLiNeBrEaK  A failed assassination attempt on a senior leader of one of the main Sunni parties in the coming provincial elections left four dead and 10 others wounded, according to the party and a security official.  Page A8 LiNeBrEaK  LARGE DONATION FOR POLIO RESEARCHLiNeBrEaK  The scourge of polio is mostly a memory in America. But in Nigeria, India, Pakistan and Afghanistan, it is still endemic. The Bill and Melinda Gates Foundation, Rotary International and the German and British governments have announced a $630 million infusion to keep the cause of polio eradication alive.  Page A10 LiNeBrEaK  IT'S HEATING UP WAY DOWN SOUTHLiNeBrEaK  Antarctica is getting warmer, say scientists analyzing a half-century's worth of temperature data. While they have yet to determine if the warming is caused by natural climate swings or by the effects of greenhouse gases, they believe that an increase in those gases would lead to a warmer Antarctica.  Page A12 LiNeBrEaK  IRAN'S PRESIDENT CALLS IN SICK AGAINLiNeBrEaK  President Mahmoud Ahmadinejad canceled his activities for four days because of a cold, Iranian newspapers reported. This is the fifth time since April that he has canceled his official itinerary because of health concerns.  Page A15 LiNeBrEaK  China Announces Health Care Plan  A15 LiNeBrEaK  WHITE PHOSPHORUS USE IN GAZALiNeBrEaK  Amnesty International announced that it had found indisputable evidence that the Israeli Army used white phosphorus in densely populated areas. The chemical is typically used to obscure battlefields, but when used on people it leaves severe burns, above. Under international convention, its intentional use against civilians is banned. The Israeli Army said it had opened an investigation into whether its use of the chemical was proper.  Page A16 LiNeBrEaK  NationalLiNeBrEaK  FIRE IS FOUL, AS WIND LiNeBrEaK  Spreads Smell of Burned LatrinesLiNeBrEaK  Nineteen portable toilets at construction sites in San Francisco have been set on fire since Nov. 6, according to the city's Fire Department. No one has been injured, but the breezes blowing in from the Pacific, which were once refreshing, are now, well, not. PAGE A17 LiNeBrEaK  DISPUTE OVER RARE DINOSAUR FOSSILLiNeBrEaK  In 2006, a respected amateur paleontologist, Nathan L. Murphy, took the bones of a new species of dinosaur to be X-rayed at Dinosaur Field Station in Montana. But law enforcement officials now say the fossil had actually been found years earlier and therefore belongs to someone else, and Mr. Murphy has been charged with felony theft.  PAGE A17 LiNeBrEaK  Evolution in Texas Schools A17 LiNeBrEaK  Senator Kennedy Out of Hospital A19 LiNeBrEaK  JUST LIKE THE FIRST DAY OF SCHOOLLiNeBrEaK  President Obama walked into the Oval Office and took a seat behind the desk. An envelope was waiting, affixed with an inscription that needed no explanation: ''To # 44, From #43.'' And with that, the first full day of the Obama administration began. White House Memo by Jeff Zeleny. PAGE A20LiNeBrEaK  Confirmation HearingsLiNeBrEaK  Attorney GeneralLiNeBrEaK  Republicans on the Senate Judiciary Committee put off voting on the nomination of Eric H. Holder Jr. as attorney general for one week. They say they need more time to collect information about Mr. Holder's time at the Justice Department under President Bill Clinton.  PAGE A22 LiNeBrEaK  TRANSPORTATION SECRETARYLiNeBrEaK  President Obama's pick for transportation secretary, Ray LaHood, answered many questions and dodged a few others at his confirmation hearing and was effectively approved by acclamation. PAGE A22 LiNeBrEaK  TREASURY SECRETARYLiNeBrEaK  Timothy F. Geithner, Mr. Obama's choice to be Treasury secretary, was questioned by the Senate Finance Committee about his failure to pay some taxes earlier in the decade. Still, it appears that the immensity of the economic threats trumped the tax controversy, even for some Republicans.  PAGE A22 LiNeBrEaK  OBAMA ATTENDS INTERFAITH PRAYERSLiNeBrEaK  President Obama spent his first morning as president at a prayer service at the Washington National Cathedral with a row of interfaith clergy leaders, some of whom may serve as advisers and supporters of his administration.  PAGE A23 LiNeBrEaK  Cleaning Up After History A24LiNeBrEaK  STRANDED WHILE HISTORY WAS MADELiNeBrEaK  Inaugural organizers fielded a flurry of complaints from people who had tickets to see President Obama's swearing-in, but who were instead stranded in an underground tunnel near the Capitol. PAGE A24 LiNeBrEaK  Science and the New Administration A24LiNeBrEaK  Rhode Island to Test Medicaid Cap A25LiNeBrEaK  New York LiNeBrEaK  BUDGET PROPOSAL SHUTS OUTLiNeBrEaK  Zoos, Aquariums and GardensLiNeBrEaK  In New York's next fiscal year, which begins in April, state financing for all 76 zoos, botanical gardens and aquariums would be eliminated under a new budget proposed by Gov. David A. Paterson.  Page A27 LiNeBrEaK  FOUND: ONE AIRPLANE ENGINELiNeBrEaK  There's no pretty blue water and colorful fish like a National Geographic special, this is the New York City Police Department's dive team. It's not a Spanish galleon that drives this search through dark water with six inches of visibility, but the missing engine of US Airways Flight 1549, which made an emergency landing in the Hudson on Jan. 15.  Page A27 LiNeBrEaK  BusinessLiNeBrEaK  NEW CHAIRMAN AT CITIGROUPLiNeBrEaK  A Smooth and Practiced OperatorLiNeBrEaK  Richard D. Parsons has stepped in as chairman of Citigroup, the struggling financial giant. Mr. Parson's bearing has frequently put him in demand for high-profile positions, including one of his most recent, a member of President Obama's transitional economic advisory board.  Page B1 LiNeBrEaK  FRESH SQUEEZED GLOBAL WARMINGLiNeBrEaK  That complete part of a balanced breakfast, the glass of orange juice, is good for you but what about your carbon footprint? PepsiCo Inc., which owns the Tropicana brand of orange juice, decided to answer that question. They hired experts who found a lot of data and came up with a number per half-gallon of juice. But what does any of it mean?  Page B1 LiNeBrEaK  CircuitsLiNeBrEaK  Pretty Much the Opposite of VistaLiNeBrEaK  What do Rome and Windows Vista have in common? They both took a lot longer to build than they took to burn to the ground. For all its work, Microsoft drew quite a lot of heat, and is clearly eager to put Vista behind it. Thus, Windows 7 -- also known as ''Vista fixed,'' David Pogue writes -- is nearly ready and could redeem Microsoft. Page B1 LiNeBrEaK  IT'S NOT INSTANT ANNIE LEIBOVITZLiNeBrEaK  It doesn't matter what amazing features are listed for that nifty little digital camera you just bought. Point and shoot might, as a phrase, mean just that, but it doesn't excuse you from needing at least a rudimentary idea of what's going to happen when you press that button.  Page B5 LiNeBrEaK  For Aspiring Spielbergs  B5LiNeBrEaK  Typing in the PlayStation Universe  B5LiNeBrEaK  A Laptop With Two Screens  B5LiNeBrEaK  A Media Center With Personal Tech  B5LiNeBrEaK  SportsLiNeBrEaK  NEW HEAD COACH OF JETS LiNeBrEaK  Opens New Era With Strong VowsLiNeBrEaK  During Rex Ryan's formal introduction as the new head coach of the New York Jets, he spent nearly two hours answering questions from the media. He was open about his plans, and he boldly said that the team would meet the president, seeing as how they weregoing to win the Super Bowl while he was in office. Page B11 LiNeBrEaK  THE MAGIC'S SECOND RETURNLiNeBrEaK  The Orlando Magic rose to stardom on a simple philosophy: find a dominating center -- then Shaquille O'Neal -- and build around him. Their rise was short-lived, but their general manager is planning a triumphant return for the team with the same plan, this time with Dwight Howard as the linchpin.  Page B13 LiNeBrEaK  ArtsLiNeBrEaK  NEW LAUGHS AND MAYBE RESPECTLiNeBrEaK  For a Neglected ArchetypeLiNeBrEaK  Retail security can be prone to such descriptions as rent-a-cop and flashlight cop, but funny isn't usually one of them. It appears that is changing. ''Paul Blart: Mall Cop,'' starring Kevin James as the title retail protector, finished this last weekend at the top of the box office charts. Similar movies and television pilots are expected. All hail the guardians of that icon of American consumerism, the mall.  Page C1 LiNeBrEaK  Abroad LiNeBrEaK  The Holocaust UnadornedLiNeBrEaK  The Bergen-Belsen Memorial sits on the site of a former concentration camp. The new memorial is made of concrete and glass and is adjacent to the grave for more than 70,000 people, a legacy of the land's former use. The memorial's function is to offer a view of the Holocaust uncontaminated by sentiment, a hard look at an even harder period of history.  Page C1 LiNeBrEaK  TO FALL AND TO SHINE AT ONCELiNeBrEaK  France remembers the film star Jean-Paul Belmondo with a charming gangster's smile and as an athlete who did his own stunts. Now 75 years old, he walks with a crutch after being cut down by a stroke. His role in the film ''A Man and His Dog,'' which opened this week in France, will show the actor, and the man, as he is now.  Page C1 LiNeBrEaK  AT LAST: THE CLARION CALLLiNeBrEaK  Of a Turning PointLiNeBrEaK  For 10 official inaugural balls, President Obama danced to ''At Last,'' a song popularized by Etta James. As history turned a long-awaited corner, the music of many artists was there to give that moment a memorable soundtrack, Jon Pareles writes. Some of the performers were, clockwise from the top left, Mary J. Blige, will.i.am, Shakira and Sheryl Crow. Page C1 LiNeBrEaK  HomeLiNeBrEaK  BUILT FOR SOLITUDE, A HOMELiNeBrEaK  That Allows Each Her OwnLiNeBrEaK  Roselyn Leibowitz, a self-described spinster, and Catherine Redmond, a divorcee, had been friends for years before they moved into a Midtown loft that they designed for both privacy and togetherness. One might call it the yin and yang of independence and togetherness, an issue that concerns many more people than it once did, how to create a supportive living structure without losing one's individual sense of privacy.  PAGE D1 LiNeBrEaK  THE CONCRETE CABINLiNeBrEaK  When most people dream of a rustic log cabin getaway, it's probably not made of concrete, but John and Mary Beth Cook have taken up mountain living amended for the modern world. Last year, they completed and moved into a house with logs made from precast concrete, then shaped and painted to look like the real thing.  PAGE D1 LiNeBrEaK  StylesLiNeBrEaK  DETOXING THE BODY, BUT SKEPTICISM REMAINSLiNeBrEaK  Thousands of Americans regularly detox. They forgo alcohol, caffeine, sugar, fats, oils and more in an effort to rid the gastrointestinal system of unsavory substances that proponents believe build up and can cause allergies, exhaustion and certain cancers. But many doctors question the legitimacy of the regimens and contend that detoxification does little good and may be harmful.  PAGE E1 LiNeBrEaK  GLOOM AND DOOM ON THE CATWALKLiNeBrEaK  Dark times call for aptly tailored fashions. At least that was the impression the Milan designers gave after four days of runway shows in which individual labels got lost in a continuous loop of gloom. With all the economic clairvoyants making prophecies that the retail sector will be a disaster well into the third quarter, designers reacted by staging a mass memorial for themselves, with one show picking up the somber thread from the last.  PAGE E1 LiNeBrEaK  ALL THE PRESIDENT'S PARTIESLiNeBrEaK  For five days and nights, as Washington partied its way toward the inauguration, the city was a mishmash of celebrities, politicos and regular people, and sometimes it was tough to tell them apart. From the unofficial kickoff on Friday night to the early hours of Wednesday, hundreds of galas, dinners and concerts throughout the city provided a round-the-clock break from the frigid January air.  PAGE E1  LiNeBrEaK  Rustic and Boxy in Brooklyn  E2 LiNeBrEaK  Front Row: Free Cosmetics  E2  LiNeBrEaK  Personal Best: Gradual Fitness  E6 LiNeBrEaK  EditorialLiNeBrEaK  FOR TREASURY SECRETARYLiNeBrEaK  Timothy Geithner's tax problems took up much of his confirmation hearing. Barring any new disclosures, we heard nothing disqualifying. He is an intelligent man, and President Obama is entitled to pick his own team. Wall Street is also comfortable with the choice. That is an endorsement that cuts both ways -- but one that could advance the cause of renewed regulation if Mr. Obama lives up to his promises and is a strong champion for reform. PAGE A32 LiNeBrEaK  FOR ATTORNEY GENERALLiNeBrEaK  After eight years of shameful policies and politicization at the Justice Department, Eric Holder has made a strong case that he is well suited to lead the needed overhaul.  PAGE A32LiNeBrEaK  FIRST STEPS AT GUANTaNAMOLiNeBrEaK  In June 2007, the White House claimed it was working on a ''number of steps'' that had to happen before it could close the prison at Guantanamo Bay -- but getting started was really hard. Well, maybe it's not so hard. It took President Obama less than 12 hours to take the first vital step of halting the military tribunals at the prison camp.  PAGE A32LiNeBrEaK  Op-EdLiNeBrEaK  GAIL COLLINSLiNeBrEaK  The inauguration left the whole country glued together emotionally -- one big American ball of hope. But there were signs in the Capitol that the new era was off to a slow start.  PAGE A33LiNeBrEaK  NICHOLAS D. KRISTOFLiNeBrEaK  President Obama is making an excellent start, and the globe is eager -- even desperate -- for renewed American leadership. In the meantime, there are two immediate litmus tests by which the world will judge the new president's policies: Guantanamo and the Middle East.  PAGE A33LiNeBrEaK  THE ONE-STATE SOLUTIONLiNeBrEaK  In an Op-Ed article, the Libyan leader Muammar el-Qaddafi writes that the longstanding two-state solution for the Levant will leave neither Israelis nor Palestinians happy, and that they would be better off forming a sole nation, ''Isratine.''  PAGE A33	http://www.nytimes.com  	INVESTIGATIONS (87%); ASSASSINATION (78%); ELECTIONS (73%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (72%); FOUNDATIONS (70%); WEATHER (69%); CLIMATE CHANGE (69%); EMISSIONS (68%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (66%); SCIENCE NEWS (66%); ARMIES (64%); ARSON (64%); POPULATION DENSITY (63%); HEALTH INSURANCE (61%); FIRE DEPARTMENTS (60%); US PRESIDENTS (78%)  	HEALTH CARE PLAN (52%)  	HAMAS (91%); BILL and MELINDA GATES FOUNDATION (55%); ROTARY INTERNATIONAL (54%)  	BARACK OBAMA (94%); MAHMOUD AHMADINEJAD (53%)  	LONDON, ENGLAND (79%); MOSCOW, RUSSIA (72%) CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) PALESTINIAN TERRITORY (94%); ISRAEL (94%); MIDDLE EAST (92%); RUSSIA (88%); NIGERIA (79%); IRAQ (79%); UNITED STATES (79%); INDIA (79%); IRAN (79%); AFGHANISTAN (79%); PAKISTAN (79%); UNITED KINGDOM (78%); ANTARCTICA (69%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  	LiNeB