The New York Times 	January 22, 2009 Thursday   Late Edition - Final	How Green Is My Orange?  	Section B; Column 0; Business/Financial Desk; Pg. 1  	976 words  	How much does your morning glass of orange juice contribute to global warming?LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo, which owns the Tropicana brand, decided to try to answer that question. It figured that as public concern grows about the fate of the planet, companies will find themselves under pressure to perform such calculations. Orange juice seemed like a good case study.LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo hired experts to do the math, measuring the emissions from such energy-intensive tasks as running a factory and transporting heavy juice cartons. But it turned out that the biggest single source of emissions was simply growing oranges. Citrus groves use a lot of nitrogen fertilizer, which requires natural gas to make and can turn into a potent greenhouse gas when it is spread on fields. LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo finally came up with a number: the equivalent of 3. 75 pounds of carbon dioxide are emitted to the atmosphere for each half-gallon carton of orange juice. But the company is still debating how to use that information. Should it cite the number in its marketing, and would consumers have a clue what to make of it? LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo's experience is a harbinger of the complexities other companies may face as they come under pressure to calculate their emission of carbon dioxide, a number known as a carbon footprint, and eventually to lower it.LiNeBrEaK  ''The main thing is helping us figure out where the carbon is in the chain,'' said Neil Campbell, president of Tropicana North America, a division of PepsiCo. While acknowledging that protocols for measuring greenhouse emissions are far from perfect, Mr. Campbell said, ''you can end up doing nothing if you let that stop you.''LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo, a manufacturer of soda, salty snacks and cereal based in Purchase, N.Y., is among a growing number of companies that hope to get ahead of potential government mandates and curb their energy use as prices and long-term supply grow less certain. LiNeBrEaK  They also want to promote supposedly low-carbon products to consumers anxious about rising global temperatures; such labeling has already appeared in Europe.LiNeBrEaK  The list of companies that have taken steps to reduce carbon emissions includes I.B.M., Nike, Coca-Cola and BP, the oil giant. Google, Yahoo and Dell are among the companies that have vowed to become ''carbon neutral.''LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo is among the first that will provide consumers with an absolute number for a product's carbon footprint, which many expect to be a  trend. The information will be posted on Tropicana's Web site. The company has not yet decided if it will eventually put it on the package. LiNeBrEaK  While carbon reduction efforts are generally welcomed by environmentalists, some complain that the marketing claims are backed by fuzzy numbers and dubious assumptions.LiNeBrEaK  Standards exist for determining a carbon footprint, but companies can apply them in different ways. They can decide how rigorous they want to be in counting emissions in the supply chain, and what data sources  they should use in the process. LiNeBrEaK  ''Any time people are making a legitimate effort to reduce emissions directly or indirectly with their product and services, most of us would think that is a good thing,'' said Michael Gillenwater, dean of the Greenhouse Gas Management Institute, a nonprofit organization that teaches greenhouse gas management and accounting.LiNeBrEaK  ''The trick is when you try to put a strict label that has implications for comparing your product to another product, or implying that you have no climate change impact,'' he said.LiNeBrEaK  Nancy Hirshberg, vice president for natural resources at the yogurt maker Stonyfield Farm, said measuring a carbon footprint is a ''fabulous tool'' for pinpointing areas to reduce emissions. For instance, her company was surprised to learn that milk production was a far bigger contributor to greenhouse gas emissions than its factory.LiNeBrEaK  But she said there were so many variables in determining a carbon footprint that an absolute number was meaningless as a marketing tool.LiNeBrEaK  ''I'm thrilled that people are thinking about their carbon footprint, but to put a number on a package is misleading at best,'' she said.LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo's interest in determining the carbon footprint of its products began in England, where carbon anxiety is further advanced than in the United States. In 2007, Walkers, a PepsiCo brand, published the carbon footprint of its potato chips on its Web site and on the package.LiNeBrEaK  Mr. Campbell, who ran the Walkers brand, championed the idea when he came to Tropicana at the beginning of 2008. As was the case with Walkers, Tropicana hired an outside auditor, the Carbon Trust, to review its calculations and certify its footprint. The Carbon Trust was set up by the British government to accelerate progress toward a low-carbon economy.LiNeBrEaK  Making orange juice is relatively straightforward: the oranges are picked by hand, trucked to the plant, squeezed, pasteurized and packed into cartons and shipped by train to distribution points around the country. Early on, company officials roughed out the carbon footprint of Tropicana juice. But when the Carbon Trust came back with its own calculations, that initial estimate was off by more than 20 percent.LiNeBrEaK  Growing the oranges accounted for a larger share -- about a third -- than PepsiCo had expected, almost entirely because of the production and application of fertilizer.LiNeBrEaK  Now, PepsiCo managers said they planned to work with their growers and with researchers at the University of Florida to find ways to grow oranges using less carbon. And they are starting to grapple with ways to teach the public how to interpret the carbon footprint of a product. LiNeBrEaK  PepsiCo is scheduled to announce its Tropicana results on Thursday, and will publish carbon-footprint numbers for products including Pepsi, Diet Pepsi and Gatorade. Said Bryan Lembke, a PepsiCo manager on the project: ''If you don't measure it, you can't improve it.''	http://www.nytimes.com  	EMISSIONS (90%); FRUIT and JUICE DRINKS (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (89%); ORANGE GROVES (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); TRENDS (77%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (77%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (76%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (73%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (73%); CITRUS GROVES (72%); CASE STUDIES (71%); FERTILIZERS (55%)  	PEPSICO INC (90%); COCA-COLA CO (58%); GOOGLE INC (55%)  			FLORIDA, USA (93%) UNITED STATES (93%); NORTH AMERICA (79%); EUROPE (73%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTOS: Above, oranges are processed at a Tropicana plant in Bradenton, Fla. (PHOTOGRAPH BY CHIP LITHERLAND FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (pg.B1)  Tom DeSaulniers, foreground, and Bryan Lembke, both of PepsiCo,  at a Tropicana plant in Bradenton, Fla. PepsiCo will announce its carbon footprint calculations on Thursday. (PHOTOGRAPH BY CHIP LITHERLAND FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES) (pg.B8) CHART: THE ENVIRONMENTAL COST OF ORANGE JUICE: Tropicana has calculated the carbon footprint of its Pure Premium orange juice -- that is, the amount of greenhouse gases produced in its manufacture and use. (Source: Tropicana) (pg.B8)                     		Newspaper  	2009 The New York Times Company   	By ANDREW MARTIN  	BRADENTON, Fla.   	PEP (NYSE) (90%); KO (NYSE) (58%); GOOG (NASDAQ) (55%)  	NAICS312111 SOFT DRINK MANUFACTURING (90%); SIC2086 BOTTLED and CANNED SOFT DRINKS and CARBONATED WATER (90%); NAICS311919 OTHER SNACK FOOD MANUFACTURING (90%); SIC2096 POTATO CHIPS, CORN CHIPS, and SIMILAR SNACKS (90%); NAICS519130 INTERNET PUBLISHING and BROADCASTING and WEB SEARCH PORTALS (55%)  												
The New York Times 	January 22, 2009 Thursday   Late Edition - Final	Study Finds New Evidence Of Warming in Antarctica  	Section A; Column 0; Foreign Desk; Pg. 12  	728 words  	Antarctica is warming.LiNeBrEaK  That is the conclusion of scientists analyzing half a century of temperatures on the continent, and the findings may help resolve a climate enigma at the bottom of the planet. LiNeBrEaK  Some regions of Antarctica, particularly the peninsula that stretches toward South America, have warmed rapidly in recent years, contributing to the disintegration of ice shelves and accelerating the sliding of glaciers. But weather stations in other locations, including the one at the South Pole, have recorded a cooling trend. That ran counter to the forecasts of computer climate models, and global warming skeptics have pointed to Antarctica in questioning the reliability of the models.LiNeBrEaK  In the new study, scientists took into account satellite measurements to interpolate temperatures in the vast areas between the sparse weather stations. LiNeBrEaK  ''We now see warming is taking place on all seven of the earth's continents in accord with what models predict as a response to greenhouse gases,'' said Eric J. Steig, a professor of earth and space sciences at the University of Washington in Seattle, who is the lead author of a paper to be published Thursday in the journal Nature.LiNeBrEaK  Because the climate record is still short, more work needs to be done to determine how much of the warming results from natural climate swings and how much from the warming effects of carbon dioxide released by the burning of fossil fuels, Dr. Steig said.LiNeBrEaK  But Drew T. Shindell of the NASA Goddard Institute for Space Studies in New York, who is another author of the paper, said, ''It's extremely difficult to think of any physical way that you could have increasing greenhouse gases not lead to warming at the Antarctic continent.''LiNeBrEaK  Dr. Steig and Dr. Shindell presented the findings at a news conference on Wednesday. They found that from 1957 through 2006, temperatures across Antarctica rose an average of 0. 2 degrees Fahrenheit per decade, comparable to the warming that has been measured globally.LiNeBrEaK  In West Antarctica, where the base of some large ice sheets lies below sea level, the warming was even more pronounced, at 0. 3 degrees  Fahrenheit, though temperatures in this area are still well below freezing and the warming will not have an immediate effect on sea level.LiNeBrEaK  In East Antarctica, where temperatures had been thought to be falling, the researchers found a slight warming over the 50-year period. With the uncertainties, East Antarctica may have indeed been cooling, but the rise in temperatures in the west more than offset the cooling. The average temperature for Antarctica is about minus 58 degrees.LiNeBrEaK  ''There is very convincing evidence in this work of warming over West Antarctica,'' said Andrew Monaghan, a scientist at the National Center for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., who was not involved with the research.LiNeBrEaK  As with earlier studies, the scientists found that more recently, since the late 1970s, temperatures had actually cooled in East Antarctica, a phenomenon that many atmospheric scientists attribute to emissions of chlorofluorocarbons, a family of chemicals used as coolants that destroyed high-altitude ozone. Because those chemicals have since been phased out, the ozone hole is expected to heal, and the cooling trend may reverse.LiNeBrEaK  The region of East Antarctica, which includes the South Pole, is at a much higher elevation and extends farther north than West Antarctica. While the scientists said the ozone hole most likely had a significant influence on Antarctic temperatures, other factors, including sea ice and greenhouse gases, may play a larger role.LiNeBrEaK  ''Obviously the situation is complex, resulting from a combination of man-made factors and natural variability,'' said Michael Oppenheimer, a professor of geosciences at Princeton, who was not involved in the research. ''But the idea of a long-term cooling is pretty clearly debunked.''LiNeBrEaK  Dr. Monaghan, who had not detected the rapid warming of West Antarctica in an earlier study, said the new study had ''spurred me to take another look at ours -- I've since gone back and included additional records.'' LiNeBrEaK  That reanalysis, which used somewhat different techniques and assumptions, has not yet been published, but he presented his revised findings last month at a meeting of the American Geophysical Union.LiNeBrEaK  ''The results I get are very similar to his,'' Dr. Monaghan said.	http://www.nytimes.com  	CLIMATOLOGY (90%); RESEARCH (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (90%); SCIENCE NEWS (90%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (90%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (78%); METEOROLOGY (78%); WEATHER (78%); MODELING and SIMULATION (78%); TRENDS (75%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (67%)  		UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON (55%)  		SEATTLE, WA, USA (79%) COLORADO, USA (79%); WASHINGTON, USA (79%); NEW YORK, USA (79%) ANTARCTICA (94%); SOUTH AMERICA (90%); UNITED STATES (79%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The New York Times Company   	By KENNETH CHANG; Andrew C. Revkin contributed reporting.  															
News and Observer (Raleigh, North Carolina)  	January 22, 2009 Thursday 	Report identifies states most at risk to rising seas  	DOMESTIC NEWS  	839 words  	RALEIGH, N.C. _ A new federal report concludes that Florida and Louisiana are the states most vulnerable to sea-level rise, followed by North Carolina and Texas.LiNeBrEaKThe new report focuses on the coastal states from North Carolina to New York where the rates of sea-level rise are moderately high. The region has extensive coastal development, a high population and is likely to be at increased risk.LiNeBrEaK"You're vulnerable," said Jim Titus, project manager for sea-level rise for the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency and lead author of the report, "Coastal Sensitivity to Sea Level Rise: A Focus on the Mid-Atlantic Region." "The people whose land could be permanently submerged aren't even flooded today." LiNeBrEaKA rise in sea level increases the vulnerability of development in coastal floodplains and diminishes the rate at which low-lying areas drain. It will result in a loss of wetlands in the mid-Atlantic.LiNeBrEaKRising temperatures cause ocean waters to warm and expand, like water heated in a tea kettle. In addition, rising temperatures near the poles cause massive ice sheets to melt, adding to the volume of water.LiNeBrEaKThe report predicts that coastal erosion will occur at higher rates as sea level rises. Particularly in the sandy shore of the mid-Atlantic coast, the report says, it is nearly certain that barrier islands, spits and coastal headlands will erode faster due to sea-level rise. The Outer Banks are particularly vulnerable.LiNeBrEaKThe report, produced by a collaboration among agencies including the U.S. Geological Survey, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and the Department of Transportation, offers three scenarios for sea-level rise by 2100: A rise of about 16 inches; of about 2 feet, and of about 3 feet.LiNeBrEaKIn 2007, an international scientific panel projected that sea level would likely rise between 7 inches and 2 feet by 2100. Those estimates do not take into account any contribution from rapid changes in ice flow from Antarctica or Greenland.LiNeBrEaKRising sea levels might be especially disastrous to North Carolina, as some sections of the coast are slowly sinking, magnifying the effects of rising seas.LiNeBrEaKTide-gauge readings in the mid-Atlantic indicate that relative sea level rise (the combination of rising waters and sinking land) was generally higher _ by about a foot _ than the global average during the 20th century.LiNeBrEaKIf sea level should rise more than three feet during the 21st century, the report says, "it is likely that some barrier islands in this region will cross a threshold" destabilizing and breaking apart.LiNeBrEaKRob Young, director of the Program for the Study of Developed Shorelines at Western Carolina University, said the report underscored that sea-level rise is a real management concern.LiNeBrEaK"There is some very important stuff in here that North Carolinians should take seriously," said Young, who said state policymakers and coastal communities should use a 3-foot sea-level rise by 2100 as a target.LiNeBrEaK"Whether sea level is rising is not something scientists argue about it," Young said. "It is. It's different than an argument about whether humans are causing global warming. We have directly measured an acceleration ... over the last two decades."LiNeBrEaKAs sea level rises, the most basic decision that states and beach communities must wrestle with is whether to try to hold back the sea or let nature take its course. Both have costs. Replenishing sand on eroding beaches allows houses and businesses to remain in place for a period of time, but is expensive to maintain. Retreating from the rising sea avoids the costs but concedes a loss of land and, in a worse case, entire communities, the report notes.LiNeBrEaKGreg Rudolph, shore protection officer for Carteret County, N.C., said people generally accept that sea level is rising. But planning for something that is occurring over decades is difficult.LiNeBrEaK"Let's face it, we live on four-year cycles when people are elected," Rudolph said. "Not many people are going to plan out 14 years or 21 years in advance."LiNeBrEaKBeach towns representing about a third of the North Carolina's 325 miles of coastline are seeking to replenish the sand on their beaches. But holding the beach may be an increasingly expensive response if erosion rates increase. "One size does not fit all," Rudolph said.LiNeBrEaKTitus, of EPA, said the report shows it is rational to take into consideration the risk of accelerated sea-level rise.LiNeBrEaK"A reasonable hope is people making decisions will start factoring it in, rather than continuing to assume that sea level is stable," Titus said. "Anyone who is making an investment, a regulation or a policy, has good reason to ask: how does sea level change the outcome of my decision?"LiNeBrEaKVisit The News and Observer online at http://www.newsobserver.com/		COASTAL AREAS (93%); RESEARCH REPORTS (90%); OCEANS (89%); ISLANDS and REEFS (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); FLOOD ZONES (78%); OCEANOGRAPHY (78%); EROSION (78%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (78%); WETLANDS (77%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (75%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (73%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (71%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (70%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (55%)  				RALEIGH, NC, USA (91%) NORTH CAROLINA, USA (94%); TEXAS, USA (92%); ATLANTIC OCEAN (79%) UNITED STATES (94%); ANTARCTICA (79%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 News and Observer   	By Wade Rawlins, McClatchy Newspapers  	RALEIGH, N.C.   			Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090122-BC-ENV-SEALEVELS  	RA  									
Omaha World - Herald (Nebraska)  	January 22, 2009 Thursday 	Hold your nose: Sarpy landfill odor solution a year away  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	506 words  	Jan. 22--There's good and bad news for Sarpy County residents suffering the obnoxious stink from their landfill.LiNeBrEaKThree companies submitted proposals to the county this month offering ways to capture the offending gases at little or no cost to taxpayers. However, the solutions would take at least a year to employ, a long time to hold one's nose. LiNeBrEaKOne company would sell the gas to Black Hills Energy, an area provider of natural gas. Another would burn it to make electricity for Omaha Public Power District. The third offered several options, including burning it off, fueling industry or generating power.LiNeBrEaKIn each case, the companies say they would finance the project themselves and make money by earning carbon and renewable energy credits and from selling energy. The county might even share in the revenue, they said.LiNeBrEaKIn asking for the proposals, Sarpy County officials made odor elimination their top priority.LiNeBrEaKCounty Administrator Mark Wayne said a key step will be measuring the quantity and quality of the gas spewing from the landfill. Stinky gas is not necessarily a good fuel to drive an electrical generator or fuel furnaces and water heaters. But finding significant amounts of highly combustible methane would make the projects feasible.LiNeBrEaKFor nearly a year and a half, Sarpy County residents have complained of a rotten-egg smell from the landfill at 156th Street and Platteview Road, aggravating nearby Springfield residents and drifting as far north as Nebraska Highway 370. Such distinctive odor usually is attributed to hydrogen sulfide gas.LiNeBrEaKSarpy County Board member Joni Jones said the county must eliminate the odor if it hopes to create an entertainment district and build a new Triple A baseball stadium near Interstate 80.LiNeBrEaK"We've got to take care of the issues we have before we invite someone into our home," Jones said.LiNeBrEaKThe Environmental Protection Agency reports that decomposing garbage is a reliable and renewable fuel option that remains largely untapped at many landfills across the United States.LiNeBrEaKMethane is a very potent greenhouse gas that is a key contributor to global climate change, the agency says.LiNeBrEaKAs of December 2007, the EPA reported approximately 445 landfill gas energy projects in operation across the country.LiNeBrEaKCompanies that destroy methane or generate electricity cleanly can receive carbon and renewable energy credits, which can be used or sold to other businesses to help them meet emission targets.LiNeBrEaKThe companies submitting proposals were SCC Americas of Houston, U.S. Energy Services Inc. of Plymouth, Minn., and Ingenco of Richmond, Va.LiNeBrEaK--Contact the writer: 444-1077, joe.dejka@owh.com		LANDFILLS (93%); COUNTIES (91%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); METHANE (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (89%); COUNTY GOVERNMENT (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (88%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (85%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (77%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (76%); ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (76%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (73%); BIOFUELS (70%); STADIUMS and ARENAS (63%); BASEBALL (63%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (60%); OMAHA PUBLIC POWER DISTRICT (57%); OMAHA WORLD-HERALD CO (50%)  			RICHMOND, VA, USA (51%) NEBRASKA, USA (92%); MINNESOTA, USA (79%); VIRGINIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Omaha World - Herald   	Joe Dejka, Omaha World-Herald, Neb.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090122-OM-Hold-your-nose-Sarpy-landfill-odor-solution-a-year-away-0122  	OM  									
The Oregonian  	January 22, 2009 Thursday 	Tree death rates up across the West, study says  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	497 words  	Jan. 22--Tree death rates in undisturbed old-growth stands across the West have more than doubled in recent decades, with the highest rate of increase in the Pacific Northwest, a team of researchers will report in the journal Science on Friday. LiNeBrEaKThe report pins increased tree mortality rates on higher temperatures and related increases in drought and summer dry periods.LiNeBrEaKThe change is tiny compared with devastating forest failures in recent years from bark beetles and fires. It amounts to roughly an extra dead tree an acre each year, said Mark Harmon, a co-author of the study and a forest ecology professor at Oregon State University.LiNeBrEaKBut it's unexpectedly widespread, the researchers from Oregon, Washington and other Western states said, hitting conifers from firs to hemlocks to pines of various sizes at all elevations.LiNeBrEaKIt's showing up in pristine stands in national parks and other areas where logging and forest fires have had no effect. And it's not being offset by increased tree establishment, the researchers said, meaning tree size and age could gradually diminish over time if the trend continues.LiNeBrEaKForests could also become more susceptible to abrupt die-backs, the researchers said, diminishing the forests' capacity to act as "carbon sinks" that could offset global warming. Western forests are among the biggest carbon sinks on the globe.LiNeBrEaKScientists have documented increased tree death rates in tropical forests. But the study is the first large-scale analysis of mortality rates in North America's temperate forests, the researchers said.LiNeBrEaKIn the Pacific Northwest and southern British Columbia, the rate of tree death in the older coniferous forests doubled in 17 years, the fastest rate among the areas studied. Mortality rates doubled in 25 years in California and 29 years in interior Western states, the researchers said.LiNeBrEaKThey based their findings on long-term tree inventories at 76 undisturbed sites across the West featuring forests with an average age of about 450 years. The plots contained 58,736 living trees over the study period, of which 11,095 died. Had mortality rates stayed constant, about 5,500 fewer trees would have died, Harmon said.LiNeBrEaKThe researchers ruled out insect attack, fire suppression, overcrowding of forests, air pollution and other potential local causes, instead attributing the increase in tree deaths on a small -- about 1 degree Fahrenheit -- increase in temperatures in the last 30 years.LiNeBrEaKThe temperature increase has reduced snow pack, they said, prolonged summer dry periods and helped insects and tree diseases flourish.		DEATHS and DEATH RATES (93%); RESEARCH (91%); FORESTS and WOODLANDS (91%); SCIENCE NEWS (90%); RESEARCH REPORTS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); TRENDS (78%); LOGGING INDUSTRY (78%); RAIN FORESTS (78%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (77%); GLOBAL WARMING (77%); CLIMATOLOGY (77%); FOREST FIRES (76%); FORESTRY and ENVIRONMENT (76%); NATIONAL PARKS (71%); FIRES (70%); AIR POLLUTION (60%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (55%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (60%)  	OREGON STATE UNIVERSITY (57%)  		PORTLAND, OR, USA (58%) OREGON, USA (97%); WEST USA (94%); NORTHWEST USA (93%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%); WASHINGTON, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (97%); NORTH AMERICA (79%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Oregonian   	Scott Learn, The Oregonian, Portland, Ore.  			Environment/Recycling/Waste  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090122-PO-TREE-DEATH-RATES-20090122  	PO  									
Philadelphia Inquirer (Pennsylvania)  	January 22, 2009 Thursday 	A more subtle leadership  	COMMENTARY  	836 words  	Barack Obama's inaugural speech answered a nagging question that much of the world has been debating: Is America too washed up to lead?LiNeBrEaKAfter years of Bush unilateralism, and with the U.S. economy in deep trouble, many claim the decline in American influence is unstoppable.LiNeBrEaKPresident Obama begs to differ. Yet the vision of U.S. leadership he laid out differs starkly from the style and substance of George W. Bush. LiNeBrEaKThe new president grasps that there is still a hunger abroad for American leadership. That's evident from a 17-nation poll for the BBC World Service released last week, which found 67 percent expressing hope that Obama's election would lead to improved relations with the rest of the world.LiNeBrEaKBut the world wants U.S. leadership that differs from that of the Bush years. Thus the key tenet of Obama's new foreign-policy doctrine is this: We must lead not just with military might, but also with diplomatic alliances and by living up to our democratic values.LiNeBrEaK"Recall that earlier generations faced down fascism and communism not just with missiles and tanks, but with sturdy alliances and enduring convictions," Obama said in his address. "They understood that our power alone cannot protect us, nor does it entitle us to do as we please.LiNeBrEaK"Instead, they knew that our power grows through its prudent use; our security emanates from the justness of our cause, the force of our example, the tempering qualities of humility and restraint."LiNeBrEaKOne of Obama's first acts will be to announce the planned closure of the Guantanamo military prison. "We reject as false the choice between our safety and our ideals," he said, "... and we will not give them up for expedience's sake."LiNeBrEaKWhat was striking in his address was the absence of any grandiose promises, such as those Bush made in his second inaugural to expand freedom and "end tyranny in our world."LiNeBrEaKObama's approach seems more Kennedy-esque _ a promise to befriend any nation seeking "a future of peace and dignity." He talked of aid to the poor. He promised to work "with old friends and former foes" to lessen the nuclear threat and combat global warming. His pledge to "responsibly leave Iraq" and forge peace in Afghanistan took up only one line.LiNeBrEaKObama also refused to view every foreign problem through the prism of a "war on terrorism." He made a hard-edged pledge to fight those "who seek to advance their aims by inducing terror and slaughtering innocents," and promised, "You cannot outlast us, and we will defeat you."LiNeBrEaKBut he specified that the "war" we are fighting is against "a network of violence and hatred." In other words, this struggle is against particular groups, not Islamic civilization.LiNeBrEaKIndeed, he added: "To the Muslim world, we seek a new way forward, based on mutual interest and mutual respect." However, he warned that those leaders who "blame their societies' ills on the West" are "on the wrong side of history." Even after this warning, however, he added "we will extend a hand if you are willing to unclench your fist."LiNeBrEaKMany say Obama can't possibly live up to the world's high expectations. Skeptics predict his hopes for smart diplomacy will run into the recalcitrance of Iran.LiNeBrEaKBut his address showed a man in tune with the times. We live today not in the unipolar world of the 1990s, but in a non-polar world. The United States has been bogged down in Iraq and Afghanistan, and unwilling to lead on key issues such as global warming. Washington has seemed incapable of leading the way out of the global recession as its own financial crisis worsens and infects others.LiNeBrEaKYet rising powers such as India and China aren't ready to lead on international problems. Europe, united in its economy, is too divided politically to take up that role.LiNeBrEaKThe world seems adrift. In such a power vacuum, extremist groups flourish. People everywhere, including here, feel they have lost control of their future.LiNeBrEaKObama recognizes that the world wants him to lead. He knows that his personal story _ and what it says about America _ give him and his country a new image. He grasps that publics abroad are hoping, even as they doubt, that he can fashion some rescue for the global economy.LiNeBrEaKSo when Obama said "we are ready to lead once more," he was emphasizing leadership with a difference. His global honeymoon may last longer than many expect.LiNeBrEaKABOUT THE WRITERLiNeBrEaKTrudy Rubin is a columnist and editorial-board member for the Philadelphia Inquirer. Readers may write to her at: Philadelphia Inquirer,  P.O. Box 8263, Philadelphia, Pa. 19101, or by e-mail at trubin@phillynews.comLiNeBrEaKVisit Philadelphia Online, the Inquirer's World Wide Web site, at http://www.philly.com		OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); FOREIGN RELATIONS (77%); FOREIGN POLICY (74%); PRISONS (69%); ARMED FORCES (67%); TERRORISM (63%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); US PRESIDENTS (78%)  	BBC WORLD SERVICE TELEVISION LTD (57%)  		BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE W BUSH (57%)  	PENNSYLVANIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%); AFGHANISTAN (79%); IRAQ (79%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO of Trudy Rubin available from the ``Columnist Mugs'' section of MCT Direct.		Newspaper  	2009 Philadelphia Inquirer   	By Trudy Rubin, The Philadelphia Inquirer  				Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090122-BC-RUBIN-COLUMN  	PH  									
