Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pennsylvania) 	January 22, 2009 Thursday   SOUTH EDITION	STUDENTS ASK OBAMA TO FIX ECONOMY, END WAR -- AND MANDATE FEWER TESTS  	METRO; Pg. S-1  	494 words  	"Dear Mr. President, do you think you could find a way to stop the war in Iraq, repair the economy, save the environment and provide more food for poor people?" LiNeBrEaKThose were just a few of the requests made by students in the Mt. Lebanon School District whose comments are part of a video letter to the president that will be posted on the district's Web site and, they hope, forwarded to Mr. Obama, who took office Tuesday.LiNeBrEaKThe students, from Lincoln Elementary, Jefferson Middle School and Mt. Lebanon High School, recently had their comments recorded by the district's multimedia staffers, Brad May and Mona Rice.LiNeBrEaKThe project was the brainchild of Superintendent John Allison, who thought it would be interesting to hear what was on the students' minds as the new president took office. Mr. Allison also hoped the project would inspire some students who might not otherwise think about national issues.LiNeBrEaKIn the 15-minute video, it's apparent the war in Iraq was on the minds of students from elementary grades through high school.LiNeBrEaKThird-grader James Wang, who said he was concerned about the war and the environment, told Mr. Obama, "Stopping the war and planting more trees would put a smile on my face."LiNeBrEaKSeveral students, including John Linderfjeld, a sophomore, talked about the poor economy and how it has affected their family and friends who have suffered job losses.LiNeBrEaKAlong with the economy, the escalating price of college was a big concern for the high school and middle school students who voiced opinions.LiNeBrEaKHigh school student Albert Li asked Mr. Obama for "a reduction in college fees." His classmates talked about working hard to get into good schools only to find that their families may not be able to afford them.LiNeBrEaK"The price of college is getting to the point where it is way too high for most families," said Danielle Nathanson, a high school student and editor-in-chief of the student newspaper, The Devil's Advocate.LiNeBrEaKDanielle also told Mr. Obama it's her hope that the Environmental Protection Agency will be strengthened under his tenure. Third-grader James Wang chimed in on this sentiment saying he was concerned about the number of cars on the road and how that contributed to global warming.LiNeBrEaKTo which James' buddy, Tesoro Fedel, a second-grader, responded: "Global warming is hurting our polar bears and penguins."LiNeBrEaKA student who didn't give his name told Mr. Obama that he was once a foster child, but was adopted at age 5. It's his hope that the president will give some attention to the issue of adoption of foster children.LiNeBrEaKOn the lighter side, Jefferson Middle School student Patrick Quirk asked Mr. Obama to consider education reform that called for fewer tests, and James Wang asked the president to make the Chinese New Year a national holiday.LiNeBrEaKAnd, high school student Anthony Kuzma asked the new president if in between handling big issues like the economy and the war in Iraq, he could find a way to create a championship series for college football.		PRIMARY SCHOOLS (90%); IRAQ WAR (90%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (90%); FAMILY (89%); CHILDREN (89%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); EDUCATION SYSTEMS and INSTITUTIONS (78%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (78%); SCHOOL DISTRICTS (77%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (73%); EDUCATION REFORM (72%); PUBLIC SCHOOLS (72%); FOSTER CARE (69%); COLLEGES and UNIVERSITIES (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (64%); ADOPTION (60%); HIGH SCHOOLS (90%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	PENNSYLVANIA, USA (73%) IRAQ (93%); LEBANON (92%); UNITED STATES (73%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 P.G. Publishing Co.   	Mary Niederberger, Pittsburgh Post-Gazette  							Mary Niederberger can be reached at mniederberger@post-gazette.com or 412-