The Record (Bergen County, NJ) 	January 22, 2009 Thursday   All Editions	A different kind of presidency  	OPINION; Pg. A11  	732 words  	PRESIDENT Obama's inauguration speech was not all that lyrical or rousing. That wasn't his purpose. The historic ceremony itself was emotional and moving enough, bringing people all over the world to tears.LiNeBrEaKWhat Obama wanted to do in his first act as president, when he had the undivided, rapt attention of the nation and the world, was to distance himself as completely as he could from his predecessor. Obviously, because George W. Bush was sitting only a few feet away, the new president had to be polite and diplomatic.LiNeBrEaKBut he wanted to make it as clear as he could that his presidency will be different, that this nation's relationship to its own people and to the people of all other nations will be dramatically different. LiNeBrEaKObama had only about 20 minutes to send that message. He spoke rather quickly, and it was easy to miss the meaning of a lot of what he said.LiNeBrEaKBut if you take the time to read the speech slowly, you will see what a powerful and precise piece of work it is. It isn't eloquent the way poetry is when read aloud, and it isn't eloquent in the way some of Obama's earlier campaign speeches have been.LiNeBrEaKInstead, the wording is economical, almost shorthand. But it speaks volumes about the Bush presidency and its signature policies, and dismisses them, in the blink of an eye.LiNeBrEaKHere are just three examples.LiNeBrEaK"We will restore science to its rightful place..."LiNeBrEaKThe phrase consists of only eight words, but it conjures up a whole host of references to Bush policies, from the rejection of the Kyoto Protocol and the long refusal to acknowledge the threat of global warming to the rewriting of findings by respected scientists to play down the effects of greenhouse gases and the hostility toward more fuel-efficient cars.LiNeBrEaKIt brings back memories of the controversy over evolution and Bush's endorsement of the teaching of intelligent design in the nation's classrooms ? which is just another way of trying to teach religion, not science, in the public schools.LiNeBrEaK"?a nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous."LiNeBrEaKA book could be written about this statement alone. Bush's eight years in office included the further decline of some of our most troubled cities, an increase in poverty in the United States and in the ranks of the uninsured, a widening of the gap between the rich and the poor, tax cuts that favored the rich, stagnation of the middle class, disdain for government programs such as Head Start and children's health insurance ? and of course, the response to Hurricane Katrina and the poor of New Orleans.LiNeBrEaKThe most vulnerable among us became even more invisible during the Bush years. Now they have been reassured that the new president hears their concerns.LiNeBrEaK"... our power alone cannot protect us, nor does it entitle us to do as we please."LiNeBrEaKThis can only be a direct reference to the visage that the Bush administration has generally presented to the rest of the world, one of arrogance, suspicion and isolation, at times almost indifference. It was that attitude that governed the run-up to the Iraq war, the rejection of treaties that the United States had been committed to and our overall relationship with the United Nations.LiNeBrEaKCooperation with other nations, including our allies, and taking our place at the world's table was often seen as weakness, not strength. Saber-rattling was often preferred to diplomacy.LiNeBrEaKBut that cowboy image vanished instantly with Obama's speech, which reiterated our strength and leadership in the world but also spoke of the power of "sturdy alliances and enduring convictions."LiNeBrEaKIn his speech, the new president extended his hand and the hand of America to our allies, to poor nations, to Muslim nations, even to those leaders who "cling to power through corruption and deceit and the silencing of dissent," if only they are willing "to unclench [their] fist."LiNeBrEaKAs the world grows smaller, Obama said, "our common humanity shall reveal itself..." and America will work to usher in "a new era of peace."LiNeBrEaKThe world is growing smaller. But in his first message, in the first minutes of his presidency, Barack Obama opened this nation's arms, expanded our horizons beyond narrow self-interest and announced that we would once again join the global community, not just as a leader but also as a partner and a friend.LiNeBrEaKMary Ellen Schoonmaker is an editorial writer and columnist for The Record. Contact her at schoonmaker@northjersey.com		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); EDUCATION SYSTEMS and INSTITUTIONS (77%); CLIMATOLOGY (69%); EMISSIONS (68%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); CREATIONISM (67%); POETRY (66%); HURRICANES (64%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (63%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (63%); AUTOMOTIVE INDUSTRY and ENVIRONMENT (63%); HEALTH INSURANCE (60%); HURRICANE KATRINA (60%); RELIGION (50%); US PRESIDENTS (90%) OBAMA  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE W BUSH (85%)  	NEW ORLEANS, LA, USA (79%) LOUISIANA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (79%); SPAIN (79%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO, The inauguration of President Obama was front-page news around the world; above, newspapers at a stand in Spain.  	OP-ED; COLUMN  	Newspaper  	2009 North Jersey Media Group Inc., All Rights Reserved  	MARY ELLEN SCHOONMAKER, North Jersey Media Group  															
