The Roanoke Times (Virginia) 	January 22, 2009 Thursday   Metro Edition	LETTERS TO THE EDITOR  	EDITORIAL; Pg. B8  	1239 words  	Forced attendance in school has eroded educationLiNeBrEaKAmelia Roberson evokes unintended irony when she brings up "Socratic dialogue" in her call for respect and support for teachers from parents, administrators and school boards ("Put teachers back in charge of their classrooms," Jan. 17 commentary).LiNeBrEaKSocrates was enraged when he was once falsely accused of accepting money for teaching. He believed the professionalization of teachers would result in an institution that existed to benefit the interests of teachers rather than students. I believe his prediction has come to pass.LiNeBrEaKIn making her argument, Roberson contends that parents should consider their children's education a privilege rather than a deserved activity. Our schools are neither. As of the early 20th century, every state in the union has adopted compulsory education laws. Failure to comply results in criminal charges, loss of custody or both. LiNeBrEaKThus, the lack of discipline in schools is an inevitable outcome of a system that mandates participation and assumes that learning must be forced. Our schools have more to do with social engineering than with education.LiNeBrEaKFred JonesLiNeBrEaKPilotLiNeBrEaKTime to rein in the anti-Bush invectiveLiNeBrEaKThis is to the Bush-haters who have constantly peppered this column with their stupid messages over the past eight years and are still doing it: Enough, already! I'm sick and tired of your foul invective about this good man, and I know a lot of others in this region are, too.LiNeBrEaKGod forbid that Al Gore should have been president during this time. We not only would have been attacked on our soil again, but we'd be worshipping at the altar of the global warming fairy tale.LiNeBrEaKCharles S. WertalikLiNeBrEaKRoanokeLiNeBrEaKWe each stand on shoulders of othersLiNeBrEaKInaugural addresses can be memorable and inspiring or simply forgotten. President John F. Kennedy's often quoted line, "Ask not what your country can do for you . . . ," is certainly memorable. This was a powerful and succinctly stated idea.LiNeBrEaKWe may never know if the message of this famous line was original with Kennedy and his speech writers. Nevertheless, we do know the same idea was penned much earlier by Kahlil Gibran. In 1925, Gibran wrote in "The New Frontier": "Are you a politician asking what your country can do for you or a zealous one asking what you can do for your country? If you are the first, then you are a parasite; if the second, then you are an oasis in a desert."LiNeBrEaKThis quotation is only one of many gems penned by Gibran, a philosopher and writer worthy of extensive study. Many leaders owe much to others for their ideas and inspiration. Let us not forget that each of us owe much to those who went before us, who taught us, or who care for and support us today.LiNeBrEaKGene CarsonLiNeBrEaKBlacksburgLiNeBrEaKGiles County can't afford a disasterLiNeBrEaKI would like to respond to the article in The Roanoke Times' Jan. 1 Current "Recent dam break highlights Narrows project." Joe Ryder, Giles County Partnership for Excellence board member and AEP environmental compliance officer, remarked that the Narrows project is never in a slurry-like state and the earthen berm is steel reinforced. I challenge him to prove this because I have hundreds of pictures and hours of video showing the progress of this project.LiNeBrEaKThe article stated that "the part of the Cumberland Park Project where the ash is already highway high has a liner under it." There is no liner, just a non-woven filter fabric that covers a layer of large rock and gravel approximately 8 feet thick and could have the potential of thousands of gallons of water under it.LiNeBrEaKThe Giles County Partnership for Excellence should release to the public the results of monitoring wells on site. Results from the two wells that the Concerned Citizens of Giles County have drilled will be published in the local newspaper and on the Web site www.concernedgilescitizens.org.LiNeBrEaKCan Giles County afford a catastrophe like the one in Harriman, Tenn., or Stevenson, Ala.?LiNeBrEaKCarleena S. BlankenshipLiNeBrEaKNarrowSLiNeBrEaKPilot's experience saved livesLiNeBrEaKRe: "All 155 on board are safe," Jan. 16 front page:LiNeBrEaKConsidering the tragic accident and the miracle that occurred on the Hudson, the miracle is due to God, the rescuers, and the experience of pilot Chesley Sullenberger. When industries such as aviation and healthcare downsize and replace experienced people with less experienced employees or hire inexperienced people due to cost-cutting measures, public safety is at risk. The Hudson incident is a prime example of why experienced workers are needed.LiNeBrEaKNext time you hear of cuts that will affect your safety and the safety of the public, make your voice heard, contact your representative. There is no replacement for experience. Experience in this case saved countless lives, those on the plane and on the ground. Can we put a price on this?LiNeBrEaKDebra ShipmanLiNeBrEaKBlacksburgLiNeBrEaKCircuses shouldn't use animal actsLiNeBrEaKIt saddens me to see that we in Roanoke are welcoming the Shrine Circus to town. With all the organizations promoting animal safety and animal welfare, it still surprises me that circuses continue to feature wild animals as entertainment for people.LiNeBrEaKIf you have seen even a picture of a majestic elephant in the wild and then compared it to the elephant dressed in a fancy headdress and doing silly tricks for people's amusement, you would realize that holding wild animals in captivity is wrong. From center stage to life in a trailer and back to center stage is abusive and degrading.LiNeBrEaKBy supporting these circuses, we support these actions. Imagine a circus with just the clowns and the high-wire acts and the trapeze artists. These acts should be enough to amuse and entertain humane people. These acts display true human talent and do not depend on the degradation of animals for their success.LiNeBrEaKNancy H. SpilbergLiNeBrEaKVintonLiNeBrEaKRoanoke council needs to take chargeLiNeBrEaKAfter reading the article in The Roanoke Times "Nonprofit group may owe Roanoke more than $333,000" (Jan. 17), I question just who is at the steering wheel here in Roanoke. It surely doesn't appear that our elected city council has been informed and included in all decisions that affect our tax dollars and how they are spent.LiNeBrEaKIt would appear that City Manager Darlene Burcham is easily able to maneuver around council members on decisions that should require their oversight. If it were not for The Times requesting information using the Freedom of Information Act, the general public and city council would still be in the dark on this issue and potentially many more that have not been brought into the light yet.LiNeBrEaKWhen are we, the citizens, and our elected officials who should speak for us going to wake up and say enough is enough?LiNeBrEaKJ.C. O'NeilLiNeBrEaKRoanokeLiNeBrEaKPilot's safe landing was a miracleLiNeBrEaKRe: "All 155 on board are safe," Jan. 16 front page:LiNeBrEaKWe've been reading about the pilot and his clear thinking and how he was able to save more than 100 people in landing on the Hudson River. While he is definitely a hero, so were those on the plane who kept a clear head and exited the plane in an orderly manner.LiNeBrEaKThe real hero in all of this was God, who was riding with the pilot to steady his hand for landing. He steered the plane away from buildings, thus avoiding hundreds of deaths. It was daylight; all the rescue ships were close by, but the plane didn't hit any of them. The crew stayed calm; the passengers looked like they were walking on water on the wings. All of this was planned and executed by God for us to witness a true miracle.LiNeBrEaKJanice WhitenackLiNeBrEaKDaleville