The San Diego Union-Tribune 	January 22, 2009 Thursday 	Eco-friendly seniors pitch in;  They hope to protect resources for offspring 	NEWS; Pg. A-1  	1120 words  	The idea of conserving resources is nothing new to 80-somethings who lived through the Great Depression. But now they're doing it not just to pinch pennies. They also want to save the Earth.LiNeBrEaKWorried about global warming, regional water shortages, too much reliance on foreign oil and other environmental problems, these retirees are finding big and small ways to go green.LiNeBrEaKFrom La Jolla and Rancho Bernardo to Hamden, Conn., and Lower Merion, Pa., older Americans are launching recycling programs, serving on committees that develop ways to save water and electricity, and encouraging managers of retirement homes to install solar panels and forgo golf courses. LiNeBrEaK"We are trying every way we know how to teach people who will be dead in a few years about environmental stewardship -- so they can teach their grandchildren," said Robert Lane, a professor emeritus at Yale University who co-founded the National Senior Conservation Corps in Hamden last year.LiNeBrEaKThe nonprofit group shares tips for green living with retirement communities -- including one in Lower Merion -- through brochures, multimedia reports and public exhibits. It helps connect seniors with environmental organizations and posts other related information on its Web site, grayisgreen.org.LiNeBrEaKAfter watching Al Gore's 2006 documentary, "An Inconvenient Truth," Lane and a few friends created an environmental council to boost recycling and other eco-friendly practices at their senior-living community. That effort expanded into a conservation corps.LiNeBrEaKThe group's pledge proclaims, in part, that each member will "conserve for the future the resources whose abundance, now waning, has made my life possible."LiNeBrEaKStatistics are scarce on the trend of Depression-era seniors making environmentally friendly lifestyle changes.LiNeBrEaKBut in a December 2007 survey of 30,000 baby boomers and Depression-era seniors, the research company Focalyst and AARP found that while both age groups are increasingly buying green products, octogenarians did so more often.LiNeBrEaKIn addition, retirees are putting more emphasis on living in homes that blend into the surrounding ecosystem, said Phyllis Isley, business manager for the Georgia-based American Association of Retirement Communities.LiNeBrEaK"For many years, the template was to build a retirement community around a golf course," she said. "The No. 1 amenities in most developments now are things like nature trails."LiNeBrEaKEcological awareness is indeed evident at retirement centers, said Maria Dwight, president and founder of Gerontological Services Inc., a market research firm in Santa Monica.LiNeBrEaK"Almost every campus I have been on, it's been the residents who have started the newspaper recycling and the glass recycling long before management catches on," she said. "They have formed committees, and they go through every department doing environmental inventories. It's really exciting to see."LiNeBrEaKAbout eight years ago, Dwight started giving presentations on environmental awareness at an annual national convention for retirees, senior-living managers and others. Sixteen people attended the first session. In 2008, the crowd numbered about 400.LiNeBrEaKAt the Classic Residence by Hyatt at La Jolla Village, resident John Werner said his neighbors "eat up" the message of conservation. He said more residents there have started turning off unnecessary lights, using low-wattage fluorescent bulbs and taking showers instead of baths to conserve water.LiNeBrEaKTwo months ago, Werner installed a shut-off valve on his shower head so he could easily turn off the water while he's scrubbing. A lower water bill would have been his only reason for doing so five years ago, he said, but today he's also concerned about California's prolonged drought.LiNeBrEaKWerner, 86, said retirement gave him time to think more about environmental issues. "This wasn't my top priority in life. As I get older, I think about it more," he said. "I want us to conserve and maintain the resources of our country."LiNeBrEaKHe has decided to spread his environmental ethic to fellow residents.LiNeBrEaKLast year, as chairman of the buildings and grounds committee, Werner worked with other seniors in urging people to wash only full loads of laundry and keep lamps away from thermostats. Heat produced from light bulbs can trigger air conditioners to run more than needed.LiNeBrEaKAt the La Costa Glen retirement community in Carlsbad, Janie Howell said her peers have recently become more receptive to tips on recycling and saving water.LiNeBrEaKHowell, 83, showers every other day and washes her hair only once a week -- in the sink instead of the shower. She also shops for gently used clothes at consignment stores and religiously reuses items such as twist-ties and plastic bags.LiNeBrEaK"I don't want all of this junk filling up our canyons," she said.LiNeBrEaKHowell said her environmental awareness has grown in the past few years because of widespread media coverage of glaciers melting, the sea level rising and water becoming more scarce.LiNeBrEaKShe pointed to the initiatives taken by La Costa Glen's residents, including their recycling programs for batteries from hearing aids and TV remote controls. These neighbors also have supported management's decisions to trim expenses and help the environment by:LiNeBrEaK* Using fewer plastic foam coffee cups.LiNeBrEaK* Posting dining-room menus online, cutting the number of printed copies from 600 to 65.LiNeBrEaK* Switching to ecologically friendly cleaning agents.LiNeBrEaK* Installing a synthetic pitch-and-putt golf course so the community wouldn't have to irrigate the grass with more than 1 million gallons of water a year.LiNeBrEaK"Many (residents) remember tricks their parents used during the lean times of the 1930s," said Darcie Gorman, accounting director and Green Team leader at La Costa Glen. "They are especially good with ideas on how to cut down on water and lighting, and some of them are even composting."LiNeBrEaKBorn near the end of the Depression era, Nancy Linton of Rancho Bernardo said she is tapping into the growing hunger for eco-based activities that don't cost much -- like washing windows with vinegar and water instead of a chemical-heavy cleaning product.LiNeBrEaKShe's planning a going-green luncheon in April for the 60- to 90-year-olds in her chapter of the American Association of University Women.LiNeBrEaK"The importance of (being environmentally friendly) has reached most of us so that it's not just an esoteric subject," said Linton, 70. "It has become a fundamental need to start doing this, but most people don't know where to start."LiNeBrEaKShe doesn't expect the changes to benefit her generation.LiNeBrEaK"Our lives are lived," Linton said, "but this group is interested in seeing a better future."LiNeBrEaKONLINE: To participate in a survey on how people often buy less and use fewer natural resources during a recession, visit uniontrib.com/more/footprint		ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (92%); RETIREMENT and RETIREES (90%); MATERIALS RECOVERY and RECYCLING (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (89%); GOLF and COUNTRY CLUBS (89%); GREAT DEPRESSION (89%); AGING (89%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (78%); TEACHING and TEACHERS (77%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (77%); TRENDS (76%); LIFESTYLE TRENDS (75%); CHILDREN (75%); BABY BOOMERS (75%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (74%); NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS (77%); GERONTOLOGY (72%); SOLAR ENERGY (70%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (70%); MARKET RESEARCH and ANALYSIS (68%); POLLS and SURVEYS (65%); DOCUMENTARY FILMS (65%); MARKET RESEARCH (63%); MARKET RESEARCH FIRMS (63%); GLOBAL WARMING (57%); WEB SITES (51%); SENIOR CITIZENS (90%); DEMOGRAPHIC GROUPS (66%) ELDERLY; ENVIRONMENT; SAN DIEGO;   		