San Gabriel Valley Tribune (West Covina, California)  	January 22, 2009 Thursday 	EDITORIAL: Green innovations require sacrifices  	COMMENTARY  	688 words  	Jan. 22--Changing from gasoline- and diesel-powered automobiles to ones powered by batteries, compressed natural gas or hydrogen will take more than the unveiling of a prototype. It will take billions of dollars in further research and development, in new fueling stations and, most importantly, a commitment to doing things differently.LiNeBrEaKLikewise, changing from filling up our local canyons with trash to relying on a remote, modern landfill system will take extra dollars to transport waste by train over many more miles. And it will take a commitment from the cities of Los Angeles County that proposed the changeover more than 20 years ago: an agreement to send their trash. LiNeBrEaKIt's easy to be in theoretical support of green innovations -- but it often amounts to mere lip service to the goals of breathing cleaner air and slowing global warming. It's much harder to commit to a green lifestyle. That usually requires sacrifice.LiNeBrEaKJust as Congress demanded the Big Three automakers re-tool by producing hybrids and alternatively fueled cars, we would like to see the same measure of green commitment from San Gabriel Valley-area cities for a new solid waste system.LiNeBrEaKOne way to really be green is to support the Los Angeles County Sanitation District's changeover to waste-by-rail that will take trash by railcars to a new landfill in Imperial County. This removes a source of air pollution and methane -- a greenhouse gas -- from our Valley.LiNeBrEaKInstead of piling the trashLiNeBrEaKhigher and higher above Hacienda Heights and the Pomona (60) Freeway, the county is committed to closing the Puente Hills Landfill by Oct. 31, 2013. But the trash brought to Puente Hills -- about 4 million tons a year, one-third of all the trash produced in the county -- has to go somewhere.LiNeBrEaKThe Sanitation Districts have invested $500 million in buying and developing the Mesquite Regional Landfill. Just this year, it received final approvals from the Imperial County Public Health Department and the Colorado River Regional Water Quality Control Board. A rail yard will be built at the site to receive trash from L.A. County by 2011 or 2012.LiNeBrEaKThe districts also began subsidizing the extra transportation costs through supplemental dumping fees. Eventually, trash rates charged residents by private waste haulers will go up by $2 to $3 a month.LiNeBrEaKWhile no one wants to pay more for trash pickup, this additional cost is worth it. One only has to look at the history of the San Gabriel Valley to understand. We used to be called "Valley of the Dumps" because the city of Los Angeles thought it was the ideal place to bury its trash. But one by one, after a commitment from San Gabriel Valley mayors and the Sanitation Districts, the local eyesores began to close: BKK Corp. Landfill in West Covina, the Azusa Landfill and the Spadra Landfill in Walnut (the latter is now part of the Center for Regenerative Studies at Cal Poly Pomona). BKK is now a new sports park and hosts a Target store.LiNeBrEaKWhile the Puente Hills Landfill is well-run and bears no comparison to BKK, it still must close in 4 1/2 years due to contractual agreement.LiNeBrEaKLocal cities, through the San Gabriel Valley Association of Cities (now the San Gabriel Valley Council of Governments), defeated plans for garbage incinerators in 1987. Instead, they offered waste-by-rail as one alternative.LiNeBrEaKAt a recent SGVCOG meeting in Irwindale, the new leaders of these cities were reminded of the foresight and leadership shown by 33 Valley cities and communities back in the 1980s. While Claremont began sending its waste to Orange County recently, we think that was a mistake. All the cities should support the new waste-by-rail project -- and finish what they started.		LANDFILLS (91%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); NA