Austin American-Statesman (Texas) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   Final Edition	In troubled times, Obama strikes a somber tone  	EDITORIAL; Pg. A18  	653 words  	President Barack Obama's inaugural speech on Tuesday had all the flourishes of inspiration we would expect on such an occasion and from such a powerful orator who touted the arrival of a new generation of Americans. Listen closely, though, and you also heard a strong undercurrent of warning - even admonishment - to the American people.LiNeBrEaKOn a cold but brilliantly lighted day, the new president summed up well the dangers and dissatisfaction facing the nation as he took office, citing the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan and an economy in recession. And, he said, "our health care is too costly; our schools fail too many; and each day brings further evidence that the ways we use energy strengthen our adversaries and threaten our planet." LiNeBrEaKJust as worrisome, Obama said, was "a sapping of confidence across our land - a nagging fear that America's decline is inevitable, and that the next generation must lower its sights."LiNeBrEaKOf course, Obama, as any new president would, promised that the challenges would be conquered by hard work, wise policies and faith in the future - that better days are to come.LiNeBrEaKBut there was also a more subtle message of admonishment, perhaps even rebuke. The United States is a young nation, he said, but "in the words of Scripture, the time has come to set aside childish things." Just what those are he didn't say.LiNeBrEaKObama also said that "our time of standing pat, of protecting narrow interests and putting off unpleasant decisions - that time has surely passed."LiNeBrEaKAgain, he didn't say what "unpleasant decisions" he had in mind.LiNeBrEaKWe suspect, we hope, that this was not a partisan rebuke to Obama's predecessor, but a warning that his administration will take on such enormous problems as future funding of Social Security and Medicare, global warming and providing and paying for health care to Americans without health insurance. (President George W. Bush, to be sure, took on Social Security, but his approach was rejected by the American people.)LiNeBrEaKIn part, Obama's speech certainly was a direct rebuke to the Republican Party's decades of anti-government rhetoric and Bush's administration of that government over the past eight years. , Obama said that the question asked today "is not whether our government is too big or too small, but whether it works."LiNeBrEaKThe November election results showed that a majority of Americans didn't think it was working.LiNeBrEaKSimilarly, Obama took a practical, does-it-work-for-the-people stance toward the free market ideology that has governed economic policy for the past several decades. While the free market remains unparalleled in its ability to produce wealth and broaden freedom, he said, "this crisis has reminded us that without a watchful eye, the market can spin out of control - and that a nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous."LiNeBrEaKAnd while the economy was damaged "by greed and irresponsibility on the part of some," Obama said, it was also damaged by "our collective failure to make hard choices and prepare the nation for a new age." Once more, he did not say what those hard choices were.LiNeBrEaKWe are glad to hear Obama's assurance that America need not compromise its commitment to human rights and common decency to fight terrorists. This, too, was a rebuke to the past eight years, when he said that "our power alone cannot protect us, nor does it entitle us to do as we please."LiNeBrEaKObama said this would be a "new era of responsibility," a phrase not likely to ring through American history like New Deal or New Frontier, though many Americans will welcome his emphasis on the duties, as well as the privileges and rights, of citizenship.LiNeBrEaKThe speech is over, though, and the first real test of Obama's leadership will come not when he tries to deliver something more for the American people but calls for giving up something, and tax cuts don't count as sacrifice. What hard choices and unpleasant decisions will he bring to the American people?		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); SOCIAL SECURITY (89%); ECONOMIC NEWS (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (77%); PUBLIC POLICY (76%); RECESSION (75%); HEALTH INSURANCE (75%); ECONOMIC POLICY (75%); ELECTIONS (74%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (70%); GLOBAL WARMING (69%); MEDICARE (67%); POLITICAL PARTIES (60%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE W BUSH (52%)  	TEXAS, USA (92%); EARTH (56%) UNITED STATES (96%); AFGHANISTAN (79%); IRAQ (79%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Austin American-Statesman All Rights Reserved  	AUSTIN AMERICAN-STATESMAN EDITORIAL AMERICAN-STATESMAN STAFF  															
Birmingham News (Alabama) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	RINGS AND WEATHER Mountain Brook students study climate through trees  	COMMUNITY NEWS; Pg. 1S Vol. 121 No. 314  	567 words  	A Mountain Brook High School science class is studying climate change, one tree at a time.LiNeBrEaKScience teacher Tony Derriso is using an $8,500 grant from Toyota's Tapestry Program to get 11th- and 12th-graders looking for centuries-old weather information.LiNeBrEaKThe study is simple. A tree's age can be counted by its rings, with each ring indicating one year of life. Some rings are wider that others, meaning the tree probably got better water and climate during that particular year. By examining a tree's rings, any observer with the right know-how can see how old the tree is and trace its development over decades. LiNeBrEaKTo study climate change, however, means looking at climate - long-term weather conditions over several centuries, not year-byyear temperatures. The problem is that, for Alabama at least, daily consistent temperature records exist only back to about 1895, Derriso said.LiNeBrEaKTo get an idea of actual climate change, scientists have to use paleoclimatology - studying tree rings, ice cores, lake sedimentation and coral reefs to get an idea of what conditions were like before temperatures were recorded.LiNeBrEaK''These are natural archives,'' Derriso said. ''And to my knowledge, this sort of thing has never been done in the Birmingham area.''LiNeBrEaKAbout 70 students are taking part in the study, which is using loblolly pines that grow in abundance on the high school campus. Students bore into trees using a tool and extracted a piece of wood about the size of a pencil, which shows the individual rings inside the trees. Derriso said the process takes only a few minutes and does not harm the trees.LiNeBrEaK''It's a standard forestry procedure that's generally used to check the health of a forest,'' he said.LiNeBrEaKThe ring samples are then sanded down and examined under a stereo microscope with a camera. Using a computer program, students canLiNeBrEaKmeasure the rings down to 1/ 10,000th of an inch. Then, using the ring measurements and comparing them with existing temperature records, students can build a weather chronology, Derriso said.LiNeBrEaK''If the tree ring was a particular width for a year that we have temperature measurements on, then we can guess pretty reliably what the weather was like for a year we don't have records on,'' he said.LiNeBrEaKThe first time Preston Ratliff, 17, attempted to get a tree sample, he wasn't sure it was going to work.LiNeBrEaK''You may realize you're going in at an angle instead of getting a straight, good sample,'' he said. ''Then you get used to it.''LiNeBrEaKAs the class gathers its information, students will publish their findings on a Web site being assembled by Stephanie Browdy, 17. The site is still in its basic stages, but Derriso hopes to link it with the International Tree Ring Data Bank, a project of the World Center for Paleoclimatology. The data bank gathers tree ring information from all over the world to compare climate patterns.LiNeBrEaK Browdy said the class will try to make their findings accessible and easy to understand.LiNeBrEaK''What we hope is that there will be interaction with other teachers so they can share and exchange their tree information,'' she said.LiNeBrEaKDerriso said the best part of the project is that students are not doing an exercise to show how science works, but actual scientific research.LiNeBrEaK''This will be publishable data, and we don't know what the outcome will be,'' he said. ''When you're doing something like this for the first time, that means something.''LiNeBrEaKEMAIL: wthornton@bhamnews.com		CLIMATE CHANGE (92%); CLIMATOLOGY (91%); WEATHER (90%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (90%); MATH and SCIENCE EDUCATION (90%); PRIMARY and SECONDARY SCHOOL TEACHERS (90%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (78%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (78%); ISLANDS and 