Chicago Tribune (Illinois)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Spring arriving almost 2 days earlier than it did 50 years ago, scientists find  	DOMESTIC NEWS  	563 words  	CHICAGO _ In the throes of a severe winter, an earlier spring may seem welcome. But be careful what you wish for.LiNeBrEaKThough researchers reported Wednesday that spring indeed has inched earlier by almost two days over the past 50 years, scientists warn that such seasonal drift could have catastrophic ecological consequences.LiNeBrEaKTo measure the seasons, the study looked at temperatures in locations around the world and compared them to the distance between the sun and the Earth at different times of the year. LiNeBrEaKHow close the Earth comes to the sun as it travels on its orbit mediates the planet's cyclical warming and cooling. Though that pattern never changes, the timing of seasons has moved forward 1. 7 days since 1957, the authors calculated.LiNeBrEaKWhy? Alexander Stine, a University of California-Berkeley graduate student who led the study, suspects the sun's distance from the Earth now affects the planet more quickly, leading to earlier springs and falls.LiNeBrEaKNormally, changes in the Earth's surface temperature take about a month to kick in _ for example, the hottest day of the year occurs about 30 days following the summer equinox, when the planet is closest to the sun.LiNeBrEaKBut various factors may have shortened that lag time, Stine said. Reduced moisture levels in the soil, for instance, could mean faster changes in temperature because drier soil heats and cools faster, as seen in the desert. More man-made aerosols in the atmosphere may also have an effect by altering how much of the sun's energy reaches Earth.LiNeBrEaKStine said the seasonal change appears to be accelerating, noting that the majority of the drift has occurred since 1981. "Really the last 27 years stand out as being different from anywhere previous in the record," he said.LiNeBrEaKThe team's analysis also found a decrease in the difference between average temperatures in summer and winter, predominantly because of higher temperatures during winter.LiNeBrEaKWhile warmer winters and earlier springs may sound nice in January, scientists have already observed that changing seasonal patterns are affecting Earth's plant and animal populations.LiNeBrEaKSome think the seasons are shifting even more rapidly than the new study suggests.LiNeBrEaKMark Schwartz, a University of Wisconsin-Milwaukee climatologist, said his own research on the blooming of lilacs indicates spring is moving earlier by slightly more than a day each decade.LiNeBrEaK"When these kind of changes are happening, you start to create a ripple effect," Schwartz said. "That begins to have ecological implications from the point of view of survival of species."LiNeBrEaKStine said he hopes his study will lead researchers to examine the effect of climate change on various temperature patterns around the world, as well as overall changes in temperature.LiNeBrEaK"If we're trying to make projections for how the planet will respond as it warms, one of the things we're all concerned about is whether there are some surprises that will change the Earth in unexpected ways," Stine said. "Most of the surprises we can think of are not real good."		SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); SCIENCE NEWS (90%); RESEARCH (90%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); GLOBAL WARMING (76%); SOIL CONTAMINATION (65%)  		UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA (56%)  		CHICAGO, IL, USA (90%); MILWAUKEE, WI, USA (71%) EARTH (95%); ILLINOIS, USA (90%); WISCONSIN, USA (71%); CALIFORNIA, USA (71%) UNITED STATES (90%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Chicago Tribune   	By Robert Mitchum, Chicago Tribune  	CHICAGO   			Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090121-BC-ENV-CLIMATE-1ST-LEDE  	TB  									
Chicago Tribune (Illinois)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Two new studies find shift in Earth's temperatures over past 50 years  	DOMESTIC NEWS  	493 words  	CHICAGO _ The news might seem welcome in the middle of a long, cold winter: Scientists have shown that the start of spring has moved almost two days earlier in the past 50 years. LiNeBrEaKBut scientists say the finding, one of two papers released Wednesday on climate change, is actually a warning sign. Together, the studies bolster the argument that the planet's temperatures have shifted significantly in the last half-century, with many of the potential consequences likely to be negative.LiNeBrEaKReporting in the scientific journal Nature, two teams of scientists presented evidence that all seasons are occurring earlier worldwide and that more of Antarctica is showing signs of warming than had been thought.LiNeBrEaKThe seasonal study, from the University of California-Berkeley and Harvard University, compared temperature data in regions around the world to the distance between the sun and Earth at various points in time.LiNeBrEaKThe information showed that warming temperatures associated with spring, as well as autumnal cooling, have moved forward by 1. 7 days from 1954 to 2007. Such a shift is not seen anywhere else in temperature records stretching back to the 19th century, and much of the change appears to have occurred since 1981, said the lead author, Berkeley graduate student Alexander Stine.LiNeBrEaK"Really, the last 27 years stand out as being different from anywhere previous in the record," Stine said.LiNeBrEaKThe other report, led by University of Washington climatologist Eric Steig, addresses previous observations that only the northwestern peninsula of Antarctica has shown significant warming over the past 40 years, while the bulk of the continent appeared to be cooling.LiNeBrEaKThose measurements were fixed on by climate change skeptics who are unconvinced that the planet is undergoing a universal warming trend.LiNeBrEaKBut by adding satellite data to temperatures collected from weather stations in Antarctica from 1957 to 2006, Steig's team found that a large portion of western Antarctica has been warming at a rate of 0. 17 degrees Celsius per decade, roughly double the global warming rate in the past century.LiNeBrEaKSteig cautioned that the limitations of the data make it hard to predict future temperature changes in the region. But if warming is occurring across a wider area than previously observed, that could increase the possibility of large ice shelves melting off the continent and changing sea levels around the world.LiNeBrEaK"This study showing warming means we can't be complacent about thinking the West Antarctica ice sheet is invulnerable," Steig said. "It will eventually melt if warming like this continues."		SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (91%); SCIENCE NEWS (91%); RESEARCH REPORTS (91%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); RESEARCH (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); WEATHER (89%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (89%); TRENDS (77%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (80%)  	HARVARD UNIVERSITY (56%); UNIVERSITY OF CALIFORNIA (56%); UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON (54%)  		CHICAGO, IL, USA (92%) ILLINOIS, USA (92%); EARTH (92%); CALIFORNIA, USA (71%) ANTARCTICA (94%); UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Chicago Tribune   	By Robert Mitchum, Chicago Tribune  	CHICAGO   			Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090121-BC-ENV-CLIMATE  	TB  									
Chicago Tribune (Illinois)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Warming extends to eastern Antarctica  	DOMESTIC NEWS  	532 words  	For a decade, climate researchers have argued about temperature change in Antarctica, the coldest place on Earth.LiNeBrEaKThe thin peninsula stretching from the northwest corner of the continent is one of the fastest-warming locations in the world. But scientists also found that the rest of the continent had cooled during the 20th century, a fact seized upon by climate-change skeptics. LiNeBrEaKNow new research has clarified the picture, showing that western Antarctica has warmed at a rapid rate over the last 50 years and eastern Antarctica has also warmed, but more slowly. The study, published Thursday, used satellites to expand upon temperature information measured at Antarctic weather stations.LiNeBrEaKIn western Antarctica, temperatures are rising at a rate of 0. 17 degrees Celsius each decade, almost double the average warming rate around the globe for the last century, the study found. Most of the warming was found to occur in winter and spring.LiNeBrEaKShould the warming continue, the millions of miles of ice covering Antarctica could begin to melt, causing sea levels around the world to rise in the long term, said lead author Eric Steig, a climatologist at the University of Washington.LiNeBrEaK"This warming means we can't be complacent about thinking the West Antarctica ice sheet is invulnerable," Steig said. "It will eventually melt if warming like this continues."LiNeBrEaKScientists who had previously documented cooling across Antarctica's interior applauded the research as providing valuable data that could help predict the impact of further Antarctic warming on the Earth's climate.LiNeBrEaKAmong them is Peter Doran, a climatologist at the University of Illinois-Chicago who said his research has been falsely distorted by those who doubt climate change is happening.LiNeBrEaKThe key issue, he said, is not whether Antarctica as a whole is warming or cooling, because even partial warming is enough to cause alarm.LiNeBrEaK"Really what's important is how does this feed into models as far as sea level rise," Doran said. "The parts that are warming are contributing to sea rise regardless of what's happening on the rest of the continent."LiNeBrEaKDoran said he hopes the new research will help convince the public of the scientific consensus on climate change.LiNeBrEaKAccording to a survey of Earth scientists he conducted with fellow UIC researcher Maggie Kendall Zimmerman, 90 percent believe that mean global temperatures have risen since 1800 and 82 percent say human activity has been a significant contributing factor.LiNeBrEaKThe survey went to more than 10,000 scientists, and more than 3,000 responded. The results appeared this week in the science newspaper EOS.LiNeBrEaK"There are a handful of doubters you see on the news all the time that keep saying it's not real, but really, the vast majority of the climate scientists say it's real," Doran said. "I think that's a powerful conclusion."		CLIMATOLOGY (91%); RESEARCH REPORTS (91%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); RESEARCH (90%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (90%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (89%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (89%); SCIENCE NEWS (89%); POLLS and SURVEYS (78%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (78%); GLOBAL WARMING (78%); WEATHER (73%)  		UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON (55%)  		CHICAGO, IL, USA (86%) EARTH (93%); ILLINOIS, USA (91%) ANTARCTICA (95%); UNITED STATES (91%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Chicago Tribune   	By Robert Mitchum, Chicago Tribune  				Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090121-BC-ENV-SOUTHPOLE  	TB  									
Contra Costa Times (California) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	For California, new clout in Obama's tech-friendly administration  	NEWS  	1011 words  	and Mary Anne OstromLiNeBrEaKWASHINGTON   Barbara Boxer remembers the "dark days" when California and its issues were dismissed by official Washington with disdain and hostility.LiNeBrEaK"Dianne Feinstein and I joked that it was ABC   anything but California, anyone but California," Boxer said, recalling when the two Democrats joined the Senate in 1993.LiNeBrEaKNow, as California Democrats fill Washington to celebrate Barack Obama's inauguration, the state can claim a surge of influence in the new, tech-friendly administration. Congress, too, is looking westward, with Californians taking key positions of power. LiNeBrEaKTwo Californians were named to Obama's Cabinet   Nobel Prize-winning physicist Steven Chu at the Energy Department and Rep. Hilda Solis at the Labor Department   and Leon Panetta, former President Bill Clinton's White House chief of staff, has been appointed to lead the Central Intelligence Agency.LiNeBrEaKObama also named a pair of Golden Staters to key White House posts: Christina Romer, a Berkeley economist, will chair the Council of Economic Advisers, and Nancy Sutley, deputy mayor of Los Angeles, will bring her experience as a state environmental regulator to the job of chairing the Council on Environmental Quality.LiNeBrEaK"These are superstar choices. California is in right now, and we can remember when California was out," Boxer said. "There is a lot more respect for the state, especially on energy issues."LiNeBrEaKShift on tech, energyLiNeBrEaKOn a policy level, it's a shift from oil drilling to renewable energy, from sidestepping the issue of global warming to dealing with it aggressively, from a pro-industry stance to greater sympathy for organized labor.LiNeBrEaKRep. Zoe Lofgren, a San Jose Democrat, measured the change this way: "I remember Gov. Jerry Brown coming to Washington talking about windmills, and people made fun of him. Now everybody is talking about wind energy and solar."LiNeBrEaKCalifornians with deep experience in tech and energy issues, particularly clean technology, have Obama's ear. That includes Eric Schmidt,  chief executive of Google, venture capitalist John Doerr, who is close to Al Gore, and John Thompson, the former Symantec CEO who may be a contender for commerce secretary.LiNeBrEaKThat influence can be seen in major ingredients in the $825 billion stimulus package prepared by the House with the Obama team's input. Doerr, for example, lobbied for the $11 billion that would go toward modernizing the electricity grid. Tech groups pushed hard for $6 billion in grants to speed up broadband deployment. Wind-energy advocates secured a long-term extension of the production tax credit.LiNeBrEaKAnd California renewable-energy companies and investors, struggling with the frozen credit market, cheered when Obama announced his goal of doubling the production of renewable energy over the next three years.LiNeBrEaK"I think what the Obama administration intends to do is move the technology that has been pioneered in California across the country," said Cathy Zoi, CEO of Palo Alto-based Alliance for Climate Protection.LiNeBrEaKThe state's new clout should not be viewed in the traditional sense of more "pork" for California, said Norm Ornstein, an author and longtime analyst of government for the American Enterprise Institute. But it will play out in other ways.LiNeBrEaK"There will be a greater sensibility on issues that matter to California and drive the California economy," Ornstein said. "It helps that Obama puts a high priority about keeping the nation's edge on technology, and is listening to Silicon Valley on that."LiNeBrEaKCalifornia-friendlyLiNeBrEaKSome appointees are not from California but tend to view key issues in California-friendly ways. Carol Browner, a top Obama adviser on energy and the environment, supported the state's pioneering regulations as Environmental Protection Agency chief. And Gov. Janet Napolitano of Arizona, a graduate of Santa Clara University who has worked on border-state issues, has been named to head the Homeland Security Department.LiNeBrEaKObama is unlikely to cultivate as cozy a relationship with the state as Bill Clinton did, predicted Jack Pitney, a professor of politics at Claremont McKenna College who worked for Republicans during the Reagan and first Bush administrations.LiNeBrEaKBut he agrees that just as Reagan-style California conservatism was adopted in Washington in the 1980s, Obama is likely to embrace California-style progressivism.LiNeBrEaKUnlike the 1990s, when Clinton had to deal with a Republican majority in Congress, Democrats now control both branches, with state leaders well-represented   starting with House Speaker Nancy Pelosi of San Francisco.LiNeBrEaKLofgren, who chairs the immigration subcommittee in the House, knows she can get Napolitano on the phone if there's a problem with the immigration bureaucracy, or she can contact Solis on a labor issue.LiNeBrEaKLofgren chairs the delegation of 34 California Democrats in the House, which met last week and bid farewell to Solis.LiNeBrEaK"There in the room were the chairmen of the Energy Committee (Henry Waxman,) Education and Labor (George Miller), Foreign Affairs (Howard Berman), and Veterans Affairs (Bob Filner)," Lofgren said. "I thought, if you wanted to get something done, come to this room."LiNeBrEaKState labor leaders expect that with Solis in the Cabinet, they will have a friendly ear on minimum-wage and family-leave issues, and other concerns of an increasingly immigrant work force. Solis, from Los Angeles, is the daughter of immigrants and her father was a union worker.LiNeBrEaK"She is very well-connected and can help bridge the gap and the tensions between immigrant workers and other sectors of the community, including some unions," said Art Pulaski, executive secretary-treasurer of the California Labor Federation, AFL-CIO.LiNeBrEaKBut Pitney, a veteran observer of Washington, warned that Californians looking for rapid change on energy, labor and other issues from Obama and other leaders they just elected may be disappointed.LiNeBrEaK"Electing officials is a lot like shopping online," Pitney said. "Everything looks better when you log on than when the package arrives at the door."LiNeBrEaKReach Frank Davies at mostrom@mercurynews.com or 415-477-3794.		POLITICAL PARTIES (90%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (90%); SOLAR ENERGY (89%); WIND ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (88%); APPOINTMENTS (77%); LOBBYING (77%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (76%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (76%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (76%); LABOR DEPARTMENTS (74%); COMMERCE DEPARTMENTS (74%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (74%); NOBEL PRIZES (74%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (74%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (71%); TAX LAW (70%); AWARDS and PRIZES (70%); US PRESIDENTS (76%); LABOR UNIONS (69%); ECONOMIC POLICY (67%); ECONOMIC NEWS (67%); TAXES and TAXATION (62%); VENTURE CAPITAL (61%); INTELLIGENCE SERVICES (53%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); BROADBAND (50%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (76%)  	GOOGLE INC (53%); XIAMEN ANNE CORP LTD (58%)  	CENTRAL INTELLIGENCE AGENCY (56%); COUNCIL ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (55%); COUNCIL OF ECONOMIC ADVISERS (55%)  	BARACK OBAMA (95%); BARBARA BOXER (92%); DIANNE FEINSTEIN (91%); STEVEN CHU (57%); BILL CLINTON (56%); LEON E PANETTA (56%); HILDA L SOLIS (56%); CHRISTINA ROMER (56%); ZOE LOFGREN (53%); AL GORE (52%); ERIC E SCHMIDT (52%); JOHN W THOMPSON (52%); L JOHN DOERR (52%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (92%); LOS ANGELES, CA, USA (79%); SAN JOSE, CA, USA (79%) CALIFORNIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Contra Costa Newspapers All Rights Reserved  	By Frank Davies Mercury, News Washington Bureau  		GOOG (NASDAQ) (53%); 002235 (SZSE) (58%)  	NAIC