Daily Camera (Boulder, Colorado)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Boulder, Colo., OKs global warming lawsuit settlement  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	507 words  	Jan. 21--BOULDER, Colo. -- Boulder's elected leaders Tuesday night unanimously agreed to settle a lawsuit against two federal agencies that the city, along with other cities and an environmental group, took to court. LiNeBrEaKThe case was an attempt to get the agencies to follow environmental regulations even for projects they fund overseas.LiNeBrEaKMayor Shaun McGrath said the case shows how much the debate over global warming has changed since 2002, when the City Council decided to join the legal fight. For one thing, a new presidential administration much friendlier to the idea of limiting greenhouse gas emissions has just taken office.LiNeBrEaK"I think the wins that we did achieve here were significant," he said. "I also think that it's appropriate for us to settle, given the many changes that have happened. ... I'm confident that the United States is back in the game."LiNeBrEaKBoulder was one of several cities to join the lawsuit, brought by the environmental activist group Friends of the Earth against the Overseas Private Investment Corp. and the Export-Import Bank of the United States in 2002.LiNeBrEaKThose two agencies fund billions of dollars' worth of projects -- many of them for exploration for oil and gas -- overseas.LiNeBrEaKThe nonprofit group, along with the cities of Boulder, Arcata, Oakland and Santa Monica, Calif., sued the two agencies to force them to abide by federal regulations -- and to assess the contribution their projects would make to climate change.LiNeBrEaKIn 2005, Boulder and the other plaintiffs won a major victory when a federal court judge agreed that they had standing -- that is, the legal right to bring a suit -- on the grounds that the cities could be affected by global warming.LiNeBrEaK"This was the first court opinion that said greenhouse gas emissions in Chad and Saudi Arabia could have an effect on the environment of the United States" and that U.S.-funded projects could therefore be subject to U.S. regulations, assistant city attorney Sue Ellen Harrison said.LiNeBrEaKUnder the terms of the settlement, which still needs a judge's approval, the Overseas Private Investment Corp. agrees to subject all "Category A" projects -- those that would result in the emission of more than 100,000 tons of carbon dioxide -- to federal regulations; report the greenhouse gas emissions of those projects; reduce the greenhouse gas emissions of Category A projects by 20 percent over the next decade; and spend millions annually on renewable-energy projects.LiNeBrEaKThe Export-Import Bank's officials would take similar steps to start addressing the impact of greenhouse gases, and to find ways to reduce them in bank-funded projects, according to the city.		SETTLEMENT and COMPROMISE (91%); CITY GOVERNMENT (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); SUITS and CLAIMS (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); BANKING and FINANCE (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); LITIGATION (89%); EXPORT TRADE (89%); MAYORS (78%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); JUDGES (78%); DECISIONS and RULINGS (78%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (77%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (77%); CITIES (77%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (77%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (75%); LAWYERS (74%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (73%); NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS (78%); LAW COURTS and TRIBUNALS (72%); OIL and GAS EXPLORATION (70%); EXPORT IMPORT BANKING (67%); OIL EXPLORATION (51%)  	OVERSEAS PRIVATE INVESTMENT CORP (70%)  	FRIENDS OF THE EARTH (55%); OVERSEAS PRIVATE INVESTMENT CORP (55%)  		COLORADO, USA (94%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%); SAUDI ARABIA (79%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Daily Camera   	Ryan Morgan, Daily Camera, Boulder, Colo.  			Environment/Recycling/Waste  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	2009