The Dallas Morning News (Texas)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	EDITORIAL: Clean coal a good goal for this session  	COMMENTARY  	398 words  	Jan. 21--Coal became a consuming controversy during the 2007 legislative session. The specter of 16 coal-fired power plants spewing pollutants spawned a slew of bills and had opponents lining up at the Capitol. LiNeBrEaKTwo years later, coal is back and ready for battle.LiNeBrEaKBut this time, lawmakers are touting a cleaner, greener version of the fossil fuel. An assortment of legislators is backing a promising bill that would give tax breaks to companies building clean-coal plants that capture greenhouse gases. Even former Dallas Mayor Laura Miller, the pied piper of coal opponents, stands foursquare behind this proposal.LiNeBrEaKOthers who were on opposite sides two years ago also have found common ground, agreeing that constructing gasification power plants is an important opportunity for Texas.LiNeBrEaKUnlike traditional coal facilities, integrated gasification combined cycle power plants capture and store most of their carbon dioxide emissions. The state, which emits more carbon than most countries, has a chance to be an early adopter and to show that coal done right can be part of the clean-energy mix.LiNeBrEaKBut unless legislators sign off on tax breaks and other incentives, utilities will be hesitant to take on the risks associated with a new technology. Gasification remains relatively untested in the United States and is significantly more expensive than old-fashioned, pollution-intensive plants.LiNeBrEaKMore worrisome should be those traditional coal plants; it's a question of when -- not if -- Congress will regulate greenhouse gases. So, Texas, the carbon king, must begin to consider a new approach to energy.LiNeBrEaKThus far, Austin has balked at making tough decisions to further restrict pollution. More should be done to strengthen environmental regulations and spur renewable energy production.LiNeBrEaKBut it's encouraging that incentives for clean energy have begun to get traction. Lawmakers should pass this gasification legislation, recognizing that it is just one piece of Texas' energy puzzle.		COAL FIRED PLANTS (92%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (91%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (91%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); POWER PLANTS (90%); EMISSIONS (90%); COAL GASIFICATION (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); COAL INDUSTRY (90%); LEGISLATORS (90%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (78%); POWER COGENERATION (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (78%); LEGISLATION (77%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (77%); TAXES and TAXATION (76%); TAX INCENTIVES (71%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (63%)  			AUSTIN, TX, USA (79%); DALLAS, TX, USA (76%) TEXAS, USA (93%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Dallas Morning News   	The Dallas Morning News  			Crime/law  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-DA-EDITORIAL-Clean-coal-a-good-goal-for-this-session-0121  	DA  									
