cal activist in Juarez who is trying to start a new political party, said Obama faces a "titanic" job as a new world leader.LiNeBrEaK"He ought to eliminate war as a policy tool, deal with global warming, and also address the world's food crisis and environmental problems," she said, "as well as work toward generating an international synergy, which will lead to more equal standards of living for everyone."LiNeBrEaKDaniel Rocha, a Juarez labor activist who worked in the maquiladora industry for 20 years, said he believes the direction of the U.S. government will change under Obama.LiNeBrEaK"He has sought a closer relationship with Latinos, and that is great," Rocha said. "We are looking for a U.S.-Mexico relationship that will produce benefits for employees of the maquiladoras, braceros and other workers, and for Mexico and Latin America in general."LiNeBrEaKDiana Washington Valdez may be reached at dvaldez@elpasotimes.com; 546-6140.		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); POLITICS (90%); TALKS and MEETINGS (78%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); POLITICAL PARTIES (78%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (77%); TRADE TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (75%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (75%); US POLITICAL PARTIES (73%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (72%); NATIONAL SECURITY (71%); IMMIGRATION (71%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (69%); HISPANIC AMERICANS (68%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (60%); 2008 GLOBAL FOOD CRISIS (60%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); ECONOMIC CRISIS (65%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  		US DEPARTMENT OF HOMELAND SECURITY (57%)  	BARACK OBAMA (95%); JANET NAPOLITANO (57%); FELIPE CALDERON (55%)  	TEXAS, USA (94%); ARIZONA, USA (79%) MEXICO (99%); UNITED STATES (95%); NORTH AMERICA (94%); LATIN AMERICA (79%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 El Paso Times (El Paso, TX)   	Diana Washington Valdez, El Paso Times, Texas  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-EY-Juarez-leaders-feel-optimistic-about-Obama-0121  	EY  									
