The Idaho Statesman (Boise)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	EDITORIAL: Obama reaches out to supporters, skeptics: OUR VIEW OBAMA'S INAUGURATION  	COMMENTARY  	594 words  	Jan. 21--In 19 minutes Tuesday morning, President Obama spoke candidly about our challenges, spoke forcefully to our foes, and spoke stirringly to our ideals.LiNeBrEaKAmerica's new president demonstrated the focus demanded by the times. It was an auspicious beginning -- one designed to inspire supporters and to include skeptics in the hard work ahead.LiNeBrEaKAddressing America for the first time as president, Obama spoke with the moving oratory that marked his campaign, and also with startling bluntness. LiNeBrEaKAmerica faces a crisis, said Obama, not once but twice. Our nation is at war. Our health care system is broken, our schools need repair. Our economy is "badly weakened," our national confidence flagging.LiNeBrEaKYet Obama managed to artfully balance the harsh reality against the promise of a better future. "(Our challenges) will not be met easily or in a short span of time. But know this, America -- they will be met."LiNeBrEaKObama's critics from an exhausting two-year campaign -- those who suggested the Illinois Democrat would be soft on defense or lavish with public spending -- can also find some common ground with the new president.LiNeBrEaKHe vowed to restore America's position of global leadership: "To those who cling to power through corruption and deceit and the silencing of dissent, know that you are on the wrong side of history, but that we will extend a hand if you are willing to unclench your fist."LiNeBrEaKHe also reframed the debate over the role of government to a proper focus on outcomes and accountability: "The question we ask today is not whether our government is too big or too small, but whether it works."LiNeBrEaKObviously, Americans will disagree over the details of a government that works. Obama gently touched on the debates to come. He made a general case for a far-reaching -- and expensive -- public works and economic stimulus plan that has drawn early, bipartisan skepticism from the Idaho congressional delegation. He spoke of confronting "the specter of a warming planet" and advocated tighter market regulations. To his credit, Obama expressed no desire for ideological social battles that consume valuable focus and precious political capital.LiNeBrEaKAnd Obama spoke eloquently about the need to work together. After a campaign predicated on change, Obama urged Americans to embrace time-honored values and a renewed sense of responsibility. "This is the price and the promise of citizenship."LiNeBrEaKToday, that promise seems brighter. Our pride, as Americans, feels more profound.LiNeBrEaKThis of course reflects the nature of Obama's election as the nation's first black president. In a time when the description "historic" is tossed about like word candy, the term applies today.LiNeBrEaKObama didn't skirt history, talking about a nation that has tasted "the bitter swill of civil war and discrimination," and emerged stronger. Obama also made us look unflinchingly at the challenges we now face together -- signaling leadership that is both disciplined and inspiring.LiNeBrEaK"Our View" is the editorial position of the Idaho Statesman. It is an unsigned opinion expressing the consensus of the Statesman's editorial board. To comment on an editorial, e-mail editorial@idahostatesman.com		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (78%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (73%); LEGISLATORS (72%); GLOBAL WARMING (65%); US PRESIDENTS (92%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	IDAHO, USA (79%); ILLINOIS, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (98%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Idaho Statesman   	The Idaho Statesman, Boise  			Arts  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-ID-EDITORIAL-Obama-reaches-out-to-supporters-skeptics-0121  	ID  									
Inland Valley Daily Bulletin (Ontario, CA) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Pomona`s Cal Spas creates new line of products  	BUSINESS  	416 words  	The nation's economic downturn has chiseled away at the profits of many manufacturing firms while others have been forced to close their doors.LiNeBrEaKBut some companies, including Cal Spas in Pomona, have taken pro-active steps to adapt to a changing climate in which many consumers no longer have as much money to spend. LiNeBrEaKCal Spas is producing a new Genesis line of spas using a "geoforming" process. This allows the shell and cabinet to be molded from a single sheet of acrylic, an alternative to the more traditional roto-molded hot tubs that are usually made with polyethylene, a plastic used in the manufacture of items like garbage cans and milk bottles.LiNeBrEaKThe geoforming method produces a product with a smooth exterior that is highly durable. More importantly, it lowers the production cost and allows Cal Spas to sell the units for much less than traditional spas.LiNeBrEaK"All of our spas are built with the same quality but this creates a lower price point," said Shiva Noble, Cal Spas' executive vice president. "The average price for a spa is $7,999, but these will go for $2,999 to $3,499. They still give you hydrotherapy and warm water therapy, but they are much more affordable to purchase."LiNeBrEaKNoble said consumers who typically buy hot tubs have not been as adversely affected by the economic downturn because most of them are middle to upper middle-class buyers and above.LiNeBrEaK"The economy has really not affected them so much, but at the same time they are being a little more conservative and they're not letting go of their dollars as easily as before," she said. "They want to pay a lower price for the same product."LiNeBrEaKRichard Giss, a retail analyst with Deloitte and Touche, said businesses across the spectrum are rethinking marketing strategies and in many cases are revamping their product lines to keep consumers coming back.LiNeBrEaK"You don't need to look any further than the auto industry, which has suffered 20, 30 and 40percent decreases in sales," he said. "And the housing market has suffered a big downturn in sales."LiNeBrEaKMany Americans who couldn't keep pace with their rising mortgage payments lost their homes to foreclosure, impacting sales of such items as furniture, appliances, carpeting, paint, wood and a variety of other products.LiNeBrEaKCal Spas was founded in 1979. The company has evolved to become the world's No. 1 manufacturer of home resort products, including hydrotherapy hot tubs, swim spas, gazebos, indoor/outdoor saunas, barbecue islands/carts/drop-in grills, outdoor fireplaces and fire pits.		MANUFACTURING SECTOR PERFORMANCE (90%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (89%); MANUFACTURING OUTPUT (89%); ECONOMIC NEWS (89%); HOUSING MARKET (78%); SALES FIGURES (78%); INDUSTRY ANALYSTS (73%); CLIMATE CHANGE (72%); RESIDENTIAL PROPERTY (69%); NEW PRODUCTS (67%); MARKETING STRATEGY (67%); PRODUCT MANAGEMENT (67%); FORECLOSURE (60%)  	DELOITTE TOUCHE TOHMATSU (65%)  			UNITED STATES (79%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 MediaNews Group, Inc. All Rights Reserved  	By Kevin Smith, Staff Writer  			NAICS541211 OFFICES OF CERTIFIED PUBLIC ACCOUNTANTS (65%); SIC8721 ACCOUNTING, AUDITING, and BOOKKEEPING SERVICES (65%)  												
Khaleej Times (Dubai, United Arab Emirates)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Coastal Areas Management Vital  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	696 words  	Jan. 21--ABU DHABI -- Better management of coastal areas was the key message sent by the Minister of Environment and Water, Dr. Rashid Ahmed bin Fahad, during his welcome speech at the Environment 2009 conference on Tuesday.LiNeBrEaKThe event is being held alongside the World Future Energy Summit, which opened in the capital on Monday. LiNeBrEaK"Around 40 per cent of the population lives in coastal areas, so there are much more activities happening on the coast than inland, which creates challenges, puts a lot of pressure and, eventually, affects the environment," stressed the minister.LiNeBrEaKAccording to him, much of the pressures come from urban development, but at the same time, UAE is on the verge of creating concrete plans for combating climate change and other environmental crises.LiNeBrEaK"Climate change is world's priority. It is our priority, too. At the federal level we are now working closely with Masdar initiative for promoting and using more renewable sources of energy," Dr. Fahad told Khaleej Times.LiNeBrEaKHe added that another environmental priority for UAE is water. "We are looking for ways to reduce the water consumption per capita, while creating more sustainable water plants," said Dr. Fahad.LiNeBrEaKSince the two-day  conference concentrates on the issues of sustainable management for coastal zones, Dr. Habib El Harb, director and regional representative of United Nations Environmental Programme (UNEP), warned against some of the most devastating consequences that climate change could have on seaside inhabitants. "As a result of development, we are using and often misusing the coastal zones, which have undergone great physical change," said Dr. Harb.LiNeBrEaK"We don't know what impact those changes will have on the coast yet, nor do we know how these coastal zones will respond to the rise in sea levels due to climate change," stressed Dr. Harb, adding that UNEP is now working on these issues. Environmental scientists have warned time and time again that the now inevitable melting of the glaciers will lead to worldwide rise in sea levels of up to four metres in 30 years' time, creating catastrophic coastal deterioration and flooding.LiNeBrEaKMohammed Raouf, programme manager at Gulf Research Centre, used even tougher tone to warn of the devastating impact urban development has on coastal areas.LiNeBrEaK"The Gulf region is now facing new environmental challenges related to urban development and population growth, which include water scarcity, pollution and waste management," said Raouf. "The GCC coast, which stretches over 15,000 kilometres, is very rich, but urban and tourism projects create too much stress, resulting in degradation of the coast," he pointed out, adding that more protected areas are needed.LiNeBrEaK"The critical problem that we are facing now is that economy comes first and environmental protection comes second. Some developers have the habit of destroying an area, then doing some kind of compensation. We don't want compensation. Do your environmental study and public consultation first, then go ahead with the plan, if it's okay. If it will harm the environment, move your project somewhere else," urged Raouf.LiNeBrEaKHe also expressed concerned for the waste of valuable water resources, especially in the UAE, where up to 80 per cent of the annual water consumption is dedicated to agriculture, mostly greening projects, which are no longer sustainable. "This was not a problem 10-15 years ago, but nowadays urban development and population growth changed the situation, so we need to conserve water and shift consumption towards more urgent and important policies such as food," explained Raouf.LiNeBrEaKToday, it will be the turn of business and industry leaders to explain their solutions for an eco-friendly coastal development.LiNeBrEaKsilvia@khaleejtimes.com		COASTAL AREAS (91%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (90%); TALKS and MEETINGS (90%); SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); CITIES (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (88%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (78%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (78%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (77%); POPULATION GROWTH (76%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (75%); ENVIRONMENTAL ACCIDENTS and DISASTERS (74%); WASTE MANAGEMENT and REMEDIATION SERVICES (73%); RESEARCH (69%); TOURISM DEVELOPMENT (69%); UNITED NATIONS INSTITUTIONS (65%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (62%); WATER QUALITY (51%)  		UNITED NATIONS ENVIRONMENT PROGRAMME (54%)  		ABU DHABI, UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (91%) DUBAI, UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (92%) UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (95%); GULF STATES (78%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Silvia Radan, Khaleej Times, Dubai, United Arab Emirates  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-KJ-Coastal-Areas-Management-Vital-0121  	KJ  									
