 already visible here. Hurricanes that hit Oman twice are something that I never thought I would see in this region. Also, the rise in temperatures in the last 2-3 years is another wary and yet no studies have been done on this issue so far," El Harb stated.LiNeBrEaKWorldwide, UNEP has been working at mobilising and re-focusing the global economy towards investments in clean technologies and natural infrastructure such as forests and soils, which will not only combat climate change, but it will also create real growth and trigger an employment boom in the 21st century, as new "green" jobs are expected to be created.LiNeBrEaKA concrete plan for fighting climate change will be discussed during an environmental conference that will take place in Denmark towards the end of 2009.LiNeBrEaK"This major international conference, which will have the participation of UAE, will conclude with an agreement signed by all participant countries on how to combat climate change," revealed El Harb.LiNeBrEaKsilvia@khaleejtimes.com		ISLANDS and REEFS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); INTERVIEWS (90%); EMERGING MARKETS (89%); ECONOMIC GROWTH (89%); ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (78%); JOB CREATION (78%); CITIES (78%); EMISSIONS (77%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (77%); COASTAL AREAS (75%); CONSUMPTION (73%); UNITED NATIONS INSTITUTIONS (72%); HURRICANES (71%); GLOBALIZATION (60%)  		UNITED NATIONS ENVIRONMENT PROGRAMME (58%)  		ABU DHABI, UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (92%) DUBAI, UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (92%) UNITED ARAB EMIRATES (97%); GULF STATES (88%); MIDDLE EAST (79%); OMAN (79%); NORTH AFRICA (79%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Silvia Radan, Khaleej Times, Dubai, United Arab Emirates  			Disasters  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-KJ-In-30-Years-We-ll-See-Many-Cities-Under-Water-Warns-Expert-0121  	KJ  									
The Oregonian  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Portland, Ore., Metro's wish list ranks desired transportation projects  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	1036 words  	Jan. 21--Motorists stuck in the molasses merger of Interstates 5 and 205, or crawling across the I-5 bridge at quitting time, no doubt have their own lists of transportation projects the federal government ought to help pay for. The same goes for people trying to bike, bus or MAX to work, the mall or school.LiNeBrEaKMetro has come up with its own version of what needs to be done, though it's more than a list of gripes. LiNeBrEaKMetro and its partner cities and counties are hoping the federal government will help pay for millions of dollars' worth of transportation improvements during the next six years. Here's a sampling of the 78 projects listed by local officials and the requested federal funding amount:LiNeBrEaK--Columbia River Crossing, a new I-5 bridge: $1. 15 billion for engineering, design, right-of-way acquisition and constructionLiNeBrEaK--Sellwood Bridge: $100 million for constructionLiNeBrEaK--TriMet: $92. 4 million for new busesLiNeBrEaK--I-5 at I-205 interchange: $14. 4 million for constructionLiNeBrEaK--Portland-to-Milwaukie light rail: $850 million for final design and constructionLiNeBrEaK--Gresham Civic Neighborhood: $5 million for a transit center parking structureLiNeBrEaK--Drive Less-Save More: $4. 5 million for a Metro marketing programLiNeBrEaK--French Prairie Bridge: $12. 6 million for a bicycle, pedestrian and emergency bridge over the Willamette River at WilsonvilleLiNeBrEaKThe regional government, in a priority list officials will vote on Thursday, is asking for federal money for more than six dozen projects, ranging from the Columbia River Crossing to new TriMet buses. Also included are a new Sellwood Bridge, a parking structure at a Gresham transit center, a Columbia River dredging project, multiple bike trails, and fixes for snarled traffic at the juncture of I-205 and I-5, Tualatin-Sherwood Road and many other spots.LiNeBrEaKNothing guarantees Congress will fund projects on the list when it appropriates 2010 transportation money and authorizes the six-year federal transportation bill later this year.LiNeBrEaKBut Metro and its partners are using the funding process to not only push local projects but also to influence federal transportation priorities. The Portland region now judges transportation improvements as involving much more than how quickly we commute from Point A to Point B, and its leaders believe the rest of the country ought to do the same.LiNeBrEaKTo that end, each project on the local list -- beyond the gripe factor -- is associated with a value, issue or concept, ranging from the economic importance of "metropolitan mobility" to the greenhouse gas reduction targets associated with climate change.LiNeBrEaKMetro Councilor Rex Burkholder said the projects list will be presented to Oregon's congressional delegation as a "list of outcomes" the region wants to accomplish with money appropriated under what used to be called the federal highway bill.LiNeBrEaK"This is what we want to achieve with this investment," he said.LiNeBrEaKIt is an ambitious statement and part of a continuing regional movement to link land-use and transportation policies. Development, the thinking goes, shouldn't happen in a way that requires major new transportation networks. That's led to Metro policies favoring transit-oriented development, compact urban centers and density goals. Officials often talk about the need for transportation options, especially ones that don't strain resources.LiNeBrEaKThe project list describes the "radically different path" with which the Portland area accommodates growth and trumpets a remark by Minnesota Rep. James Oberstar, who said the region is the "template for America."LiNeBrEaKThe remark is significant because Oberstar, a Democrat, is chairman of the House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee and has called for passing the biggest transportation investment package since the federal highway system was created in the 1950s. Local officials count another funding friend in Rep. Peter DeFazio, an Oregon 4th District Democrat who is chairman of the House Highways and Transit Subcommittee. Meanwhile, Democratic Rep. Earl Blumenauer of Portland is on the House Ways and Means Committee, which decides how things get paid for.LiNeBrEaKWith the Obama administration saying infrastructure repair and investment are crucial and with a congressional delegation in position to pull strings, Portland-area officials are optimistic that federal money may be available to help pay for dozens of road, rail, trail and bridge projects.LiNeBrEaKThe list of projects was endorsed last week by Metro's Joint Policy Advisory Committee on Transportation, made up of officials representing cities, counties, Metro and key state departments.LiNeBrEaKA report accompanying the list describes the Portland area's regional strategy as an example to the rest of the nation. Since the 1970s, the metro area has chosen to stop sprawl by enforcing a tight urban growth boundary, canceled the Mount Hood freeway in favor of a light-rail train system and aligned its land-use plans to support urban centers, according to the report.LiNeBrEaKIt cites the recession, energy costs, deteriorating infrastructure, climate change and increased global economic competition as elements that call for a similar approach at the federal level.LiNeBrEaKTo that end, local transportation projects are bunched under factors that contribute to a livable community. Among them are metropolitan mobility, freight movement, system maintenance and help with "mega projects" such as the Columbia River Crossing. In addition, projects throughout the region must be held accountable to meeting greenhouse gas reduction targets.LiNeBrEaKBurkholder, who was chairman of the Metro advisory committee, said he is optimistic about influencing a "major shift" nationally in how regional transportation and land-use policies are examined, linked and funded.LiNeBrEaK"We're one of the few regions that sits down, has this discussion and comes up with a regional agenda," he said.		CONSTRUCTION (90%); VEHICLE TRAFFIC (89%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (77%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (77%); APPROPRIATIONS (77%); LEGISLATORS (77%); LAND USE PLANNING (74%); ENGINEERING (73%); TRANSPORTATION REGULATION (72%); CYCLING (72%); MOTORCOACHES and BUSES (72%); EASEMENTS and RIGHTS OF WAY (68%); CLIMATE CHANGE (61%)  				PORTLAND, OR, USA (94%) OREGON, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Oregonian   	Eric Mortenson, The Oregonian, Portland, Ore.  			Automobiles/Highways  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-PO-TRANSPORTATION-PROJECTS-20090121  	PO  									
The Oregonian (Portland, Oregon) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   Sunrise Edition	Metro list ranks desired transportation projects  	Local News  	894 words  	SUMMARY: Outcome-based   | Each project for road, rail and rivers is associated with a value, issue or conceptLiNeBrEaKMetro's wish list for feds ranks desired transportation projects Each project for road, rail and rivers is associated with a value, issue or concept Metro list ranks desired transportation projects Land use andLiNeBrEaKmobility go LiNeBrEaKhand in handLiNeBrEaKERIC MORTENSONLiNeBrEaKMotorists stuck in the molasses merger of Interstates 5 and 205, or crawling across the I-5 bridge at quitting time, no doubt have their own lists of transportation projects the federal government ought to help pay for. The same goes for people trying to bike, bus or MAX to work, the mall or school.LiNeBrEaKMetro has come up with its own version of what needs to be done, though it's more than a list of gripes.LiNeBrEaKThe regional government, in a priority list officials will vote on Thursday, is asking for federal money for more than six dozen projects, ranging from the Columbia River Crossing to new TriMet buses. Also included are a new Sellwood Bridge, a parking structure at a Gresham transit center, a Columbia River dredging project, multiple bike trails, and fixes for snarled traffic at the juncture of I-205 and I-5, Tualatin-Sherwood Road and many other spots.LiNeBrEaKNothing guarantees Congress will fund projects on the list when it appropriates 2010 transportation money and authorizes the six-year federal transportation bill later this year.LiNeBrEaKBut Metro and its partners are using the funding process to not only push local projects but also to influence federal transportation priorities. The Portland region now judges transportation improvements as involving much more than how quickly we commute from Point A to Point B, and its leaders believe the rest of the country ought to do the same.LiNeBrEaKTo that end, each project on the local list --beyond the gripe factor --is associated with a value, issue or concept, ranging from the economic importance of "metropolitan mobility" to the greenhouse gas reduction targets associated with climate change.LiNeBrEaKMetro Councilor Rex Burkholder said the projects list will be presented to Oregon's congressional delegation as a "list of outcomes" the region wants to accomplish with money appropriated under what used to be called the federal highway bill.LiNeBrEaK"This is what we want to achieve with this investment," he said.LiNeBrEaKIt is an ambitious statement and part of a continuing regional movement to link land-use and transportation policies. Development, the thinking goes, shouldn't happen in a way that requires major new transportation networks. That's led to Metro policies favoring transit-oriented development, compact urban centers and density goals. Officials often talk about the need for transportation options, especially ones that don't strain resources.LiNeBrEaKThe project list describes the "radically different path" with which the Portland area accommodates growth and trumpets a remark by Minnesota Rep. James Oberstar, who said the region is the "template for America."LiNeBrEaKThe remark is significant because Oberstar, a Democrat, is chairman of the House Transportation and Infrastructure Committee and has called for passing the biggest transportation investment package since the federal highway system was created in the 1950s. Local officials count another funding friend in Rep. Peter DeFazio, an Oregon 4th District Democrat who is chairman of the House Highways and Transit Subcommittee. Meanwhile, Democratic Rep. Earl Blumenauer of Portland is on the House Ways and Means Committee, which decides how things get paid for.LiNeBrEaKWith the Obama administration saying infrastructure repair and investment are crucial and with a congressional delegation in position to pull strings, Portland-area officials are optimistic that federal money may be available to help pay for dozens of road, rail, trail and bridge projects.LiNeBrEaKThe list of projects was endorsed last week by Metro's Joint Policy Advisory Committee on Transportation, made up of officials representing cities, counties, Metro and key state departments.LiNeBrEaKA report accompanying the list describes the Portland area's regional strategy as an example to the rest of the nation. Since the 1970s, the metro area has chosen to stop sprawl by enforcing a tight urban growth boundary, canceled the Mount Hood freeway in favor of a light-rail train system and aligned its land-use plans to support urban centers, according to the report.LiNeBrEaKIt cites the recession, energy costs, deteriorating infrastructure, climate change and increased global economic competition as elements that call for a similar approach at the federal level.LiNeBrEaKTo that end, local transportation projects are bunched under factors that contribute to a livable community. Among them are metropolitan mobility, freight movement, system maintenance and help with "mega projects" such as the Columbia River Crossing. In addition, projects throughout the region must be held accountable to meeting greenhouse gas reduction targets.LiNeBrEaKBurkholder, who was chairman of the Metro advisory committee, said he is optimistic about influencing a "major shift" nationally in how regional transportation and land-use policies are examined, linked and funded.LiNeBrEaK"We're one of the few regions that sits down, has this discussion and comes up with a regional agenda," he said.LiNeBrEaKEric Mortenson; 503-294-7636; ericmortenson@news.oregonian.comLiNeBrEaKFor environment news, go to: oregonlive.com/environment		APPROPRIATIONS (89%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); CITY LIFE (78%); TRANSPORTATION REGULATION (78%); HIGHWAY FUNDING (78%); LEGISLATORS (78%); LAND USE PLANNING (77%); VEHICLE TRAFFIC (76%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (75%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (75%); PUBLI