Palm Beach Post (Florida) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL EDITION	OBAMA SETS THE BAR HIGH FOR HIMSELF AND THE NATION  	OPINION; Pg. 8A  	1032 words  	Barack Obama told supporters how his 10-year-old daughter, Malia, summed up the expectations for Tuesday's inaugural address: "First African-American president; better be good." The speech was very good. Now, Mr. Obama has to match his presidency to his words.LiNeBrEaKAs a candidate, Mr. Obama talked of change. As president, he did the same -- with a twist. Change, he said, depends on a return to old ideals: sacrifice, duty, responsibility. Directly and indirectly, echoing Washington, Lincoln and Roosevelt at other times of crisis in earlier centuries, Mr. Obama explained how he wants to change American policy here and abroad. But he cautioned that the change to restore our economy and our standing in the world won't happen unless it rises from Main Street, Wall Street and Capitol Hill. LiNeBrEaK"Our challenges may be new," Mr. Obama said. "The instruments with which we meet them may be new. But those values upon which our success depends -- hard work and honesty, courage and fair play, tolerance and curiosity, loyalty and patriotism -- those things are old. These things are true. They have been the quiet force of progress throughout our history."LiNeBrEaKStill, President Obama made clear that when it comes to change, he will set the example, starting here. After eight years of the country investing in the Iraq war and tax cuts for the wealthy and winding up with an intensive-care economy, Mr. Obama wants to "build the roads and bridges, the electric grids and digital lines that feed our commerce and bind us together."LiNeBrEaKThat is change.LiNeBrEaKMore pointedly, Mr. Obama vowed to "restore science to its rightful place." Former President Bush politicized science in everything from abstinence-only sex education to global warming. Former Vice President Dick Cheney drew up energy policy based on what the country's largest polluters wanted. In contrast, the new president stated that "... each day brings further evidence that the ways we use energy strengthen our adversaries and threaten our planet." In the Obama administration, "We will harness the sun and the winds and the soil to fuel our cars and run our factories."LiNeBrEaKThat is change.LiNeBrEaKIn the larger sense, Mr. Obama's election marks the final, overdue end of the anti-government era that began when Ronald Reagan proclaimed in 1981 that "government is not the solution to the problem; government is the problem." His election caused an overreaction to the New Deal and Great Society that drained Washington and the Congress of people who understood government and filled the capital with lawmakers who denigrated government. Here, again, Mr. Obama staked out the sensible middle ground: "...the stale political arguments that have consumed us for so long no longer apply. The question we ask today is not whether our government is too big or too small, but whether it works."LiNeBrEaKThat is change.LiNeBrEaKSimilarly, President Obama noted that while the country is not about to jettison the free market, it cannot tolerate the financial deregulation market that has helped to cause the economic crisis: "Nor is the question before us whether the market is a force for good or ill. Its power to generate wealth and expand freedom is unmatched, but this crisis has reminded us that without a watchful eye, the market can spin out of control -- and that a nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous."LiNeBrEaKThat is change.LiNeBrEaKMoving to national security, Mr. Obama sounded much like George Bush when he told the world that the United States "will not apologize for our way of life, nor will we waver in its defense. And for those who seek to advance their aims by inducing terror and slaughtering innocents, we say to you that our spirit is stronger and cannot be broken. You cannot outlast us, and we will defeat you." That, correctly, is not change.LiNeBrEaKPresident Obama departed from Mr. Bush, though, when he said, "As for our common defense, we reject as false the choice between our safety and our ideals ... Those ideals still light the world, and we will not give them up for expedience's sake ... know that America is a friend of each nation and every man, woman and child who seeks a future of peace and dignity, and that we are ready to lead once more."LiNeBrEaKThat is change.LiNeBrEaKAs stated, though, America cannot lead the world if we are divided within. Mr. Obama's toughest task will be to end the Mafia politics that began during the Clinton administration with the battle over impeachment and continued into the Bush administration with the disputed election of 2000 and the invasion of Iraq in 2003.LiNeBrEaKBut Washington got sidetracked over the past decade by more than the big stuff. While Democrats and Republicans argued over social issues, the economy ran off the rails. So it matters that Mr. Obama referred to America as "a nation of Christians and Muslims, Jews and Hindus -- and nonbelievers." It matters that he called for "an end to the petty grievances and false promises, the recriminations and worn-out dogmas that for far too long have strangled our politics."LiNeBrEaKThat would be change.LiNeBrEaKTuesday was a wonderful day for America. Merely by taking the oath that was fumbled by Chief Justice John Roberts, Barack Hussein Obama made this country look good to the world. The Rev. Joseph Lowery, who founded the Southern Christian Leadership Conference with the Rev. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr., brought home the moment with an eloquent benediction. The Obamas were dreams come true for record crowds.LiNeBrEaKMeanwhile, though, the banking news got worse, and the markets dropped sharply again. Today, history gives way to urgent work. President taking office at the most critical time in more than 50 years; better be good.LiNeBrEaKExcerpts from the inaugural addressLiNeBrEaK'Our time of standing pat, of protecting narrow interests and putting off unpleasant actions -- that time has surely passed.'LiNeBrEaK'A nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous.'LiNeBrEaK'The question we ask today is not whether our government is too big or too small, but whether it works.'LiNeBrEaK'As for our common defense, we reject the choice between our safety and our ideals.'LiNeBrEaK'To those leaders around the globe who seek to sow conflict ... know that your people will judge you on what you can build, not what you destroy.'		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (78%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (74%); PUBLIC POLICY (74%); LEGISLATORS (74%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); TAXES and TAXATION (71%); TAX LAW (64%); SEX EDUCATION (62%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE H W BUSH (53%); DICK CHENEY (53%); RONALD REAGAN (51%)  	EARTH (77%) UNITED STATES (94%); IRAQ (79%)  	March 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	LiNeBrEaKPHOTO (BandW)  RON EDMONDS/The Associated Press  	EDITORIAL  	Newspaper  	2009 The Palm Beach Newspapers, Inc. All Rights Reserved  																
Palm Beach Post (Florida) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL EDITION	VEGGIE FARMS BRACE FOR DIP  	LOCAL and BUSINESS; Pg. 1B  	624 words  	At Palm City Palms and Tropicals Tuesday afternoon, Rick and Susan Frostrom and their eight employees were powering up a contraption that looks like a helicopter, runs on a 454 cubic inch Chevy engine, and keeps the wind rushing over plants to prevent frost from settling.LiNeBrEaK"If you are standing 100 feet from it, it will take your hat off," Rick Frostrom said. LiNeBrEaKWith temperatures forecast to reach the low 30s in the Treasure Coast and in western Palm Beach County, Florida agricultural producers were preparing for a two-night chill, with Thursday morning expected to be the coldest.LiNeBrEaKHardier crops like citrus are expected to come through largely unharmed, but ornamental plants such as ferns and tender vegetables such as green beans are at risk.LiNeBrEaK"We are mostly worried about the beans that we are harvesting and the young sweet corn," said Rick Roth, president of Roth Farms east of Belle Glade.LiNeBrEaKPalm Beach County, a major source of the nation's winter vegetables, has an estimated 40,000 acres of vegetables planted, including bell peppers, tomatoes, celery, Chinese vegetables, radishes, and lettuces. This regional "salad bowl" is valued at more than $200 million a year, according to the U.S. Department of Agriculture.LiNeBrEaKCorn and green bean growers in the Glades can't do much to protect their crops, beyond raising water levels in canals to warm the air.LiNeBrEaK"Most of the big farms have pumped the water in to raise the water table higher; that is the first line of defense," said David Sui, an agent with the Palm Beach County cooperative extension service.LiNeBrEaKWhile Glades vegetable farmers sometimes hire helicopters to fly above their crops and push the warm air down, Tuesday night winds were expected to keep blowing throughout the night.LiNeBrEaKAs for tonight, "I think tomorrow night we will see some upper 20-degree temperatures in the colder areas," said John S. Hundley, vice president of Hundley Farms, east of Belle Glade. Lake Okeechobee's water level is higher, which will bring a warming effect in certain areas, he said. "We will see how we fare. We are expecting some losses. We have losses every year."LiNeBrEaKCitrus growers aren't worried about the cold. It typically takes temperatures of 28 degrees or lower for four to five hours to damage a citrus tree. "The lowest temperature forecast in the Indian River district is 31," said Doug Bournique, executive vice president of the Indian River Citrus League. "This is not going to be a killer freeze for citrus at all."LiNeBrEaKIn fact, if the chill kills psyllids, which spread citrus greening disease, "It could end up being semi-beneficial," Bournique said.LiNeBrEaKTemperatures are still forecast to be the coldest this year, although they won't come close to the freeze of Jan. 19-20 of 1977. Exactly 32 years ago this week, Palm Beach County was shocked with a low of 27 degrees and a dusting of snowflakes.LiNeBrEaKHundley says this cold snap is more like the Christmas Eve freeze of 1989.LiNeBrEaK"I remember all of them," he said. "When you get hammered, you remember those dates."LiNeBrEaK~susan_salisbury@pbpost.comLiNeBrEaKCold snapLiNeBrEaKCold weather shelters opened overnight Tuesday, and officials plan to open them tonight as the frigid weather lingers:LiNeBrEaKPalm Beach County:LiNeBrEaKCapacity 75 each. Both open 6 p.m. to 9 a.m. Call '211' or (866) 882-2991.LiNeBrEaKSalvation Army Center of Hope, 1577 N. Military Trail, West Palm Beach.LiNeBrEaKWest County Senior Center, 2916 State Road 15, Belle Glade.LiNeBrEaKMartin CountyLiNeBrEaKOpen 7 p.m. to 6 a.m.LiNeBrEaKCall (772) 287-2002LiNeBrEaKRed Cross Headquarters, 2750 S. Kanner Highway. Capacity 40.LiNeBrEaKFamily Worship Center, 15285 S.W. Indian Mound Drive, Indiantown. Capacity 75.LiNeBrEaKSt. Lucie CountyLiNeBrEaKCapacity 45-50.LiNeBrEaKOpen 7 p.m. to 7 a.m.LiNeBrEaKCall (772) 461-5201.LiNeBrEaKFort Pierce Community Center, 600 N. Indian River Drive.LiNeBrEaKNo illegal drugs, alcoholic beverages, weapons or pets.		VEGETABLE and MELON FARMING (90%); MISC VEGETABLE FARMING (90%); FARMERS and RANCHERS (89%); GLOBAL WARMING (76%); COASTAL AREAS (76%); AGRICULTURE (75%); CITRUS GROVES (75%); AGRICULTURAL COMMODITY REGULATION (75%); CANALS and WATERWAYS (70%); LAKES (70%); AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENTS (70%)  		US DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE (55%)  	MICHAEL I ROTH (70%)  	FLORIDA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (79%)  	March 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	LiNeBrEaKPHOTO (C) and MAP (C)  1. Photo by SARAH GRILE With some chilly weather on the way, Juan Hernandez, who works at Palm City Palms and Tropicals, covers some palm trees on Tuesday. 2. BRENNAN KING/Staff Artist MAP 		Newspaper  	2009 The Palm Beach Newspapers, Inc. All Rights Reserved  	By SUSAN SALISBURY Palm Beach Post Staff Writer  							Info. box at end of text.   								
