Philadelphia Inquirer (Pennsylvania)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Words to inspire and unite, not divide  	COMMENTARY  	738 words  	Finally, after a campaign that claimed two years of national attention, after a transition that seemed almost as long, Barack Obama was sworn in as the 44th, and the first African American, president of the United States.LiNeBrEaKOn a clear January morning drenched in sunlight, it was possible to be overwhelmed by the panoply of ceremony and symbols, by the jubilant gathering of citizens, and the massive weight of history.LiNeBrEaKPresident Obama delivered an inaugural address in his customary measured calm that, in part, belied the sheer fierceness of his language in a striking rebuke of President Bush's policies. LiNeBrEaKIt took but four paragraphs for the new president to begin methodically yet insistently hammering away at the legacy of the man sitting several feet away at the Capitol. "Our economy is badly weakened, a consequence of greed and irresponsibility on the part of some, but also our collective failure to make hard choices and prepare the nation for a new age," Obama intoned.LiNeBrEaKHe called for "an end to the petty grievances and false promises, the recriminations and worn-out dogmas, that for far too long have strangled our policies."LiNeBrEaKTime and again, with deliberate purpose, Obama refuted the practices of the last eight years. "A nation cannot prosper long when it favors only the prosperous," he said.LiNeBrEaKOf course, now even the prosperous are less so.LiNeBrEaKHe follows a president who questioned human contribution to global warming and continued, even in his waning weeks, to champion business interests over the environment. Instead, Obama said, "We will restore science to its rightful place."LiNeBrEaKHe spoke of making America more self-reliant: "Each day brings further evidence that the ways we use energy strengthen our adversaries and threaten our planet." For the Department of Energy, where Bush first installed as secretary a former legislator who once wanted the department abolished, and followed that with a chemical executive, Obama tapped Nobel physicist Steven Chu.LiNeBrEaK"The question we ask today is not whether our government is too large or too small, but whether it works," Obama said.LiNeBrEaK"As our common defense, we reject as false the choice between our safety and our ideals," he said.LiNeBrEaKIndirectly, Obama condemned the use of torture, honoring "the rule of law and the rights of man" and that "we will not give them up for expedience's sake." Instead, the president noted "that power alone cannot protect us, nor does it entitle us to do as we please."LiNeBrEaKEven in a democracy, a president stands alone. So it's telling that one of the most commonly used words in Obama's speech was the inclusive we, uttered 62 times. Wisely, Obama was restrained in his use of the campaign mantra hope, giving it only three mentions should it risk becoming a hollow platitude.LiNeBrEaKThe president's sole reference to race _ the word mentioned once in 20 minutes _ and his lineage arrived in the final moments of his speech.LiNeBrEaK"This is the meaning of our liberty and our creed_why men and women and children of every race and every faith can join in celebration across this magnificent mall," he said, "and why a man whose father less than 60 years ago might not have been served at a local restaurant can now stand before you to take a most sacred oath."LiNeBrEaKIf the address failed to astonish _ as did his historic "A More Perfect Union" speech on race in Philadelphia _ perhaps it's because the nation has become accustomed to a man who was an accomplished writer before he became a legislator, and whose impressive oratorical skills have become an accepted part of our political landscape.LiNeBrEaKThe pageantry and assembled crowd created the electricity. It was left to the rest of us to be overwhelmed by the moment while Obama, once again, exhibited his notable restraint and resolve.LiNeBrEaKABOUT THE WRITERLiNeBrEaKKaren Heller is a columnist for Philadelphia Inquirer. Readers may write to her at the Philadelphia Inquirer, P.O. Box 8263, Philadelphia, Pa. 19101, or send e-mail to kheller@phillynews.comLiNeBrEaKVisit Philadelphia Online, the Inquirer's World Wide Web site, at http://www.philly.com		OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (77%); AWARDS and PRIZES (76%); LEGISLATORS (75%); GLOBAL WARMING (64%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (63%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE W BUSH (71%); STEVEN CHU (52%)  	PENNSYLVANIA, USA (79%); EARTH (74%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO of Karen Heller available from the ``Columnist Mugs'' section of MCT Direct.		Newspaper  	2009 Philadelphia Inquirer   	By Karen Heller, The Philadelphia Inquirer  				Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090121-BC-HELLER-COLUMN  	PH  									
Plain Dealer (Cleveland) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   Final Edition; All Editions	Attempting to harness the energy of the stars Fusion reactor's plasma to be hotter than sun  	NATIONAL; Pg. A1  	1207 words  	Provence, France - In June 1889, six months after he had slashed off his earlobe in a maniacal frenzy, Vincent van Gogh sat in his tiny sanitarium room and painted what became his most famous work.LiNeBrEaK"The Starry Night" depicts the landscape the troubled impressionist saw from his asylum window. Its swirling indigo sky is filled with luminous stars, orbs so large and close to the ground they almost seem to scrape the church steeple of the village of Saint-R&eacute;my-de-Provence.LiNeBrEaKPerhaps van Gogh saw the future. More than a century later, on a Provence hillside barely 50 miles from where the artist produced his masterpiece, scientists are building a giant machine to bring the stars to Earth.LiNeBrEaKLike van Gogh's visionary canvas, the International Thermonuclear Experimental Reactor, or ITER, blends creativity, boldness and a dash of lunacy. LiNeBrEaKThe $7 billion fusion device, arguably the most complex gadget humans have ever tried to construct, will attempt to re-create - in a controlled way - the violent process that powers the stars. It may be the best hope to break the world's oil dependence and restrict climate-change damage.LiNeBrEaKHarnessing fusion's immense energy has been science's long elusive obsession. Researchers have tried for 50 years to bottle the sun. Although the technology has vastly improved, none of the several dozen test facilities around the world has kept the fusion reaction going for more than a couple of seconds, and none has made more energy than it has consumed.LiNeBrEaKITER's designers aim to change that. By leveraging the expertise and bankrolls of the project's seven partners - a sometimes prickly alliance of the United States, the European Union, Russia, China, India, South Korea and Japan - the ITER organization intends to construct a fusion reactor much bigger and more advanced than its predecessors.LiNeBrEaK21st century research in old-world settingLiNeBrEaKWithin site of a medieval French chateau, workers are clearing land and raising buildings where hundreds of ITER researchers will work. They're reinforcing bridges to accommodate the heavy reactor components that will be trucked in from the Mediterranean port.LiNeBrEaKThe fusion machine is so complicated it will take a decade to build, and engineers must overcome profound technical challenges. ITER's ultracold magnets, only a whisper above absolute zero, will have to corral a super-hot plasma that's more than 10 times the temperature of the sun's core - making the hilltop facility simultaneously the hottest and coldest place in the universe.LiNeBrEaKITER will help scientists determine whether sustained fusion is achievable, or too difficult for current human knowledge. "This is a go [or] no-go proof, from my point of view," said physicist Norbert Holtkamp, the project's principal deputy director-general.LiNeBrEaKBut even if the experimental reactor works, that will not yet prove fusion is a reliable, economical power source. That will require a commercial-scale demonstration plant, envisioned for no earlier than 2040.LiNeBrEaKWhile fusion may sound like a lengthy, expensive gamble, proponents say its possible payoffs - virtually unlimited power, readily available fuel, no greenhouse-gas emissions and relatively manageable radioactive waste - make it worth the chase.LiNeBrEaK"Fusion is one of very few options for large-scale, environmentally responsible power generation," said ITER governing council chair Chris Llewellyn-Smith.LiNeBrEaKScientists reach for the starsLiNeBrEaKThe key to tapping a star's power is finding a way to replicate what happens in its hellishly hot, dense core. There, extreme conditions create a fourth state of matter called a plasma, whose energy is far higher than solids, liquids or gases.LiNeBrEaKPinging around in this chaotic atomic stew are positively charged hydrogen nuclei (hydrogen, the lightest element, is the main component of stars) and negatively charged electrons that have gained enough energy to rip free from their orbits around the hydrogen nuclei.LiNeBrEaKUsually, particles with the same electric charge repel each other like the feuding housemates on TV's "The Bad Girls Club." But hydrogen nuclei in the stellar plasma collide so hard they overcome resistance and fuse, releasing energy that keeps the reaction going.LiNeBrEaKBy 1952, government scientists had mastered fusion's rudiments well enough to turn it into a weapon - the hydrogen bomb.LiNeBrEaKBut sustaining and controlling the fusion reaction has proved maddeningly difficult. At its heart: How do you contain a plasma so energetic it threatens to rip itself apart, and so hot it melts anything?LiNeBrEaKStars, which don't have to worry about melting, use their huge mass to squeeze the plasma's components and keep fusion going.LiNeBrEaKSuch gravitational confinement isn't possible on Earth. But scientists came up with another approach, one that takes advantage of the plasma's own properties. Its charged particles - the hydrogen nuclei and electrons - can be wrangled by a magnetic field.LiNeBrEaKTo make the plasma, scientists heat up the reactor's fuel, a gas composed of the hydrogen isotopes deuterium and tritium.LiNeBrEaKSurrounding the plasma with powerful magnets in the right configuration traps it, like a balloon caught between two facing electric fans. The magnetic bottle keeps the multimillion-degree plasma away from the reactor vessel's walls to prevent melting.LiNeBrEaKThe doughnut-shaped bottle, called a tokamak, retains the highly energetic, positively charged helium atoms produced by the fusion reaction, keeping the plasma hot enough to "burn" without a lot of outside energy. (At the ITER reactor, the maximum 17-minute fusion burn is expected to use about 50 megawatts of electricity to heat the plasma, while producing 500 megawatts of energy.)LiNeBrEaKThe other fusion product - streams of neutrons with no charge - sail unhindered through the magnetic bottle and strike a swath of metal "blankets," which capture their energy. If ITER were a real power plant, the superheated blankets would flash water to steam to turn a turbine and make electricity.LiNeBrEaKThat's the principle, at least. Researchers have spent decades wrestling with fusion's technical problems. Among them: The edges of the turbulent plasma blob tend to bulge against the containment walls, which can cause damage as well as stifle the reaction.LiNeBrEaKThe most successful tokamak to date, Britain's JET facility, has sustained fusion for only about two seconds at a time, and its power output is only 16 megawatts - about 1 percent the capacity of a commercial nuclear reactor.LiNeBrEaK"We've made tremendous progress in the last 30 years, and we realize there's still a significant distance to go," said Massachusetts Institute of Technology physicist Earl Marmar, who runs the university's experimental fusion reactor. "I think there's no question fusion will be a viable energy source. The time scale - that's a tricky question."LiNeBrEaKThe joke among fusion's critics is that, for the last 50 years, commercial fusion has always remained 30 years in the future. Fusion researchers contend that's been a result of inadequate funding.LiNeBrEaK"After ITER, that excuse is gone," Holtkamp said. "Either there is a big step and this thing works and it's clear there is a path to magnetic fusion or . . . it's pretty clear that fusion based on tokamaks is over."LiNeBrEaKTo reach this Plain Dealer reporter: jmangels@plaind.com, 216-999-4842		NUCLEAR ENERGY (90%); ART and ARTISTS (77%); ARTISTS and PERFORMERS (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (74%)  				PROVENCE-ALPES-COTE D'AZUR, FRANCE (92%) FRANCE (92%); MEDITERRANEAN (79%); UNITED STATES (79%); SOUTH KOREA (79%); JAPAN (75%); EUROPE (73%); INDIA (73%); E