San Jose Mercury News (California)  	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Pelosi: '10-ton anvil lifted' when Bush departed  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	545 words  	Jan. 21--WASHINGTON -- Watching George W. Bush leave the presidency and take off on his helicopter "was like having a 10-ton anvil lifted from my shoulders," House Speaker Nancy Pelosi said Wednesday, describing her emotions and thoughts on Inauguration Day.LiNeBrEaKShe was just a few feet away from Barack Obama when he took the oath of office, and Pelosi said she "thought about his mother, and how she raised him and shaped this extraordinary young man." LiNeBrEaKIn a wide-ranging interview with Bay Area reporters, the San Francisco Democrat said the Obama administration "will be great for California," especially on the environment and the economy.LiNeBrEaKObama "has an entrepreneurial way of thinking, a fresh way of thinking, a commitment to the environment, a push for green jobs and reversing global warming, and that will help California," she said.LiNeBrEaK"Continually frustrated" by Bush on many issues, Pelosi said the change in administrations "will be like night and day" for the state and nation.LiNeBrEaKOn a related issue, Pelosi said she supports Rep. Henry Waxman, the Los Angeles Democrat and new chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee, who wants his panel to approve a climate change bill with limits on carbon emissions by the end of May.LiNeBrEaK"Our plan is to pass it (in the House) this year, though I don't know what the Senate will do," the speaker said.LiNeBrEaKShe expressed a need to move urgently on economic issues, including the $825 billion recoveryLiNeBrEaKpackage, to take advantage of President Obama's high approval ratings.LiNeBrEaKThe new administration and Congress also need to improve oversight of the banking system and markets, she said: "We need more cops on the street. There has been a lack of discipline, supervision and regulation."LiNeBrEaK"The American people want to give the new president a chance," Pelosi said. But Congress has been "a world of incrementalism. And if you want to change the world, much of it has to go through Congress."LiNeBrEaKDuring the transfer of power Tuesday, Pelosi said she watched Bush when Obama pledged a new foreign policy and a clean break from the last eight years.LiNeBrEaK"That must have been a painful part" for Bush, she said. When asked if she felt at all sorry for Bush, she demurred: "I feel sorry for the people hurt by his policies."LiNeBrEaKPelosi also praised Rep. Zoe Lofgren, a San Jose Democrat, whom she named as the new chairman of the Ethics Committee, a sensitive post that calls for decisions on whether to investigate one's colleagues.LiNeBrEaK"Zoe is so talented, she knows the law, is very fair-minded and commands respect on both sides of the aisle," Pelosi said. That appointment also means Lofgren will meet with other House chairs on high-level policy decisions.LiNeBrEaK"She will have a seat at the table, and the world will know more about her extraordinary talents," the speaker said.LiNeBrEaKContact Frank Davies at fdavies@mercurynews.com or (202) 662-8921.		US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (90%); APPOINTMENTS (88%); EXECUTIVE MOVES (88%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); EMISSIONS (74%); CLIMATE CHANGE (74%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (72%); ETHICS (72%); TALKS and MEETINGS (71%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (69%); ENTREPRENEURSHIP (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); APPROVALS (66%); BANKING and FINANCE (63%); FOREIGN POLICY (60%); INVESTIGATIONS (60%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE W BUSH (94%); NANCY PELOSI (93%); HENRY WAXMAN (55%); ZOE LOFGREN (51%)  	SAN FRANCISCO, CA, USA (79%); SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (79%); SAN JOSE, CA, USA (79%); LOS ANGELES, CA, USA (79%) CALIFORNIA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 22, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News   	Frank Davies, San Jose Mercury News, Calif.  			Faith  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090121-SJ-Pelo