The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL Edition	A great American moment  	Op-Ed; EDITORIALS; Pg. B6  	571 words  	The 44th president of the United States honored our history as he made history Tuesday. He struck just the right tone for these perilous times.LiNeBrEaKPresident Obama reminded America that change - and great challenges - have defined this nation. The inauguration of the first African American president celebrated the cherished but sometimes elusive American ideal that "all men are created equal." His references to his place in history were spare, understated and poignant. LiNeBrEaK"This is the meaning of our liberty and our creed - why men and women and children of every race and every faith can join in celebration across this magnificent mall, and why a man whose father less than 60 years ago might not have been served at a local restaurant can now stand before you to take a most sacred oath," he said.LiNeBrEaKObama is not the first president to suggest "our patchwork heritage is a strength, not a weakness." But no inauguration has drawn an audience as large and as diverse, or a president who, at long last, embodied the realization of the inclusive meritocracy he espoused. LiNeBrEaK"We are shaped by every language and culture, drawn from every end of this Earth; and because we have tasted the bitter swill of civil war and segregation, and emerged from that dark chapter stronger and more united, we cannot help but believe that the old hatreds shall someday pass; that the lines of tribe shall soon dissolve; that as the world grows smaller, our common humanity shall reveal itself; and that America must play its role in ushering in a new era of peace," he said.LiNeBrEaKWithin the soaring themes of unity was a promising blueprint for some of the ways his administration will change direction from Bush policies. He suggested that the power of free markets to "generate wealth and expand freedom" must be tempered with the "watchful eye" of government. Obama, a constitutional lawyer, said he rejected "as false the choice between our safety and our ideals" - an apparent reference to the use of torture and the civil liberties rollbacks during the Bush era. He spoke of leaving Iraq "to its people" and taking on the challenge of global warming. He promised an ambitious effort to revitalize the economy.LiNeBrEaKThough inaugural addresses often avoid mention of contemporary problems, once again, Obama's decision to discuss the problems we face was fitting. Even as he spoke, the difficult circumstances that Obama was chosen to address were bubbling beneath the surface. LiNeBrEaKOn the heels of fresh worries about bank stability, Wall Street welcomed the new president with a record Inauguration Day tumble. The Dow Jones industrial average lost just over 4 percent; the Standard and Poors 500 Index dropped by more than 5 percent. In the Senate, Sen. John Cornyn, R-Texas, temporarily blocked Hillary Rodham Clinton's confirmation as secretary of state, which suggests that Obama will not find partisanship easy to overcome. And in the Middle East, Obama's first international challenge flared as Hamas leaders stood atop the shattered landscape of Gaza and claimed that they had won a victory over the Israeli army, simply because they had survived.LiNeBrEaKFew presidents in modern history will encounter the magnitude of problems, domestic and international, that confront President Obama. His speech was sober about the challenges and powerful in its expression of resolve to meet them. He will need every ounce of the remarkable goodwill that was on display Tuesday. 		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); US PRESIDENTS (93%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); STOCK INDEXES (85%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (73%); RELIGION (70%); LANGUAGE and LANGUAGES (51%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%) OP-ED; EDITORIAL; INAUGURATION; PRESIDENT  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); JOHN CORNYN (50%); HILLARY ROD