The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL Edition	The nation's capital feels the warmth  	Op-Ed; PERSONAL PERSPECTIVE; Pg. B6  	545 words  	Inaugurations can be misleading stuff, a political fiesta filled with promises, fresh energy and defeats untasted. The glittering swearing-ins come with fanfare, snapping flags on the gleaming-white Capitol and 21-gun salutes. LiNeBrEaK Then the hard grind of Washington reality takes over as Congress cuts a new president down to size and the mistakes pile up. The January honeymoon ends fast. LiNeBrEaK President Obama seems to sense this, even if his adoring army doesn't quite yet. For weeks, and especially the last few days, Washington has become an occupied city, filled with Obamaites who've driven, bused and flown thousands of miles for the big moment that came at 12: 10 p.m.LiNeBrEaKOver the weekend, a row of police cars with flickering blue and red lights brought an instant crowd to the curb. Is he about to drive by? One small neighborhood eatery - Ben's Chili Bowl - has a 50-foot line from early morning to past midnight, all because Obama grabbed a quick lunch there. Who knows, he might return, and that's why a satellite TV truck and police car are stationed outside. LiNeBrEaKThe real proof was the enormous turnout for the swearing in. The crowd filled the 2-mile Mall from the Capitol to the Lincoln Memorial. Crowd estimates are notoriously hard to pin down, but the first-blush number is put at more than 1 million. And it was January, and nearly everyone had to be there by 8 a.m. for any hope of claiming a doormat-sized standing spot.LiNeBrEaKWith the headliners so distant and tiny to most of the crowd, the action was followed by watching dozens of billboard-sized TVs. Each backstage glimpse of Obama or his family waiting to take their places brought huge roars that echoed through the open acres filled with his supporters. Who were these cheering hand-clappers? Women in thick minks, schoolchildren in matching jackets and stocking caps, and families who'd driven in overnight from North Carolina or Pennsylvania, nearly all of them with Obama buttons trailing down shirt fronts. It was multiracial, peaceful and friendly, and it brought Washington to a halt.LiNeBrEaKIn White House terms, this onslaught should be converted into something politics here hasn't seen in years, presidential political capital. But with so many problems - two wars, a recession, and feckless solutions to all of it - this advantage may quickly dwindle to pocket change. LiNeBrEaKHence Obama's mix of caution and confidence in his inauguration speech. He underlined the generational and racial turning points that his candidacy represents. He went after the Bush record that ignored science, played down global warming and undercut civil liberties in the name of fighting terrorism. Hard, plain talk on the issues that won him the top job.LiNeBrEaKBut then he came up with a new slogan, a "new era of responsibility." By that he appeared to mean that even the best solutions such as negotiated pullout in Iraq or a return to financial stability aren't enough. His grassroots listeners need to back up Washington with their own personal rescue packages built on thrift, charity and hard work. LiNeBrEaKIt may sound like a dodge to turn the country's problems back on its citizens. But the notion could capture the masses - his backers with Hope buttons and Yes We Can T-shirts - who are wondering where their leader is taking them tomorrow. 		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); POLITICS (78%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (77%); MOTOR VEHICLES (74%); FAMILY (73%); RESTAURANTS (68%); TELEVISION EQUIPMENT (66%); SATELLITE TELEVISION (66%); CHILDREN (61%); GLOBAL WARMING (60%); OUTDOOR ADVERTISING (51%); TERRORISM (50%); US PRESIDENTS (90%) OP-ED; INAUGURATION; PRESIDENT  			BARACK OBAMA (95%) Barack Obama  	NORTH CAROLINA, USA (79%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspape