ue, even in a state where many of his GOP colleagues believe global warming is a hoax.LiNeBrEaKInstead of having employees working eight hours a day, five days a week, Huntsman ordered about 17,000 of the state's 24,000 executive branch employees to begin working four days a week, 10 hours a day.LiNeBrEaKInitially, Huntsman's staff set a target of closing 1,000 of the state's 6,000 buildings on Fridays. College campuses, court houses, liquor stores, veterans hospitals and emergency services remain open on Fridays.LiNeBrEaKHowever, the state has only been able to close 900 buildings and some government offices such as the Utah National Guard had been closing on Fridays before the switch was made this summer. Of those 900 buildings, the state is leasing about 500 of them, reducing the ability to save on energy costs, said John Harrington, state buildings energy manager.LiNeBrEaKHarrington said state officials are been able to identify about 100 buildings where the opportunity for cost savings is significant. However, initial reviews show that about half of those buildings are reducing energy consumption by less than 10 percent, he said.LiNeBrEaK"It's a challenge. It's a work in progress," he said.		US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); WORK WEEK (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (89%); LEGISLATORS (89%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (89%); GOVERNORS (78%); OIL and GAS PRICES (77%); CONSUMPTION (77%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (77%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); POLITICAL PARTIES (66%); VETERANS HOSPITALS (50%); VETERANS HEALTH CARE (50%); BEER WINE and LIQUOR STORES (50%)  				UTAH, USA (96%) UNITED STATES (96%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Salt Lake Tribune All Rights Reserved  	By Brock Vergakis The Associated Press  															
