ople cross there every day, and they can get seriously injured. I know it's rare but it can happen, and the car on Monday that almost ran me over was only stopped about 2 feet away.LiNeBrEaKLoic CiampossinLiNeBrEaKLittering is a serious issueLiNeBrEaKI am going to tell you what I think needs improvement. That would be that people litter too much. For instance, someone could start a car accident when they throw something out the window. It is not safe for the environment either when someone throws trash on the ground when they could just throw it away in the garbage can. If you're thinking, "Well, we are trying to stop it, but people don't follow the rules," here is what you can do to help:LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaKEnforce the $1,000 fine because if you enforce it may work a little. LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaKInstead of just making them pay the fine, have them pick up trash on the highway. LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaKWhen someone does litter there is not a police in sight so they think its OK. So you should try to have police looking for that a little better or at least in more places. LiNeBrEaKPlease take this letter into consideration because I know a lot of people do care about this.LiNeBrEaKSarah Palermo		ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); ENDANGERED SPECIES (78%); MARINE MAMMALS (78%); MAMMALS (78%); GLOBAL WARMING (72%); TRAFFIC ACCIDENTS (70%)  				EARTH (94%) ICELAND (79%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News All Rights Reserved  	The following letters were written to the Los Gatos Weekly-Times by Rolling Hills Middle School sixth-graders as a classroom project assigned by their teacher, Dorrie Scamporrino:  															
San Jose Mercury News (California) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Pelosi: '10-ton anvil lifted' when Bush departed  	BREAKING; Politics; News; National; State; Local  	472 words  	WASHINGTON   Watching George W. Bush leave the presidency and take off on his helicopter "was like having a 10-ton anvil lifted from my shoulders," House Speaker Nancy Pelosi said Wednesday, describing her emotions and thoughts on Inauguration Day. LiNeBrEaKShe was just a few feet away from Barack Obama when he took the oath of office, and Pelosi said she "thought about his mother, and how she raised him and shaped this extraordinary young man."LiNeBrEaKIn a wide-ranging interview with Bay Area reporters, the San Francisco Democrat said the Obama administration "will be great for California," especially on the environment and the economy.LiNeBrEaKObama "has an entrepreneurial way of thinking, a fresh way of thinking, a commitment to the environment, a push for green jobs and reversing global warming, and that will help California," she said.LiNeBrEaK"Continually frustrated" by Bush on many issues, Pelosi said the change in administrations "will be like night and day" for the state and nation.LiNeBrEaKOn a related issue, Pelosi said she supports Rep. Henry Waxman, the Los Angeles Democrat and new chairman of the Energy and Commerce Committee, who wants his panel to approve a climate change bill with limits on carbon emissions by the end of May.LiNeBrEaK"Our plan is to pass it (in the House) this year, though I don't know what the Senate will do," the speaker said.LiNeBrEaKShe expressed a need to move urgently on economic issues, including the $825 billion recovery package, to take advantage of President Obama's high approval ratings.LiNeBrEaKThe new administration and Congress also need to improve oversight of the banking system and markets, she said: "We need more cops on the street. There has been a lack of discipline, supervision and regulation."LiNeBrEaK"The American people want to give the new president a chance," Pelosi said. But Congress has been "a world of incrementalism. And if you want to change the world, much of it has to go through Congress."LiNeBrEaKDuring the transfer of power Tuesday, Pelosi said, she watched Bush when Obama pledged a new foreign policy and a clean break from the last eight years.LiNeBrEaK"That must have been a painful part" for Bush, she said. When asked if she felt at all sorry for Bush, she demurred: "I feel sorry for the people hurt by his policies."LiNeBrEaKPelosi also praised Rep. Zoe Lofgren, a San Jose Democrat, whom she named as the new chair of the Ethics Committee, a sensitive post that calls for decisions on whether to investigate one's colleagues.LiNeBrEaK"Zoe is so talented, she knows the law, is very fair-minded and commands respect on both sides of the aisle," Pelosi said. That appointment also means Lofgren will meet with other House chairs on high-level policy decisions.LiNeBrEaK"She will have a seat at the table, and the world will know more about her extraordinary talents," the speaker said.LiNeBrEaKContact Frank Davies at fdavies@mercurynews.com or (202) 662-8921. 		US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (90%); APPOINTMENTS (88%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (75%); EMISSIONS (74%); CLIMATE CHANGE (74%); ETHICS (73%); EXECUTIVE MOVES (73%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (72%); TALKS and MEETINGS (71%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (69%); ENTREPRENEURSHIP (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); APPROVALS (66%); BANKING and FINANCE (63%); FOREIGN POLICY (60%); INVESTIGATIONS (60%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); NANCY PELOSI (94%); GEORGE W BUSH (94%); HENRY WAXMAN (55%); ZOE LOFGREN (51%)  	LOS ANGELES, CA, USA (79%); SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (79%); SAN JOSE, CA, USA (79%); SAN FRANCISCO, CA, USA (79%) CALIFORNIA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 24, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News All Rights Reserved  	By Frank Davies Mercury News Washington Bureau  															
San Jose Mercury News (California) 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday 	Opinion: Saving the economy and the planet, one furnace at a time  	NEWS; Opinion  	636 words  	Like most Americans, I'm guarding my dollars, but when my furnace died during Seattle's coldest winter in decades, I needed to replace it. And when I did, with a high-efficiency Trane model made in Trenton, N.J., the costs and gains underscored key lessons about what we need to do to craft a stimulus package that actually builds for America's future.LiNeBrEaKMy new furnace saves energy and fights climate change. It promotes American jobs, and pays back its costs in a reasonable time frame. It points toward how to genuinely renew America's economy instead of encouraging the same consumption for consumption's sake that has helped create our current problems. LiNeBrEaKLet's look at what my $5,000 purchased. It supported Trane's factory workers, the local installers and beleaguered local tax bases. It meant I'll save more than a third of my yearly gas bill and a commensurate amount of my carbon-dioxide emissions. My old furnace was a 13-year-old, 70 percent efficient model that was down to barely 60 percent because single-cycle furnaces lose 1 percent a year as their burners corrode and heat exchangers get less efficient. The new one is 97 percent efficient and its variable speed motor is designed to maintain far more efficiency. I live in a small, well-insulated house in a temperate climate, and keep my thermostat low, but have still been spending $850 a year on gas heat. Add in electric bill savings from the furnace's extra-efficient fan, and I'll save roughly $340 a year at current gas prices. If natural gas costs keep increasing at their recent rate, 61 percent in five years, my investment will pay back in roughly nine years   a yield approaching that promised by Bernie Madoff. I'll also prevent the release of roughly three tons of carbon-dioxide emissions every year.LiNeBrEaKSo how do we make similar choices affordable for everyone, whether or not they have the savings to do this on their own? Imagine if the pending stimulus package helped people make such investments nationwide, combining direct incentives with low- or no-interest loans. Imagine if it prioritized energy efficiency and investment in American-made renewables,LiNeBrEaKI'm not saying high-efficiency furnaces solve our every problem. Plugging building leaks, adding insulation and switching light bulbs give the maximum energy-efficiency yield even more efficiency for fewer dollars. We need solutions that move us toward eliminating fossil-fuel use altogether, like solar thermal, advanced geothermal and ultra-efficient green buildings, and smart electrical grids. The 300,000-person Swedish city of Malmo already gets 40 percent of its residential heat (and 60 percent of its electricity) from a municipal incinerator plant.LiNeBrEaKBut adding a high-efficiency furnace buys time   like scrapping a Hummer to drive a Ford Focus   and if the furnaces are American-made, recycles money through our domestic economy. If we could replace every inefficient furnace with a high-efficiency model, we'd come out far ahead.LiNeBrEaKEvery industry is hurting these days. But if we spend close to a trillion dollars to jump-start the economy without simultaneously addressing issues such as fossil-fuel dependence, we may not have the resources to do so later on. We can continue to support consumption for its own sake, and that's what we've been doing. But although $5,000 granite countertops look swell, they don't solve global warming, heal our trade deficits or move us toward a more sustainable society. By addressing our root problems, we'd actually be investing in the future instead of cannibalizing it. We might even look back on our present crisis as a national turning point   but we have to make the wise investments now.LiNeBrEaKPaul Rogat Loeb is the author of "The Impossible Will Take a Little While  and "Soul of a Citizen.  He wrote this article for the Mercury News.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (92%); OIL and GAS PRICES (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (89%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (89%); NATURAL GAS PRICES (77%); GREEN BUILDING (77%); UTILITY RATES (76%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (76%); CLIMATE CHANGE (76%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (76%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (76%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (76%); CLIMATOLOGY (71%); FACTORY WORKERS (68%); INTEREST RATES (63%); ECONOMIC NEWS (63%); SOLID WASTE TREATMENT and DISPOSAL (50%)  		RENEW AMERICA (57%)  	BERNARD MADOFF (53%)  	SEATTLE, WA, USA (92%); TRENTON, NJ, USA (90%) WASHINGTON, USA (92%); NEW JERSEY, USA (90%) UNITED STATES (96%); SWEDEN (79%)  	January 24, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News All Rights Reserved  	By Paul Rogat Loeb Special to the Mercury News  															
