ctories are beginning to change global climate.LiNeBrEaK"The skeptics apparently have one less leg to stand on," Bromwich said.LiNeBrEaKBut he doesn't agree completely with the new study. In a new analysis of his own, as yet unpublished, Bromwich also finds evidence of significant warming in West Antarctica. But it's not enough to cancel out the cooling in East Antarctica for a continentwide temperature increase.LiNeBrEaKThe cooling in East Antarctica started in the late 1970s, Steig said, coinciding with a seasonal hole in the ozone layer caused by aerosol chemicals.LiNeBrEaKLower ozone concentrations cause the atmosphere to cool, and the effects are most pronounced over East Antarctica.LiNeBrEaKTemperature gradients due to the cooling in turn strengthen westerly winds, which at least partly explain the rapid warming on the Antarctic Peninsula _ though the new study suggests that global warming or other factors may have overtaken the ozone hole in shaping Antarctic climate.LiNeBrEaKThe culprit chemicals were phased out years ago, and the ozone hole is expected to heal by the middle of the century.LiNeBrEaK"If that happens, all of Antarctica could begin warming on a par with the rest of the world," Steig said.		RESEARCH REPORTS (92%); RESEARCH (91%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (90%); SCIENCE NEWS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (89%); TRENDS (89%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (89%); WEATHER (89%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (78%); GLOBAL WARMING (78%); OZONE DEPLETION (71%); AIR POLLUTION (66%); COASTAL AREAS (66%)  		UNIVERSITY OF WASHINGTON (57%)  		SEATTLE, WA, USA (95%) WASHINGTON, USA (95%); EARTH (79%); OHIO, USA (79%); NORTH DAKOTA, USA (75%) ANTARCTICA (96%); UNITED STATES (95%); SOUTH AMERICA (88%); MEXICO (79%); NORTH AMERICA (79%)  	August 11, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Seattle Times   	By Sandi Doughton, The Seattle Times  	SEATTLE   			Distributed by 