THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER 	January 21, 2009 Wednesday  Correction Appended	GREGOIRE PUSHES CAP-AND-TRADE BILL\ EMISSIONS WOULD COME AT A COST  	NEWS; Pg. A19  	750 words  	Companies that emit high greenhouse gases may need to change their ways or pay for it.LiNeBrEaKA bill called the Climate Action Plan has been requested by Gov. Chris Gregoire that places a cap on companies' emissions.LiNeBrEaKThe process, known as cap and trade, is nothing new and the bill has yet to be introduced this legislative session. But having the governor's backing gives it a better chance of becoming reality than ever before.LiNeBrEaKThough details of the program - which wouldn't be implemented until 2011 - are complex, here's the gist of what cap and trade would do, said Jay Manning, director of the Department of Ecology: LiNeBrEaKA cap would be placed on the amount of carbon dioxide emissions that companies release, and companies would be required to buy permits in order to emit at the acceptable level. Companies also could auction off their permits between each other, creating their own market system.LiNeBrEaKFor example, if Company A can reduce its emissions more easily than Company B, Company A can auction off its permit - also known as an allowance - and Company B can buy that permit.LiNeBrEaKDifferent companies would have different costs and because permits would be auctioned, there is no concrete amount of how much a company would have to pay. Manning said that an initial design sets the minimum cost at $3 per ton of carbon dioxide and its equivalent gases, but the cost may be higher.LiNeBrEaKAnd what about companies that find it too hard to comply with the cap and can't find an allowance? Then they can buy an offset.LiNeBrEaKOffsets in this case would be forestland that companies can buy and plant trees on if they cannot find an allowance on the market. A company would calculate how much carbon dioxide could be reduced by the amount of trees it plants. That would make up for not being able to comply with the cap.LiNeBrEaKEvery three years, the cap will decrease.LiNeBrEaK"Typically, (companies) grow over time," Manning said. The idea is that companies will gradually reduce their reliance on fossil fuels and transition toward renewable energy alternatives as they expand and must decrease their carbon dioxide emissions, he said.LiNeBrEaKOne company that would be affected by this bill is Weyerhaeuser Co. "We support cap and trade," public affairs manager Anthony Chavez said. But he said Weyerhaeuser does not support the auction system that this program would create.LiNeBrEaKHe said the trading of allowances should be free, because all companies would have to work to reduce emissions, and companies that could not stay below the cap shouldn't be penalized by paying more.LiNeBrEaKHowever, Chavez said Weyerhaeuser does support offsets, since it could make money by selling its forestland to other companies.LiNeBrEaKBecky Kelley of the Washington Environmental Council and campaign director of the bill said that revenue generated from permit sales would be invested to create green jobs.LiNeBrEaKA criticism of a cap-and-trade system is that gas prices would increase and families with low to moderate income could be hurt by high energy bills.LiNeBrEaKBut Kelley said the revenue generated from cap and trade would be used to provide assistance for those families, in addition to green investment.LiNeBrEaKAnother criticism is that the nuances of the system are too complicated. Even Manning, an ardent supporter of the bill, said the creation of a new market system opens up room for manipulation that could potentially reach Enron-like proportions.LiNeBrEaK"We're hoping to create an oversight body that would watch over the market," Manning said. And with the state facing a $6 billion deficit, it is unlikely any kind of tax would fly high with lawmakers, anyway, he said.LiNeBrEaKIf passed, the program would not be implemented until 2011. Manning said if the cost of running the program would be too high, then the governor could suspend it.LiNeBrEaKCap and trade is no stranger to national politics, either. On June 2, the Lieberman-Warner Climate Security Act was introduced to the U.S. Senate, calling for a similar national program.LiNeBrEaKAfter four days of debate and filibuster tactics - including a reading of the 492-page bill in its entirety - it failed, having stood little chance of passing at a time when gas was $4 a gallon.LiNeBrEaKIf the bill is introduced in Olympia, Rep. Dave Upthegrove, D-Des Moines, will sponsor it. Upthegrove said it was critical that the state get a head start on investing in a greener economy. "It's as much an economic issue as an environmental one," he said. "Do we want to be in the front or at the end of that?"		EMISSIONS (91%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (90%); LEGISLATORS (78%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (78%); GOVERNORS (77%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (73%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (65%) STATE; ENVIRONMENT; POLLUTION  	WEYERHAEUSER CO (81%)  	A BETTER CHANCE (57%)  	CHRISTINE GREGOIRE (92%)  	SEATTLE, WA, USA (92%) WASHINGTON, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 28, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   	JUDY VUE P-I reporter  	OLYMPIA   	WY (NYSE) (81%)  	NAICS322130 PAPERBOARD MILLS (81%); NAICS322121 PAPER (EXCEPT NEWSPRINT) MILLS (81%); NAICS321211 HARDWOOD VENEER and PLYWOOD MANUFACTURING (81%); NAICS113310 LOGGING (81%)  					Wednesday, January 21, 2009  	Under the provisions of a proposed state program that would place a cap on companies' emissions, Weyerhaeuser Co. might be able to sell carbon credits from forest and forest products to other companies. Weyerhaeuser would not sell its forestlands to other companies. A story on Page A19 Wednesday incorrectly described what Weyerhaeuser might be able to do under the proposed program, known as "cap and trade."  						
