Bangkok Post (Thailand)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	Forests hold carbon credit opportunities  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	551 words  	Jan. 20--Forestry activities are emerging as opportunities for Thailand to tap into the fast growing international voluntary carbon credit market, which offers cheaper and faster project development than the regulated carbon credit market. LiNeBrEaKAfforestation, reforestation, revegetation, agricultural land management, improved forest management and reduced emission from deforestation (RED) projects could all sell carbon credits to the voluntary market, said the Thailand Greenhouse Gas Management Organisation (TGO), which co-hosted a carbon credit conference on Friday with Tisco Securities and carbon credit consultancy Emergent Venture India (EVI)LiNeBrEaKThe US-initiated voluntary market enables emission reduction projects to sell credits to buyers without commitments under the Kyoto Protocol. These buyers are countries or organisations that volunteer to cut emissions for corporate social responsibility (CSR) motives or to build a green image.LiNeBrEaKThe voluntary market grew 165 percent in volume to 65 million tonnes of CO2 equivalent (mtCO2e) in 2007 to reach a value of $331US million.LiNeBrEaKAs environmental awareness and CSR activities have soared in the private sector, the voluntary carbon market has risen dramatically, said Wannawut Apinanratanakul, Tisco's senior vice-president for investment banking group.LiNeBrEaKYet the regulated market remains far larger as buyers have mandatory targets under the Kyoto Protocol. The regulated market has been valued at $63. 6 billion with 2. 9 billion mtCO2e sold through Clean Development Mechanism (CDM) projects.LiNeBrEaKA Certified Emission Reduction (CER) sold in the regulated market is also priced much higher than a Verified Emission Reduction (VER) traded in the voluntary market (around 12 compared with 2).LiNeBrEaKBut TGO deputy executive director Prasertsuk Chamornmarn said project development costs in the voluntary market are also significantly lower -- at $25,000 compared with $65,000 for a small CDM project and $160,000 for a large-scale one.LiNeBrEaKEmergent Venture India added that issuing a VER is also faster, requiring only about five months compared with 16-20 months for a CER to win approval from the CDM project's host country and the United Nations.LiNeBrEaKSmall forestry projects in rural areas of Thailand are best suited to the voluntary market due to their low transaction costs and faster development times, said EVI country manager Jatin Kapor.LiNeBrEaKMr Wannawut said the voluntary carbon market's growth had outstripped projections, with trading estimated at 150 mtCO2e according to investment analysts New Carbon Finance.LiNeBrEaKWith expected continued growth in over-the-counter transactions, total transactions in the voluntary market are expected to hit 557 mtCO2e in 2012.LiNeBrEaKCarbon brokers in the voluntary market include Tisco, HSBC, Google, Yahoo and Microsoft. Buyers are mainly banks, retailers such as Unilever and non-profit organisations such as the World Wildlife Fund (WWF).		EMISSIONS (92%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (91%); FORESTS and WOODLANDS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); FORESTRY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); CARBON OFFSETS (90%); BANKING and FINANCE (89%); DEFORESTATION (78%); REFORESTATION (78%); FOREST RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (78%); BANKING and FINANCE REGULATION (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (77%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (77%); INVESTMENT BANKING (75%); CORPORATE SOCIAL RESPONSIBILITY (74%); CONSULTING SERVICES (72%); RURAL COMMUNITIES (72%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (72%); NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS (78%); RETAILERS (64%); APPROVALS (61%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (60%); UNITED NATIONS INSTITUTIONS (60%)  	MICROSOFT CORP (50%); UNILEVER PLC/NV (50%); GOOGLE INC (50%)  			BANGKOK, THAILAND (93%) THAILAND (95%); UNITED STATES (79%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLI