Florida Times-Union (Jacksonville) 	January 20, 2009 Tuesday  Correction Appended	We need to know effects of dredging river channel  	RONALD L. LITTLEPAGE; Pg. B-7  	422 words  	If it comes to jobs and money vs. the health of the St. Johns River, which would be the loser?LiNeBrEaKThat's a critical question to ask as the Jacksonville Port Authority pursues deepening the river's main channel to accommodate the bigger ships Jaxport hopes to bring here. LiNeBrEaKMuch of the recent debate on the river's health has focused on a proposal by the St. Johns River Water Management District to withdraw up to 262 million gallons of water a day from the river and its main tributary, the Ocklawaha, to supply water to Central Florida.LiNeBrEaKOpponents of the plan have argued that taking that much water could change the salinity levels farther upstream and harm the vegetation and fish and critters that live there.LiNeBrEaKAfter listening to the protests, the water management district began a three-year scientific study of the effects of the water withdrawal.LiNeBrEaKThe first phase was completed in December and an interim report was released last week (www.sjrmd.com/surfacewaterwithdrawals).LiNeBrEaKAs you might imagine, the report contains a lot of big words.LiNeBrEaKBut one thing is clear: The water withdrawal isn't the only concern.LiNeBrEaKThe first phase of the study looked at three other factors:LiNeBrEaK- The removal of wastewater now going into the river for reuse and the reduction of nutrients.LiNeBrEaK- The rise in sea level that's likely with climate change.LiNeBrEaK- And the port's plan to deepen the main channel from 40 feet to 45 feet.LiNeBrEaKAccording to the report's executive summary, "Results show that the proposed channel deepening scenarios ... cause the greatest increase in St. Johns River salinity."LiNeBrEaKAnd that's at 45 feet. It's likely Jaxport will want to go deeper to handle even larger ships.LiNeBrEaKThe district's study will now try to gauge the effects of salinity changes on the river's inhabitants. That phase of the study is scheduled to be completed in the fall of 2010.LiNeBrEaKTo deepen the channel, the Port Authority will have to get a dredging permit from the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers.LiNeBrEaKThe corps will take into consideration the environmental impact of the dredging.LiNeBrEaKBefore making a decision, it should wait until the results of this study are known.LiNeBrEaKObviously, the St. Johns River system is complex, and as we humans have proved many times, messing with nature can have devastating effects.LiNeBrEaKJust as obvious, the jobs that come with additional port activity are a big part of our economy.LiNeBrEaKBut just as the water withdrawal needs a thorough vetting so does doing additional dredging.LiNeBrEaKWe should know what we are getting into before and not after.LiNeBrEaKron.littlepage@jacksonville.com, (904) 359-4284		RIVERS (91%); HARBORS and PORTS (90%); WATER and WASTEWATER MANAGEMENT (90%); WATER RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (90%); MARINE and WATERWAY CONSTRUCTION (89%); PORT AUTHORITIES (89%); HARBOR and PORT OPERATIONS (89%); SEWERAGE SYSTEMS (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (74%); ENGINEERING (73%); WATER QUALITY (72%); SCIENCE NEWS (71%); CIVIL ENGINEERING (71%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (71%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (65%); ARMIES (65%); ENVIRONMENTAL PERMITS (65%); ENVIRONMENTAL RESEARCH (74%)  	ASK ASA (91%)  			JACKSONVILLE, FL, USA (92%) FLORIDA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 30, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Florida Times-Union   	RONALD L. LITTLEPAGE  								January 21, 2009  	The Web address for an interim report of the St. Johns River Water Management District's study on the effects of water withdrawal from the river is www.sjrwmd.com/surfacewaterwithdrawals. Because of a writer's error, the address was incorrect on Page B-7 Tuesday.  						
