arren a role in the inauguration sparked protests from the gay community and the National Organization for Women. At the Atlanta service, about 100 protesters gathered across the street.LiNeBrEaKFarris defended The King Center's choice of keynote speaker, saying Warren's stances on issues such as global warming, AIDS and poverty are in keeping with King's ideals.LiNeBrEaKKing preached at Ebenezer from 1960 until his death in 1968, and a service commemorating his birthday and life are held there annually. On Election Night, the mainly black audience there was moved to tears when news networks announced that Obama had won the presidential race.LiNeBrEaKKing would have been 80 on Jan. 15.LiNeBrEaKOnly one of King's three living children, Bernice, attended the Monday event. His sister, Christine King Farris, led the ceremony.LiNeBrEaKKing's son Martin Luther King III was in Washington already and his other son Dexter King -- who lives in California -- did not attend. Their sister, Yolanda, died in 2007.		CHRISTIANS and CHRISTIANITY (90%); CIVIL RIGHTS (90%); PROTESTANTS and PROTESTANTISM (90%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (89%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (89%); ELECTIONS (78%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); GAYS and LESBIANS (77%); HUMAN RIGHTS ORGANIZATIONS (77%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (76%); HOLIDAYS and OBSERVANCES (76%); CHILDREN (73%); WOMEN (72%); WILLS (64%); SAME SEX MARRIAGE and UNIONS (63%); MARRIAGE (63%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%) Event; Government  			BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	ATLANTA, GA, USA (93%) GEORGIA, USA (93%); CALIFORNIA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Grand Rapids Press All Rights Reserved  							grp  									
