d that such children don't have parents and could be out on the street.LiNeBrEaK"They need help. They need a real family," she said.LiNeBrEaK-- "I would ask him if he could try to get everybody out of the war in Iraq and try to stop global warming," said third-grader Cerena Cass.LiNeBrEaKCerena thought helping people hold onto their homes and have money for food was important, too. Perhaps lowering taxes would help them, she said.LiNeBrEaKBut the war is No. 1 on Cerena's priorities. That's because she had an uncle who served in Iraq.LiNeBrEaKHer uncle came home safe, but it would be hard for families to cope if their loved ones died in the war, she said.		PRIMARY SCHOOLS (90%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (77%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); CHILDREN (89%); AUTOMAKERS (87%); RACE and RACISM (77%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (77%); FAMILY (76%); HOUSING MARKET (72%); OIL and GAS PRICES (71%); CLOSINGS (71%); AUTOMOTIVE MFG (69%); DISMISSALS (64%); UTILITY VEHICLE MFG (64%); WAR and CONFLICT (62%); IRAQ WAR (60%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); US PRESIDENTS (78%); HOME PRICES (71%)  	LEAR CORP (66%); GENERAL MOTORS CORP (55%)  		BARACK OBAMA (95%); JOHN P JONES III (57%)  	DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (94%); WISCONSIN, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (97%); IRAQ (92%); MIDDLE EAST (79%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Janesville Gazette   	Frank Schultz, The Janesville Gazette, Wis.  		LEA (NYSE) (66%); GMP (PAR) (55%); GMB (BRU) (55%); GM (NYSE) (55%) NYSE:LEA, NYSE:GM  	NAICS336370 MOTOR VEHICLE METAL STAMPING (66%); NAICS336360 MOTOR VEHICLE SEATING and INTERIOR TRIM MANUFACTURING (66%); SIC3465 AUTOMOTIVE STAMPINGS (66%); SIC2531 PUBLIC BUILDING and RELATED FURNITURE (66%); NAICS336112 LIGHT TRUCK and UTILITY VEHICLE MANUFACTURING (55%); NAICS336111 AUTOMOBILE MANUFACTURING (55%) Social Issues  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090120-JG-Kids-offer-words-of-praise-advice-for-Obama-0120  	JG  									
Khaleej Times (Dubai, United Arab Emirates)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	Rise in Desert Visitors Prompts Sharjah Awareness Drive  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	950 words  	Jan. 20--SHARJAH -- The Environment and Protected Areas Authority (EPAA) in Sharjah will soon launch an environmentally-friendly camping initiative to raise awareness of the activity among outdoor enthusiasts, according to a top official.LiNeBrEaK"Every municipal council in the emirate is supposed to conduct its own environmental camp this year to enlighten camping enthusiasts about the rules and regulations to follow when camping. The activities to be run during these camps would include an exhibition on wildlife, an environmental play, along with traditional songs, games, meals and competitions," said EPAA Director Hana Al Suwidi. LiNeBrEaKVisits will be paid to bedouin localities, where brochures, plastic bags and waste bins would be distributed.LiNeBrEaKElaborating, Al Suwidi said camping enthusiasts would be told how to get permits from the bodies concerned prior to camping, and how to avoid fires, and collect and dump wastes at designated areas.LiNeBrEaKExcerpts of the interview:LiNeBrEaKGreen buildings regulations have been introduced both Abu Dhabi and Sharjah. Does the authority have any plans in this regard?LiNeBrEaKThe EPAA is more interested in sustainable development that goes in harmony with environment. The latest massive development projects have had very destructive impact on the wildlife.LiNeBrEaKOil tankers have terribly damaged the environment. The sewage waters are also said to have resulted in the red tide phenomenon. Global warming poses a risk to all creatures as well.LiNeBrEaKTherefore, samples of all the emirate's environments are declared as protected areas. There is a continuous coordination with all the bodies concerned, particularly the Environmental Section at the Sharjah Municipality.LiNeBrEaKThe Sharjah Desert Park (SDP) under the EPAA has seen a noticeable increase in visitors. What are the reasons?LiNeBrEaKThe four centres under the Park, including the Arabian Wildlife Centre, Breeding Centre for Endangered Arabian Wildlife, Children's Farm, Natural History Museum and Plant Life Centre are attracting thousands of visitors every year.LiNeBrEaK"As many as 300,000 visitors visited the SDP's four centres in 2008 as compared to 155,000 in 2007. Besides UAE nationals, who visit the Park throughout the year, Asian guests, including Indians, Japanese and Chinese are among the bulk of visitors. Delegations from European countries, including Russia, Spain and Germany,  followed by Arabs, visit the Park, especially in the winter season -- December 15 to January 15.LiNeBrEaKThe recent renovations, activities and programmes were attracting more visitors to the centres. Further facilities, including a cafeteria and mosque, were built.LiNeBrEaKThe EPAA, in association the Sharjah Commerce and Tourism Development Authority, has entered in several agreements with international travel agencies. Various awareness campaigns have been launched on the Authority website, as well as Sharjah TV Channel.LiNeBrEaKThe tickets are affordable.LiNeBrEaKVisitors pay only Dh15 to visit all the centres in the Park.LiNeBrEaKSchool children are charged Dh2 each, and people with special needs and members of the Holy Quran memorisation centres are exempted from entrance fees.SDP provides 12 well-trained tour guides who speak Arabic, English, Urdu, French and other languages fluently.LiNeBrEaKWe would like to have a better idea on the centres under the Park?LiNeBrEaKThe EPAA provides a significant opportunity for researchers to study the natural environment systems in their original condition as well as offering a chance for gaining environmental awareness and education by facilitating easy access to protected areas for students, interested individuals and even picnickers to enjoy kind of environmental tourism.LiNeBrEaKProtected AreasLiNeBrEaKEPAA had also emphasised on researching a network of protected areas representing a variety of habitats in the emirate, such as desert, sand dunes, hills and valleys, coastal and marine areas. Certain sites characterised by their environmental and biological diversity, have been designated to form the core of protected areas programme in Sharjah. These areas include Sir-bin-Ni'eer marine protected area, Khor Kalba seashore protected areas for mangroves and their habitat, and Al Zulaiyma enclave protected area for Sand Dunes system.LiNeBrEaKArabia's Wildlife Centre (AWC):LiNeBrEaKThe centre, which is considered a unique scientific and educational landmark, was inaugurated in 1999 to offer the chance of learning about the animals that exist in the Arabian Peninsula.LiNeBrEaKIt also facilitates the researchers to observe animals, which might not be seen in the wild at all.LiNeBrEaKSharjah Natural History Museum (SBHM):LiNeBrEaKThe Sharjah Natural History Museum opened in 1995 and is considered a distinguished landmark providing the opportunity to the public to learn about natural life in the Arabian Peninsula in its various forms -- marine, land and flora -- different geological periods as well as its entire natural history.LiNeBrEaKBreeding Centre for Endangered Wildlife (BCEAW)LiNeBrEaKEstablished in 1996, the breeding centre aims at preserving wildlife in Arabia. It has taken giant steps that transformed its size, goals and nature of its human resources since its inception.LiNeBrEaKThe centre intends to design conservation strategies for wild animals, especially in the Northern Emirates. It also carries out research work on animals in captivity and the wild.LiNeBrEaKahmedshaaban@khaleejtimes.com		ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (90%); DESTINATIONS and ATTRACTIONS (89%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (78%); SEWERAGE SYSTEMS (78%); GREEN BUILDING (78%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (77%); CITY GOVERNMENT (77%); INTERVIEWS (77%); MUSEUMS and GALLERIES (75%); SUSTAINABLE D