 racial inequities, an educational system still separate and unequal, inadequate health care coverage - all of these and more must be addressed for a fairer America.LiNeBrEaKEnvironmentLiNeBrEaK Fuel standards, investments in alternative fuels, green jobs and more attention to the threat of global warming - Obama must make inroads on all of these.LiNeBrEaK A tall order.LiNeBrEaK Today, we celebrate an American first. Now, Mr. President, on to the job of making America work again.		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (89%); LAYOFFS (75%); EDUCATION SYSTEMS and INSTITUTIONS (73%); EDUCATION (50%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); HEALTH INSURANCE (50%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  	JOURNAL/SENTINEL INC (63%)  		BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	MILWAUKEE, WI, USA (79%) WISCONSIN, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (96%); AFGHANISTAN (92%); IRAQ (92%); PAKISTAN (79%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Journal Sentinel Inc.   	O. RICARDO PIMENTEL, Staff, Milwaukee Journal Sentinel  															
Milwaukee Journal Sentinel (Wisconsin) 	January 20, 2009 Tuesday   Final Edition	YOUR OPINIONS  	A News; Pg. 12  	875 words  	INAUGURATIONLiNeBrEaKA great presidentLiNeBrEaK They called it the Great War. That is, until there was another one. Then it was World War I.LiNeBrEaK They called it the Great Depression. Will it become Depression I? I hope not.LiNeBrEaK The entire system of numbering history practically sets up the future for sequels. Why not just call it War: To Be Continued?LiNeBrEaK The word "great" has taken a lot of flak in history books. Taken out of context, it is synonymous with inspiring and extraordinary. Neither of those comes to mind when war or economic disaster are pending. LiNeBrEaK Why not save the word "great" by using it for inspirational titles? Great Britain and Great Plains are much more inspiring uses of the word "great," but there will not likely be a Britain II or a Plains II.LiNeBrEaK I'm just glad that today, we are historically inaugurating a Great African-American President, and I hope there will be many more to come.LiNeBrEaK John BoeroLiNeBrEaK ThiensvilleLiNeBrEaKObama needs the prayers of citizensLiNeBrEaK As the immediate past chairman of the Republican Party of Wisconsin, I was disappointed that Republican nominee John McCain lost his bid for the presidency of the United States. I voted against Barack Obama because I believe he is wrong on numerous issues. I am concerned that many of his policies will hurt business, and I am leery of his potential judicial appointments.LiNeBrEaK He will be our president, and he needs our prayers. I will pray for him to receive strength, courage and wisdom. I also will pray for his safety and for those around him.LiNeBrEaK I may disagree with him on his policies, but I will be praying for Obama over the next four years. I encourage everyone else to pray for the president, too.LiNeBrEaK Brad CourtneyLiNeBrEaK Whitefish BayLiNeBrEaKNow's the time for environmental actionLiNeBrEaK With the inauguration of President Barack Obama, now is the time to act on our car mania's environmental effects. As someone with no driver's license, dependent on public transportation, I have seen over the past 70 years the manipulation by both oil and automobile companies. Despite oil being non-renewable, the Big Three U.S. automakers have continued to promote in ads big gas guzzlers.LiNeBrEaK Al Gore pointed out in "An Inconvenient Truth" that the Big Three have continued to sue states such as California over higher energy standards instead of putting money into researching and developing hybrids and other environmentally friendly cars, contributing to their poor financial health in the current economic downturn. "The 11th Hour" notes the same poky behavior by corporate executives in the oil business toward research and development in renewable resources.LiNeBrEaK Obama can jump-start a clean energy economy and start reducing global warming pollution by immediately directing the Environmental Protection Agency to grant the waiver that will allow California and other states to limit global warming pollution from cars.LiNeBrEaK Stop subsidies to oil companies and invest instead to move public transportation from the margins to the mainstream.LiNeBrEaK Miu TorkeLiNeBrEaK GreendaleLiNeBrEaKHope for a new eraLiNeBrEaK Behold, we have been "Obama-tized!" Has Karl Rove's marriage of the Christian right to George Bush and the Republican Party given birth to an abomination? No! It has given birth to an "ObamaNation"! America will now move on to better times.LiNeBrEaK My expectations are that the successors of the "ObamaNation" will be as happy and hopeful as we are today. Also that our world, our nation and our children will be healthier and better educated and feel as we do today.LiNeBrEaK Eugene FowlerLiNeBrEaK MilwaukeeLiNeBrEaKTone down the hypeLiNeBrEaK Enough, already! We have been "treated" to nonstop coverage of the event that hasn't happened yet: the Obama inauguration.LiNeBrEaK Printed news, Internet news, television news and radio news have been relentless in the search to find another angle to this "story." The crowning touch to this coverage was during the Steelers-Ravens football game on Sunday. The half time report from Katie Couric was a fawning preview of today's inauguration. A good portion of the bill for this occasion (services, security, etc.) will be left to the taxpayers to pay.LiNeBrEaK Wouldn't it be better to wait until President Barack Obama actually does something?LiNeBrEaK David V. SzymczakLiNeBrEaK MilwaukeeLiNeBrEaKChange has been a long time comingLiNeBrEaK The Jan. 14 article "Hoover museum tells a cautionary tale," with its statement on how Barack Obama could take some cues from the Hoover Museum exhibit, made me think of a specific story in the exhibit. When first lady Lou Henry Hoover invited the wife of Illinois congressman Oscar DePriest to the White House, it was the first time an African-American woman had entered through the front door. Hoover was harshly criticized for this action.LiNeBrEaK Letters in response to this incident in the exhibit show the fascinating range of responses, and values, of Americans of the time. Whether Mr. Obama knows this story I don't know, but it shows how far we have come as an electorate and as Americans. My colleagues and I learned this and much more as our firm, Teller Madsen Inc., designed the exhibits in 1992. The project remains one of my favorite work and learning experiences.LiNeBrEaK Frank MadsenLiNeBrEaK Delavan		GREAT DEPRESSION (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); WORLD WAR I (90%); ECONOMIC DEPRESSION (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (88%); AUTOMAKERS (85%); AUTOMOBILE MFG (85%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (84%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (79%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); HISTORY (78%); ECONOMIC NEWS (77%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (75%); POLITICAL PARTIES (72%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (68%); AUTOMOTIVE INDUSTRY and ENVIRONMENT (67%); VEHICLE EMISSI