The New York Times 	January 20, 2009 Tuesday   Late Edition - Final	More-Reflective Crops May Have Cooling Effect  	Section D; Column 0; Science Desk; OBSERVATORY; Pg. 3  	337 words  	Some of the most imaginative solutions to the problem of global climate change involve planetary-scale geoengineering projects to reduce the sunlight reaching the Earth's surface. But proposals like building a huge sunshade in space or seeding the atmosphere with sulfate particles would cost enormous sums and require a degree of international cooperation that is difficult to achieve. LiNeBrEaK  Andy Ridgwell and colleagues at the University of Bristol in England have another idea, one they call bio-geoengineering. Rather than developing infrastructure to help cool the planet, they propose using an existing one: agriculture. LiNeBrEaK  Their calculations, published in Current Biology, suggest that by planting crop varieties that reflect more sunlight, summertime cooling of about 2 degrees Fahrenheit could be obtained across central North America and a wide band of Europe and Asia.LiNeBrEaK  ''Arable agriculture is already a global-scale undertaking,'' Dr. Ridgwell said. ''We wondered whether you might grow slightly different crops and have some sort of climate impact.''LiNeBrEaK  Plants reflect slightly different amounts of light depending on factors like how waxy  the leaves are. Even differences in growth patterns between two varieties of a crop -- the way leaves are arranged -- can affect reflectivity.LiNeBrEaK  Existing varieties could be used, Dr. Ridgwell said, or crops could be bred or genetically engineered for greater reflectivity (without affecting yields, nutritional values or other important characteristics). But shifts to different crops -- from wheat to corn, for instance -- would be too disruptive, he said.LiNeBrEaK  Dr. Ridgwell acknowledged that the idea would not be a complete solution to the climate change problem. For one thing, the Southern Hemisphere would be less affected, in part because there is much less agricultural land. LiNeBrEaK  But it wouldn't cost much, and it wouldn't require much international cooperation. ''It's very practical, and it could just be done,'' he said. ''It's not some trillion-dollar pie-in-the-sky idea.''	http://www.nytimes.com  	CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (78%); BIOTECHNOLOGY and GENETIC SCIENCE (52%); GENETIC ENGINEERING (50%)  				EARTH (92%) NORTH AMERICA (79%); ENGLAND (72%); UNITED KINGDOM (72%); ASIA (55%); EUROPE (55%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	DRAWING (DRAWING BY CHRIS GASH)     		Newspaper  	2009 The New York Times Company   	By HENRY FOUNTAIN  															
The Oakland Tribune (California)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	Cal professor sends Obama a reading assignment  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	506 words  	Jan. 20--Barack Obama certainly has a lot of goals to conquer as he becomes the 44th president of the United States, but understanding radioactive decay and uranium bombs might not be on his short list of things to do. LiNeBrEaKBut Richard Muller, a UC Berkeley professor of physics and past winner of the MacArthur Fellowship, commonly called the "genius award," hopes Obama, 47, will take time out to read his book "Physics for Future Presidents: The Science Behind the Headlines."LiNeBrEaKHe said he has sent several copies to Obama's advisers and even managed to get a book to Michelle Obama through a personal friend of his.LiNeBrEaKThe 346-page hardback, released last year, covers everything from the difference between a uranium bomb, a plutonium bomb and a hydrogen bomb to solar power to space and global warming.LiNeBrEaK"What I've done is taken physics and eliminated everything that isn't urgently important," he said from his Berkeley home.LiNeBrEaKMuller's book is not political, and he openly admits he sent a copy to people who work with former Republican presidential nominee John McCain before Obama won the election.LiNeBrEaK"Physics is nonpartisan, and I think that it's really important to realize that physics is nonpolitical," said the 65-year-old South Bronx native who came to Berkeley in 1964.LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are topics in his book that will enable the president to act quickly and wisely in the event of a terrorist attack or a nuclear bombing. Muller explainsLiNeBrEaKin his book that the country likely will be highly dependent on fossil fuels for many generations and that there are no easy answers to global warming.LiNeBrEaKMuller said his book can lead the president through a wealth of conflicting information about a bevy of subjects, which if not understood could lead to "solutions" that will actually make things worse.LiNeBrEaK"The president can't just be told that a nuke in the hands of North Korea is a big danger," he said. "The president must understand what a big danger it is."LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are many valuable lessons for Obama -- or any leader -- in his book.LiNeBrEaK"We live in a high-tech world, and many of the decisions we face on an individual level and on the presidential level have high-tech components. If you are talking about alternative energy, you need to understand coal, clean coal, nukes, solar and geothermal energy.LiNeBrEaK"If you are going to be the leader of the country, you can't depend on simply picking science advisers to tell you what to do. Decisions (about alternative energy) can't be based on science alone. They have to be based on science, economics and business and even on issues regarding diplomacy," said Muller.		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (91%); NUCLEAR WEAPONS (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (88%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (88%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); NUCLEAR CHEMISTRY (77%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (76%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (73%); SOLAR ENERGY (73%); TERRORISM (72%); GEOTHERMAL ENERGY (68%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (60%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); MICHELLE OBAMA (57%); JOHN MCCAIN (55%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (90%) CALIFORNIA, USA (90%) UNITED STATES (92%); NORTH KOREA (79%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Oakland Tribune   	Kristin Bender, The Oakland Tribune, Calif.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090120-OX-Cal-professor-sends-Obama-a-reading-assignment-0120  	OX  									
The Porterville Recorder (California)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	EDITORIAL: Transfer of power  	COMMENTARY  	613 words  	Jan. 20--The rituals have become so commonplace that we sometimes forget just how significant an accomplishment this country has managed. Power will be passed peacefully not just from one elected leader to another but to a leader from a different party, with a different governing philosophy. A man who won election in part by systematically disparaging the record and perhaps even the character of the man he will replace will be -- has been -- treated graciously and with full cooperation by the outgoing president and his minions.LiNeBrEaKIt doesn't happen that way in every country; some countries seem to need bloodshed and armed combatants to change political governance. When a change from one party to the other first occurred in this country, it wasn't a certainty by any means that the transition would be entirely peaceful. John Adams refused to attend the inauguration of the man who replaced him, Thomas Jefferson. The campaign had been bitter and personal in ways that would shock some moderns. LiNeBrEaKAs President-elect Obama put it in a newspaper interview last week, "Elections aren't democracy, as we understand it. They are one facet of a liberal order." A democratic order requires not just a mechanical process for counting votes, but a willingness on the part of the losing party to abide by the results, and a concomitant willingness on the part of the winner not to persecute a minority or undermine individual rights. It is a delicate balance, and today we celebrate an America that through numerous tests and trials has maintained that balance.LiNeBrEaKPresident Barack Obama no doubt anticipated having to handle two unresolved wars, but until quite recently he didn't expect to have to deal with an economic and financial crisis. He has for the most part moved deftly to put people in place who command respect, although he may soon learn that government cannot command recovery.LiNeBrEaKAmid the pomp and pageantry today, it is worth remembering that life in America is richer and more complex than the political side of life can begin to reflect. Some now-obscure scientist toiling patiently on approaches to cancer, some techie seeking new uses for microchips, a climatologist getting to the root of climate change rather than reflecting a mock consensus, a novelist who finally captures the American scene, a composer working on a symphony or a songwriter crafting the perfect song may change America more than all the dignitaries assembled today in Washington, D.C. Far greater things are almost always afoot than are dreamt of in our capitals.LiNeBrEaKSo politics is hardly everything in life. But a political order that can accommodate changes that seem wrenching at the time, a country that began with black people in chains that can elect an African-American to the highest office in the land, are worth celebrating.LiNeBrEaKPresident-elect Obama has stressed personal responsibility and accountability during the transition. The time will come, and sooner than he would probably prefer, to hold him accountable for mistakes and misjudgments in office. For today, however, let us celebrate the fact that an awesome amount of power -- perhaps too much power -- can be passed from one person to another amid revelry rather than recrimination and even bloodshed.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); ELECTIONS (77%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (77%); POLITICS (76%); CLIMATE CHANGE (74%); INTERVIEWS (72%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (69%); CLIMATOLOGY (65%); MUSIC COMPOSITION (64%); SONG WRITING (64%); ECONOMIC CRISIS (50%); US PRESIDENTS (89%)  			BARACK OBAMA (83%)  	CALIFORNIA, USA (79%); DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (95%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Recorder   	The Porterville Recorder, Calif.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090120-PI-EDITORIAL-Transfer-of-power-0120  	PI  									
The Record-Eagle (Traverse City, Michigan)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	Geography education takes students over the planet and maybe to D.C.: What's required  	LIFESTYLE  	1019 words  	Jan. 20--TRAVERSE CITY -- Noah Aulicino, 11, wrote his answer, then held his breath.LiNeBrEaK"The Gulf of Guinea is off the west coast of what continent?"LiNeBrEaKThe Central Grade School student answered "Africa" and, whew, he was right.LiNeBrEaKNoah and nine other fifth-graders had made it to the finals of Central's Geography Bee, a competition that's part of the National Geographic Bee. As a school winner, Noah "gets the honor of taking a test," said his teacher, Jaye Lynn Trapp. If he places in the top 100 in the state, he'll go to the state bee April 3 at Central Michigan University. LiNeBrEaKThe 50 state winners compete in Washington, D.C., May 19-20. Students in grades 4 through 8 are eligible.LiNeBrEaKLearning geography is more than maps and colored pencils, although her students do like those, said Nancy Fitzpatrick, a teacher at East Middle School in Traverse City.LiNeBrEaK"I try to help them become aware of people outside their world," she said. "At this age, they're thinking about themselves, their family, maybe Traverse City. My goal is to get them to realize we're all connected."LiNeBrEaKHer Eastern Hemisphere Studies students just finished projects about countries in Africa.LiNeBrEaK"They made presentations and a lot of them said things like, 'Maybe you complain when you don't get that new bicycle, but can you imagine not knowing what a bicycle is?' They're becoming more aware and they have more empathy," Fitzpatrick said.LiNeBrEaKShe said wishes they posted on a bulletin board after Christmas included finding a cure for AIDS and ending the civil wars in Congo.LiNeBrEaKDessie Hughes, a geography and history teacher at West Middle School, said geography is "the most important subject, given the flat world we live in."LiNeBrEaKShe said geography is engaging because it's always current. "When teaching about Antarctica, we discuss the international issue on global warming. Students may simulate studying elements on Antarctica like our scientists, then make decisions based on their findings."LiNeBrEaKBee winner Noah said it's important because it helps him learn about history, but also because geography will tell "scientists and travelers cool places to go."LiNeBrEaKBoys disproportionately outnumber girls in geography bees, Trapp said, but she's not exactly sure why.LiNeBrEaK"There aren't any conclusive studies," she said, "but there is a lot of spatial thinking in geography and there are studies that say boys are better at that."LiNeBrEaKJessica Budz, 11, another Central Grade School finalist, studied by reading "a lot of atlases, taking tests online and using the National Geographic study guide," she said.LiNeBrEaK"Instead of reading 'Harry Potter,' I'd read the atlas," Jessica said. She likes to learn what happens in other places and "how it became that way."LiNeBrEaKGary Howe, an adjunct professor of geography at Northwestern Michigan College, said the State Department is always in need of geographers.LiNeBrEaK"Some say, with our less-than-robust success in Afghanistan, that it's because we don't know enough about how the place works," Howe said. "Geography is all-encompassing. When we study a region, we look at the major things that define it -- like language and the major issues that the people face and the major issues that the environment faces.LiNeBrEaK"When we study Saudi Arabia, for instance, we talk a lot about water," Howe said. "Where do the people live? They're clustered around water. What are they doing about their water shortage? Are they using their oil money wisely and building desalination plants?LiNeBrEaK"In geography, the answers are always going to change," he said. "We need to be able to formulate good questions."LiNeBrEaKFifth-grade teacher Trapp is a member of the Michigan Geographic Alliance, a network of teachers and geographers, and has developed a course of study for teachers about American Indians and their first encounters with Europeans. The students use maps to trace settlement routes and compare patterns from 1491 to 1650. Technology, geography and history are incorporated, she said.LiNeBrEaK"Geography is a great way to incorporate technology, math, science and the arts," she said. "When you're studying maps, you're reading. When you're studying relationships and patterns, you're doing math. We use charts, graphs and tables all the time."LiNeBrEaKTrapp said one of the most interesting themes for fifth-graders in her gifted services classes is when they talk about regions.LiNeBrEaK"It leads to talking about languages, recipes and customs. It's just fascinating," she said.LiNeBrEaKThe Michigan Department of Education outlines expectations for K-8 geography. Among them are:LiNeBrEaK-- Places and Regions (physical and human characteristics);LiNeBrEaK-- The World in Spacial (spacial thinking, geographic understanding)LiNeBrEaK-- Physical Systems (ecosystems, physical processes)LiNeBrEaK-- Human Systems (cultures, patterns of human settlement, conflict)LiNeBrEaK-- Environment and Society (global issues past and present, humans and the environment)LiNeBrEaKAre you smarter than a fifth-grader?LiNeBrEaKHere are some sample questions from the National Geographic Bee.LiNeBrEaK1. Which state has a climate suitable for growing citrus fruits -- California or Maine?LiNeBrEaK2. Which country has the world's largest Muslim population -- Indonesia or Mexico?LiNeBrEaK3. The North Atlantic current brings warm waters from the tropics to the west coast of which continent?LiNeBrEaK4. What is the term for a part of an ocean or sea that cuts far into the bordering landmass and may contain one or more bays?LiNeBrEaK5. The port of Rotterdam is built on the delta of which major European river?LiNeBrEaK6. Which Canadian province produces more than half of the country's manufactured goods?LiNeBrEaK7. To visit the ruins of Persepolis, an ancient ceremonial capital of Persia, you would have to travel to what present-day country?LiNeBrEaKAnswers: 1. California 2. Indonesia 3. Europe 4. Gulf 5. Rhine River 6. Ontario 7. Iran		PRIMARY SCHOOLS (90%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (90%); PRIMARY and SECONDARY SCHOOL TEACHERS (89%); CHILDREN (77%); HISTORY (77%); RANKINGS (70%); GLOBAL WARMING (61%); AIDS and HIV TREATMENT (50%)  		CENTRAL MICHIGAN UNIVERSITY (56%)  		MICHIGAN, USA (96%); DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (92%); ATLANTIC OCEAN (91%) UNITED STATES (96%); AFRICA (93%); ANTARCTICA (91%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Jodee Taylor, The Record-Eagle, Traverse City, Mich.  			Education  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090120-ZK-Geography-education-takes-students-over-the-planet-and-maybe-to-D-C-0120  	ZK  									
The Roanoke Times (Virginia)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	EDITORIAL: A historic presidency: Barack Obama starts his term of office assured of a place in history. Let's hope the first black president is remembered, though, as a great one.  	COMMENTARY  	455 words  	Jan. 20--Barack Obama becomes president of the United States today, the first African-American to lead a nation born of freedom yet built in part on black slavery. LiNeBrEaKIt is a joyously historic day of triumph for human resilience and of redemption for American ideals.LiNeBrEaKYet Obama's historic presidency begins in a time of historic peril.LiNeBrEaKThe country is mired in an economic recession unlike any in most Americans' lifetime, the financial foundation of the nation so shaken it threatens to crumble.LiNeBrEaKThe country is engaged in wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, and a worldwide battle against terrorism that, empowered by technology, threatens mass destruction against nation-states by small groups of extremists.LiNeBrEaKThe country is called to respond to the growing evidence of global warming by finding alternatives to fossil fuels to provide the energy that runs its households and its industries -- alternatives that still need to be developed.LiNeBrEaKAnd the country faces these big challenges, and more, at a time when the world's confidence in America and Americans' confidence in its leaders are at an ebb.LiNeBrEaKObama takes the oath of office today, but he took the reins of government to a perhaps unprecedented degree in the weeks between his election and inauguration day.LiNeBrEaKThe campaign cry of "Change" is already, of necessity, under way.LiNeBrEaKNow the country will see how an Obama presidency unfolds.LiNeBrEaKObama did not campaign to become the president of black Americans, but of all Americans. And the enormity of the work ahead ensures that. The challenges are national in scope, giving all Americans a stake in the course he sets.LiNeBrEaKThis day undeniably is one of special significance and pride to his fellow African Americans. It is fraught with symbols of the past, of the journey of a people brought to America in chains who have endured and overcome.LiNeBrEaKObama -- who becomes president 200 years after the birth of the Great Emancipator, Abraham Lincoln -- will take his oath of office on the same Bible that Lincoln used for his first inauguration in 1861.LiNeBrEaKBut the youthful Obama is all about the future, a man of mixed race whose campaign transcended racial politics to address the fears and the aspirations of all Americans. Since his election, he has stepped into a leadership breach with intelligence, seriousness and unflappable confidence.LiNeBrEaKHe offers hope.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (91%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (90%); HUMAN RIGHTS VIOLATIONS (90%); POLITICS (78%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); TERRORISM (75%); IRAQ WAR (75%); RECESSION (56%); ECONOMIC NEWS (56%); GLOBAL WARMING (54%); US PRESIDENTS (91%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (61%)  		BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	VIRGINIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (99%); AFGHANISTAN (79%); IRAQ (79%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Roanoke Times   	The Roanoke Times, Va.  			Arts  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090120-RO-EDITORIAL-A-historic-presidency-0120  	RO  									
