San Jose Mercury News (California) 	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	Cal professor sends Obama a reading assignment  	BREAKING; News  	432 words  	Barack Obama certainly has a lot of goals to conquer as he becomes the 44th president of the United States, but understanding radioactive decay and uranium bombs might not be on his short list of things to do. LiNeBrEaKBut Richard Muller, a UC Berkeley professor of physics and past winner of the MacArthur Fellowship, commonly called the "genius award," hopes Obama, 47, will take time out to read his book "Physics for Future Presidents: The Science Behind the Headlines."LiNeBrEaKHe said he has sent several copies to Obama's advisers and even managed to get a book to Michelle Obama through a personal friend of his.LiNeBrEaKThe 346-page hardback, released last year, covers everything from the difference between a uranium bomb, a plutonium bomb and a hydrogen bomb to solar power to space and global warming.LiNeBrEaK"What I've done is taken physics and eliminated everything that isn't urgently important," he said from his Berkeley home.LiNeBrEaKMuller's book is not political, and he openly admits he sent a copy to people who work with former Republican presidential nominee John McCain before Obama won the election.LiNeBrEaK"Physics is nonpartisan, and I think that it's really important to realize that physics is nonpolitical," said the 65-year-old South Bronx native who came to Berkeley in 1964.LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are topics in his book that will enable the president to act quickly and wisely in the event of a terrorist attack or a nuclear bombing. Muller explains in his book that the country likely will be highly dependent on fossil fuels for many generations and that there are no easy answers to global warming.LiNeBrEaKMuller said his book can lead the president through a wealth of conflicting information about a bevy of subjects, which if not understood could lead to "solutions" that will actually make things worse.LiNeBrEaK"The president can't just be told that a nuke in the hands of North Korea is a big danger," he said. "The president must understand what a big danger it is."LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are many valuable lessons for Obama   or any leader   in his book.LiNeBrEaK"We live in a high-tech world, and many of the decisions we face on an individual level and on the presidential level have high-tech components. If you are talking about alternative energy, you need to understand coal, clean coal, nukes, solar and geothermal energy.LiNeBrEaK"If you are going to be the leader of the country, you can't depend on simply picking science advisers to tell you what to do. Decisions (about alternative energy) can't be based on science alone. They have to be based on science, economics and business and even on issues regarding diplomacy," said Muller.		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (91%); NUCLEAR WEAPONS (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (88%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (88%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); NUCLEAR CHEMISTRY (78%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (77%); SOLAR ENERGY (73%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (73%); TERRORISM (72%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); GEOTHERMAL ENERGY (68%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (60%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); MICHELLE OBAMA (57%); JOHN MCCAIN (55%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (90%) CALIFORNIA, USA (90%) UNITED STATES (92%); NORTH KOREA (79%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News All Rights Reserved  	By Kristen Bender Bay Area News Group  															
