t from at least one critic before Warren addressed the audience.LiNeBrEaKFarris defended the King Center's choice of keynote speaker, saying that Warren's stances on issues like global warming, AIDS and poverty are in keeping with King's ideals.LiNeBrEaKKing preached at Ebenezer from 1960 until his death in 1968, and a service commemorating his birthday and life are held there annually. On election night, the mainly black audience there was moved to tears when news networks announced that Obama had won.LiNeBrEaKKing would have been 80 years old on Jan. 15.		PROTESTANTS and PROTESTANTISM (90%); CHRISTIANS and CHRISTIANITY (90%); CIVIL RIGHTS (90%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (89%); ELECTIONS (78%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); HOLIDAYS and OBSERVANCES (76%); GAYS and LESBIANS (72%); WILLS (64%); SAME SEX MARRIAGE and UNIONS (50%); MARRIAGE (50%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%) {DOC SEPARATOR}  			BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	ATLANTA, GA, USA (93%); BARCELONA, SPAIN (79%) GEORGIA, USA (93%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%); CATALONIA, SPAIN (74%) UNITED STATES (93%); SPAIN (79%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO - Faye Walker; Lourdes Alvarez of Barcelona, Spain; Veronica Gonzalez-Diez of Argentina; and an unidentified woman sing along with the Urban Nation H.I.P.-H.O.P. Choir during the Martin Luther King Jr. Day celebration at the Washington National Cathedral.   Getty Images   		Newspaper  	2009 St. Louis Post-Dispatch, Inc. All Rights Reserved  	By Errin Haines The Associated Press  							martin luther king jr. day   								
The Star-Ledger (Newark, New Jersey) 	January 20, 2009 Tuesday   FINAL EDITION	Goodbye, George, I fear you were a total failure  	EDITORIAL; Pg. 015  	783 words  	As I was driving around the Capitol area with my brother Sunday evening observing the preparations for today's inaugural ceremony, I heard a radio announcer running through the usual list of suggestions. Arrive early, dress for the cold, etc.LiNeBrEaKAnd then he brought on another expert who warned Washingtonians to make sure and wear sunscreen. Sunscreen? Yes, this expert went on to warn of the possibility of getting a bad sunburn in mid-winter Washington. LiNeBrEaKMy brother didn't seem shocked by this. He has lived inside the Beltway for 30 years and is used to such unapologetic alarmism. But I found myself wondering just how it would be possible to get a sunburn at this latitude on a day in mid-January on which overcast skies were forecast. Somehow I suspect the emergency rooms will not be packed this evening with people who used SPF-15 sunscreen when they really needed SPF-45.LiNeBrEaKBut that's the Beltway mentality. Someone is always selling some imaginary fear, warning of some unmenacing menace. And that is where George W. Bush went so horribly wrong. Every president in the modern era has been surrounded by people who believe that the only thing we need to fear is fear itself - so let's drum up some fear. Fear more than money is the mother's milk of D.C. politics. The greater the fear, the more power the Washington crowd can concentrate inside the Beltway.LiNeBrEaKAnd much of this is our fault, by which I mean the fault of those of us in the media. The sycophantic Beltway pundits like William Kristol and Charles Krauthammer and the moronic radio talkers like Rush Limbaugh and Sean Hannity insist that the media were biased against Bush. Nonsense. We gave him a free pass when it came to peddling panic. In fact, it was the New York Times itself, in the person of then-reporter Judy Miller, that handed Bush and Dick Cheney the paranoic conspiracy theory about a nonexistent Saddam-al Qaeda link that led to the biggest foreign-policy blunder in American history. That was well within the tradition of American journalism. It's been almost a century since Baltimore's H.L. Mencken wrote that the most prominent aspect of American journalism was "its constant effort to evade the discussion of fundamentals by translating all issues into a few elemental fears."LiNeBrEaKThe duty of a president is to keep a calm head amidst all this. Bush failed miserably. The man who went to Washington hoping to reduce the role of the federal government ended up expanding it immeasurably.LiNeBrEaKHis failure represents a victory for all of the people I saw yesterday lining the route for today's inaugural parade. They were handing out leaflets for every liberal cause imaginable, from national health care to ending global warming. The media are mainly covering the ethnic angle of the inauguration, the election of the first African-American president and all that, but the real celebration is the triumph of the Beltway bureaucracy. Thanks to Bush's bungling, the bureaucracy is stronger than ever. It is impossible to overestimate the damage he has done. He inherited a country in which the economy was strong and young people wanted to work in private industry. He's leaving us with a country in which the idea of public employment and public power is ascendant.LiNeBrEaKWorse, he and the aforementioned sycophant pundits argued for adoration of that public power. Well, adoration they shall have. As of this afternoon, a Democrat inherits all the vast powers of the so-called "unitary executive." If Barack Obama leads us into some form of socialism, he will only be carrying Bush's "compassionate conservatism" to its logical end.LiNeBrEaKAs for me, I will be glad to see this gang of rascals routed. They were awful human beings and they destroyed everything they hoped to stand for.LiNeBrEaKBut if the future is bleak, at least a proper perception of the political spectrum will be restored. I recall in the Clinton years being regularly denounced for my acerbic attitude toward the Beltway crowd. After a particularly harsh piece on Hillary Clinton, I got to read this passage in a letter to the editor of this newspaper calling for me to be forever silenced:LiNeBrEaK"While we all enjoy spirited political commentary, many of us would prefer if the paper limited the publication of personal attacks on our nation's leaders," the reader wrote.LiNeBrEaKIt was a better day when it was the Democrats who were calling for an end to criticism. And now that day is upon us again. Every cloud has a silver lining, they say, even the mid-January cloud that will permit me to risk spending the day in Washington without sunscreen.LiNeBrEaKNotes: Paul Mulshine appears regularly in The Star-Ledger.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); JOURNALISM (89%); HISTORY (66%); EMERGENCY ROOMS (54%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%)  			GEORGE W BUSH (83%); RUSH LIMBAUGH (53%); DICK CHENEY (52%)  	BALTIMORE, MD, USA (54%) DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (79%); NEW JERSEY, USA (72%); MARYLAND, USA (54%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Newark Morning Ledger Co. All Rights Reserved  	PAUL MULSHINE, STAR-LEDGER STAFF  	WASHINGTON   					nsl  									
St. Paul Pioneer Press (Minnesota) 	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	A lesson from Estrella  	LETTERS  	1313 words  	If Estrella Seals, a sixth grader from Cherokee Heights Elementary School in St. Paul, is an example of our future -- there is hope ("An inaugural winner," Jan. 19).LiNeBrEaKAs a "conservative old guy," it seems that I have let myself become overwhelmed by the negativity in our world today. The economy is in turmoil; our leaders are less than trustworthy; terrorists are in the shadows; our retirement savings are shrinking fast; TV displays our decadence. And, heaven forbid, Al Franken will represent Minnesota.LiNeBrEaKIt seems to me that Estrella, winner of an essay contest on black excellence, has been blessed with positive, supportive and loving parents.LiNeBrEaKI pray that Estrella realizes her dreams and that she continues to be surrounded with positive role models. She has the right idea. She has the right goals. LiNeBrEaKAs we welcome President Barack Obama, it is comforting to know that Estrella and other young people will be there to witness this most historic and special time in our country's history.LiNeBrEaKI think we can all take a lesson from Estrella.LiNeBrEaKJohn R. Santos, MaplewoodConfusing weatherwith climateLiNeBrEaKI am somewhat dismayed that many readers are still confusing weather (individual storms and air masses) with climate (long-term trends in such weather attributes as temperature, precipitation, wind, etc.) when they contemplate how seriously they should take environmental issues.LiNeBrEaKI realize that some individuals respond more to the messenger than to the message, but when it comes to climate change, it is my opinion that it is real, it can be substantiated by the scientific data and it is already having observable consequences, even in Minnesota.LiNeBrEaKAs someone who has studied atmospheric and climate science for more than 35 years, I still have to admit that science cannot explain precisely all of the atmospheric processes and interactions driving climate change, often overly simplified in the popular media. But we must acknowledge that climate change is happening, and we should use our knowledge and technology to adapt to it or to mitigate its human-induced drivers.LiNeBrEaKMinnesotans have a reputation for valuing citizenship and community action, overcoming our differences and, in the end, doing the right thing. As we grapple with our struggling economy and what to do about it, let's also consider doing the right thing for Minnesota's rich landscape and resources.LiNeBrEaKMark Seeley, St. PaulLiNeBrEaKThe writer is professor and extension climatologist/meteorologist with the Department of Soil, Water and Climate at the University of Minnesota.Cost of smoking banLiNeBrEaKThis letter is to all the people at the Capitol who passed the smoking ban on a legal product.LiNeBrEaKI, and many others, would like to know how much tax money the state has lost because of this ban. You can bet it is huge. People have lost jobs and businesses have closed or are struggling to make it. The money being lost could have helped pay for services that are going to be cut (police, fire, health, education and many more jobs).LiNeBrEaKThe governor and his crew at the Capitol should face the fact this ban was a huge mistake. If they are worried about people's health, then they should put a ban on a lot of food and drinks that can be bad for your health.LiNeBrEaKI'm a nonsmoker, by the way.LiNeBrEaKMary Wenner, St. Paul IRV: What's not to like?LiNeBrEaKJason Hoppin reported that instant-runoff voting is "supported in Minnesota by a bevy of left-leaning politicians and interest groups" ("Instant-runoff voting gets nod from court," Jan. 15). Maybe so, but as a longtime Republican, not known to be "left-leaning," I find IRV a welcome proposal for electoral reform, as well.LiNeBrEaKIt is less costly, may produce a more timely outcome and will produce a majority winner. I don't see what's not to like -- no matter which way people lean.LiNeBrEaKLoanne R. Thrane, St. PaulSoucheray's right about 'miracle' flightLiNeBrEaKWay to go, Joe Soucheray. Your column on the US Airways plane's "miracle" flight (Jan. 18) was great and so true.LiNeBrEaKWe have turned into a "sue you, sue me" society in which you can spill hot coffee on yourself and sue the restaurant for damages.LiNeBrEaKEveryone on that plane has so much to be thankful for. They all walked off and went home to their loved ones. You cannot put a price on that. Please, as Joe said, "let's keep lawsuits off this miracle."LiNeBrEaKLaura McGinn, St. PaulA voice aimedat the futureLiNeBrEaKTo the letter writer ("Interpreting votes and recount rules," Jan. 15) who wondered where the Democratic voices are: The election is over, and most of us, along with most Republicans, are waiting for the judges to determine who will represent Minnesota in the U.S. Senate, and as soon as possible.LiNeBrEaKI trust these distinguished jurists to do the job specified by the laws and Minnesota Constitution. Whoever wins will be accepted by most of us as the legally elected senator.LiNeBrEaKUnlike sports, there are no photo finishes with two gold medals; there will be only one person elected. And in an election, there is no such thing as a "statistical dead heat."LiNeBrEaKThis voice has been urging legislators to use the economic stimulus package to rebuild the badly neglected infrastructure: highways, bridges, dams and the electrical distribution system. And this voice has been calling for more investment in education, funded by rescinding the unwarranted tax cuts of recent years, the tax cuts that have caused the current financial mess (along with irresponsible deregulation). And I have been urging investment in nuclear power to support a move to electric cars.LiNeBrEaKLen Schakel, LakelandPerceptions aboutoff-duty officersLiNeBrEaKRub&eacute;n Rosario's recent column on police officers' activity while off duty was on target ("Cop's off-duty club questioned in lawsuit," Jan. 11).LiNeBrEaKBeing a police officer, I agree that my personal life off duty will determine how I am perceived by others. Whom I socialize with, where I spend my time and money and how I live my life will be used in this determination. Public perception may not always be accurate, but our actions determine how people arrive at their opinions. Be assured, many in police officer motorcycle groups are non-drinking officers simply looking for an escape and allowing themselves to leave their jobs behind.LiNeBrEaKThe law enforcement profession has a higher rate of divorce, alcoholism and suicide than the general public. While we remain brave and strong, while solving the world's problems and making split-second decisions, we are often questioned by others who disagree with our reasoning. While we have a need to let our hair down and cut loose, we need to remember that ethics and integrity will shape the way we are perceived. How we are perceived will determine how effective we are in working in our communities.LiNeBrEaKPaul A. Johnson, Spooner, Wis. Why reveal hockey players' names?LiNeBrEaKI felt great anger at your newspaper's absolute dogged determination to find and reveal the names of the four Hill-Murray High School hockey players who were removed from the team roster ("Down four, Hill-Murray regroups," Jan. 16).LiNeBrEaKIf the team and the administration wanted to give privacy to the boys, that was their decision, and it was kind, considerate and wise. It was an internal thing.LiNeBrEaKIt appears your paper dug and dug until it found the four names. What did you prove, except that you can destroy and invade privacy and make the boys feel even worse? I don't know the boys, but you certainly let everyone know who they are.LiNeBrEaKLila J. Recksiedler, Roseville'Dream' still eludes usLiNeBrEaKNot to rain on anybody's parade, but the way the media is fawning over President Barack Obama is very disturbing. It's as if we elected a god, not just a man.LiNeBrEaKMartin Luther King Jr. dreamed of a day when we would judge a person by the content of his character, not the color of his skin. Ronald Reagan sought a "colorblind" society.LiNeBrEaKBut sadly, the only thing people are focusing on with Obama is the color of his skin. Apparently, the dream still eludes us.LiNeBrEaKMatt Marchetti, North St. Paul		LETTERS and COMMENTS (92%); PRIMARY SCHOOLS (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (88%); CLIMATE CHANGE (87%); HISTORY (72%); METEOROLOGY (71%); PERSONAL FINANCE (71%); TRENDS (71%); SCIENCE NEWS (69%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (69%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (66%); SMOKING (63%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (60%); TERRORISM (56%)  			AL FRANKEN (57%); BARACK OBAMA (56%)  	MINNESOTA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 St. Paul Pioneer Press All Rights Reserved  	Pioneer Press  															
The Tribune (San Luis Obispo, California)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	EDITORIAL: A glorious burden, and a heavy one  	COMMENTARY  	359 words  	Jan. 20--The American presidency has been described as a glorious burden, and never has that phrase seemed to ring more true -- at least in our lifetimes -- than it does today. When he is sworn into office, Barack Obama will indeed take on a glorious burden -- one so heavy that many are left wondering why on earth anyone would want it. LiNeBrEaKYet Obama takes office with the knowledge that the majority of Americans are confident in his ability to do the job.LiNeBrEaKAccording to a recent New York Times/CBS News poll, 79 percent of Americans are optimistic about the next four years under Obama. Of those who voted for John McCain, 58 percent feel optimistic about an Obama administration.LiNeBrEaKPerhaps the respondents felt that things can't get much worse. That would be understandable, given the disastrous worldwide economy, rising unemployment at home, the plight of the uninsured, continued war in the Middle East, global warming ... the list goes on.LiNeBrEaKStill, given the divisiveness of the Obama-McCain election, we find it remarkable that in a few short months, so many Americans have been able to move past the bitterness and rancor of the campaign to unite behind the new president.LiNeBrEaKThat says much about Obama's ability to inspire, but we believe it says even more about ourselves as a nation -- a nation of people willing to look past their many differences, especially in a time of crisis, to give a new president a fair shake.LiNeBrEaKGiven the high expectations for his presidency, Obama's honeymoon period could be short-lived indeed if he fails to deliver positive results, especially when it comes to the economy.LiNeBrEaKFor today, though, may the "glorious burden" not weigh too heavily on his shoulders -- and may we all join in celebrating a new beginning.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATE