The Tribune-Star (Terre Haute, Indiana)  	January 20, 2009 Tuesday 	EDITORIAL: Let us put divisions aside on this inauguration day  	COMMENTARY  	403 words  	Jan. 20--The litany of "challenges" facing the new president of the United States of America is long and ominous -- an economy in trouble, two wars, a lingering terrorist threat, climate change, chronic instability in the Middle East, and it doesn't stop there. LiNeBrEaKNone of these issues will be far from center stage today as Barack Obama is sworn in as the nation's 44th president. But for a brief period, as the peaceful transfer of power occurs in our nation's capital, Americans should make an effort to pause from their collective worries to revel in the greatness of this system of government and rule of law that has guided the country through good times and bad for the past 232 years.LiNeBrEaKAmericans are passionate about their nation and their legacy of self-government. And they should be. But that shared passion does not mean they are always in agreement. In fact, they are often bitterly divided along political and philosophical lines. Despite the rancor those divisions produce, we come together every four or eight years as fellow citizens to inaugurate a new president and pay respect to that individual we have elected to represent us around the world.LiNeBrEaKToday's inauguration is especially noteworthy as the first African-American president takes the oath of office. Barack Obama's election was dramatic in many ways, including its shattering of a significant social barrier. It is a proud and poignant moment for a country that has struggled throughout its history with racial injustice.LiNeBrEaKObama seems destined to enjoy a groundswell of goodwill as his term begins. How long that will last is uncertain, although partisan bickering in Washington, D.C. never takes much of a holiday. With all the problems facing America, the new president will need all the goodwill he can find.LiNeBrEaKFor the man who 