he downturn.LiNeBrEaKSo that's why "taxing the rich" is one essential solution to our crisis.LiNeBrEaKRobert BlauLiNeBrEaKBerkeleyLiNeBrEaKBART bus rampLiNeBrEaKBART's Oakland Airport connector project is dead because it can't fund a $386 million tramway between the Coliseum and the airport. A cheaper solution is needed.LiNeBrEaKAirBART shuttle buses suffer from three problems: they get delayed in traffic, riders must descend from the station platform to reach buses and buses have steps, making them hard to board with luggage. Relatively-inexpensive solutions exist to two of these problems while we wait for BART's solution to all three.LiNeBrEaKFirst, build a spiral, buses-only ramp at the Coliseum station from the train platform level to the ground. Passengers would no longer have to descend from the station to reach buses.LiNeBrEaKThey would ride down on the bus on the way to the airport. Second, eliminate stairs from buses. At the Coliseum and airport buses would descend into a well or climb a ramp, allowing passengers to wheel their luggage on and off the bus as they do on BART trains.LiNeBrEaKThere would be no going up and down escalators or elevators, or lifting luggage, and the cost would a small fraction of $386 million.LiNeBrEaKGordon DebooLiNeBrEaKWalnut CreekLiNeBrEaKOverspendingLiNeBrEaKThe Times' editorial position is dead wrong. California's economy is in the tank not because of under-taxation, but overspending.LiNeBrEaKJay MillerLiNeBrEaKPittsburgLiNeBrEaKBudget miracle?LiNeBrEaKI read with interest the Jan. 4 Sunday Forum solutions of the state budget problem put forth by readers.LiNeBrEaKI was especially interested in the solutions offered by Ernest Hampson and Pete Laurence as they are regular contributors to the opinion pages of the Times.LiNeBrEaKThey didn't disappoint, as I expected the same view points as they regularly express on any matter of interest. However, I disagree strongly with their proposals because slash-and-burn tactics are not the answer.LiNeBrEaKIf these individuals had their way, we Democrats, union members, teachers and anyone else whom they determined to be not to their liking would be eliminated.LiNeBrEaKThen the Republican right would come to the rescue with the same type of expertise that has served us so well in the past.LiNeBrEaKWe don't need to completely gut all programs and government to solve our budget problems if our elected representatives, both Democrats and Republicans, would just cooperate and do what's best for our state.LiNeBrEaKThat seems very unlikely given the constant comments of the far-right Republican partisan members of our community. The mantra of "no new taxes" is their battle cry, and that wont change.LiNeBrEaKWe just have to hope for a miracle but don't hold your breath!LiNeBrEaKDave SuttonLiNeBrEaKConcordLiNeBrEaKRight about GazaLiNeBrEaKThe Times explained the situation in Gaza exactly as it is and I commend you for it.LiNeBrEaKThe marchers and the media do not seem to be interested in the truth of what is going on and only consider what the media present   civilians and children being killed, homes being destroyed, and not in the real story, as you present.LiNeBrEaKCongratulations for doing the right thing and shedding light instead of heat on a very contentious subject.LiNeBrEaKEugene MyersLiNeBrEaKWalnut Creek		LETTERS and COMMENTS (94%); TERRORISM (90%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (89%); MOTORCOACHES and BUSES (85%); SHUTTLE BUS and VANPOOL SERVICES (85%); WEALTHY PEOPLE (73%); ECONOMIC DEPRESSION (70%); GREAT DEPRESSION (65%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (59%); GLOBAL WARMING (53%); ECONOMIC CRISIS (65%)  			GEORGE W BUSH (94%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (94%) CALIFORNIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Contra Costa Newspapers All Rights Reserved  	Letters from our readers  															
Contra Costa Times (California) 	January 19, 2009 Monday 	Cal professor sends Obama a reading assignment  	MY TOWN; Alameda; Oakland-Berkeley; News; Local  	739 words  	Barack Obama certainly has a lot of goals to conquer as he becomes the 44th president of the United States, but understanding radioactive decay and uranium bombs might not be on his short list of things to do.LiNeBrEaKBut Richard Muller, a UC Berkeley professor of physics and past winner of the MacArthur Fellowship, commonly called the "genius award," hopes Obama, 47, will take time out to read his book "Physics for Future Presidents: The Science Behind the Headlines."LiNeBrEaKHe said he has sent several copies to Obama's advisers and even managed to get a book to Michelle Obama through a personal friend of his. LiNeBrEaKThe 346-page hardback, released last year, covers everything from the difference between a uranium bomb, a plutonium bomb and a hydrogen bomb to solar power to space and global warming.LiNeBrEaK"What I've done is taken physics and eliminated everything that isn't urgently important,'' he said from his Berkeley home.LiNeBrEaKMuller's book is not political, and he openly admits he sent a copy to people who work with former Republican presidential nominee John McCain before Obama won the election.LiNeBrEaK"Physics is nonpartisan, and I think that it's really important to realize that physics is nonpolitical," said the 65-year-old South Bronx native who came to Berkeley in 1964.LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are topics in his book that will enable the president to act quickly and wisely in the event of a terrorist attack or a nuclear bombing.LiNeBrEaKMuller explains in his book that the country likely will be highly dependent on fossil fuels for many generations and that there are no easy answers to global warming.LiNeBrEaKMuller said his book can lead the president through a wealth of conflicting information about a bevy of subjects, which if not understood could lead to "solutions" that will actually make things worse.LiNeBrEaK"The president can't just be told that a nuke in the hands of North Korea is a big danger," he said. "The president must understand what a big danger it is."LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are many valuable lessons for Obama   or any leader   in his book.LiNeBrEaK"We live in a high-tech world, and many of the decisions we face on an individual level and on the presidential level have high-tech components. If you are talking about alternative energy, you need to understand coal, clean coal, nukes, solar and geothermal energy.LiNeBrEaK"If you are going to be the leader of the country, you can't depend on simply picking science advisers to tell you what to do. Decisions (about alternative energy) can't be based on science alone. They have to be based on science, economics and business and even on issues regarding diplomacy," said Muller.LiNeBrEaKMuller teaches a class called "physics for future presidents" at UC Berkeley and used his wildly popular course (there are 512 students enrolled and a waiting list) as a blueprint in his writing.LiNeBrEaK"We talk about the physics of energy, we do a lot on nukes, we learn about Hiroshima and nuclear power, then I talk about space," said Muller, who has been teaching at UC Berkeley since 1974 and became a professor in 1980.LiNeBrEaKAbout half of those in his class are freshman, and many come to the class hating physics or being afraid of it, Muller said.LiNeBrEaK"I regard my students as being courageous," he said. "They are taking the course even though they dread physics."LiNeBrEaKIn his attempt to get his book into Obama's hands, Muller asked a friend (he won't say who because he fears his pal will be besieged with requests to pass on other books) who knows Michelle Obama to get her to slip it to her husband. He said he is hopeful Obama will see the book and maybe even read it.LiNeBrEaK"I suspect (Michelle Obama) will give it to him, but I don't know how to evaluate the promises of friends of 