lly make things worse.LiNeBrEaK"The president can't just be told that a nuke in the hands of North Korea is a big danger," he said. "The president must understand what a big danger it is."LiNeBrEaKMuller said there are many valuable lessons for Obama   or any leader   in his book.LiNeBrEaK"We live in a high-tech world, and many of the decisions we face on an individual level and on the presidential level have high-tech components. If you are talking about alternative energy, you need to understand coal, clean coal, nukes, solar and geothermal energy.LiNeBrEaK"If you are going to be the leader of the country, you can't depend on simply picking science advisers to tell you what to do. Decisions (about alternative energy) can't be based on science alone. They have to be based on science, economics and business and even on issues regarding diplomacy," said Muller.		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (91%); NUCLEAR WEAPONS (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (88%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (88%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); NUCLEAR CHEMISTRY (78%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (77%); SOLAR ENERGY (73%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (73%); TERRORISM (72%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); GEOTHERMAL ENERGY (68%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (60%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%); MICHELLE OBAMA (57%); JOHN MCCAIN (55%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (91%) CALIFORNIA, USA (91%) UNITED STATES (92%); NORTH KOREA (79%)  	January 24, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Richard Muller of Berkeley is the author of "Physics for Future Presidents, The Science Behind the Headlines," a book he is hoping makes it into the hands of President Barack Obama (Doug Oakley/Staff)  		Newspaper  	2009 Contra Costa Newspapers All Rights Reserved  	By Kristin Bender Oakland Tribune  															
