Daily Camera (Boulder, Colorado)  	January 19, 2009 Monday 	CU, OSMP to battle invasive plants on the plains  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	490 words  	Jan. 19--BOULDER, Colo. -- With the help of a $500,000 federal grant, a team of Front Range researchers is hoping to find new ways to deal with non-native plant species on the warmer, drier high plains. LiNeBrEaKUniversity of Colorado professor Timothy Seastedt received the grant from the U.S. Department of Agriculture to create a project focused on invasive plant species in the Boulder region. The research, modeling and outreach effort will try to find new and cost-effective methods for addressing plant problems in an environment that is seeing dramatic climate change.LiNeBrEaK"Things are hitting the fan in terms of environmental changes and their impacts on native plants," said Seastedt, an ecology professor and fellow at CU's Institute of Arctic and Alpine Research. "A number of invasive plant species have become better adapted for some of these altered Great Plains ecosystems than dominant native species."LiNeBrEaKThe program will focus on three species: dalmation toadflax, Canada thistle and cheatgrass. Those species are specifically threatening the conservation goals of Boulder's Open Space and Mountain Parks, which is partnering with CU for the program.LiNeBrEaKSeastedt has had success before in combating the influx of non-native species. In the late 1990s he and his colleagues successfully controlled knapweed, which was taking over some Boulder County grasslands. They used a species of weevil to consume knapweed seeds and foliage, and plan on using other insects for this project.LiNeBrEaKBut there will be more challenges now, partially because of climate change. Seastedt said he has seen some "annuals" become more vibrant in the last few decades because of longer growing seasons and less moisture. Those species have also become particularly adept at filling "vacuums" created by weed-control methods used in the past.LiNeBrEaKThe annuals, such as stork's bill, have pushed out species that have dominated the plains ecosystem. So part of the project will be finding a balance between non-natives that are detrimental and some that may be positive.LiNeBrEaKSeastedt and his team will do a large part of their research on OSMP land, thanks to the partnership between the university and the city. The partners are also hoping to use each other to help get kids interested in plants.LiNeBrEaK"It is harder to get people's attention about plants. They usually say, 'Let's talk about bears. Let's talk about lions,'" said Steve Mertz, spokesperson and outreach coordinator for OSMP.LiNeBrEaK"But Professor Seastedt has an excitement about it that really makes it come alive."		CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (89%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (78%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (78%); GRANTS and GIFTS (78%); MAMMALS (78%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (78%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (60%)  	US DEPARTMENT OF AGRICULTURE (58%)  		COLORADO, USA (95%) UNITED STATES (95%); ARCTIC (79%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Daily Camera   	Zak Brown, Daily Camera, Boulder, Colo.  			Education  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090119-BO-PLANT-RESEARCH-GRANT-20090119  	BO  									
The Denver Post 	January 19, 2009 Monday   FINAL EDITION	Our romance with a '57 Chevy  	A SECTION; Pg. A-27  	685 words  	The fins, long, sleek and ending in a sharp-angled sideways "7" pointing toward the ground, defined this car. My older brother's '57 Chevy was a cherry red jewel posing in front of our house. It was the coolest coupe yet in those days of automobile architecture that changed each year like fall dress fashions.LiNeBrEaKIt was an era that underscored Veblen's conspicuous consumption, a socio-economic phenomenon that epitomized capitalism and the financial well-being it could produce if only Americans would just buy, baby, buy. LiNeBrEaKWe did, especially cars - one a year was how it was done then.LiNeBrEaKA recent story on National Public Radio told of a longtime San Francisco dealership that had stopped selling new Chevrolets altogether and was converting to a used-car outlet. Besides describing the pain of firing 45 long-time employees, the dealership spokesman reminisced about learning to drive his first Chevrolet at the age of 12, taught by his grandfather on the dealership lot. He said that while he would no longer sell new Chevrolets, he would continue to drive them exclusively.LiNeBrEaKThat sort of brand loyalty was nurtured by advertising tied to appeals to patriotism that branded not only an automobile but a lifestyle. Remember Dinah Shore's anthem to see the USA in your Chevrolet because America's the greatest land of all?LiNeBrEaKWe were a Chevrolet family. My mother always bought her cars from a West Denver Chevrolet salesman she had dealt with for nearly two decades. My first car was a used, olive green, four-door 1951 Chevrolet that I fueled at a self-serve station where a dollar's worth of tokens filled a glass container nearly to the four-gallon mark. I dispensed the gas into my tank and then did what Dinah implored.LiNeBrEaKLike Kerouac's car-crazed Neal Cassady, I drove the streets of Denver, around Sloan's Lake, up and down Colfax Avenue into Bear Creek Canyon and Evergreen, to the top of Lookout Mountain.LiNeBrEaKThat California dealership's market-driven decision is but the latest pang in a painful divorce in the century-long romance between Americans and automobiles they invented. The romance clich&eacute; is apt; novels have been penned and films produced adoring the car and the open road.LiNeBrEaKThe Bush administration's multibillion-dollar loan to the industry seems more of a last-ditch counseling effort to prolong this doomed relationship, which has been on the skids for the last three decades, than the long-term solution the carmakers desperately need.LiNeBrEaKCar consumerism has detoured into another direction. Asian and European manufacturers, encouraged by high gas prices and angst over carbon-fueled global warming, long ago steered the automobile conversation away from mag wheels and four-barrel carbs toward long warranties, controlled emissions, fuel efficiency, hybrids and voltage.LiNeBrEaKSimply, Americans stopped wanting what the American car dealers were selling. Because of their stubborn insistence on pushing the fuel-hungry, power-boasting behemoths of yore, the domestic manufacturers are experiencing the economic consequences of a pass&eacute; business strategy based primarily, like the elements of a failed marriage, on looks and status.LiNeBrEaKIt was a blast, in those days of my Denver driving youth, hanging dice from the rear-view mirror, dangling arms out the rolled down window that let in a summer breeze, blaring KIMN radio's electric guitars on car speakers and gunning the engine as we shifted our four-on- the-floor down 16th Street on Friday nights. Our cars then were the centers of everything, where deals were made, hamburger-and- fries meals devoured at the Sheridan Boulevard AandW, movies watched at the West drive-in, kisses savored in parks.LiNeBrEaKThe slogan then, that what is good for General Motors is good for America, is now a plea. Instead of "See the USA," the song became: "Save the USA; Drive a Chevrolet."LiNeBrEaKBut the American public stopped buying into it, and it is questionable whether they will come back.LiNeBrEaKSteve Hallock, a University of Colorado graduate and author of ``Editorial and Opinion: The Dwindling Marketplace of Ideas in Today's News.'' He teaches journalism at Point Park University in Pittsburgh.		AUTOMAKERS (89%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS (78%); AUTOMOBILE MFG (78%); USED CAR DEALERS (78%); AUTOMOTIVE MFG (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); BRANDING (71%); PUBLIC BROADCASTING (69%); NOVELS and SHORT STORIES (69%); PUBLIC RADIO (69%); EMISSIONS (67%); BRAND EQUITY (66%); OIL and GAS PRICES (62%); PRODUCT WARRANTIES (60%); GLOBAL WARMING (60%)  	NATIONAL PUBLIC RADIO (56%)  	NATIONAL PUBLIC RADIO (56%)  		DENVER, CO, USA (91%); SAN FRANCISCO, CA, USA (79%) COLORADO, USA (91%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%); EUROPE (77%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  		Column  	Newspaper  	2009 The Denver Post All Rights Reserved  	Steve Hallock Guest Commentary  															
