r jobLiNeBrEaKOn being president of the United States: I don't think that 98 percent of Americans really understand the impact of being president. I run a small company, and I know the problems I have daily. The president has the problems of the whole world. It doesn't matter who you are or the color of your skin. It's still the same.LiNeBrEaK- CARL J. SCHIRO, HoustonLiNeBrEaKLet's build planes like thatLiNeBrEaKREGARDING Friday's Page One article "FIRST A TAKEOFF, THEN A 'MIRACLE' / EXPLOSION: Witnesses say birds may have caused N.Y. jet crash": Besides the professional work of the pilots and crew, Americans might want to ask themselves why an Airbus made by the French is equipped with a mechanism to seal all the doors/openings on the plane, enabling it to float for a period of time. Strangely, our profit-oriented U.S. companies often feel it is not cost effective and do not provide all our planes with this capability. There were 155 lives preserved for all their families and our nation. It seems very cost effective to me.LiNeBrEaK- NANCY WILLIAMS, KatyLiNeBrEaKA doctor's advice on fluLiNeBrEaKIn response to the recent Chronicle article regarding recent reports of influenza strain resistance to Tamiflu, I wanted to take the opportunity to reinforce the importance of annual influenza vaccination with your readers. (Please see "NEW STRAIN OF FLU HITS AREA / CDC advises combined drugs to treat children," Page One, Jan. 9.)LiNeBrEaKWorking at Texas Children's Hospital, I see firsthand how dangerous the influenza virus can be for my patients, especially for the ones at increased risk for serious complications (such as those with chronic medical conditions like asthma). I emphasize to parents the best way to help prevent the spread of influenza is through an annual vaccination and encourage the entire family and all close contacts to get immunized.LiNeBrEaKI have joined with the American Lung Association's Faces of Influenza educational initiative. This campaign is designed to help our community put a "face" on this serious disease and recognize the importance of annual influenza immunization for themselves and their loved ones.LiNeBrEaKThe Centers for Disease Control and Prevention estimates more than four out of five individuals should get vaccinated against influenza this year. In Houston, on average, between 97,681 and 390,726 people will suffer from influenza.LiNeBrEaKThe flu season usually peaks in February or March, so there is still time for individuals to get vaccinated if they have not yet done so this season. I speak for my profession and encourage all community members to get immunized this year. You can also find a flu clinic on the America Lung Association's Flu Clinic Locator at www.facesofinfluenza.org.LiNeBrEaK- DR. CARLA M. DAVIS, assistant professor, Section of Allergy and Immunology, Department of Pediatrics, Baylor College of Medicine, Texas Children's Hospital		SEPTEMBER 11 ATTACK (90%); LETTERS and COMMENTS (90%); TERRORIST ORGANIZATIONS (90%); TERRORISM (89%); US PRESIDENTS (89%); VETO (78%); IRAQ WAR (78%); WAR and CONFLICT (77%); CHILDREN (76%); HUMAN RIGHTS (76%); LAW ENFORCEMENT (75%); INTERROGATION OF SUSPECTS (74%); NATURAL DISASTERS (73%); CENSORSHIP (72%); REFUGEES (72%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (71%); LOBBYING (71%); GOVERNMENT HEALTH INSURANCE (71%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (70%); WIRETAPPING (69%); JUSTICE DEPARTMENTS (67%); RELIGION (65%); SEX EDUCATION (63%); GREAT DEPRESSION (62%); STEM CELL RESEARCH (50%); EDUCATION (50%); BIOTECHNOLOGY and GENETIC SCIENCE (50%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); HEALTH INSURANCE (50%)  		AL-QAEDA (57%); US DEPARTMENT OF JUSTICE (55%)  	GEORGE W BUSH (95%); BARACK OBAMA (81%)  	UNITED STATES (98%); IRAQ (93%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  		Letters  	Newspaper  	2009 The Houston Chronicle Publishing Company All Rights Reserved  	KEITH M. PARSONS, JOHNNIE RUTLEDGE, OREN M. SPIEGLER, CARL J. SCHIRO, NANCY WILLIAMS, DR. CARLA M. DAVIS  															
