ector of the Minerals Management Service,  to complete your work on the Cape Wind project in an expeditious manner. LiNeBrEaKAfter seven years of exhaustive study, numbingly numerous public hearings and the nefarious intervention of well-funded opposition, it s time to get on with building a flagship project that will provide needed jobs and a source of clean, renewable energy that will ease our addiction to oil from foreign sources. With the Cape Wind project, New England would be the center of catalyzing a new clean-energy economy with many construction and professional employment opportunities.LiNeBrEaKIn 18 years of experience with 17 operational shallow-water offshore wind farms in Europe, there has never been a vessel collision with a wind turbine or between two shallow-draft vessels within a wind farm. Having been in a fishing vessel myself within the Nysted wind farm, between Denmark and Germany in the Baltic Sea, and observing the on-board radar, I can assure you that there is obviously no risk of misinterpretation of radar signals. In fact, the wind turbines are viewed as an aid to navigation. You can see exactly where you are. And one can see the majestic slowly rotating blades that are a source of energy from a fuel that is free and forever.LiNeBrEaKCharles Kleekamp, a retired engineer, is vice president of Clean Power Now.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); ARMED FORCES (90%); WEALTHY PEOPLE (90%); WIND POWER PLANTS (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (89%); WIND ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (89%); EMPLOYMENT (77%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (76%); NAVIGATION SYSTEMS (76%); RADAR SYSTEMS (76%); ENVIRONMENTAL PERMITS (73%); MARINE TRANSPORTATION ACCIDENTS (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (71%); APPROVALS (70%); PUBLIC HEARINGS (70%); ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ASSESSMENT (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL RESEARCH (76%) Editorial Commentary  		MINERALS MANAGEMENT SERVICE (56%)  	JIM OBERSTAR (57%); NICK J RAHALL II (56%