The San Diego Union-Tribune 	January 19, 2009 Monday 	It's time to rethink local food-stamp program  	LOCAL; Pg. B-2  	789 words  	The lean young man who becomes the 44th president tomorrow was, for a short time in his youth, nourished by food stamps, the relief program with roots in the Depression.LiNeBrEaKAs if we needed further proof that there should be no stigma to poverty, especially in this benighted day and age.LiNeBrEaKSan Diego County is notable, we are told, in that local participation in the federal Supplemental Nutritional Assistance Program -- that's food stamps to you and me -- is far and away the worst of any American metropolitan area. LiNeBrEaKOnly 29 percent of those eligible receive the debit card. Denver has the next lowest rate of enrollment, at 42 percent.LiNeBrEaKWhat should be the lowest-hanging fruit appears to be out of reach to the majority of San Diego's poor people.LiNeBrEaKSan Diego's poor may have more convenient options to forage for free calories. Food banks and charitable kitchens may have been more effective in these parts.LiNeBrEaKOn the other hand, the county's bureaucracy, encouraged to prevent fraud, could be especially forbidding in San Diego, a stronghold of conservative social values that include self-reliance.LiNeBrEaKWhatever the reason, anti-hunger champions, including San Diego Councilwoman Marti Emerald, are agitating for a higher rate of participation.LiNeBrEaKThe trendy adjective in policy circles is "smart," as in smart growth and, as recently articulated by Hillary Rodham Clinton, smart power.LiNeBrEaKMaybe the time is ripe for smarter food stamps. When the subject is the American way of eating, arguably the smartest voice on the public stage belongs to Michael Pollan, the Knight Professor of Journalism at UC Berkeley and most recently the author of "In Defense of Food: An Eater's Manifesto."LiNeBrEaKIn an open letter to "Farmer in Chief" Barack Obama, published in The New York Times, Pollan contends that energy independence, health care and global warming are inextricably linked to agricultural reform.LiNeBrEaKBoiled down, healthful food is created by traditional farming that requires far less fossil fuel than large corn and soybean producers and generates far less pollution.LiNeBrEaKMuch of the food we buy in supermarkets and consume in fast-food restaurants, Pollan argues, is artificially cheap and as bad for the human body as it is for the environment.LiNeBrEaKAmong his prescriptions for a sustainable food economy, Pollan's view of food stamps struck me as particularly pointed.LiNeBrEaK"It makes no sense," Pollan says to Obama, "for government food-assistance dollars, intended to improve the nutritional health of at-risk Americans, to support the consumption of products we know to be unhealthful."LiNeBrEaKAs it is, government debit cards cannot be used to buy tobacco and alcohol, "so why not prohibit something like soda, which is arguably less nutritious than red wine? ... We need to stop flattering nutritionally worthless food-like substances by calling them `junk food' -- and instead make clear that such products are not in fact food of any kind."LiNeBrEaKPollan acknowledges that redefining food will be difficult in a grossly obese culture that savors cheap, fast sustenance.LiNeBrEaK"One approach would be to rule that, in order to be regarded as a food by the government, an edible substance must contain a certain minimum ratio of micronutrients per calorie of energy. At a stroke, such a definition would improve the quality of school lunch and discourage sales of unhealthful products, since typically only `food' is exempt from local sales tax." Naturally, Pollan is an ardent champion of farmers' markets, the portable bazaars of locally grown food.LiNeBrEaK"Food-stamp debit cards should double in value whenever swiped at a farmers' market," Pollan suggests.LiNeBrEaKHe also advocates an expansion of WIC, which supplements the diets of at-risk mothers and children younger than 5: "Such programs help attract farmers' markets to urban neighborhoods where access to fresh produce is often nonexistent."LiNeBrEaKSan Diego County may be behind the curve in food-stamp enrollment, but in one sense, it's ahead.LiNeBrEaKThree farmers' markets run by the San Diego County Farm Bureau -- Lakeside, Valley Center and City Heights -- either do or will accept food stamps.LiNeBrEaKThe challenge for the county, according to bureau Director Eric Larson, is keeping up with the demand. Much of San Diego County's locally grown produce is trucked to more lucrative markets in Los Angeles and Orange County.LiNeBrEaKLarson estimates that 20 million food-stamp dollars a year are left on the table because San Diego's poor do not enroll.LiNeBrEaKIt's one thing to bring up the numbers of food-stamp recipients in the county. The cratering economy will solve that anomaly, I suspect.LiNeBrEaKWhat's ultimately as important is that struggling families be nourished by the same good food the lean new president has learned to love.LiNeBrEaKLogan Jenkins:LiNeBrEaK(760) 737-7555; logan.jenkins@uniontrib.com		FOOD STAMPS (91%); FOOD CHARITIES (89%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (89%); NUTRITION (89%); FAST FOOD (73%); RESTAURANTS (73%); DEBIT CARDS (70%); SUSTAINABLE AGRICULTURE (67%); SOYBEAN FARMING (65%); CRIME PREVENTION (52%); GROCERY STORES and SUPERMARKETS (50%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%)  			BARACK OBAMA (82%); HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (54%)  	CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The San Diego Union-Tribune   	Logan Jenkins  															
The Salt Lake Tribune 	January 19, 2009 Monday 	Landfills bring 'green' cash in N. Utah  	NEWS; State  	735 words  	Massive piles of rotting garbage dumped in landfills over decades in Ogden and Layton are creating cash, foot by cubic foot.LiNeBrEaKWeber County and Wasatch Integrated Waste Management System not only make money by turning methane gas generated in the trash heaps into electricity, but they're also selling carbon offset credits on the Chicago Climate Exchange.LiNeBrEaKWhile it's not a lot of money, it makes the green landfill projects even greener. LiNeBrEaKLast spring, Weber County made $102,000 selling carbon credits it was awarded by the Chicago Climate Exchange for reducing greenhouse gases in 2005, 2006 and 2007, said Gary Laird, the county's solid-waste manager.LiNeBrEaKLaird sold at the top of the market, when carbon credits were worth $6. 30 to $7 each. Friday on the Chicago Climate Exchange, the credits were down to $1. 95 each.LiNeBrEaKWasatch Integrated sold about $14,000 worth at a lower $2 market rate, but is holding onto more than 88,000 credits, figuring the price will rise with demand when the government gets around to regulating greenhouse gas emissions, said Wasatch's Executive Director Nathan Rich.LiNeBrEaK"It's sure worked out neat so far," he said.LiNeBrEaKChicago Climate Exchange is one of dozens of markets that have cropped up worldwide in recent years as pressure has mounted on countries and companies to reduce greenhouse gases.LiNeBrEaKWasatch Integrated, which burns and puts into landfills almost all the waste in Davis County and all of Morgan County's, joined in January 2007; Weber County joined that spring.LiNeBrEaKEach had begun capturing methane natural gas generated in capped trash heaps a few years earlier, mainly to keep it from migrating and, later, exploding.LiNeBrEaKThe gas is piped to nearby power generating stations. Weber County owns its station and sells electricity to Rocky Mountain Power -- a source that gave the county a tidy $240,000 last year. Wasatch Integrated's methane goes to a plant over the fence at Hill Air Force Base. Sales last year amounted to $40,000 for Wasatch.LiNeBrEaKWhile energy and environmental activists applaud such efforts, some are not so enthusiastic about the markets, like Chicago Climate Exchange, that let those curbing emissions trade on their own good deeds.LiNeBrEaKOne, Joseph Romm, a senior fellow at the Center for American Progress and author of the book Hell and High Water: Global Warming -- the Solution and the Politics -- and What We Should Do, calls them carbon "rip-offsets."LiNeBrEaKHe doesn't like that the Chicago Climate Exchange rewards companies or governmental agencies for past greenhouse-gas reductions.LiNeBrEaK"If I'm going to put up money, I want my money to go to a project that wouldn't otherwise happen," Romm said.LiNeBrEaKHe also believes there isn't enough scrutiny of the projects that earn the credits, and likens the market to the mortgage-backed securities market now in shambles.LiNeBrEaK"The offset business is unregulated and voluntary, and it doesn't take a genius to see unregulated markets tend to attract a lot of dubious players," said Romm, who is also editor of the Web site www.climateprogress.org . LiNeBrEaKRich disagreed.LiNeBrEaK"I've been through the verification process, and it's crazy, very detailed," he said. "If you're buying these credits, they're real."LiNeBrEaKThe Chicago Climate Exchange uses independent engineers to verify emission reductions and Wasatch, which is a full member of the exchange, also is scrutinized by auditors who verify that it is reducing emissions at its burn plant, as promised when it became a full exchange member.LiNeBrEaKWasatch agreed to reduce burn plant emissions by 6 percent by 2010.LiNeBrEaKRich also defended the market's practice of rewarding credits for past good work.LiNeBrEaK"What's wrong with rewarding people for good behavior?" he said.LiNeBrEaKAlthough Wasatch didn't expect to make a bundle of money, selling carbon offset credits can help new green projects pencil out, he said.LiNeBrEaKLaird said the sale of carbon credits was part of Weber County's calculation all along.LiNeBrEaK"This was what made our project feasible," he said.LiNeBrEaKkmoulton@sltrib.com What's a carbon credit?LiNeBrEaKIt's a marketable security, traded like a corporate stock or futures contract. New markets, such as the Chicago Climate Exchange, have emerged to award companies or government agencies "credits" for projects that reduce greenhouse-gas emissions. They sell the credits, via the exchange, to individuals or companies that want to offset their own carbon emissions -- or to appear more "green." The value of each credit fluctuates, as in any market.		LANDFILLS (93%); CARBON OFFSETS (90%); EMISSIONS (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); WASTE MANAGEMENT and REMEDIATION SERVICES (90%); METHANE (90%); POWER PLANTS (77%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (77%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (77%); ELECTRICITY MARKETS (77%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (77%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (77%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (77%); GLOBAL WARMING (75%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (73%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (72%); PRICE INCREASES (52%); ARMED FORCES (50%); AIR FORCES (50%); MORTGAGE BACKED SECURITIES (50%)  	PACIFICORP (58%)  			UTAH, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Salt Lake Tribune All Rights Reserved  	By Kristen Moulton The Salt Lake Tribune  															
THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER 	January 19, 2009 Monday 	'WARS ARE UNHELPFUL - YOU SHOULD STOP THEM'  	NEWS; Pg. A10  	466 words  	Asked to write a letter to the president-elect, 7-year-old Avante Price came up with a lot of questions and a few suggestions.LiNeBrEaKFirst, though, he shared an observation. LiNeBrEaK"You are just like a big me," the boy wrote, "because I am from Chicago, and I am biracial and have curly hair."LiNeBrEaKPrice's letter and those of several other students involved in the 826 Seattle writing center will be part of a collection released later this week, letters written mostly by children who have no memory of any president but George Bush.LiNeBrEaKThe collection - titled "Have Fun Running the Country: Kids' Letters to President Obama" and published by McSweeney's - contains letters written by students at 826 centers around the country.LiNeBrEaKBarack Obama's election came as a surprise, a welcome one, to many of the children studying at the Greenwood neighborhood writing center, said Toffer Lehnherr, a programs assistant there.LiNeBrEaKStudents age 6 to 18 come to the 826 center for help with schoolwork and writing workshops.LiNeBrEaKMany are children of recent immigrants or immigrants themselves, Lehnherr said, or face adversity at home.LiNeBrEaKAsked to write letters to the soon-to-be president at a Saturday workshop, the kids jumped at the chance.LiNeBrEaK"Students were saying, 'Now I could be president,' " Lehnherr said. "You tell kids they can be anything they want when they grow up. But to show kids, to have them see this kind of barrier being broken, it's really powerful."LiNeBrEaKSome of the students' writings read like notes to a pen pal, others like more serious letters to Santa. One child requests less expensive college tuition; he has a friend who couldn't go because he couldn't pay. Others request a better economy, cheaper gas, an end to the wars most can't recall living without.LiNeBrEaK"I think you should focus on education, and global warming, and the wars," wrote Renea Harris Peterson. The 9-year-old went on to note that "wars are unhelpful - I think you should stop them, if you can."LiNeBrEaKThe kids also offered suggestions, and advice to the Obama girls.LiNeBrEaKThe president-elect, one wrote, should sit down with a cool glass of water and get his bearings after the inauguration.LiNeBrEaKAnother advised Sasha and Malia on how to make friends at the girls' new school.LiNeBrEaKJory John, programs director for the 826 center in San Francisco, said the nonprofit launched the initiative in part because of the excitement so many of their students showed following the election.LiNeBrEaK"Most of these kids have only known one president all their lives," John said.LiNeBrEaK"Suddenly kids are saying they want to be president. I've worked with kids for (10) years, and I've never heard them say they want to be president."\ ON THE WEBLiNeBrEaKMore information about the organization is available at 826national.org .		CHILDREN (90%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (90%); CREATIVE WRITING (76%); EDUCATION (76%); OIL and GAS PRICES (73%); TUITION FEES (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS (70%) SCHOOL  			BARACK OBAMA (92%); GEORGE W BUSH (57%)  	SEATTLE, WA, USA (93%) WASHINGTON, USA (93%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Chart  		Newspaper  	2009 Seattle Post-Intelligencer   	LEVI PULKKINEN P-I reporter  							INAUGURATION 2009  								
St. Joseph News-Press (Missouri)  	January 19, 2009 Monday 	The light bulb dilemma: What you need to know about disposing of CFLs  	LIFESTYLE  	727 words  	Jan. 19--Congratulations! You've been doing your part to slow down global warming by switching to the new energy-efficient compact fluorescent lights (CFLs) -- those swirly bulbs that claim to use up to 75 percent less energy than incandescent light bulbs and last up to 10 times longer, according to the United States Department of Energy.LiNeBrEaKBut before you smugly pat yourself on the back, answer this: What do you do with them when they burn out? LiNeBrEaKDon't put them with your regular recyclables, says Tim Basta, co-owner of stjoegreen, a St. Joseph curbside recycling company. Although customers regularly try to leave them in the recycling bins, he says his company can't take them because the bulbs are considered a hazardous waste.LiNeBrEaK"I was kind of shocked to be honest," Mr. Basta says about when he first learned of the situation. "They are supposed to be the greatest invention since sliced bread and then there's mercury in it."LiNeBrEaKMercury is a highly toxic heavy metal that, when put into landfills, will leach into the ground water and contaminate streams, rivers, lakes and drinking water. According to the HTR-Group, a government-certified resource recovery facility in Kaiser, Mo., 1/70th of a teaspoon of mercury can contaminate a 25-acre lake to the point that the fish in it are unsafe to eat for 50 years. Although one CFL only contains a tiny amount of mercy (an average of 4 milligrams, according to the EPA), small amounts add up and are a hazard if not disposed of properly.LiNeBrEaKDISPOSELiNeBrEaKOne option is to take your CFLs to a hazardous waste collection site. The city of St. Joseph household hazardous waste program is held twice a year, once in the spring and once in the fall, says Public Works Director Bill Woody. You also can take your batteries, paint and other hazardous waste at the same time. The dates are not yet scheduled for this year, but it's always on a Saturday from 9 a.m. to 3 p.m., and the city advertises the date several weeks ahead of time. It's free, however, it is only open to St. Joseph resident property owners.LiNeBrEaKIt is legal to throw the bulbs in your regular trash, says Mark Conner, public information specialist with the Missouri Department of Natural Resources Hazardous Waste Program. If you do, the department recommends putting the bulb in a zipper-type plastic bag before disposal. The Environmental Protection Agency suggests two bags. Although it is legal, he says the department recommends recycling them instead. But it must be a recycling facility that handles bulbs with mercury.LiNeBrEaKRECYCLELiNeBrEaKProbably the easiest and best thing to do is to take your bulbs to Home Depot. All stores recently began accepting them for recycling at no charge as part of the Eco Options program. Simply bring unbroken bulbs to the service desk at any Home Depot. They'll take your batteries, too.LiNeBrEaKThe city of St. Joseph also will recycle them if you bring them to the landfill (not the recycling center). The cost is 50 cents per bulb (which is at cost for the city to recycle them), and anyone can bring them in. They also take other types of fluorescents for a fee. Call the landfill at 253-9764 for more information.LiNeBrEaKIf you break one, the Missouri Department of Natural Resources has a seven-step process to follow (www.dnr.mo.gov and click on Fluorescent Bulbs in the directory). Essentially, you should evacuate and ventilate the room for 15 minutes before cleaning it up. Then wear disposable gloves to pick up the broken pieces and put them in a glass jar with a metal lid or a zipper-type plastic bag. Clean the area with a wet paper towel and put the towel and the gloves in the container. Do not use a vacuum because it will spread the mercury vapor and dust throughout the room. The site also suggests that consumers may want to avoid using CFL's in bedrooms or carpeted areas frequented by infants, small children or pregnant women.LiNeBrEaKLifestyles reporter Sylvia Anderson may be reached at sylviaanderson@npgco.com		TOXIC and HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES (92%); MATERIALS RECOVERY and RECYCLING (90%); HAZARDOUS WASTE (89%); SOLID WASTE COLLECTION (89%); WASTE MANAGEMENT and REMEDIATION SERVICES (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (89%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (89%); HAZARDOUS WASTE TREATMENT and DISPOSAL (88%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (78%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (78%); HEAVY METALS and TOXIC MINERALS (73%); LANDFILLS (73%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); LAKES (72%); WATER POLLUTION (72%); HOME CENTERS (66%)  		US DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY (57%); CANADIAN FOOTBALL LEAGUE (54%)  		MISSOURI, USA (90%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 St. Joseph News-Press   	Sylvia Anderson, St. Joseph News-Press, Mo.  		NYSE:HD  	General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090119-JM-The-light-bulb-dilemma-0119  	JM  									
Tulsa World (Oklahoma) 	January 19, 2009 Monday   Final Home Edition	Inauguration is poetry in motion  	Satellite (new); Pg. D1  	343 words  	 You, created only a little lower than The angels, have crouched too long in The bruising darkness, Have lain too long Face down in ignorance. LiNeBrEaKThis verse was delivered by Maya Angelou in the inaugural poem she wrote on behalf of President Bill Clinton. Her words are especially applicable now, 16 years later. However, this time it is a new president, and a new poet.  LiNeBrEaKElizabeth Alexander has every poet's dream and nightmare composing the perfect poem, especially for an event so fraught with symbolism. LiNeBrEaKBut, if she's like Angelou, her poem will be focused on the nameless people in the crowd and beyond. And I feel so lucky to be just one of those in the crowd. LiNeBrEaKYes, I actually have a ticket to the inauguration. LiNeBrEaKI spent weeks naively daydreaming about what it would be like to huddle in the cold in Washington, D.C., when my mom finally broke the news that we were going. LiNeBrEaKNow that I've fully digested the fact, I can think about what this is actually going to entail messy crowds, frigid weather and sore feet. But I don't care. LiNeBrEaKThere should be no petty disclaimer such as the aforementioned onmy ticket. LiNeBrEaKThis kind of opportunity just doesn't come around twice in a lifetime. LiNeBrEaKBut even for those just sitting at home on the couch, this is a big deal. Never before have Americans straddled such a range of emotion: dread and hope. LiNeBrEaKEvery day there's a new headline of disaster: the economy, Iraq, Gaza, Afghanistan, global warming. &acirc;[#x20ac]&brvbar; And yet people are working for the solutions. LiNeBrEaKWhether you supported Barack Obama or not, you must want him to succeed, for America's sake. You must think that this inauguration symbolizes more than just the first African- American presidency or perhaps a new era of liberalism. LiNeBrEaKThere is the potential for this to be the starting point for a more united America, where more work is done and more problems are solved. LiNeBrEaKYes we can? Depends on where you stand. But all of us, inaugural attendees or not, will be standing on the verge of history Tuesday. LiNeBrEaKGabi Inhofe 581-8480 Booker T. Washington freshman satellite@tulsaworld.com		POETRY (90%); US PRESIDENTS (89%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (64%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%) Satellite (new)  			BILL CLINTON (58%); BARACK OBAMA (53%)  	DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (95%); IRAQ (79%); AFGHANISTAN (67%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Tulsa World   	GABI INHOFE Satellite Correspondent  															
USA TODAY 	January 19, 2009 Monday   FIRST EDITION	The scientific climate is changing;  Obama vows to 'value science,' but the budget and politics play roles 	LIFE; Pg. 9B  	1562 words  	The politics of science, which has been storm-tossed for the past eight years, heads for uncharted waters with the inauguration of Barack Obama.LiNeBrEaKThe Bush administration has fought a long battle with the nation's scientific community over funding and philosophy, and great divides have formed over such issues as global warming and stem cell research. Scientists are hopeful that Obama, who has called for increased research spending, will bring a new dawn. But how realistic are their hopes? And can the nation afford to make them a reality?LiNeBrEaK"My administration will value science. We will make decisions based on the facts, and we understand that facts demand bold action," Obama said at the nomination of Nobel Prize-winning physicist Steven Chu, a climate-change technology advocate, as the next secretary of Energy.LiNeBrEaKSays environmental scientist Donald Kennedy, Stanford University's president-emeritus: "I think we are seeing some really good first steps, appointment of people that the science community takes seriously, people who value science." LiNeBrEaKBut others sound a note of caution.LiNeBrEaK"The air of anticipation in the nation's laboratories and faculty clubs is not unfounded; the danger is that it will become excessive," writes David Goldston, a former chief of staff with the House Science Committee, in a recent Nature  magazine.LiNeBrEaK"Scientists are going to have to contain their insatiable appetite for dollars, and their tendency to see politicians as either with them or against them, for the current mood to survive much beyond inauguration," Goldston says.LiNeBrEaKThe most immediate change may be in the White House's attitude toward global warming.LiNeBrEaKObama has selected other key advisers who are strong advocates of taking action to address climate change. In addition to Chu, he picked Harvard's John Holdren, a climate and energy expert, to be his science adviser and marine biologist Jane Lubchenco as head of the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration.LiNeBrEaKObama has pledged to curb heat-trapping "greenhouse" gases by selling industries limited rights to release emissions, creating a "cap and trade" market. Cap and trade markets, such as the existing European Union Emission Trading Scheme, allow firms to buy and sell emission credits while keeping the total amount of emissions under an upper limit, or cap.LiNeBrEaKFor the average household, a cap and trade plan in which credits are sold to polluters -- and "dividend" money is returned to taxpayers -- would affect power rates, boosting annual household energy costs $809, a Resources for the Future analysis has found. But the poorest 20% of consumers would gain an average $145 through tax breaks.LiNeBrEaKStriving for balanceLiNeBrEaK"We must also take a leadership role in designing technologies that allow us to enjoy a growing, prosperous economy while reducing greenhouse gas emissions by 80% below 1990 levels by 2050," Obama pledged during the campaign. His energy plan includes yearly weatherization of 1 million homes, $7,000 tax credits for fuel-efficient cars and putting 1 million hybrid cars on roads by 2015.LiNeBrEaKThe Bush administration has not capped power-plant emissions, stressing the need for voluntary agreements and technological advances to address climate change. In 2001, President Bush renounced the Kyoto Protocol, an international pact to limit greenhouse gas emissions, on the grounds that it could hurt the U.S. economy and unfairly exempted China.LiNeBrEaKResearch involving human embryonic stem cells is another area that may change significantly.LiNeBrEaKIn his first televised presidential address on Aug. 9, 2001, Bush kick-started a long-running tussle with scientists by limiting funding for such research. The president allied himself with abortion opponents who are against the destruction of embryos required to harvest these stem cells. "While we must devote enormous energy to conquering disease, it is equally important that we pay attention to the moral concerns raised by the new frontier of human embryo stem cell research," he said.LiNeBrEaKObama has pledged to reverse Bush's funding limits and said they "have handcuffed our scientists and hindered our ability to compete with other nations." The National Institutes of Health allocated $655 million this year for stem cell research of all sorts, so human embryonic researchers would compete against other stem cell researchers for money from that pot. Studies also focus on animal and adult stem cells.LiNeBrEaKFor the average American, embryonic stem cell treatments are still years away, say researchers such as George Daley of Children's Hospital in Boston. Nearly 1,000 lines of embryonic stems would become eligible for research funding, Daley says, if Obama follows through on his pledge. Only 22 are now allowed under the Bush rule.LiNeBrEaKBush detractors, defendersLiNeBrEaK"Anything would likely be an improvement for scientists after Bush," says physicist Robert Park of the University of Maryland-College Park, who writes an Internet roundup of science politics widely read by researchers.LiNeBrEaKIn 2004, Nobel-winning scientists campaigned against Bush. The 250,000-member Union of Concerned Scientists and the 131,000-member American Association for the Advancement of Science have criticized administration stands on science questions.LiNeBrEaKBut some, such as current White House science adviser John Marburger, say the controversy has  overshadowed actions by the Bush administration that have won favor with conservation groups, such as declaring four oceanic national monuments, which created the world's largest marine reserve.LiNeBrEaK"When you consider the real behavior, as opposed to the symbols, the past eight years have been good for science," Marburger says. He points to the administration's steady support for research funding, including the doubling of the NIH  budget to about $28 billion in 2004.LiNeBrEaKAnd Marburger notes that the Bush administration started a new research agency at the Department of Homeland Security while also proposing a doubling of money two years ago for basic research.LiNeBrEaKBut right up to the finish line, the administration is battling it out with science and health advocates in high-profile science-related scraps over mercury levels in fish, the endangered status of polar bears and air pollution limits.LiNeBrEaK"Science enjoys a very high prestige," Marburger says. "That makes it attractive to anybody who wants to sell something. Everyone who wants to sell patent medicine or a cure for climate change will claim science is on their side."LiNeBrEaKAnd Bush has other defenders. "I don't think George Bush changed the fundamental relationship between the scientific and political establishments," says Arizona State University's Daniel Sarewitz, author of Frontiers of Illusion: Science, Technology, and the Politics of Progress, who remains critical of some administration moves.LiNeBrEaK"Federal support for science is usually a function of the size of the federal discretionary budget, no more, no less," Sarewitz says. "Virtuous noises about protecting the purity of science arise from politics just like everything else."LiNeBrEaKScientific integrityLiNeBrEaKSo what exactly do the scientists want from Obama?LiNeBrEaKFor one thing, more clout. In an Oct. 30 letter to the presidential candidates, 178 organizations (ranging from AAAS to the business-oriented Council on Competitiveness to the Center for the Study of the Presidency) urged the next president to make the science adviser a Cabinet position.LiNeBrEaKThe adviser heads the White House's Office of Science and Technology Policy and has a role in every scientific matter -- in today's world that is to say practically everything -- the federal government touches.LiNeBrEaKMarburger wasn't named until five months into the Bush administration and held a lower rank. Past presidential advisers, such as Clinton science adviser Neal Lane, now at Rice University, suggest this made him a less powerful figure. Lane was not the head of a federal agency but enjoyed Cabinet status.LiNeBrEaKIn past interviews, Marburger has downplayed that notion, suggesting that rank matters less than presidential access. The "real challenge" for the science adviser, he says, will be keeping federal support for science amid a budget straitjacketed by mandatory spending and tough economic times.LiNeBrEaK"President Obama does not need a high-profile science adviser," agrees physicist Richard Muller of the University of California-Berkeley, author of the just-released Physics for Future Presidents: The Science Behind the Headlines. "He needs a low-profile one whom he trusts completely, one who knows or can quickly gather the scientific information that the president needs, and educate him so that the scientific, technical and engineering information plays its proper role in the making of the decision."LiNeBrEaKAlso important is the membership of roughly 1,000 scientific advisory committees, called the "fifth arm of government" by Harvard science policy expert Sheila Jasanoff. The administration appoints members of the committees, which can exert tremendous influence on government decisions. Perhaps the best known are the ones advising the Food and Drug Administration on whether new drugs are safe for approval to the market.LiNeBrEaKMoves by the Obama administration in naming committee members and making their deliberations public, Jasanoff suggests, will influence how scientists see the new administration: "The same virtues of good science, openness and communication are good government and good democracy." 		SCIENCE NEWS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); 