Austin American-Statesman (Texas) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   Final Edition	For Griffin to fly, OU needs wingmen  	SPORTS; Pg. C01  	868 words  	COLLEGE STATION - After his Sooners' 69-63 win on Saturday, Oklahoma point guard Austin Johnson had a few choice words for Texas AandM's head basketball coach, the Aggies and possibly even the raucous Reed Arena crowd as he left the court.LiNeBrEaKMaybe Johnson was just upset about global warming or Bernard Madoff's hand in the $50 billion cookie jar. LiNeBrEaKOr as Aggies coach Mark Turgeon said, "He might have been talking to himself. No big deal."LiNeBrEaKOn the contrary, the senior point guard for the sixth-ranked team in the nation was the biggest deal in this very important matchup early in the Big 12 season.LiNeBrEaKOU pulled out a second road victory in as many tries, a week after holding off Kansas State by eight points in Manhattan, where it unveiled a nifty 1-3-1 zone defense for the first time. No other Big 12 team has a pair of wins away from home, and OU also catches Kansas in Norman in their lone meeting.LiNeBrEaKAdd in a blowout win over arch-rival Texas sandwiched between these road triumphs, and the Sooners have clearly established themselves as the team to beat in a league short on heavyweights.LiNeBrEaKBut if OU is to live up to its midseason ranking , it will have to get better backcourt help, as it did Saturday from Tony Crocker, freshman Willie Warren and especially Johnson.LiNeBrEaKBlake Griffin has to be considered one of the early frontrunners for national player of the year awards , but he'll need consistent play from his teammates for OU to claim the Big 12 title and some NCAA tournament wins . He got it on a day when he scored just 16 points and had only six rebounds before a rowdy crowd of 12,720.LiNeBrEaK"They played extremely well," Griffin said of his teammates, who include his older brother, Taylor. "I think we out-toughed them in the end. Taylor and I can't slack off and play mediocre basketball, but we're incredibly better."LiNeBrEaKTwice Blake Griffin left this game because of foul trouble. Twice, OU extended its lead.LiNeBrEaK"He still dictated the whole game," Turgeon said. "He knows how to play. You can hold him down. That makes their other players better. He's so smart. The reason Blake Griffin is better is all the players around him are better. They're all grown up."LiNeBrEaKNone moreso than the heavily tattooed, willowy Johnson, his postgame antics aside. Third-year Sooners coach Jeff Capel has spent immeasurable time with the 6-foot-3-inch guard from Amarillo, trying to groom him in Capel's own Duke image and develop night-in, night-out consistency.LiNeBrEaK"I was good, I wasn't great," Capel said, kidding about his college career. "Austin is playing at a high level right now. He's got a great assists-to-turnover ratio (of a Big 12-best 80 to 25). He's just scoring more now."LiNeBrEaKJohnson's 19-point game, peppered with clutch shots, seven assists and even a couple of blocked shots, was the latest example of an improved Sooners team. Capel's hungry to make a statement in the NCAA tournament after losing by 30 to Louisville in the second round of last year's tournament.LiNeBrEaKThe Sooners are more prepared this go-around.LiNeBrEaK"Give them credit. There's a reason they're 17-1," Turgeon said. "They make plays. And they believe. Not to say we didn't but ""LiNeBrEaKOU believed more when Johnson rained in a three-pointer from an eye-popping 26 feet at the shot-clock buzzer, extending the Sooners' lead to seven with 4: 02 to play.LiNeBrEaKThe normally unreliable long-distance shooter cranked out another three-pointer with 95 seconds remaining to keep the OU advantage at five. Johnson had three for the game in six tries, a drastic improvement over his 29. 4 percent marksmanship this season behind the arc.LiNeBrEaKBut then OU got a lot from Johnson it didn't expect Saturday.LiNeBrEaKHe's not known for his long-range accuracy or the feistiness that spilled over at the end of the game when, as Turgeon put it, Johnson "barked at our bench."LiNeBrEaKCapel admitted after his postgame news conference that the scene was out of character for his senior, but said he "got on him" about his verbal outburst. Johnson spoke to the media before reporters learned of the incident, but said earlier that his team was better-prepared to handle testy situations on the road and was more adapt at closing out games.LiNeBrEaK"We've been through this a lot," Johnson said. "We know we've got a target on our back because we're a top-five team and because of our record."LiNeBrEaKJohnson was just as instrumental in OU's win over Texas six days ago. The former high school teammate of Longhorn guard Justin Mason scored the first five points of the game and finished with 15, taking the game to the Longhorns' Damion James to the point where a steamed Rick Barnes took James out of the game.LiNeBrEaKThere will be nights when Johnson may defer to 6-6 Tony Crocker or the precocious Warren, a McDonald's All-American who can create for himself as well as his teammates, but on this one Johnson stole the show.LiNeBrEaKIs he setting the new standard in the Big 12, a league that sorely misses D.J. Augustin, Mario Chalmers and Acie Law?LiNeBrEaK"Collins is the best in the conference," Capel said emphatically, referring to Kansas' Sherron Collins. "But Austin has played well. On two of those threes, he wanted the ball. That was the main thing. He really wanted the ball."LiNeBrEaKAnd Capel is more than glad to give it to him.LiNeBrEaKkbohls@statesman.com; 445-3772		BASKETBALL (90%); ATHLETES (89%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY SPORTS (89%); SPORTS AWARDS (78%); STADIUMS and ARENAS (77%); SPORTS and RECREATION EVENTS (77%); TOURNAMENTS (70%); GLOBAL WARMING (57%)  			BERNARD MADOFF (57%)  	OKLAHOMA, USA (92%); TEXAS, USA (92%); KANSAS, USA (91%); NEW YORK, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Austin American-Stat