The Baltimore Sun (Maryland)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	The Baltimore Sun Jean Marbella column: Joe Flacco: The fame without the flash  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	1006 words  	Jan. 18--Maybe some time down the road, he'll be dating a series of those interchangeably beautiful women you see on the arms of athletes and actors. He'll be driving some hot stud-machine car, turning up in South Beach clubs and surrounding himself with an entourage of assorted hangers-on.LiNeBrEaKIn other words, maybe someday Joe Flacco will start acting like the NFL quarterback that he is.LiNeBrEaKBut for now, let's enjoy our pre-if-ever-hip QB and his helmet-haired, nearly uni-browed and decidedly non-metrosexual grooming. Let's enjoy the utter nerditude of a guy who drives his grandmother's Volvo to training camp and rooms with his little bro. Let's enjoy his total lack of flash, the bone-dry, ice-water, dead-eye diffidence with which he reacts to thrilling victories and agonizing defeats alike. LiNeBrEaKLet's sing an ode to Joe, the anti-divo.LiNeBrEaKHas there ever been such an amazing athlete on the field who once off it turns so ordinary? Well, actually yes, that would be his fellow Baltimore sports star, Michael Phelps, dolphin-sleek in the water, tripping on his own feet on terra firma. But even he has gone glam in his own way since temporarily hanging up the Speedos after his dazzling Olympics in favor of the cards and the cocktail waitresses of Vegas.LiNeBrEaKWhatever it is Flacco does in his off-hours largely seems to have escaped the tabloids -- but then, of course, no one was really watching for him until recently, when he's been a bit preoccupied with the playoffs. If the news stories are right, his nighttime activities largely involve falling asleep in front of the TV before the 11 o'clock news. Has anyone ever seen him, say, at Pazo, as Ray Lewis and Phelps were recently spotted, arriving separately but on the same night?LiNeBrEaKWe know where he'll be tonight of course, hopefully leading the Ravens to the AFC championship, which will only heighten the mania around our improbable leading sports man. But what has been funny about watching Flacco's growing stardom is that as the mania grows more feverish, he gets even freakishly cooler.LiNeBrEaKListening to his post-game interviews has been almost as much fun as the games themselves. I find myself rooting for him to say something even more deadpan and less quotable than the last time -- and he's never let me down. Someday, someone will have to make one of those beer commercials where they splice Flacco's actual statements with entirely different questions.LiNeBrEaKQ: Joe, in an effort to highlight the perils of global warming, the AFC championship is going to be played on a rapidly melting iceberg, meaning you may occasionally find yourself sloshing through Arctic waters. How will that affect your game?LiNeBrEaKA: I've never played in weather that cold, but I'm not really planning on it being too much of a factor.LiNeBrEaKQ: Joe, after your game-winning performance in the Super Bowl, as you were driving from the stadium, you joined a police chase that was under way and, breaking the speed of sound, managed to capture the killer of JonBenet. What was that like?LiNeBrEaKA: Same as any other drive.LiNeBrEaKThe other day, in an attempt to get to the bottom of the whole Flacconomenon, I tried to get into the heart of the heart of the beast -- at least the T-shirts.LiNeBrEaKYou've seen them on every other person in town -- "Joe Cool" or "Wacko for Flacco" or "Triple Threat See Joe Pass See Joe Run See Joe Catch."LiNeBrEaKSee Joe Save the Local T-Shirt Industry. Like the rest of the economy, it had been rather flat of late, said Craig Pfeifer, owner of Maryland Screen Printers, which has the exclusive licensing agreement to print Flacco shirts.LiNeBrEaKPfeifer had been to an industry meeting, where everyone was complaining about how T-shirts -- with the exception of those Life is Good ones -- just aren't selling. Not so here, though, where Pfeifer estimates he's sold more than 20,000 Flacco shirts -- there are five different designs -- since he received the licensing agreement about four weeks ago.LiNeBrEaKThey were still rolling off the presses when I stopped into the printing plant, located in an industrial park off Holabird Avenue in East Baltimore, where Pfeifer was trying to keep up with the demand for them. Workers pulled a stream of purple shirts, one after the other, off one machine, next to another one that was spitting out black ones bearing the visage of that fellow cool cat, Barack Obama.LiNeBrEaKFlacco has been an added boost to his usual client base -- Marriott, Constellation and Special Olympics of Maryland, on whose board of directors he serves -- and gotten him off to a good start in the new year.LiNeBrEaK"It's important for business. It's huge. It's not just me; it's the whole town," he said. "If the Ravens weren't in the postseason, the bars and restaurants wouldn't be full. Of course, the city might be a lot more productive on Mondays."LiNeBrEaKPfeifer and some of his 35 employees will be watching tonight's game right here, since they also have the contract with Reebok to print the official AFC Champion T-shirts.LiNeBrEaK"We gotta start printing as soon as the game ends," Pfeifer said. "We'll be printing at 10 o'clock at night until 7 o'clock the next morning."LiNeBrEaKPfeifer has met The Man himself, when Flacco came to the Special Olympics summer games last year. Pfeifer characterized him as, not surprisingly, "very quiet."LiNeBrEaK"He didn't even know if he'd be playing at that point," Pfeifer said. "I told him about the T-shirts I'd done before and said if he ever wanted to do some T-shirts. ... He just kind of shrugged and said, 'You think I could sell that many T-shirts with my name on it?,"LiNeBrEaKIf anyone can explain Flacco's appeal, perhaps it's Pfeifer: "It's his name. He's got a cool football name. And he can throw the ball 75 yards."		SPORTS (90%); SPORTS and RECREATION (90%); ATHLETES (89%); SPORTS and RECREATION EVENTS (89%); AMERICAN FOOTBALL (89%); MARINE MAMMALS (77%); CELEBRITIES (77%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (73%); INTERVIEWS (71%); ALCOHOLIC BEVERAGES (64%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); ACTORS and ACTRESSES (89%); BEER and ALE (64%)  			MICHAEL PHELPS (68%)  	BALTIMORE, MD, USA (90%) MARYLAND, USA (91%) UNITED STATES (91%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Baltimore Sun   	Jean Marbella, The Baltimore Sun  		OTC-PINK:VOLVY, NYSE:MAR  	Lifestyle  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090118-BZ-The-Baltimore-Sun-Jean-Marbella-column-0118  	BZ  									
Chicago Tribune (Illinois)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	U.S., Europe feel big chill, but climate change shows no end in sight, scientists say  	INTERNATIONAL NEWS  	779 words  	LONDON _ Where has global warming gone when we need it most?LiNeBrEaKAs cities from Chicago to London deal with an unusually bitter winter, weather records show that 2008 was one of the cooler years in the last decade. And the early months of 2009 are shaping up as "numbing" in the United States, according to the Farmer's Almanac, that nearly 200-year-old source of traditional weather lore.LiNeBrEaKThe chilly weather has fueled arguments that man-made global warming is bunk. "This (climate) 'crisis' is over," insists Joseph Bast, president of the Chicago-based Heartland Institute, which will sponsor a conference for climate change dissenters in March in New York. LiNeBrEaKBut most meteorologists say climate change shows little sign of slowing, and they blame our shivering misery this season on two key factors: normal variation in weather, which happens on a much shorter scale than climate shift, and short memories, or a gradual shift in what we think of as "normal" winter weather.LiNeBrEaKBritain this year has had its coldest start to winter in 30 years, with temperatures 5 degrees below average, but "this would have felt like a warm year as recently as the 1980s, and an exceptionally warm year in Victorian times," said Myles Allen, an atmospheric physicist at the University of Oxford.LiNeBrEaKIn most parts of the world, "what we regard as normal weather is the average weather over the past 10 years," he said. "We forget what it was like before then," even if someone occasionally drags out old photos of houses roof-high in snowdrifts or tales of slogging miles to school in near-impassable conditions.LiNeBrEaKBritain's recent deep freeze _ its coldest spell since 1996 _ is due to stalled weather patterns that have funneled in frigid air from Siberia and from continental Europe, which is also shivering after years of unusually mild winters, according to the Hadley Center, the United Kingdom's leading weather service.LiNeBrEaKStalled or unusual weather patterns also have contributed to remarkable snow and cold across much of the United States this winter. So far, this winter has been the 22nd coldest in 139 years of record-keeping in Chicago, and the fourth-snowiest in 124 years of records, according to Tom Skilling, chief meteorologist at WGN-TV.LiNeBrEaK"Just because certain areas cool down in the midst of an overall warming trend doesn't mean warming isn't going on," Skilling said. But the intensity of the cold and snow over the past two winters is raising some questions about how well scientists understand the interaction of an array of weather-changing forces, from sunspots to volcanic activity.LiNeBrEaKFor instance, one reason the last two winters have been chillier than normal, climate scientists say, is a cyclical change in Pacific Ocean currents known as La Nina. In La Nina years, cold ocean currents rise to the surface near the equator, often causing cooler winters in northern regions like the United States. An opposite warming effect occurs in El Nino years.LiNeBrEaKMeteorologists say La Nina phase in the Pacific is now ending, and some predict that by 2010 the world should again be seeing some of the warmest years on record _ warm enough that the Hadley Center is warning that poor residents of Britain may need help paying air-conditioning bills this summer.LiNeBrEaKBut other meteorologists see evidence of an unusual second La Nina on the rise in the Pacific, which could extend the current stretch of colder-than-average winters.LiNeBrEaK"It's a very complex puzzle, this whole climate thing," Skilling said.LiNeBrEaKSnowfall in Chicago in recent years still isn't anything approaching the snowy winters of the 1970s, when the Chicago average was 54 inches, Skilling said. But he said graphs that his research department has drawn up suggest "we're cycling back into an era of a little more snow."LiNeBrEaKWhether that is a simply a temporary break from a long-term rise in planetary temperatures or a new, not-well-understood winter trend isn't entirely clear. But "the fact that 2009, like 2008, will not break records does not mean that global warming has gone away," warned Phil Jones, director of climate research at the University of East Anglia in England.LiNeBrEaKIn fact, "when you step back and look at the bigger picture, the overwhelming evidence is that temperature is increasing around the world," said John Hammonds, a meteorologist with the Hadley Center.		CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); WEATHER (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); SCIENCE NEWS (89%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (89%); METEOROLOGY (89%); EL NINO and LA NINA (78%); TRENDS (77%)  				CHICAGO, IL, USA (90%); LONDON, ENGLAND (90%) ILLINOIS, USA (90%); NEW YORK, USA (79%); PACIFIC OCEAN (50%) UNITED STATES (93%); EUROPE (91%); UNITED KINGDOM (90%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Chicago Tribune   	By Laurie Goering, Chicago Tribune  	LONDON   			Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090118-BC-ENV-GLOBALCHILL  	TB  									
The Columbus Dispatch (Ohio) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   Home Final Edition	OUTDOORS;  Climate change threatens Ohio;  'Cracked Earth' video outlines dangers and what can be done about them	SPORTS; Pg. 09C  	828 words  	A dismal prognosis for polar bears and Pacific salmon isn't likely to incite panic among the bulk of Ohio's sportsmen. At the same time, most carry an inkling something is amiss in the immediate neighborhood.LiNeBrEaK"Surveys show that 70 percent or more of hunters and anglers say they have seen changes consistent with climate change," said Jim Wentz, an Ohio native who toiled for the Ohio Division of Wildlife before becoming a nationally known producer of films about fishing, wildlife and outdoor recreation.LiNeBrEaKWentz, a hunter and fisherman with a science background, saw the same things others were seeing and wanted to know why he was seeing them. LiNeBrEaKAfter study and discussion with experts, Wentz reached a conclusion: Global warming is real; it's caused in large part by humans; it's happening now.LiNeBrEaK"I have no doubts," he said.LiNeBrEaKWentz's Reynoldsburg-based company, Silvertip Productions, recently released Cracked Earth -- A Call to Action from the League of Ohio Sportsmen. The DVD, which is available and free to sportsman's groups, schools and the like, outlines what climate change means to hunters, to fishers, to wildlife watchers and to wildlife managers.LiNeBrEaKThe film includes a message on global warming from Jack Hanna, director emeritus of the Columbus Zoo and Aquarium, and excerpts from several on-the-ground experts, including Alan Wentz, Jim's brother and Ducks Unlimited's senior group manager for conservation.LiNeBrEaKWhat the experts relate is how disrupted cycles of heat and cold in North America are altering behavior in animals and growth in plants.LiNeBrEaKOne example: "Driven by temperature, some birds come north before there is anything to eat. Or, in the fall, they're hanging in when there's no longer food for them to eat," Wentz said.LiNeBrEaKBirds often can fly out of problems, he pointed out, and in some cases can cope with short-term variations in climate. However, damage to habitat caused by rising temperatures threatens the forest and wetlands homes of many animals common to Ohio.LiNeBrEaKAmong the tree species that will have a tough time surviving an over-warmed Ohio are sugar maple, black cherry, white ash, American elm, white oak, red maple, American beech, slippery elm, black walnut and yellow poplar or tuliptree. Many such trees are valuable as lumber but vital to the health of wild turkeys, deer, squirrels and songbirds.LiNeBrEaKInsects previously restricted to warmer climes are moving northward, some rapidly.LiNeBrEaKNorthern-dwelling Inuit people of late have been seeing "insects and bugs they have no name for," Wentz said.LiNeBrEaKSome insects, like the pine bark beetle and the spruce beetle, are wiping out huge tracts of forest. Canadian researchers recently reported that parts of the northern forest are releasing more carbon than they are absorbing because insects previously not seen in those regions have killed so many trees.LiNeBrEaKClimate models vary, meaning nobody claims the power to predict precisely what the world will look like in 80 years, but a consensus is emerging if present trends continue unaltered.LiNeBrEaK"The Union of Concerned Scientists is saying that Ohio's summertime climate could end up pretty much like Arkansas and wintertime like South Carolina," Wentz said.LiNeBrEaKIn such a case, southern pine forests would begin to replace leafy trees. Rivers, inland lakes and streams would become too warm to sustain cool-water fish like muskies, trout and saugeyes. Lake Erie would shrink by one-sixth, wiping out buffer wetlands and exposing land that today is fish-ridden reef and shoal in the western basin.LiNeBrEaKAs Lake Erie heats, dead zones can be expected to increase, and species such as walleye and yellow perch will give way to largemouth bass, bluegills and catfish.LiNeBrEaK"In general, we're looking at loss of habitat for cool-water and cold-water species," Wentz said.LiNeBrEaKWentz understands, however, that many persons, for reasons other than science, cling to doubts. Some even reject climate change altogether as a conspiracy against, for example, free enterprise.LiNeBrEaKBut the doubters and the disbelievers, particularly the sportsmen among them, are risking more than they realize. Hunters and fishermen began the conservation movement and need to recommit themselves to the danger, which to Wentz is clear and present.LiNeBrEaK"If we as sportsmen do not take an active role in doing something about climate change," he said, "hunting, fishing and wildlife-watching opportunities are likely to decline. That, to me, makes this a quality-of-life issue."LiNeBrEaKoutdoors@dispatch.comLiNeBrEaKBox Story: For more informationLiNeBrEaKGroups can obtain a copy of the DVD, Cracked Earth --A Call to Action from the League of Ohio Sportsmen, by sending an email request to climate@silvertip.net Jim Wentz is available to groups and schools for talks about the impact of climate change on Ohio wildlife.LiNeBrEaKFor detailed information on how some groups believe global warming is changing hunting, fishing and wildlife watching, check out the following Web sites:LiNeBrEaK* www.seasonsend.orgLiNeBrEaK* www.targetglobalwarming.orgLiNeBrEaK* www.ohioforwildlife.org		MAMMALS (90%); BIRDS (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (89%); WILDLIFE (89%); GLOBAL WARMING (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); SPORT FISHING (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (76%); ZOOS and AQUARIUMS (76%); MOVIE and VIDEO PRODUCTION (75%); POLLS and SURVEYS (72%); WETLANDS (71%); RODENTS (69%)  		DUCKS UNLIMITED (54%)  		COLUMBUS, OH, USA (90%) OHIO, USA (93%) UNITED STATES (93%); NORTH AMERICA (79%); CANADA (79%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Columbus Dispatch All Rights Reserved  	Dave Golowenski, FOR 