The Denver Post 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL EDITION	Livestock and bonds Life at Collins Ranch keeps rollin' along into fifth generation  	DENVER and THE WEST; Pg. B-01  	890 words  	WILD HORSE - Through decades raising beef amid health-food crazes, fuel-price crises and global-climate changes, the nemesis of 75-year-old ranching matriarch Polly Collins Johnson was as ancient as the hills: the tumbling tumbleweed.LiNeBrEaKRussian thistle breaks free from desiccated roots 30 miles to the north of here, rolls across the dryland prairie of eastern Colorado, and comes to rest against Collins Ranch fences that enclose 40,000 acres. The tumbleweeds pile up relentlessly, standing on one anothers' shoulders as if to better mock the cattle. In blizzards, tumbleweeds accumulate snow, and knock over fence posts. LiNeBrEaKThe other preoccupation of a dryland rancher, Johnson notes as she bumps her pickup through a close-in pasture, is waiting for rain.LiNeBrEaKAnd there lies the balance of a life tied to the soil: "Good rain brings more tumbleweeds later," she smiles.LiNeBrEaKEquanimity in the face of natural injustice has been one key to the long-term thriving of Collins Ranch and its 1,000-head herd. Johnson was honored by the National Western Stock Show on Saturday as only the second female rancher ever named a "Livestock Leader."LiNeBrEaKIn an age when the number of cattle ranches and farms dropped by nearly 400,000 nationwide in 20 years, Johnson held Collins Ranch together and is now ready to turn it over to two of her sons who live on the property. A daughter ranches two hours away in Wray.LiNeBrEaKThe grandchildren are thriving, 6 miles away at Kit Carson's tiny school, and far off at Princeton, Penn and Colorado College. Among the 13 grandchildren from her four children, there very likely lurks the heart of another Collins Ranch overseer who will extend family supervision into a fifth generation.LiNeBrEaKOne of the earliest female livestock judges in Colorado, Johnson is brutally honest when 421 red and black yearling heifers trip past her feet on their way to their hay- filled lunch wagon. This one is too skinny for birthing. That one is too short for the bloodline.LiNeBrEaKBut she simply beams when one of her own offspring crosses her path, as when 4-year-old Tess, daughter of her son Toby, gets underfoot during preparation of a hot farm lunch, hoping for a stray cookie.LiNeBrEaK"I'm so happy they like ranching life and chose to do it," Johnson said. Her ranching life would get plenty lonely otherwise, when the street address is little more than Milepost 439. "I feel very fortunate."LiNeBrEaKReading the landLiNeBrEaKLuck is for meteorologists, though, as Collins Ranch admirers well know. Holding a ranch through five generations and only 13 inches of rain a year requires animal stewardship, business savvy, kindness to ranch hands and a war of attrition with burrowing prairie dogs.LiNeBrEaK"They know how to read the land," said Bill Wailes, chairman of the department of animal sciences at Colorado State University. Johnson was a third-generation graduate of what was then Colorado AandM, in 1956, and was the first woman on the school's livestock judging team.LiNeBrEaK"They were always ahead of the game," Wailes said. "It's a neat legacy they have left. My guess is their kids are going to want to do the same thing."LiNeBrEaKThe Collins Ranch reading of the terrain this year is to take a break from the spring dangers of calving. A thousand-head herd usually yields about 945 calves in spring; nearly all males are sold to feed lots, while about 200 heifers are kept to become mother cows the next year.LiNeBrEaKLast summer was so dry on the ranch and prices were high enough that the family sold those replacement heifers for beef rather than spend money bringing in feed to supplement stunted pastures.LiNeBrEaK"It will be strange not calving, it's hard to remember our last skipped year," said Johnson, pointing to spots in her pastures where sudden spring storms and snowdrifts can make calving an adventure for all involved. "What do you think, Toby? Gosh, I guess it's been 20 years."LiNeBrEaKShe'll take it as a mixed blessing, she said. Toby, wife Amy and their three children (including Tess) will be using that calmer time this spring to move from an outlying ranch house 15 miles away to the original Collins Ranch home, which is being remodeled. Johnson moved out of the 103-year-old home, built with adobe from surrounding mud pits, a few weeks ago and into a newly built home that's an extension of the old hacienda compound.LiNeBrEaK"This is home"LiNeBrEaKPacking and unpacking brings up fond memories of her late husband, Rogers Johnson, who died in 1993 after a two-year battle with lymphoma. His stamp remains on every corner of the ranch, including on the walls of the new home he never saw.LiNeBrEaKPolly Johnson hung some of his favorite cowboy paintings by former Denver Post Sunday artist Paul Gregg, who was her great-uncle. The framed cowboys spur their steeds in bright sunshine streaming through windows that look out on the main pastures where Toby, brother Scott and the rest of the family glide on real horses.LiNeBrEaKJohnson is still figuring out where the kids put her silverware in the new kitchen, but she can't stop smiling at the prospect of growing older just a few feet from where she grew up.LiNeBrEaK"I did think of assisted living seriously," said Johnson, who in her running shoes, quilted jacket and perfect makeup seems much more likely to be doing the assisting. "A lot of my friends have moved to places like that. But this is home, I guess. This is where I like to be."LiNeBrEaKMichael Booth: 303-954-1686LiNeBrEaKor mbooth@denverpost.com		FARMERS and RANCHERS (90%); BEEF CATTLE FARMING (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); MAMMALS (90%); WEATHER (78%); METEOROLOGY (73%)  				DENVER, CO, USA (57%) COLORADO, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Denve