The Denver Post 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL EDITION	Priming pump against Ritter  	DENVER and THE WEST; Pg. B-01  	590 words  	And so it starts.LiNeBrEaKThe unofficial campaign to unseat Gov. Bill Ritter has begun as a crusade against his new oil and gas rules.LiNeBrEaKYou've heard the drill. Gas companies long have grumbled, illogically, that drilling regs would force you to pay more at the pump and otherwise bring end times to Colorado.LiNeBrEaKNow - months before the rules even go into effect - the state's most ambitious Republican is blaming them not only for a drilling slowdown but also for the economic downturn. LiNeBrEaK"They're contributing to industry pulling back. They're costing jobs. They're affecting the bread and butter in my district," says Senate Minority Leader Josh Penry, R-Fruita. "The governor needs to take responsibility."LiNeBrEaKThe oil and gas lobby is all too eager to fuel the hysteria, suggesting Ritter's regs may encourage terrorism aimed at our gas patches.LiNeBrEaK"Hopefully, we don't see that kind of thing come down to Colorado," said Ken Wonstolen, inciting Club 20, a group of Western Slope leaders, on Thursday.LiNeBrEaKThere are lots of reasons to knock Ritter.LiNeBrEaKHis oil and gas rules aren't among them. They call for basic accountability such as drilling away from homes and rivers.LiNeBrEaKFact is, new drilling has slowed in Colorado and nationally for reasons that have nothing to do with regulations.LiNeBrEaKAmong those are that natural-gas prices have plummeted 60 percent since July as part of a global market whose rates rise and fall with worldwide, not statewide, factors. Also, as Penry well knows, the credit crunch has hit businesses that are speculative and capital intensive, like drilling companies.LiNeBrEaKWhile Ritter's rulemaking dominated headlines in 2008, Colorado still allowed more drilling than any other Rocky Mountain state, issuing total permits second only to Texas nationally.LiNeBrEaKEven Penry's own sister disproves his arguments.LiNeBrEaK"It would be false to say" that Chevron's decision to curb investment in Colorado "is a direct result of the rules," that company's Kristi Pollard was quoted as saying in November.LiNeBrEaKPenry's lack of reason is stunning, like blaming global warming on the market crash.LiNeBrEaKSo, too, is the hypocrisy that he and his limited-government cronies are calling for a study group on the same rules the state worked on for 18 months, held 24 days of hearings and spent more than two weeks deliberating. The state even boasts - amazingly - that 95 percent of the wording in some drilling rules comes verbatim from industry.LiNeBrEaKIllogical, indeed. Unless Penry's Mountain Dew-induced rants have less to do with drilling than with raw politics.LiNeBrEaKStalling the rules enables Penry to drag out his crusade against Ritter long past April, when they're slated to take effect. That gives him a wedge issue pitting jobs against the environment and Western Slopers against Front Rangers - all leverage the 32-year-old Grand Junction resident could use to challenge Ritter in 2010, as expected. It also ups Penry's stock among the companies that helped put energy lobbyist Bill Owens into office and would relish bringing Ritter down.LiNeBrEaKThe governor so far is 0-for-1 against the industry, having been trounced in trying to convince voters to nix severance subsidies in November.LiNeBrEaKEven in a state that overwhelmingly wants more-LiNeBrEaKresponsible drilling, he has failed to make his case for why companies should be held accountable when pocking up our land.LiNeBrEaKRitter has 22 months to defend what has emerged all too quietly as his pet issue, or he risks being scapegoated and Swiftboated out of office.LiNeBrEaKSusan Greene writes Sundays, Tuesdays and Thursdays. Reach her at 303-954-1989 or greene@denverpost.com		OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (90%); GOVERNORS (78%); NATURAL GAS MARKETS (78%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (78%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); A