Detroit Free Press (Michigan)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	Pulte to raise home energy efficiency, hopes to be leader  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	878 words  	Jan. 18--Pulte Homes Inc. plans to increase the energy efficiency in homes built in Michigan this year, part of a national trend toward saving resources.LiNeBrEaKSteven Atchison, president of Pulte Homes' Michigan division, said the company has been building its homes to most of the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency's Energy Star requirements in Michigan. But now, the Bloomfield Hills-based builder is making it official.LiNeBrEaKMore than 200 builders in Michigan are involved in the Energy Star program, but Pulte is the largest. LiNeBrEaK"It is right for the environment. As a large national builder ... we think we can possibly influence other builders," Atchison said.LiNeBrEaKThe mainstreaming of energy efficiency is an offshoot of a rocky economy as people are more worried about energy costs and also a rise in environmental consciousness, said Mark J. Bennett, leader of the climate change practice team at Miller Canfield in Troy.LiNeBrEaK"Michigan builders are finally getting into the game," Bennett said. "You have significant challenges in residential homebuilding so it's a competitive tool on behalf of the homebuilder."LiNeBrEaKSaving energy costs were important to Justin Haas, 38, a Farmington Hills attorney, and his fiancee, Wendy Hoefer, 33, an economic-development worker in Detroit.LiNeBrEaKHaas and Hoefer researched several Michigan builders before deciding to buy a 3,700-square-foot Pulte home in Northville last month. The first utility bill hasn't arrived yet, but they are expecting savings compared with their previous homes.LiNeBrEaK"Obviously, one of the going trends was going green, and that was very important for us," Haas said. "It not only benefits the environment, but also impacts the long-term cost of living in the home."LiNeBrEaKAtchison said that the company had been building energy-efficient homes, but, for the Energy Star certification, some changes were made. The company needed to partner with an independent third-party inspector to examine its homes. And it needed to increase its insulation requirements to meet the home energy-rating score set by EPA guidelines.LiNeBrEaK"We want to continue increasing the efficiencies of our homes. We think energy costs are a concern for all our customers," Atchison said.LiNeBrEaKEnergy Star-certified homes can reduce energy bills by 30% to 50%, he said.LiNeBrEaKHaas said they found that many builders don't add the energy-efficient furnaces, appliances, extra attic insulation and foam sealing and other conservation methods because it adds to their costs.LiNeBrEaKAtchison said that making each home Energy Star-certified would cost just a few hundred dollars extra. Pulte Homes has built Energy Star-rated homes in many other states with a total of 69,500 through September 2008, according to Pulte.LiNeBrEaKThe company has 15 communities in Michigan that are building Energy Star homes, including ones in Canton, Lake Orion, Holly, Northville, Macomb and Novi.LiNeBrEaKPulte hired Don Nelson, president of D.R. Nelson and Associates in Lake Orion, to handle the home inspections. He conducts what is known as a Minneapolis Blower Door test to see how much air is leaking from a house. To do the test, a fan is put into a door opening. "The blower door test tells us how the whole house performs," Nelson said.LiNeBrEaKHe said a typical house that has not been sealed up to the Energy Star standard can leak 400 to 600 square feet of air, which is equivalent to leaving a small window open all the time.LiNeBrEaKThe interest in Energy Star has risen as the building boom has waned. Nelson said he started working with Pulte on the Energy Star plan in 2007. The company committed to it last summer and then in October, new state energy codes took effect that mandate energy-efficient standards in new residential construction.LiNeBrEaKBuilders can comply with the code in two different ways, Nelson said. One is the performance method, which measures how efficiently a home performs. The second is prescriptive, which means the builder constructs a home according to a chart of specifications.LiNeBrEaKBrian Yeck, project manager for MJC Builders in Macomb Township, started building to Energy Star specifications in 2007.LiNeBrEaK"We were trying to be one step ahead just like Pulte when we started this program," Yeck said. "Now everyone pretty much has to comply with this code."LiNeBrEaKAnd while there are other ways to comply with the code, Yeck said the company selected Energy Star because it is the most recognized by consumers.LiNeBrEaK"There is a name recognition with Energy Star. It is something people have seen, they are comfortable with," he said. "We wanted to convey to homeowners that you are getting a quality, energy-efficient home."LiNeBrEaKMJC has three condominium projects in Macomb County with the Energy Star features. But they have not built any single-family homes lately.LiNeBrEaK"When we get through these tough economic times and start building again, we will go Energy Star," Yeck said.LiNeBrEaKContact GRETA GUEST at 313-223-4192 or gguest@freepress.com		ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (94%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); RESIDENTIAL CONSTRUCTION (90%); TRENDS (89%); GREEN BUILDING (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (78%); COST OF LIVING (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (77%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (77%); CONSTRUCTION SECTOR PERFORMANCE (76%)  	PULTE HOMES INC (94%)  	US ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (58%)  		DETROIT, MI, USA (79%) MICHIGAN, USA (99%) UNITED STATES (99%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Detroit Free Press   	Greta Guest, Detroit Free Press  		PHM (NYSE) (94%) NYSE:PHM  	NAICS236116 NEW MULTIFAMILY HOUSING CONSTRUCTION (EXCEPT OPERATIVE BUILDERS) (94%); NAICS236115 NEW SINGLE-FA