Florida Times-Union (Jacksonville) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	REDEFINING 'EVANGELICAL';  Pastor Rick Warren is at the center of a debate on the very meaning of the word 	Pg. D-1  	970 words  	The howls came from the left and the right when President-elect Barack Obama announced that evangelist Rick Warren would give the opening prayer at Tuesday's presidential inauguration.LiNeBrEaKMany liberals were outraged because Warren openly supported last year's successful effort to ban same-sex marriage in California, his home state.LiNeBrEaKConservative Christians didn't like that such a high-profile evangelical Christian - and a Southern Baptist to boot - would so openly embrace a Democrat they consider to be one of the most liberal in history. LiNeBrEaKBut some say the controversy is a sign that white, conservative Christians, so influential in Republican politics for the past three decades, are losing their grip not only on political power but on the power to exclusively define the word "evangelical."LiNeBrEaKThe real source of confusion and frustration about Warren is that he has long bucked the accepted definition of what it means to be an evangelical Christian, said the Rev. Spike Hogan, leader of a Southern Baptist church in Jacksonville that is modeled after Warren's Saddleback church.LiNeBrEaKWhile conservative on issues like same-sex marriage and abortion, Warren has routinely reached across political and theological lines to combat poverty, AIDS and global warming.LiNeBrEaK"He's a [political] independent, his heart is for change," said Hogan, pastor of Chet's Creek Church. "Mr. Obama must have looked at him and said 'Here's a man I can ask to pray without an agenda.' "LiNeBrEaKIN THE TRUEST SENSE . . .LiNeBrEaKTo be theologically conservative and socially progressive is neither a novelty nor a contradiction, said the Rev. Timothy Simpson, a Presbyterian minister in Jacksonville and an editor of the academic journal Political Theology.LiNeBrEaKIn the truest sense, an evangelical is a Christian who believes in the authority of Scripture, holds that Jesus Christ is the sole path to salvation and who feels an imperative to share his faith with others.LiNeBrEaK"Literally, it means 'that which pertains to the good news, the gospel,' " said Simpson, also an adjunct religion professor at the University of North Florida.LiNeBrEaKBut in the media and in common usage the word has become almost exclusively associated with the religious right, a movement that came to prominence in the late 1970s, Simpson said.LiNeBrEaK"It created the impression that all evangelicals were only anti-abortion, anti-gay marriage ... denied global warming and didn't care about social issues" like hunger, education and AIDs, Simpson said.LiNeBrEaKBut the war, increased evidence of climate change and the growth of government became a concern even to the white conservative Christians who voted overwhelmingly for President George W. Bush in 2000 and 2004.LiNeBrEaK"As a result, the religious right has fragmented," Simpson said.LiNeBrEaKUniversity of North Florida political scientist Henry B. Thomas agreed, but suggested the cause of that fragmentation may be a generational phenomenon.LiNeBrEaK"I think that young evangelicals are much more likely to take seriously a thesis like global warming than are elderly evangelicals," Thomas said.LiNeBrEaK"Those differences may lead folk to different places on public policy issues even though they fundamentally agree on a lot of faith stuff."LiNeBrEaK'RELYING ON LABELS'LiNeBrEaKThe problem is that Christians are both the purveyors and targets of stereotyping, said the Rev. Mark Griffin, pastor of Wayman Chapel African Methodist Episcopal Church in Jacksonville.LiNeBrEaKBy and large, Griffin said, the black church falls in line with white conservative Christians on issues like abortion and gay marriage.LiNeBrEaKPost-election analysis concluded correctly that the large number of Florida's African-Americans who turned out for Obama in November also sealed the passage of an amendment to the Florida constitution banning same-sex marriage, Griffin said.LiNeBrEaKYet black ministers and churches are often considered liberals - and, therefore, not evangelicals - because their day-to-day focus is on issues like crime, education, justice and poverty, he said.LiNeBrEaKEvangelical "has become more of a political word than a religious word, and that's unfortunate," Griffin said. "Because the black church is largely evangelical - we are all supposed to spread the good news."LiNeBrEaKAt heart the misunderstanding stems from the desire to easily label individuals and groups, Griffin said. There are dissenters within every liberal and conservative church.LiNeBrEaK"We have to get beyond 'liberal' or 'conservative,' " he said. "We rely too much on labels."LiNeBrEaK'WONDERFUL PRECEDENT'LiNeBrEaKThe Rev. Ruth Jensen-Forbell won't be stereotyped when it comes to Warren.LiNeBrEaKThe lesbian pastor and her First Coast Metropolitan Community Church in St. Augustine were on the forefront of efforts to defeat the state constitutional amendment prohibiting same-sex marriage in Florida.LiNeBrEaKShe worked closely with Equality Florida, the gay-rights group whose leader, Nadine Smith, told the Times-Union Obama's selection of Warren "was a slap in the face of the gay community."LiNeBrEaKComplaints from the gay community about Warren may well have led to Obama's subsequent announcement that openly-gay Episcopal bishop Eugene Robinson would also lead a prayer during the ceremony, Smith said.LiNeBrEaKBut Jensen-Forbell - who describes herself as an evangelical - said she was delighted by Warren's selection.LiNeBrEaK"We use Rick Warren's materials in our church," Jensen-Forbell said about the evangelist's book Purpose Driven Life and related teaching materials.LiNeBrEaK"I don't agree with him on [same-sex marriage], on stem cell research and abortion, but that's his opinion," Jensen-Forbell said. "There's nothing in the Purpose Driven Life that's anti-anything."LiNeBrEaKBy picking Warren, Obama's is living up to his pledge to represent all Americans.LiNeBrEaKObama "is trying to integrate people with different views," Jensen-Forbell said. "In fact that's something we have lacked the last few years."LiNeBrEaKjeff.brumley@jacksonville.com, (904) 359-4310		RELIGION (97%); CHRISTIANS and CHRISTIANITY (92%); PROTESTANTS and PROTESTANTISM (90%); CLERGY and RELIGIOUS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); POLITICS (90%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); GAYS and LESBIANS (89%); GLOBAL WARMING (87%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (78%); SAME SEX MARRIAGE and UNIONS (77%); MARRIAGE (77%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (77%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); MARRIAGE LAW (72%); POLITICAL SCIENCE (69%); ABORTION (66%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (66%)  			BARACK OBAMA (92%); GEORGE W BUSH (50%)  	JACKSONVILLE, FL, USA (90%) FLORIDA, USA (94%); CALIFORNIA, USA (93%); KANSAS, USA (79%); ILLINOIS, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Photo MICHAEL GOULDING/Orange County Register In December 2006, Illinois Sen. Barack Obama (from left), Rick Warren, pastor of the Saddleback Church in Lake Forest, Calif., and Kansas Sen. Sam Brownback pray at the closing of their session at the 2006 Global Summit on AIDS and the Church in Lake Forest. BRUCE LIPSKY/The Times-Union Spike Hogan, pastor of Chet's Creek Church in Jacksonville, says Rick Warren as a "political independent" whose "heart is for change." WILL DICKEY/The Times-Union The Rev. Ruth Jensen-Forbell, pastor at First Coast Metropolitan Community Church in St. Augustine, praises Obama's choice of Warren. BRUCE LIPSKY/The Times-Union Chet's Creek Church pastor Spike Hogan said President-elect Barack Obama "must have looked at [Rick Warren] and said 'Here's a man I can ask to pray without an agenda.' " 		Newspaper  	2009 The Florida Times-Union   	JEFF BRUMLEY  															
Grand Rapid Press (Michigan) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   ALL S EDITION	The Bush record, issue by issue  	NATION / WORLD; Pg. A16  	724 words  	Ups and downs of George W. Bush's presidency:LiNeBrEaKBUDGETLiNeBrEaKBlack ink to red: Bush inherited a record $236 billion surplus, but the fiscal picture deteriorated sharply on his watch. The 2008 deficit was a record $455 billion.LiNeBrEaKThe national debt: It almost doubled, to $10. 7 trillion, as did the wartime defense budget, to $594 billion in 2008. LiNeBrEaKInterest payments on the debt were $451 billion in 2008.LiNeBrEaKCONGRESSLiNeBrEaKFirst term: Bush's popularity and role as a wartime president -- as well as Republican majorities -- translated into notable successes:LiNeBrEaK-- Homeland security.LiNeBrEaK-- Combating terrorism.LiNeBrEaK-- $1 trillion in tax cuts.LiNeBrEaK-- No Child Left Behind education reforms.LiNeBrEaK-- Medicare drug benefit.LiNeBrEaK-- Fighting AIDS in Africa.LiNeBrEaKSecond term: Bush was not able to cash in on his "political capital," failing to overhaul Social Security and immigration law. Hurricane Katrina and bad news from Iraq laid him low in polls.LiNeBrEaKECONOMYLiNeBrEaKRecession: The downturn that began in December 2007 has lasted longer than any in a quarter-century.LiNeBrEaKFinancial crisis: The most severe since the Great Depression:LiNeBrEaK-- American households have seen trillions of dollars in savings evaporate.LiNeBrEaK-- The Dow Jones average fell by 33. 8 percent in 2008, the biggest decline since 1931.LiNeBrEaK-- The economy has lost nearly 2 million jobs.LiNeBrEaKENVIRONMENTLiNeBrEaKClimate change: Bush spurned government-imposed emissions cuts, and he stopped in its tracks further consideration of the Kyoto Protocol as well as stopped Congress capping carbon dioxide.LiNeBrEaKWetlands: The administration fulfilled promises to scale back standards, narrowing what is considered a wetland.LiNeBrEaKENERGYLiNeBrEaKPolicy-making: An effort led by Vice President Dick Cheney called for more domestic production of oil and gas, development of renewable energy, reduction on reliance on foreign oil, greater support for nuclear energy and need to modernize the aging electric power grid. Most of those goals have yet to be met..LiNeBrEaKDrilling: The Bush administration gave energy companies greater access to tens of thousands of acres of federal land in the intermountain West.LiNeBrEaKFuel efficiency: Bush mostly opposed attempts in Congress to increase the federal Corporate Average Fuel Economy (CAFE) standard but finally embraced a 40 percent hike to 35 mpg.LiNeBrEaKHEALTH CARELiNeBrEaKMedicare drug benefit: The largest expansion of the government health care for the elderly eased the financial burden of more than 25 million seniors and disabled people. It cost less than anticipated.LiNeBrEaKGovernment coverage: Bush's attempts to reduce spending on Medicaid and Medicare by slowing the growth of provider payments were thwarted by Congress. He blocked lawmakers' attempt to expand an insurance program for children.LiNeBrEaKThe uninsured: At the same time, the ranks of those without coverage grew from 38. 4 million in 2000 to 45. 7 million in 2007.LiNeBrEaKStem-cell research: Bush put in place a policy that limited federal funding of research on human embryonic stem cells.LiNeBrEaKJUSTICE AND TERRORLiNeBrEaKExecutive authority: The Bush administration pushed it to its limits -- and the Constitution's -- in dealing with terror suspects, in the U.S. and at Guantanamo Bay. Federal courts overruled the president in both areas.LiNeBrEaKCIA interrogation: Bush also held the line on numerous attempts by Congress to rein in the CIA's interrogation, detention and extraordinary rendition program. He signed an executive order in 2007 deeming it compliant with a law requiring all detainees to be treated humanely.LiNeBrEaKNo second attack: Terrorists have not struck the U.S. since 2001. But Bush's central promise to get al-Qaida leader Osama bin Laden "dead or alive" remains unfulfilled.LiNeBrEaKAttorney firings: Justice Department investigations found that hiring and firing decisions at the once-fiercely independent agency was the result, in part, of White House political meddling. The firing of nine U.S. attorneys, including West Michigan's Margaret Chiara, ultimately forced the resignation of Attorney General Alberto Gonzales.LiNeBrEaKREPUTATION ABROADLiNeBrEaKTravel: Bush made less frequent trips than many presidents, and always seemed uncomfortable with the pomp. The unease was mutual, even among historical allies such as France and Germany.LiNeBrEaKGlobal support: Bush marshaled global support after the Sept. 11, 2001, attacks and quickly lost much of it. People in Europe as well as the few allies in the Muslim world clucked that he squandered good will by the 2003 invasion of Iraq.		MEDICARE (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (87%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (86%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (78%); ECONOMIC DEPRESSION (78%); GOVERNMENT BUDGETS (78%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (78%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (77%); PUBLIC DEBT (77%); NATIONAL DEBT (77%); SOCIAL SECURITY (76%); LEGISLATORS (76%); US NO CHILD LEFT BEHIND ACT (74%); CHILDREN (74%); ACADEMIC STANDARDS (74%); SCHOOL PERFORMANCE (74%); EDUCATION LAW (74%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (73%); DEFENSE SPENDING (73%); AGING (73%); PUBLIC SCHOOLS (73%); STOCK INDEXES (73%); CLIMATOLOGY (72%); TAXES and TAXATION (72%); RECESSION (72%); ECONOMIC NEWS (72%); NATIONAL SECURITY (72%); GREAT DEPRESSION (72%); TAX LAW (71%); IMMIGRATION LAW (71%); AIDS and HIV (70%); CHEMICALS (70%); TERRORISM (70%); EMISSIONS (69%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (69%); WETLANDS (69%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (68%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (68%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (68%); IMMIGRATION (68%); AUTOMOTIVE FUELS (67%); ELDER HEALTH (66%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (66%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (64%); AUTOMOTIVE INDUSTRY and ENVIRONM