The Idaho Statesman (Boise)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	Kempthorne's legacy may lie in his lesser-known efforts: His success in ending the Klamath River stalemate and protecting parks may outlive his ESA rule changes  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	1758 words  	Jan. 18--If Dirk Kempthorne gets his name in a history book, it's likely to be for listing the polar bear as a threatened species under the Endangered Species Act.LiNeBrEaKBut that decision, which showed global warming was a serious threat, came with faint praise because Kempthorne sought to take the teeth out of the listing so it couldn't be used to control greenhouses gases.LiNeBrEaKLike most of Kempthorne's achievements in his short time leading the 73,000 employees of the Department of the Interior, this one was tainted by the environmental record of the Bush administration's prior six years -- and by the agency's record of ethical lapses and questionable decision-making.LiNeBrEaKStill, even his critics acknowledge that Kempthorne cleaned up the corruption and the political interference that marred many of the agency's years under Bush. He also stood up for the nation's national parks, resolved one of the most polarizing water disputes in the West, and aggressively pushed oil and natural gas drilling -- either helping boost the nation's energy independence or further destroying the environment, depending on whom you ask. LiNeBrEaK"Secretary Kempthorne came in the wake of the Abramoff scandal and bitter record of Gale Norton, and he could only go up from there," said Bob Irvin, senior vice president for conservation programs at Defenders of Wildlife. "He didn't go far enough."LiNeBrEaKGreg Schildwachter, a former Kempthorne gubernatorial aide who works in the White House Council of Environmental Quality, said polar bears get the most attention, but Kempthorne's actions on parks and his approach to solving a controversy along the Klamath River may be his longest-lasting legacies.LiNeBrEaK"In retrospect, those very unsexy institutional things may have more reckoning in history," Schildwachter said.LiNeBrEaKThe former Boise mayor, U.S. senator and Idaho governor leaves office Tuesday along with his boss. He has no new job lined up and plans a long vacation with his wife, Patricia.LiNeBrEaKKempthorne helped persuade Bush to end the offshore drilling moratorium put in place in the early 1990s by Bush's father, and wrote a five-year plan for oil and gas development that included new drilling for the first time and kept aggressively pushing natural gas drilling in the West. Yet at the same time, Kempthorne took steps to improve protections for everything from mule deer to antelope and sage grouse -- not enough for some environmentalists.LiNeBrEaK"Whenever there was a conflict, the weight of the decision went to energy and industry interests, and that just didn't change," said William Meadows, executive director of the Wilderness Society.LiNeBrEaK1. THE POLAR BEAR BREAKS A LONG ESA SILENCELiNeBrEaKFor years before being pegged to head Bush's Interior Department, Kempthorne had made a political career of advocating alternatives to protecting animals and plants under the Endangered Species Act. His goal: to protect species with the least amount of regulations.LiNeBrEaKAnd for almost two years as head of the agency that makes these decisions, he added no new species to the list.LiNeBrEaKTo some, like Kieran Suckling, executive director of the Center for Biological Diversity, this was "the worst record in the history of the Endangered Species Act."LiNeBrEaKHis group filed the lawsuit that ultimately forced Kempthorne's hand.LiNeBrEaKThe environmentalists had a far-reaching goal: If polar bears were listed as endangered, and global warming was named as the culprit, it could force the government to stop greenhouse gas sources like coal-fired power plants all around the country.LiNeBrEaKFederal scientists told Kempthorne what the Bush administration had denied for most of the president's term: that global warming, caused in part by greenhouse gases in the atmosphere, was melting the Arctic ice where the polar bear lived. He had no choice but to list.LiNeBrEaK"Reality was outpacing the models," Kempthorne said. "I think history will prove it was the correct decision."LiNeBrEaKBut Kempthorne immediately began writing rule changes that would prevent using the act against distant power plants.LiNeBrEaKThose rules, which took effect in December, also allowed federal agencies to avoid consulting with fish and wildlife agencies to determine whether things like operating a dam or logging in national forests were jeopardizing an endangered species.LiNeBrEaK"The new regulations make the most sweeping changes in nearly a quarter century to the way the statute works and not in a way that will advance protection and recovery of threatened and endangered species," said Lewis and Clark Law School professor Daniel Rohlf of Portland, Ore.LiNeBrEaKThe rules may not survive a more environmentally friendly administration, but Kempthorne's action gave climate change an icon. Just as the bald eagle was long the symbol of the Endangered Species Act, now the polar bear is linked to the world fight against global warming.LiNeBrEaKKempthorne is satisfied with that result, and in a sense it was a natural passing of the torch.LiNeBrEaKHe was able to take the bald eagle off the list.LiNeBrEaK2. INTEGRITY NOTICEABLY LACKINGLiNeBrEaKInterior had troubles under Gale Norton, the biggest coming from the connection of her deputy Steve Griles to lobbyist Jack Abramoff -- a scandal that helped Republicans lose the Senate and the House in the 2006 elections.LiNeBrEaKWhen Kempthorne arrived, he came with marching orders from Bush: Take care of the ethics problems.LiNeBrEaK"The president told me to make some changes," Kempthorne said. "I did."LiNeBrEaKKempthorne has not been free of minor scandals himself. From the latest Taj Mahal-like bathroom renovation to accepting ski junkets as a senator, the University Place fiasco in Boise and his use of campaign funds for personal use as governor, Kempthorne has had his own ethics questioned throughout his career. But nothing rose to a level that threatened to slow his confirmation.LiNeBrEaKOne of the first Interior staffers Kempthorne met with was Earl Devaney, the department's inspector general, whose job is to audit agencies and investigate allegations of wrongdoing. He had been busy under Norton's watch.LiNeBrEaKKempthorne spent two hours with Devaney, asking his advice on how to change the culture of the agency and where to set the ethical lines. From his first day in office, Kempthorne told the entire staff that he would not tolerate ethical violations.LiNeBrEaK"The willingness of this secretary, as opposed to his predecessor, to hold people accountable for ethical failure is night and day," Devaney said.LiNeBrEaKDevaney was impressed enough by Kempthorne's attitude and the changes he instilled that he asked the secretary to address the National Inspector Generals' Association.LiNeBrEaKIn June 2008, Devaney reported that 12 Mineral Management Service employees and former employees handling billions of dollars in oil royalties had received numerous gifts from and improperly engaged in relationships -- including sexual ones -- with energy company staff, all before Kempthorne's administration.LiNeBrEaKKempthorne turned to one of his own to help clean up that part of the agency. Stephen Allred was a no-nonsense former Morrison-Knudsen executive and Idaho Department of Environmental Quality director whom Kempthorne had named assistant secretary for land and minerals management.LiNeBrEaK"He's never really told me what to do," Allred said. "He told me 'do what you think is right.' "LiNeBrEaKKempthorne acted immediately, and when Congress demanded a report, he testified along with Devaney.LiNeBrEaK"It was outrageous," Kempthorne said. "There has to be consequences for that kind of behavior."LiNeBrEaKBut it turned out that the agency's ethical lapses also were affecting policy.LiNeBrEaKIn December 2008, Devaney showed how the meddling of engineer Julie MacDonald, Norton's deputy assistant secretary for fish, wildlife and parks, undercut what was supposed to be the solely scientific listing decisions for more than 13 species.LiNeBrEaK"MacDonald's zeal to advance her agenda has caused considerable harm to the integrity" of the Endangered Species Act, "and to the morale and the reputation" of the Fish and Wildlife Service, "as well as potential harm to individual species," Devaney wrote.LiNeBrEaKDevaney calls the improvements Kempthorne made in the integrity and morale of the department "incredible."LiNeBrEaK3. A RENEWED FOCUS ON NATIONAL PARKSLiNeBrEaKKempthorne's first official conversation with Ken Salazar, the Democratic Colorado senator whom Barack Obama has picked for Interior, came during Kempthorne's own confirmation in 2006. The topic was a cause the two shared: protecting national parks.LiNeBrEaKSalazar asked Kempthorne to reconsider a 2005 plan that would have placed more emphasis on recreation and expanded the use of snowmobiles and ATVs in national parks.LiNeBrEaKThe plan proposed that in order for activities to be prohibited in parks, they must "irreversibly" harm the parks, instead of only harming them. Within weeks of taking over, Kempthorne reversed the decision.LiNeBrEaKHe persuaded President Bush to approve a decade-long program to upgrade and improve the national parks, and in 2008 Bush approved the largest budget increase in the history of the National Park Service. He established the centennial funding program that allows the government to match -- dollar for dollar -- private donations for the parks.LiNeBrEaK4. A STALEMATE BREACHED ON THE KLAMATH RIVERLiNeBrEaKWhen a judge in 2001 forced farmers along the Klamath River to aid salmon by draining their irrigation water downstream, they formed a "Freedom Cavalry" to unlock the headgates and close off the water. They captured national attention.LiNeBrEaKThe Bush administration sided with the farmers and vowed not to leave them high and dry, especially with the 2002 midterm elections coming up. Bush brought in Vice President Dick Cheney to force Interior officials to toe the line.LiNeBrEaKThe result killed more than 10,000 salmon -- exactly what the administration's own scientists predicted. This time Bush aide Karl Rove urged managers to stand strong.LiNeBrEaKTalks between the Klamath tribe, the farmers and the environmentalists found common ground in support of removal of four hydroelectric dams on the river, but it took Kempthorne to persuade the dams' owners to come aboard.LiNeBrEaK"I'll tell you what changed," Oregon Gov. Ted Kulongoski said after the longstanding impasse ended. "Dirk became the secretary of Interior."LiNeBrEaKRocky Barker: 377-6484		ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); NATIONAL PARKS (90%); MARINE MAMMALS (90%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (90%); ENDANGERED SPECIES (90%); WILDLIFE (90%); THREATENED and SENSITIVE SPECIES (90%); MAMMALS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (89%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (89%); NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (87%); CRUDE OIL and NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (87%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (77%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (77%); ETHICS (77%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); WILDERNESS (72%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (72%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (72%); OIL EXTRACTION (72%); OIL and GAS EXTRACTION (72%); GOVERNORS (69%); WATER RIGHTS (67%)  		DEFENDERS OF WILDLIFE (54%)  	DIRK KEMPTHORNE (96%)  	BOISE, ID, USA (79%) IDAHO, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Idaho Statesman   	Rocky Barker, The Idaho Statesman, Boise  			Real Estate  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090118-ID-Kempthorne-s-legacy-may-lie-in-his-lesser-known-efforts-0118  	ID  									
Knight Ridder Washington Bureau  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	Advanced car battery makers seek juice from stimulus plan  	WASHINGTON DATELINE  	856 words  	WASHINGTON _ The U.S. is struggling to catch up with China, Japan and Korea in a race to build the advanced batteries needed to power the electric cars of the future.LiNeBrEaKThe latest setback came last week, when General Motors picked a Korean company over an American rival to build lithium ion batteries for GM's Chevy Volt, which is due on the market late next year.LiNeBrEaKLithium ion is the current hot technology to replace the familiar lead-acid batteries used in most cars today, and the newer nickel-metal hydride batteries in hybrid electric vehicles, such as Toyota's popular Prius. LiNeBrEaKThe National Alliance for Advanced Transportation Battery Cell Manufacture intends to ask the U.S. government for as much as $2 billion in grants and loans during the next five years to jump-start the American lithium ion industry, while creating thousands of jobs in the process.LiNeBrEaKThe alliance, a group of 14 U.S. battery manufacturers that was formed in December, hopes it will be funded as part of the stimulus package proposed by Congress and the incoming Obama administration. Electric cars reduce the demand for oil and contribute less to global warming.LiNeBrEaKLithium ion is an extremely light metal atom that's lost or gained an electron and can be used to produce an electric current. Small lithium ion batteries are widely used in cell phones, power tools and laptop computers, but aren't yet ready for mass use in cars.LiNeBrEaKThe battery gap has major implications for the health of the U.S. auto industry and, more broadly, for U.S. competitiveness in the world.LiNeBrEaK"For 20 years, the United States has sat idly and waited for foreign markets to become the leaders in lithium ion technology," said Alan Eishafei, chief executive of MicroSun Technologies of Lisle, Ill.LiNeBrEaKExperts say a moderately priced battery with enough power and endurance may be the key to survival as the industry attempts the difficult transition from gasoline engines to an electric future.LiNeBrEaK"Whoever makes the batteries will one day make the cars," said James Greenberger, an attorney for the battery alliance. "If we don't secure a supply, we'll be at the mercy of foreign suppliers _ not just for the battery but for everything else that goes into a car."LiNeBrEaKAsian firms, backed by heavy government subsidies, currently dominate the growing advanced battery market. The U.S. has no large-scale domestic manufacturer, and must import almost all the lithium ion "cells" that make up the battery, said Greenberger, a lawyer with Reed Smith LLP in Chicago.LiNeBrEaK"Electric engines will help break our reliance on petroleum," Greenberger said. "They are cleaner and much more efficient than the internal combustion engine."LiNeBrEaKA123 Systems of Watertown, Mass., the company that lost the Chevy Volt contract, had recently applied for a $1. 84 billion loan from the Energy Department to open a large battery assembly plant in the Detroit area.LiNeBrEaKGM announced on Jan. 12, however, that it would buy lithium ion cells from LG Chem of Seoul, South Korea. The cells will be manufactured in Korea and assembled into battery packs at a new facility that GM will build in Michigan. Robert Lutz, a GM vice chairman, said that his company preferred the Korean design.LiNeBrEaK"LG Chem has massive support from the Korean government," Lutz said at the Detroit Auto Show. "Korea recognizes that advanced battery technology is a key component of the country's competitiveness."LiNeBrEaKAmerican lithium ion backers acknowledge that their batteries face a number of problems before they can be widely used in cars and trucks. They include cost, endurance and the need for a nationwide infrastructure of recharging stations.LiNeBrEaKThe Energy Department has set a target price of $1,700 to $3,400 for an all-electric car battery that could go 40 miles on a full charge.LiNeBrEaKThe lithium ion battery in the Chevy Volt is believed to cost significantly more than that, but the price should go down as more vehicles are sold. GM said the first Volts are expected to sell for about $35,000.LiNeBrEaKTheoretically, lithium ion batteries could be recharged in a home or office garage. Public charging stations can be set up in parking lots and shopping malls. Stations are currently being installed in Portland, Ore.; Boulder, Colo.; and San Jose, Calif.LiNeBrEaK"This offers new business opportunities _ charging stations at Starbucks or Wal-Mart," said Michael Brylawski, a vehicle efficiency expert at the Rocky Mountain Institute, an environmental policy organization in Snowmass, Colo.LiNeBrEaKBrylawski acknowledged that it's easy to install a few dozen recharging stations, but hundreds of thousands eventually will be required. "That's very different than (what) we have now," he said.		AUTOMOTIVE TECHNOLOGY (93%); MOTOR VEHICLES (91%); AUTOMAKERS (90%); BATTERY MFG (90%); ELECTRIC VEHICLES (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (78%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (77%); AUTOMOTIVE MFG (77%); GRANTS and GIFTS (74%); HYBRID VEHICLES (72%); LEAD (71%); GOVERNMENT GRANTS and SUBSIDIES (71%); IMPORT TRADE (71%); PUBLIC FINANCE (70%); MOBILE and CELLULAR TELEPHONES (69%); TELECOMMUNICATIONS EQUIPMENT (69%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (68%); ECONOMIC NEWS (68%); JOB CREATION (68%); PETROLEUM PRODUCTS (66%); MAJOR US LAW FIRMS (65%); LAWYERS (62%); GLOBAL WARMING (51%); LAPTOP COMPUTERS (50%); MOBILE and CELLULAR COMMUNICATIONS (78%)  	GENERAL MOTORS CORP (91%); REED SMITH LLP (81%); MOTORS LIQUIDATION CO (91%)  		BARACK OBAMA (55%)  	ILLINOIS, USA (79%); MASSACHUSETTS, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (96%); JAPAN (92%); CHINA (92%); NORTHERN ASIA (91%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO (from MCT Photo Service, 202-383-6099): BIZ AUTO-DETROITSHOW 13 DELiNeBrEaKARCHIVE GRAPHIC on MCT Direct (from MCT Graphics, 202-383-6064): 20080725 GM Vo