Milwaukee Journal Sentinel (Wisconsin) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   Final Edition	MARTIN LUTHER KING JR. &lt;|&gt; World must work together  	S Special; Pg. 3  	405 words  	First PlaceLiNeBrEaK Grade 6LiNeBrEaKBy William P. EstyLiNeBrEaK Golda Meir SchoolLiNeBrEaK Today is the day that we must live together in peace. The world is fighting, the economy is falling, and our hope is dying. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. won the Nobel Peace Prize in 1964. In his acceptance speech, he said, "Sooner or later all the people of the world will have to discover a way to live together in peace." Because of the problems in the world, we need to live together in peace sooner, rather than later. LiNeBrEaK The war in Iraq is causing many needless deaths. After 9-11, we had the world's sympathy on our side. Instead of just going into Afghanistan after al-Qaeda, we also marched into Iraq. Besides causing more deaths and costing lots of money, we also lost the goodwill of much of the world. We could have just stopped the threat in Afghanistan and lived in peace with Iraq. Dr. Martin Luther King Jr. taught nonviolence to work against discrimination and violence toward African-Americans. Fighting violence with violence never works because each person thinks what the other person did to them was worse. We can choose peaceful ways to settle our problems. We need to live together in peace.LiNeBrEaK With the whole world together we can eliminate problems such as world hunger, poverty and global warming. Living in peace would give countries the chance to build their economies. However, if we all act like different continents instead of one joint world, these problems will be almost impossible to solve. Dr. King helped bring attention to the fact that people were poor and hungry. Today, we can help by donating to causes that help the less fortunate. We need to live together in peace.LiNeBrEaK We must give our children hope that they will live to see a brighter future. If we live in peace, the world will be better for the next generation and the next and the next. The next president of the United States, Barack Obama, says, "Yes we can!" Yes, we can change the world. We may be individuals, but together we are a community, a town, a city, a state, a country, a world and a family. We must live together in peace.LiNeBrEaK Together we could start to see less destruction and more creation, less war and more peace, less hate and more love. Now is the time for us to live together in peace!		AFRICAN AMERICANS (77%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (89%); AWARDS and PRIZES (79%); NOBEL PRIZES (78%); IRAQ WAR (75%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); US PRESIDENTS (61%)  	JOURNAL/SENTINEL INC (62%)  	AL-QAEDA (56%)  	BARACK OBAMA (52%)  	MILWAUKEE, WI, USA (79%) WISCONSIN, USA (79%) IRAQ (93%); UNITED STATES (92%); AFGHANISTAN (91%)  	January 24, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Journal Sentinel Inc.   																
