The New York Times 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   Late Edition - Final	Green Building Trend Picks Up Pace in County  	Section WE; Column 0; Westchester Weekly Desk; YONKERS; Pg. 2  	722 words  	  LIVING in a building with geothermal heat makes Garfield Hylton happy. He enjoys knowing his carbon footprint is smaller because he uses less energy in his apartment here.LiNeBrEaK  ''I'm a positive person, and this is a positive thing to be doing,'' said Mr. Hylton, 28, a network technology specialist who lives at 66 Main Street, Yonkers's first geothermally heated and cooled apartment building. The system will pay for itself in energy savings over 10 years, said Ken Dearden, the developer of 66 Main.LiNeBrEaK  The new Ossining Public Library and the almost completed Mount Kisco Public Library  also use geothermal heating and cooling systems. They are part of a green building trend -- one that uses energy-efficient materials and technologies and minimizes disruption to the environment -- that has accelerated in Westchester over the past two years. LiNeBrEaK  The economic slowdown accentuates this shift in construction practices, said Steven Winter, an energy and construction consultant in Norwalk, Conn.LiNeBrEaK  ''Commercial and speculative projects have fallen off, but school buildings, affordable housing, government buildings and health facilities are least affected, and these tend to be green projects,'' Mr. Winter said.   He was chairman of the United States Green Building Council  in 2000 when it released its  Leadership in Energy and Environmental Design program, known as LEED, which  is a nationally recognized third-party certification process for the construction of green buildings.LiNeBrEaK  More than three dozen new building projects in Westchester have  sought  or completed LEED certification,  according to the Green Building Council, which is based in Washington.LiNeBrEaK  Building green in the county does not always mean building to LEED certification standards. Some local governments, like New Rochelle's and the county Department of Public Works, have committed to green building in principle but are not going for LEED sign-off because of extra costs of hiring consultants and paying certification fees.LiNeBrEaK  ''We are requiring all of our staff and consultants to provide us with a listing of options for the different levels of certification, and then we are analyzing the costs,'' said Ralph L. Butler, commissioner of public works for the county, who has begun offering LEED certification training to county engineers but has not adopted LEED standards.LiNeBrEaK  Reese Berman, the supervisor of the Town of North Castle, has been working with a team of county leaders on climate-change issues for the past few years and now, as a member of the Westchester Municipal Officials Association executive committee, is working on green guidance for local governments.LiNeBrEaK  ''It's hard when development is slow for towns to make this kind of legislation,'' said Ms. Berman, whose town has had to shelve plans for a new highway garage with solar panels. ''Unless there are really big incentives from the state or federal government, we are not going to see the kind of green initiatives we were hoping to see.''LiNeBrEaK  Yonkers, which has the most at stake in the county with Struever Fidelco Cappelli's $1. 6 billion redevelopment plan in the works, as well as other waterfront and downtown building proposals, has drafted the most aggressive green building standards in Westchester.LiNeBrEaK  ''We had heard that it was not going to be economically feasible,'' said Liam J. McLaughlin,  the Republican minority leader on the City Council, who  heads its Environmental Policy and Protection Committee. ''Then we talked to other developers and municipalities and found that the added expense is not that great.''LiNeBrEaK  Mr. Dearden, the developer of 66 Main, estimated that complying with LEED standards would have added up to 4 percent to his building costs.LiNeBrEaK  In a rare instance of unanimity, the Yonkers City Council is expected to pass a green building code this month that will require that most new construction, including the Struever Fidelco Cappelli project, comply with LEED standards, Mr. McLaughlin said.LiNeBrEaK  Mayor Phil Amicone  has not endorsed the law yet but is  likely  to support some form of green building code, said David Simpson, his spokesman.LiNeBrEaK  ''Especially in Yonkers, where we have the Hudson River and the Saw Mill River,'' Mr. Simpson said, ''we have to do the best thing to protect these environmental assets, at the same time that we are developing the city.''  	http://www.nytimes.com  	GREEN BUILDING (92%); GEOTHERMAL ENERGY (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (90%); TRENDS (89%); CONSULTING SERVICES (88%); COUNTIES (87%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (87%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (78%); ROAD and BRIDGE CONSTRUCTION (78%); CONSTRUCTION (78%); HVAC SYSTEMS (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); COUNTY GOVERNMENT (75%); LOW COST HOUSING SCHEMES (75%); PUBLIC LIBRARIES (75%); CLIMATE CHANGE (74%); SOLAR ENERGY (73%); CITY GOVERNMENT (71%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (68%); INFRASTRUCTURE (66%); ECONOMIC NEWS (53%); HIGHWAYS and STREETS (50%)  				CONNECTICUT, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO: A FIRST: Ken Dearden in 66 Main, which uses geothermal power.(PHOTOGRAPH BY SUSAN FARLEY FOR THE NEW YORK TIMES)                                		Newspaper  	2009 The New York Times Company   	By ABBY GRUEN  	YONKERS   														
Patriot News (Harrisburg, Pennsylvania) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL EDITION	Hiring of 'Wilds' adviser is affront to taxpayers  	REVIEW and OPINION; Pg. F04  	471 words  	Upon hearing that we are in for some of the coldest temperatures in years, I was reminded that we are still very much in the throes of winter. But while we endure the chilly conditions, there is climate change going on in Harrisburg. LiNeBrEaKThe mercury is rising in Gov. Ed Rendell's office, as a thaw in the hiring freeze has apparently begun. In the midst of these difficult economic times, the governor has taken job creation to a new level by bringing on board defeated former 75th Legislative District state Representative Dan Surra as a senior adviser for the "Pennsylvania Wilds," a 12-county region of northern Pennsylvania being marketed as an outdoors destination. Surra, who was voted out of office after 18 years when he was beaten by Matt Gabler in the November General Election, will be tasked with balancing the region's tourism with the surging interest in drilling for natural gas.LiNeBrEaKRendell's office is calling the hiring a "wise investment." The governor is banking on Surra's experience in the area, as the 75th District is made up of all of Elk County and the northwest portion of Clearfield County. The clincher is Surra's $95,000 salary, which is more than he would have made had he remained in office.LiNeBrEaKI do not have a great deal of experience in the region of the state that is of concern here. But a simple look at a Pennsylvania map leads me to believe that there is sufficient land in the 12-county region to keep tourists from being told that their camp can be found by turning right after the third drilling site. Also, while I will not deny that a balance must be struck, I will not agree with the notion that there are not sufficient government entities already in place that can work together to achieve that desired balance.LiNeBrEaKThe people of Pennsylvania are being asked to do more with less. We as employees of the voters who send us into state government to work for them must do likewise. The hiring of Dan Surra is a slap in the face to hard-working taxpayers who are fighting to hold on to their jobs while the economy crumbles around them. It is a classic case of repetition of services and mutual back-scratching that sours our citizens on state government.LiNeBrEaKOn Feb. 2, Punxsutawney Phil will emerge from his den in northern Pennsylvania and make his prediction on our meteorological future, and there will be good-natured debate as to the accuracy of his prognostication.LiNeBrEaKThe following day, Rendell will emerge from his office with a budget address on our economic future, and I guarantee he will forecast more than six weeks of financial "winter." What follows will be not-so-good natured debate that questions how sincere he is about finding solutions to a huge budget shortfall when he can't follow his own directives about spending cuts.LiNeBrEaKROSEMARIE SWANGER is a republican representing Lebanon Country.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); GOVERNORS (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (89%); COUNTIES (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); METEOROLOGY (77%); ELECTIONS (76%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (76%); JOB CREATION (76%); RECRUITMENT and HIRING (76%); ELECTORAL DISTRICTS (75%); VOTERS and VOTING (74%); PUBLIC FINANCE (72%); LEGISLATORS (72%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (71%); WAGES and SALARIES (71%); NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (68%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (68%)  			ED RENDELL (73%)  	HARRISBURG, PA, USA (92%) PENNSYLVANIA, USA (95%) UNITED STATES (95%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Patriot News Co. All Rights Reserved  							hrn  									
Patriot News (Harrisburg, Pennsylvania) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL EDITION	Obama's window of opportunity won't last long  	REVIEW and OPINION; Pg. F01  	867 words  	The results of the 2008 national elections and the unfolding economic crisis have given Barack Obama the support and resources necessary to launch a program of major policy change. The extent to which his leadership project will be successful depends in large part on the choices the new president will make during his first 100 days in office.LiNeBrEaKFew presidents in the past century have entered the Oval Office with such a leadership opportunity. In shattering the idea that Americans could never elect an African-American president, Obama received nearly 70 million votes, the highest popular vote total in history. He received 53 percent of the popular vote, the highest percentage for a Democratic candidate since Lyndon Johnson in 1964. He will have large, though not filibuster-proof, Democratic majorities in Congress. LiNeBrEaKThough his platform addressed dozens of issues, four major initiatives stood out: (1) a plan for economic growth that included tax cuts for the middle and working class; (2) proposals to help the U.S. achieve energy independence in 10 years, together with efforts to combat global warming; (3) a strategy to make health care more accessible and affordable; and (4) ideas for increasing educational opportunity.LiNeBrEaKIt is clear that the economy will dominate President Obama's first 100 days. The question is, what will happen to the rest of his domestic agenda? Before he goes forward, there are three key questions he must address.LiNeBrEaKFirst, how big should his agenda be? Scholars of presidential agenda-setting such as Paul Light of New York University argue that presidents should focus on only a few domestic issues in the first months of office. The model was President Reagan, who, like Obama, entered office during an economic downturn and focused exclusively on economic reform in his first year.LiNeBrEaKObama's potential agenda is large; however, it is likely that his early proposals on energy, climate change, health care and education will be tied to his economic stimulus plan. Spending on energy efficient buildings, creating green jobs in alternative energy, and computerizing all health records will be described in terms of infrastructure investment.LiNeBrEaKSecond, what should be the timing and sequence of introducing domestic initiatives? President Clinton followed the Reagan example to win congressional support for his economic program, but this forced him to delay introducing his health care reform plan until the fall of his first year. This proved a fatal decision.LiNeBrEaKWhether Obama will go further to include human investment proposals, such as increased funding for early childhood education or creating a new government healt insurance program, in his economic program is one of the most important decisions he will make. He must decide whether to address only the economic crisis in his first few weeks or to make his American Recovery and Reinvestment Plan the vehicle for comprehensive domestic reform.LiNeBrEaKThird, what strategy should be used to mobilize political support for the domestic program? When presidents have overwhelming party majorities in Congress as Lyndon Johnson did in 1964, they do not need help from the opposition; however, most first-year presidents need to build cross-party coalitions.LiNeBrEaKTo illustrate, Reagan overcame a Democratic majority in the House of Representatives by putting together a conservative coalition of Republicans and Southern, boll-weevil Democrats. By winning support from Ted Kennedy, George W. Bush was able to secure passage of No Child Left Behind.LiNeBrEaKThough he has spoken of wanting to bring sweeping bipartisan change to Washington, Obama will be tempted to push a more partisan program. Already some Democratic leaders in Congress have criticized his stimulus plan for providing too much in tax cuts in order to placate Republicans.LiNeBrEaKTo succeed in moving his domestic agenda through Congress in the first hundred days, Obama will have to be disciplined, strong, and lucky. He will have to tell powerful elements of his electoral coalition, such as labor unions, that they should be patient.LiNeBrEaKAnd, he must hope that unexpected international events or scandals will not drown out his message of reform. We should remember that as the new president deals with what is arguably the worst economic crisis since the Great Depression, he must simultaneously confront challenges in the Middle East and the ongoing threat of terrorism.LiNeBrEaKEven if everything breaks his way, Obama will learn, as all modern presidents must, that the window for major domestic change does not remain open indefinitely. Inevitably supporters will be disappointed, the opposition party will make a stand, the media will resume its adversarial role, and the public will want instant results from a plan that even Obama's advisers say will take months, if not years, to implement.LiNeBrEaKGiven the historic nature of his ascension to the presidency, the enormous challenges that face him, and the best wishes of the nation for his success, Obama has the opportunity to join FDR and Reagan as an architect of a new political regime. But his defining moment will not last long.LiNeBrEaKDr. E. Fletcher McClellan is professor and Chair of the Department of Political Science at Elizabethtown College		ELECTIONS (90%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); ECONOMIC POLICY (89%); ECONOMIC NEWS (89%); EMERGING MARKETS (89%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); FILIBUSTER (89%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (78%); POLITICS (78%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (78%); ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT (78%); PLATFORMS and ISSUES (78%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (89%); HEALTH CARE POLICY (78%); ECONOMIC GROWTH (73%); JOB CREATION (73%