or where this money is going. Where did it go and did it produce results?"LiNeBrEaK--Charles ThompsonLiNeBrEaKMelvin Johnson // Chairman, Capital Region Fair Housing CouncilLiNeBrEaKJohnson would like to see a public works project, similar to the Depression-era Works Progress Administration, one that would build bridges and roads.LiNeBrEaK"My fear however is that, if not administered properly, it will not impact the people it will be designed to help," said Johnson, who is also president of M.T. Johnson Group LLC.LiNeBrEaK"It should help not only the people who are unemployed right now, but also some of the traditionally underemployed individuals. I think we've got to reach further than putting people back to work who recently lost jobs," said Johnson, whose company does construction and diversity consulting. "I think any kind of economic stimulus should benefit people from the bottom to the top and from the top to the bottom."LiNeBrEaKAny new public works project must adhere to federal guidelines on hiring minorities and women, laws rarely enforced, Johnson said.LiNeBrEaK--Diana FishlockLiNeBrEaKPaul Navarro // President, Hispanic Chamber of Commerce.LiNeBrEaK"Like everyone else out there, we're hoping the stimulus package reaches the communities in a quick time frame to get everybody back in the working ranks," said Navarro of Navarro and Wright Consulting Engineers Inc. in New Cumberland.LiNeBrEaK"We'd like to see some Hispanics be appointed to cabinet positions where he would be more in tune with the needs of the Hispanic community," Navarro said..LiNeBrEaK"I think the other area that still needs addressed is the immigration reform," Navarro said.LiNeBrEaKIf illegal immigrants doing farm work were given guest-worker status, both the immigrants and farmers would benefit, he said.LiNeBrEaK--Diana FishlockLiNeBrEaKStephen R. Reed // Harrisburg MayorLiNeBrEaKReed said economic growth over the next two years could be supercharged by the federal stimulus package.LiNeBrEaKHe is requesting $700 million for the city.LiNeBrEaKEven if Reed only gets some of that amount, he said residents would soon see results in the form of streets under construction, more police on the streets and new local jobs.LiNeBrEaKAmong the Harrisburg requests: $7. 2 million for repaving 75 streets, $3. 1 million to hire 50 police officers, $9 million for a citywide recreation center and skating rink, $2 million for bus stops with LED signs and $98 million for the southern gateway project at Paxton and Second streets.LiNeBrEaKThe mayor also seeks $22 million for the city's two downtown hotel Proposals. Reed said both projects were put on hold as a direct result of the rocky economy, which tightened up financing and inflated commodity prices. --John LuciewLiNeBrEaKLinda Thompson //LiNeBrEaKHarrisburg city council presidentLiNeBrEaKThompson expressed both enthusiasm and caution about the impact of a potential spending spree on the city.LiNeBrEaK"We must think through these projects with the high spirit of stimulating our local economy for the purposes of creating sustainable jobs to stabilize our local economy," she said.LiNeBrEaKThompson said she would revive a plan by Brinjac Engineering for a $50 million upgrade of the city's wastewater treatment plant to meet nitrate removal standards. However, that plan was discarded last year by the Harrisburg Authority board appointed by the council in favor of purchasing credits to continue to discharge nitrates into the Susquehanna River.LiNeBrEaKThompson also would spend up to $100 million to upgrade the city's network of sewer pipes. "No matter how many new schools, businesses and new housing we create, if our underground current system is outdated and insufficient to handle the growth it defeats the purpose," she said.LiNeBrEaK-- John LuciewLiNeBrEaKDr. Roger Longenderfer // PinnacleHealth System CEOLiNeBrEaKLongenderfer said he hopes Obama continues a push to cover uninsured children. The logical first step is to 