Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pennsylvania) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FIVE STAR EDITION	Goodbye, Mr. Bush;  NO JOY FOR US 	EDITORIAL; ISSUE ONE; Pg. G-3  	242 words  	President George W. Bush, about to leave office, described his two-term presidency as a "joyous" time. Here's what the last eight years have brought us: an economy teetering on the brink of a depression, an unnecessary war in Iraq that is helping to bleed us dry and a war we're losing in Afghanistan, the shame of Abu Ghraib and Guantanamo, the pathetic response to Hurricane Katrina, the threat of global warming not only ignored but even denied, civil liberties disregarded and put in danger, the reputation of our country at an all-time low throughout the world and the list goes on. But for Mr. Bush, "Every day has been joyous." LiNeBrEaKIn a recent interview, President Bush was asked what achievement he is most proud of, and he responded that he's kept al-Qaida from having a safe haven in Iraq. When the interviewer noted that al-Qaida wasn't in Iraq until we invaded the country, he said, "So what?" That says it all.LiNeBrEaKOne has to wonder if "the boy in the bubble," as he once was described, understands the world or sees everything in terms of black and white.LiNeBrEaKPresident Bush's father said his son can leave office "with his head held high." Given the current president's arrogance, I have no doubt that he will hold his head high as he leaves. But if he could remove his blinders and face reality, he would leave with his head forever bowed in disgrace.LiNeBrEaKGoodbye and good riddance, Mr. President. May our country never be subjected to the likes of you again.		US PRESIDENTS (91%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); INTERVIEWS (79%); IRAQ WAR (78%); HURRICANE KATRINA (56%); GLOBAL WARMING (56%)  		AL-QAEDA (83%)  	GEORGE W BUSH (96%)  	IRAQ (94%); AFGHANISTAN (92%); UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 P.G. Publishing Co.   	ROBERT AIELLO, Whitehall  															
Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pennsylvania) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FIVE STAR EDITION	THE PRIESTLY ERA;  WHEN SCIENCE AND POLITICS WORKED HAND IN HAND 	ARTS and ENTERTAINMENT; BOOK REVIEW; Pg. E-6  	585 words  	Joseph Priestley was "a great, excellent and extraordinary man, whom I sincerely loved, esteemed and respected,"? John Adams recalled. He "was really a Phenomenon, a Comet in the System." LiNeBrEaKCelebrated for his discovery of oxygen, the process later called photosynthesis and soda water, Priestley was also a controversial theologian and political thinker.LiNeBrEaKHe had a profound impact on his native England and the fledgling United States, his home for the last decade of his life.LiNeBrEaKSteven Johnson, the author of "Interface Culture: How New Technology Transforms the Way We Create and Communicate," here uses Priestley's life to explore and celebrate the space that connected science, religion and politics in the late 18th century.LiNeBrEaKAlthough occasionally overheated and not always original, his account of a world we have lost is accessible and engaging.LiNeBrEaKThe great minds of the Enlightenment, including Benjamin Franklin and Thomas Jefferson, learned from the ascent of science that society could improve "if the light of reason was allowed to shine upon it ?," Johnson points out.LiNeBrEaKWith Priestley, they grasped the political power of the air pump and the electrical machine.?LiNeBrEaKIn addition to invoking "the spirit of the age,"?Johnson credits the emergence and circulation of so many revolutionary ideas at one time to the unstructured, cross-disciplinary environment in which?"dabblers and amateurs"?worked.LiNeBrEaKPriestley's roving intelligence,? he acknowledges, was better-suited to exploding old conventions than setting forth new paradigms. ?LiNeBrEaKPriestley's ideas, Johnson points out, were nurtured, spread and sustained by an increasingly robust information network, the Enlightenment era's ecosystem. Whether they are disseminated through clubs, correspondence, publications or the World Wide Web, ideas differ from energy in one fundamental respect: the supply of energy is finite, while ideas can gather strength as they "attract the attention of the ingenious."?LiNeBrEaKThe restoration of Charles II, Newton's theory of gravity and the South Sea Bubble, Johnson proclaims, with a straight face, occurred, in part, because Englishmen had developed a taste for coffee and a fondness for shoptalk in coffeehouses.LiNeBrEaKReplacing alcohol as the daytime drug of choice, coffee improves cognitive function. Create enough caffeine abusers in your society and you'll be statistically more likely to launch an Age of Reason.?LiNeBrEaKAs he embraces the "new openness" of the Enlightenment, Johnson sends a shot across the bow of American conservatives.LiNeBrEaKVoters, Johnson insists, should repudiate any politician who pushes a policy agenda without a good grasp of atomic energy, global warming, evolution and stem cell research.LiNeBrEaKFor better and worse, of course, specialization is here to stay.LiNeBrEaKJohnson admits that the Enlightenment world view may well be obsolete, especially as more and more ?progressives conclude that catastrophe is imminent.LiNeBrEaKJohnson maintains, passionately and persuasively, that to disconnect the timeless insights of science and faith from the transitory world of politics, to give up the sublime view of progress and to rely on the old institutions without conjuring new ones is to betray the core and connected values that Priestley shared with the American founders.LiNeBrEaKAnd that Priestley's legacy, the ability to understand life with ever-increasing precision, can be cause for hope that radical change is possible.LiNeBrEaKb&gt; "THE INVENTION OF AIR: A STORY OF SCIENCE, FAITH, REVOLUTION AND THE BIRTHLiNeBrEaKOF AMERICA"LiNeBrEaK/b&gt;LiNeBrEaKBy Steven JohnsonLiNeBrEaKRiverhead Books ($25. 95)		POLITICS (90%); RELIGION (89%); BOOK REVIEWS (79%); ASTRONOMY and SPA