Providence Journal-Bulletin (Rhode Island) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	How Europe can break Russia s gas grip  	COMMENTARY; Pg. 4  	740 words  	BLOOMINGTON, Ind.LiNeBrEaKMANY EUROPEANS have been learning a hard lesson: It s better to be upstream than downstream in a shared gas pipeline.LiNeBrEaKWhile Russia and Ukraine quarreled over payments for Russian gas, downstream customers felt the chill. Central and southeast European countries were especially hard-hit. Serbs and Bosnians plugged in electric space heaters to replace lost home-heating gas. Gas shortages were blamed for a production halt at an auto-assembly plant in Hungary. Bulgaria and Slovakia contemplated restarting mothballed nuclear-power plants.LiNeBrEaKGas is flowing again, now that Russia and Ukraine have inked a new gas-delivery deal. However, the new agreement may prove as volatile as the gas itself. LiNeBrEaKRecent history shows that when Russia signs even richer gas contracts downstream, prior agreements between Russia and Ukraine are imperiled. A new standoff could emerge in 2011 or 2012 if not earlier.LiNeBrEaKTo protect themselves, some European countries could build liquefied-gas terminals so as to diversify imported gas supplies. This is a costly option that fails to advance energy self-reliance.LiNeBrEaKA much-awaited gas pipeline from the Caspian, designed to bypass Russian sources, is another medium-term palliative. As intermediate solutions, docking points for liquefied gas and the Caspian route are seductive but their benefits are fleeting. The long run demands a bolder vision.LiNeBrEaKThe recent U.S. presidential campaign featured two nominees pledging to invest boldly in alternative energy and to diversify America s energy supply. But Europe s current energy-supply crisis demonstrates vividly that energy diversification is even more urgent for Europe than for America.LiNeBrEaKWhat s more, unlike the U.S., most European countries are legally bound to reduce greenhouse-gas emissions.LiNeBrEaKNatural gas, while cleaner than coal and oil, does not measure up to the demands of the Kyoto Protocol nor the tougher treaty rules that will follow. For many European countries, the prospects of replacing Russian gas with substitutes like wind energy, solar and biogas make good environmental and economic sense and, if scaled up, could largely replace gas delivered from Russia via Ukraine.LiNeBrEaKElectricity production in Europe, particularly in new power plants, relies heavily on natural gas. Renewable energy could eventually replace much of this supply at a reasonable cost with fewer environmental problems.LiNeBrEaKConsider solar s prospects. Italy and Turkey, hurt by the latest gas dispute, are well bathed in the sun s energy. But this essentially free energy source is unharnessed. Bulgaria should also set its sights skyward. As a new European Union country, it is eligible for grants and other subsidies from Brussels that could help its solar energy industry leapfrog past neighbors who rely on heavily-polluting coal.LiNeBrEaKRussian gas importers in southern and southeastern Europe are also major producers of another important but mostly untapped energy source: rice husks. Too often discarded as waste, rice husks are rich in hydrogen and are ingredients in the emerging synthetic natural gas industry.LiNeBrEaKProduction of biomass crops could revolutionize European agriculture and help repair Europe s battered image in world trade discussions. Today, European farmers receive billions of euros in export subsidies.LiNeBrEaKEurope s heavily protected sugar-beet industry stifles Africa s trade in cane sugar, and sugar beets yield little or no byproduct for biomass energy. If agricultural subsidies are an unavoidable political reality, than they should support production of biomass crops that have little or no value for export but are vital for domestic energy security.LiNeBrEaKProduction of substitutes for natural gas in Europe can be justified on many levels, from agricultural-policy reform to environmental treaty obligations, not to mention energy security. But the latter resonated particularly loudly this past winter as steam lines cooled off and generators blinked out for European customers.LiNeBrEaKEuropean countries that depend on Russian gas, tired of the games played at the front of the supply line, can eventually leave that line and determine their own energy futures, even as they tackle other problems such as unfair trade practices and climate change.LiNeBrEaKMatthew R. Auer ( mauer@indiana.edu) is a professor of public and environmental affairs at Indiana University. He is the author of Restoring Cursed Earth: Appraising Environmental Policy Reforms in Eastern Europe and Russia.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); PIPELINE TRANSPORTATION (90%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (90%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (89%); WIND POWER PLANTS (89%); POWER PLANTS (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (89%); SOLAR ENERGY (89%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (87%); EMISSIONS (78%); CRUDE OIL and NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); AUTOMOTIVE FUELS (78%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (78%); BIOMASS (78%); OIL and GAS EXTRACTION (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (78%); METHANE (78%); OIL and GAS EXPORTS and IMPORTS (78%); SOLAR POWER PLANTS (75%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (74%); OIL and GAS STORAGE FACILITIES (73%); INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC ORGANIZATIONS (72%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (72%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (71%); WIND ENERGY (71%); MANUFACTURING FACILITIES (71%); AUTOMOTIVE MFG (71%); GRANTS and GIFTS (71%); NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS (70%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (68%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (66%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (65%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (60%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (50%); BIOFUELS (50%); US PRESIDENTS (65%) Editorial Commentary  				BRUSSELS, BELGIUM (58%) INDIANA, USA (90%) EUROPE (99%); UNITED STATES (94%); UKRAINE (93%); SOUTHEASTERN EUROPE (93%); BOSNIA and