Providence Journal-Bulletin (Rhode Island) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	Studies shed light on ecosystems  response to change  	NEWS; Local; Pg. 4  	1959 words  	Two recent studies by scientists at the University of Rhode Island shed more light on the sensitivities of ecosystems to climate change and varying inputs of nutrients.LiNeBrEaKOne study by oceanographer John King and a collaborator at the Geological Survey of Canada shows that the Great Lakes have reacted dramatically to past changes in the climate.LiNeBrEaKScientists were aware of great fluctuations in Great Lakes water levels in the past, according to King, but believed they were due to the movement of glaciers. But the new study finds that the last time the lake levels fell dramatically   some 20 meters   was between 7,900 and 7,500 years ago. The cause was a climate so dry even the Niagara River ran dry.LiNeBrEaK People used to say that the oceans are so big, we can dump whatever we want in them and nothing will happen,  said King, whose study was published last month in the journal EOS.  They thought of the Great Lakes in the same way, that the system is too large to be sensitive to climate variations. But now we know that to be untrue.  LiNeBrEaKA second study by Autumn Oczkowski, a doctoral student, found that due to increased runoff of sewage and fertilizers the fisheries in the delta of Egypt s Nile River have recovered from virtual collapse.LiNeBrEaKShe used stable isotopes of nitrogen to show that 60 to 100 percent of the fishery production was supported by nutrients from fertilizer and sewage.LiNeBrEaKBefore construction of the Aswan High Dam in 1965, the Nile flooded its delta each fall, irrigating agricultural land and carrying nutrients out to the Mediterranean, where the nutrients supported a large fishery. When the dam ended the flooding, the fishery collapsed.LiNeBrEaKOczkowski said farmers responded by dramatically increasing their use of fertilizers. A population boom also triggered expansion of public water and sewer systems.LiNeBrEaKNow, fish landings are three times the levels that were recorded in the pre-dam days, indicating that nutrients from people have more than replaced those formally carried by flooding.LiNeBrEaKOczkowski said her findings raise questions among scientists concerned about adding too many nutrients from people into local waterways.LiNeBrEaKFor instance, after the Greenwich Bay fish kill in 2003, the State of Rhode Island ordered many sewage treatment plant operators to reduce their output of nitrogen into Narragansett Bay, using processes that cost millions of dollars.LiNeBrEaK We re programmed in the West to think of nutrient enrichment of coastal systems as bad,  Oczkowski said.  But the Egyptians don t think it s a bad thing. For them, it s producing tons of fish and feeding millions of hungry people. It s forcing us to reconsider whether we can say that nutrient inputs are always a bad thing. LiNeBrEaKOczkowski s research will be reported in the Jan. 21 online edition of the Proceedings of the National Academy of Sciences.LiNeBrEaKPets focus of disaster summitLiNeBrEaKIn partnership with the Department of Environmental Management, the Rhode Island Disaster Animal Response Team has received a $20,000 Emergency Preparedness Initiative grant from the State Animal Response Team and PetSmart Charities Inc. The grant will be used to improve care for pets, farm livestock and wildlife animals in disasters, which could range from storms or floods to fires and oil spills. The grant will finance a two-day summit at the University of Rhode Island s Bay Campus on Friday and Saturday and assure national certification and continued development of RIDART.LiNeBrEaKThe grant requires a state match, and DEM has fulfilled this requirement by purchasing a pair of trailers full of equipment and supplies that will be used for pet sheltering in a state emergency.LiNeBrEaKOn Friday from 10: 30 a.m. to 3 p.m. at the URI Coastal Institute in Narragansett, the first day of the summit will focus on the dairy industry. Managers and owners of all Rhode Island dairies, as well as processing, transportation and regulatory agency staff, are invited to attend. .LiNeBrEaKThe second session will be held Saturday from 8: 30 a.m. to 4 p.m. and will focus on shelter and rescue of pets in an emergency. The morning sessions are geared toward current and prospective RIDART volunteers. The afternoon sessions are for people interested in learning more about leadership opportunities on the shelter management teams for the two state animal shelters.LiNeBrEaKThe summit is free and open to current and prospective RIDART volunteers. Advance registration is required. Register online at www.RIDART.org by using the link to the registration form on the RIDART calendar for Jan. 23 and 24. For information, call Richard Horwitz in DEM s Division of Agriculture at (401) 222-4700, ext 2411.LiNeBrEaKComments sought on dredging planLiNeBrEaKAt the request of the Town of New Shoreham, the U.S. Army Corps of Engineers, New England District, is proposing to perform maintenance dredging of portions of Great Salt Pond on Block Island.LiNeBrEaKThe proposed work involves dredging portions of the 18-foot-deep mean lower low water entrance channel. According to project manager Michael Walsh, natural shoaling has reduced available depths to as little as 3. 5 feet MLLW.LiNeBrEaKHe said,  There is a particularly hazardous shoal at the eastern, or inner, end of the entrance channel, which is making navigation to and from the pond hazardous at all stages of the tide. LiNeBrEaKThe last complete maintenance dredging was performed in 1982. Emergency dredging efforts were performed in 2000 and 2004, in which 12,250 and 9,970 cubic yards of material respectively were removed from a hazardous shoal area and disposed of at a site on the west side of the island.LiNeBrEaKDisposal options, possible temporary adverse effects on essential fish habitat and environmental assessment for the work is available for review at www.nae.usace.army.mil. Select  public services,  then  navigation  and then  public notices.  Public comments on the proposal may be emailed to nae-pn-nav@usace.army.mil by Thursday.LiNeBrEaKNature session set for childrenLiNeBrEaKThe Rhode Island Wild Plant Society and Blithewold Mansion and Garden in Bristol are co-sponsoring a nature journaling workshop for children on Saturday from 2 to 4 p.m. at Blithewold. Children are invited to explore a variety of nature printing techniques and create a handmade field guide with instructor Chris Kalina. The class is for students in grades 3 to 5. Acrylic paints will be used; therefore, appropriate clothing is recommended. Fee is $10 plus $5 material fee to be paid on the day of the workshop. Advance registration is required at www.blithewold.org. For information, call the society office at (401) 789-7497.LiNeBrEaKDEM to offer services at showLiNeBrEaKDepartment of Environmental Management staff will be at the Providence Boat Show at the Convention Center to renew current boat registrations, answer questions about registering new boats and have available boating safety information. Boat registrations can be renewed, by check only, on Friday, Jan. 30, from 4 p.m. to 8 p.m., Saturday, Jan. 31, 10 a.m. to 8 p.m., and Sunday, Feb. 1, from noon to 5 p.m. There will also be a secured drop box at the boat show for boat registration renewals by check only. Renewal registrations left in the drop box will be processed on Monday, Feb. 2.LiNeBrEaKThe DEM s environmental police officers will host a center featuring information on boater education courses that are now mandatory for all boaters born after Jan. 1, 1986, who operate a boat with a motor greater than 10 horsepower, and for all operators, regardless of age, of personal watercraft. They will also offer safety tips, provide information about boating laws and equipment requirements and answer questions on boating, hunting, fishing and shellfishing.LiNeBrEaKIndividuals seeking summer employment can pick up application forms at the DEM s boat registration booth. The department is seeking seasonal employees 16 and older for such positions as park rangers, beach managers, seasonal laborers, lifeguards, lifeguard captains, program interns, recreation area clerks, student researchers and mosquito technicians.LiNeBrEaKPaid positions are also available as part of the department s minority internship program, which is designed to encourage minorities to pursue careers in the environmental field. The program gives qualified individuals a chance to explore jobs in agriculture, parks and recreation, fish and wildlife, air resources, waste management, forest environment, water resources, management services and policy and planning.LiNeBrEaKThe DEM has mailed out more than 22,000 boat registration renewal forms to boaters whose current registrations expire at the end of February.LiNeBrEaKForms for registering and titling new boats will be available at the show and are also available on the DEM Web site, www.dem.ri.gov. New boats must be registered at DEM headquarters, 235 Promenade St., Providence.LiNeBrEaKSolar energy firm holds open houseLiNeBrEaKAlteris Renewables, formerly SolarWrights and Solar Works Inc., is sponsoring an open house for business people and members of the public interested in solar energy from 6 to 8 p.m. Thursday at the Wolcott Eco-Office at 28 Wolcott St. in Providence.LiNeBrEaKThe company says it wants to celebrate its new name, a new year and  a new energy direction for our country.  It will offer locally made food and wine. For questions, call (401) 396-9901 or send an e-mail to kdewitt@alterisinc.comLiNeBrEaKSchools awarded Tisdale grantsLiNeBrEaKThe Environment Council of Rhode Island Education Fund recently announced the winners of the fourth-annual Loraine Tisdale Environmental Education Awards. The winners and their projects are:LiNeBrEaK The collaboration between Bridges 4 Learning and the Coleman Elementary School in Woonsocket to develop an in-school worm composting system.LiNeBrEaK The Ocean Tides School in Providence to develop a composting system for the school.LiNeBrEaK The collaboration between the Met School and All Children s Theater to produce a play written by students about global warming and present it to area schools.LiNeBrEaKEach fall the council holds an open competition for schools in Rhode Island for the opportunity to be funded for a spring environmental project. Each winning school is awarded $250 to carry out the project. This year a record 19 schools applied, according to Tisdale awards coordinator Greg Gerritt.LiNeBrEaKThe council raises funds for the awards through the annual ECRI Ed Fund Earth Day Raffle. The award is named after a long time Rhode Island educator and environmental activist, Loraine Tisdale. For information, visit www.environmentcouncilri.org.LiNeBrEaKWoodland grant workshops offeredLiNeBrEaKThe Natural Resources Conservation Service will conduct two workshops for owners of private agricultural land or forest/woodland, who may apply for $7 million in grants approved by the 2008 Farm Bill. Workshops are scheduled for Wednesday, at Chepachet Grange, 56 Victory Highway, Chepachet; and Jan. 28 at the Eastern Conservation District Office, 2490 Main Rd., Tiverton. Each will run from 6 to 8 p.m.LiNeBrEaKThe grants are intended to provide financial and technical aid in composting; protecting field crops; preventing erosion; eradicating invasive plants; managing manure; reducing irrigation water use and improving water quality; and protecting and enhancing woodland, pastureland and wildlife areas. The workshops will help prospective applicants through the application and contract process. For information or to register, call Tom Sandham, at (401) 949-1480 in Chepachet, or (401) 624-7490 in Tiverton.LiNeBrEaKThe Environmental Journal is a listing of brief news items about the actions of individuals, 