The Record (Bergen County, NJ) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   All Editions	Mr. President;  Scholars weigh in on agenda for Obama;  Global warming	OPINION; Pg. O01  	966 words  	WE ARE PLEASED to see that President-elect Obama recognizes global warming as a serious threat. He is promoting renewable energy as part of the solution to climate change and has also expressed support for the Lieberman-Warner bill meant to confront global warming, which was defeated recently in Congress.LiNeBrEaKObama's focus on renewable energy is laudable, but his endorsement of the failed legislation, although well meaning, is misplaced. LiNeBrEaKIn fact, the measure's defeat may prove a blessing in disguise.LiNeBrEaKThis bill and many other proposals are based on unrealistic policies that cannot prevent harmful climate changes. As long as the greenhouse gas concentration in the atmosphere continues to increase, global warming and resulting climate changes are bound to grow worse.LiNeBrEaKOne would expect climate policymakers to focus on reducing the gas levels in the air, but this is not the aim of the Lieberman-Warner bill or other current and proposed programs.LiNeBrEaKRather, they are designed only to cut existing emissions, called "business-as-usual" discharges, by a percentage-reduction rate over some number of years, regardless of whether these cutbacks will achieve any improvement in the atmospheric greenhouse gas concentration.LiNeBrEaKFor example, California regulations would require vehicles to reduce gas emissions 30 percent by 2016, allowing the remaining 70 percent of business-as-usual discharges to increase gas levels in the air every year.LiNeBrEaKThe Lieberman-Warner bill called for cutting gas emissions in stages, culminating in a 66 percent reduction by 2050. This bill would have allowed a third of current business-as-usual discharges to continue in 2050, permitting larger emissions in the years up to that date.LiNeBrEaKAll of these first-step regulatory programs would allow persistent gas discharges to increase the atmospheric concentration every year. In short, these emissions-reduction programs would not decrease crucial greenhouse levels in the air; instead, they would only reduce the increases in annual greenhouse gas pollution.LiNeBrEaKEmissions-reduction approaches that do no more than reduce annual greenhouse gas increases, including cap-and-trade pollution credit schemes that many experts prefer, are merely first-step or interim measures that cannot achieve long-term climate change solutions.LiNeBrEaKA first step is only valuable if it is a step in the right direction.LiNeBrEaKWe believe a much better strategy would focus nearly all energy research, regulatory initiatives and financial investments on enabling a reasonably rapid but feasible transition to greenhouse gas-free technologies in as many economic contexts as possible.LiNeBrEaKThe technology needed to meet interim emissions-reduction targets, such as those in the Lieberman-Warner measure, will often be wholly different from the technology required to attain a carbon-free standard.LiNeBrEaKSmaller enginesLiNeBrEaKMotor vehicles, for example, can cut greenhouse gas discharges by using smaller engines and lighter materials, substituting biofuels for high-carbon dioxide petroleum, or by adopting hybrid engine designs.LiNeBrEaKBut these first-step modifications can go only so far in reducing greenhouse gas pollution. They can never approach the cleanliness of all-electric or hydrogen fuel-cell vehicles.LiNeBrEaKIf we spend billions of dollars on first-step technology improvements, the funding available for carbon-free vehicles will be reduced. If auto manufacturers make first-step changes at relatively high costs, they will undoubtedly resist replacing these interim modifications with carbon-free designs.LiNeBrEaKUnder the Lieberman-Warner approach, we would have to pay the cumulative costs of first-step improvements, likely second-step improvements, and eventually, conversion to carbon-free technologies that are essential over the long term.LiNeBrEaKSimilarly, implementing interim end-of-the-pipe pollution control devices is simply an expensive stop-gap measure that will ultimately be scrapped in favor of newer technologies, such as "carbon capture and storage" systems that would inject large quantities of greenhouse gases deep underground instead of letting the harmful gases reach the atmosphere.LiNeBrEaKThere is an international consensus that developed nations cannot overcome global warming without the cooperation of developing nations, including China and India, which rank among the five worst greenhouse gas polluters. Yet, developing countries will not agree to mitigation measures that would impede their pursuit of greater prosperity.LiNeBrEaKA first step of paying these states to adopt our emissions-reduction programs would neither enable economic development nor improve the atmospheric greenhouse gas concentration.LiNeBrEaKThe only thing we could give poor nations that will meet their objectives and ours is greenhouse gas-free technologies that promote economic progress without exacerbating global warming.LiNeBrEaKDecentralized generatorsLiNeBrEaKRenewable energy technologies would be especially suitable for developing states because the power generators could be decentralized without the enormous cost of creating nationwide electricity networks.LiNeBrEaKAny genuine effort to combat global warming will evoke a political and economic Battle Royale. The new administration cannot afford to squander financial and political capital on first-step approaches that detract from our long-term needs.LiNeBrEaKCurrent and proposed first-step programs are diverting vital resources from development of greenhouse gas-free methods that can actually improve the critical atmospheric gas levels.LiNeBrEaKConverting the world's economies to primary reliance on greenhouse gas-free technologies will be difficult and costly, but we see no other way to avoid the terrible impact of global climate change that nearly all atmospheric scientists are now predicting.LiNeBrEaKHoward Latin and Louis Raveson are law professors at Rutgers University School of Law, Newark.		GLOBAL WARMING (94%); EMISSIONS (90%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (89%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (77%); LEGISLATION (77%); ENERGY RESEARCH (73%); HYBRID VEHICLES (72%); PETROLEUM PRODUCTS (69%); BIOFUELS (50%); US PRESIDENTS (90%) OBAMA; GLOBAL WARMING  			BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	CALIFORNIA, USA (70%) UNITED STATES (70%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO, OBAMA  		Newspaper  	2009 North Jersey Media Group Inc., All Rights Reserved  	By HOWARD LATIN and LOUIS RAVESON, Wire Services  															
San Antonio Express-News 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   STATEandMETRO Edition	Focus: health and the environment  	VIEWS; Pg. 8B  	763 words  	Bumper sticker mentalityLiNeBrEaKI'm embarrassed to have a governor so out-of-touch with climate change. When he suggests that CO2 being a pollutant is a "bit of a stretch," it shows he doesn't even understand the issue. Governor, we're adding to the CO2 that naturally exists and, in so doing, making the bio system of the whole planet unstable. CO2 alone is no more a pollutant than is water - but too much of that and you drown.LiNeBrEaKJohn McCain said that global warming was troubling 30 years ago, alarming 20 years ago and outright dangerous today. The current president said that climate change is a result of our "addiction to oil." The U.S. Geological Survey and Columbia University say we are playing with a "near permanent drought developing in the American Southwest" (Earthweek, 12/26/2008). This should alarm anyone concerned with Texas. I know it alarms Sen. Kay Bailey Hutchison. Frankly, if she runs for governor, I think she'll prevail among cerebral Republicans. LiNeBrEaKAs to the green-friendly advocates throughout Texas, I'm not embarrassed at all, but I am concerned that they often put the "cart before the horse." I always read of the solutions to the problem (conservation, alternate energy, etc) - but as evidenced by people like the governor, I think restating the "problem" is needed as well as addressing "solutions."LiNeBrEaKFace it, many people get their news through television only. This may be OK generally, but I don't want my governor to be so limited. After all, TV is to the news what bumper stickers are to philosophy.LiNeBrEaK-- Bill HurleyLiNeBrEaKIt's time for wise choicesLiNeBrEaKRe: "Texas must keep water taps flowing," (Other Views, Jan. 4):LiNeBrEaKMany cultures around the world have historically captured rainwater.LiNeBrEaKPerhaps this drought will prompt us to do likewise. However, we'll have to overcome a lack of education on this topic as illustrated by some local talk show hosts who stated that recapturing rainwater wouldn't be a good idea because it would prevent the aquifer from recapturing it, all the while ignoring the fact that the floods that we get end up with most of the water entering the sewer system, not the aquifer.LiNeBrEaKFurthermore, most communities in the area don't allow cisterns for water storage on home properties due to rules written by the developer. Do we need the dreaded legislative process to require communities to allow capturing of rainwater similar to the newly submitted bill to the Texas Legislature that requires communities to allow solar panels? Or, as citizens, could we just go ahead and make wise decisions that will provide for the current need and certainly solve the future water problem of a growing population in a dry environment?LiNeBrEaK-- Sandra MoodyLiNeBrEaKWhat's the outlook?LiNeBrEaKI enjoyed Forrest Mims' column ("One day closer to next rain," Jan. 5) about the current drought.LiNeBrEaKThere's "good news and bad news" - is the glass half full, or is it half empty? It's attitude, right? Ranchers know this story:LiNeBrEaKTwo ranchers were talking across the fence, standing in the mud after a deluge.LiNeBrEaK"Nice rain," says the optimist.LiNeBrEaK"Yep," says the other. looking to the clearing sky. "That's just the way the last drought started."LiNeBrEaK-- Clay McGaughyLiNeBrEaKFirst-hand dangerLiNeBrEaKPlease help us, City Council. Manslaughter is in progress. I represent (cough) the majority of (cough, cough) San Antonians who don't inhale toxic fumes into our lungs for enjoyment (by the way, lungs are meant to breath clean air). We love to frequent restaurants, and we also enjoy dance clubs (cough), but we are unwillingly being exposed to "second-hand smoke" by the minority of inconsiderate smokers in this (cough-cough) city.LiNeBrEaKDozens of major cities, including Los Angeles and New York, have adopted bans on smoking in bars and restaurants. So why hasn't San Antonio taken action yet? Studies in these cities have proven there is no significant negative impact on the (hack-hack) economy of these establishments, so why haven't you acted on behalf of the health of all of us here?LiNeBrEaKOur outside air is bad enough, and having to (cough) inhale toxic fumes in restaurants and bars is killing us all slowly, but surely. Conventions will still come, people can smoke outside and the city will still make its (hack-cough) money. It's a crime, honestly, that you put money above the health of each one of us. Think of the millions/billions saved in health care (less heart attacks).LiNeBrEaKWake up, City Council. Act now. The next target after (cough-cough) fixing this problem: obesity. Another health problem. Suggestion: Organize a "Biggest Loser Contest in San Antonio" with a prize of $50,000. Imagine the result.LiNeBrEaK-- J. Bernal, Schertz		CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); DROUGHT (89%); AQUIFERS and WATERSHEDS (89%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); GOVERNORS (78%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); LEGISLATORS (78%); WATER SUPPLY UTILITIES (76%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); SEWERAGE SYSTEMS (71%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (69%); SOLAR ENERGY (65%)  		COLUMBIA UNIVERSITY (56%); UNITED STATES GEOLOGICAL SURVEY (56%)  	JOHN MCCAIN (57%); KAY BAILEY HUTCHISON (55%)  	SAN ANTONIO, TX, USA (92%) TEXAS, USA (94%); SOUTHWEST USA (71%); SOUTHWEST, USA (71%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  	A reader decries the second-hand smoke in local establishments. PHOTO: JOEL RYAN/ASSOCIATED PRESS  	Letter  	Newspaper  	2009 San Antonio Express-News All Rights Reserved  																
San Jose Mercury News (California)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	For California, new clout in Obama's tech-friendly administration  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	1096 words  	Jan. 18--WASHINGTON -- Barbara Boxer remembers the "dark days" when California and its issues were dismissed by official Washington with disdain and hostility.LiNeBrEaK"Dianne Feinstein and I joked that it was ABC -- anything but California, anyone but California," Boxer said, recalling when the two Democrats joined the Senate in 1993.LiNeBrEaKNow, as California Democrats pour into Washington to celebrate Barack Obama's inauguration, the state can claim a surge of influence in the new, tech-friendly administration. Congress, too, is looking westward, with Californians taking key positions of power. LiNeBrEaKTwo Californians were named to Obama's Cabinet -- Nobel Prize-winning physicist Steven Chu at the Energy Department and Rep. Hilda Solis at the Labor Department -- and Leon Panetta, former President Bill Clinton's White House chief of staff, has been appointed to lead the Central Intelligence Agency.LiNeBrEaKObama also named a pair of Golden Staters to key White House posts: Christina Romer, a Berkeley economist, will chair the Council of Economic Advisers, and Nancy Sutley, deputy mayor of Los Angeles, will bring her experience as a state environmental regulator to the job of chairing the Council on Environmental Quality.LiNeBrEaK"These are superstar choices. California is 'in' right now, and we can remember when California was 'out,' " Boxer said. "There is a lot more respect for the state, especially on energy issues."LiNeBrEaKShift on tech, energyLiNeBrEaKOn a policy level, it's a shift from oil drilling to renewable energy, from sidestepping the issue of global warming to dealing with it aggressively, from a pro-industry stance to greater sympathy for organized labor.LiNeBrEaKRep. Zoe Lofgren, a San Jose Democrat, measured the change this way: "I remember Gov. Jerry Brown coming to Washington talking about windmills, and people made fun of him. Now everybody is talking about wind energy and solar."LiNeBrEaKCalifornians with deep experience in tech and energy issues, particularly clean technology, have Obama's ear. That includes Eric Schmidt, &iuml;&raquo;&iquest;chief executive of Google, venture capitalist John Doerr, who is close to Al Gore, and John Thompson, the former Symantec CEO who may be a contender for commerce secretary.LiNeBrEaKThat influence can be seen in major ingredients in the $825 billion stimulus package prepared by the House with the Obama team's input. Doerr, for example, lobbied for the $11 billion that would go toward modernizing the electricity grid. Tech groups pushed hard for $6 billion in grants to speed up broadband deployment. Wind-energy advocates secured a long-term extension of the production tax credit.LiNeBrEaKAnd California renewable-energy companies and investors, struggling with the frozen credit market, cheered when Obama announced his goal of doubling the production of renewable energy over the next three years.LiNeBrEaK"I think what the Obama administration intends to do is move the technology that has been pioneered in California across the country," said Cathy Zoi, CEO of Palo Alto-based Alliance for Climate Protection.LiNeBrEaKThe state's new clout should not be viewed in the traditional sense of more "pork" for California, said Norm Ornstein, an author and longtime analyst of government for the American Enterprise Institute. But it will play out in other ways.LiNeBrEaK"There will be a greater sensibility on issues that matter to California and drive the California economy," Ornstein said. "It helps that Obama puts a high priority about keeping the nation's edge on technology, and is listening to Silicon Valley on that."LiNeBrEaKCalifornia-friendlyLiNeBrEaKSome appointees are not from California but tend to view key issues in California-friendly ways. Carol Browner, a top Obama adviser on energy and the environment, supported the state's pioneering regulations as Environmental Protection Agency chief. And Gov. Janet Napolitano of Arizona, a graduate of Santa Clara University who has worked on border-state issues, has been named to head the Homeland Security Department.LiNeBrEaKObama is unlikely to cultivate as cozy a relationship with the state as Bill Clinton did, predicted Jack Pitney, a professor of politics at Claremont McKenna College who worked for Republicans during the Reagan and first Bush administrations.LiNeBrEaKBut he agrees that just as Reagan-style California conservatism was adopted in Washington in the 1980s, Obama is likely to embrace California-style progressivism.LiNeBrEaKUnlike the 1990s, when Clinton had to deal with a Republican majority in Congress, Democrats now control both branches, with state leaders well-represented -- starting with House Speaker Nancy Pelosi of San Francisco.LiNeBrEaKLofgren, who chairs the immigration subcommittee in the House, knows she can get Napolitano on the phone if there's a problem with the immigration bureaucracy, or she can contact Solis on a labor issue.LiNeBrEaKLofgren chairs the delegation of 34 California Democrats in the House, which met last week and bid farewell to Solis.LiNeBrEaK"There in the room were the chairmen of the Energy Committee (Henry Waxman,) Education and Labor (George Miller), Foreign Affairs (Howard Berman), and Veterans Affairs (Bob Filner)," Lofgren said. "I thought, if you wanted to get something done, come to this room."LiNeBrEaKState labor leaders expect that with Solis in the Cabinet, they will have a friendly ear on minimum-wage and family-leave issues, and other concerns of an increasingly immigrant work force. Solis, from Los Angeles, is the daughter of immigrants and her father was a union worker.LiNeBrEaK"She is very well-connected and can help bridge the gap and the tensions between immigrant workers and other sectors of the community, including some unions," said Art Pulaski, executive secretary-treasurer of the California Labor Federation, AFL-CIO.LiNeBrEaKBut Pitney, a veteran observer of Washington, warned that Californians looking for rapid change on energy, labor and other issues from Obama and other leaders they just elected may be disappointed.LiNeBrEaK"Electing officials is a lot like shopping online," Pitney said. "Everything looks better when you log on than when the package arrives at the door."LiNeBrEaKContact Frank Davies at fdavies@mercurynews.com or (202) 662-8921. Contact Mary Anne Ostrom at mostrom@mercurynews.com or (415) 477-3794.		US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (90%); POLITICAL PARTIES (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (89%); SOLAR ENERGY (89%); WIND ENERGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (88%); APPOINTMENTS (77%); LOBBYING (76%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (76%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (76%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (76%); NOBEL PRIZES (74%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (74%); LABOR DEPARTMENTS (74%); COMMERCE DEPARTMENTS (74%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (74%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (71%); TAX LAW (70%); AWARDS and PRIZES (69%); LABOR UNIONS (69%); US PRESIDENTS (76%); ECONOMIC POLICY (67%); ECONOMIC NEWS (67%); TAXES and TAXATION (62%); VENTURE CAPITAL (60%); INTELLIGENCE SERVICES (53%); BROADBAND (50%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (76%)  	GOOGLE INC (52%); SYMANTEC CORP (52%)  	CENTRAL INTELLIGENCE AGENCY (56%); COUNCIL OF ECONOMIC ADVISERS (55%); COUNCIL ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (55%)  	BARACK OBAMA (95%); BARBARA BOXER (92%); DIANNE FEINSTEIN (91%); BILL CLINTON (56%); HILDA L SOLIS (56%); LEON E PANETTA (56%); STEVEN CHU (56%); CHRISTINA ROMER (55%); ZOE LOFGREN (53%); ERIC E SCHMIDT (52%); AL GORE (52%); JOHN W THOMPSON (52%); L JOHN DOERR (52%)  	LOS ANGELES, CA, USA (79%); SAN JOSE, CA, USA (79%) CALIFORNIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News   	Frank Davies and Mary Anne Ostrom, San Jose Mercury New