San Jose Mercury News (California)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	The Scene: Where techies want to be seen in D.C.  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	1113 words  	Jan. 18--Hollywood may have it's A-list parties, but so does the tech crowd. Here's where the digital glitterati want to be seen. Unscientific ratings based on buzz and how hard Mercury News reporters had to try to get into the party:LiNeBrEaKFive starsLiNeBrEaKThe Green Ball, Monday night: LiNeBrEaKThis enviro-star-studded party for foes of global warming is the hottest ticket in town for the green-tech crowd. Al Gore star attraction and attendees will walk down a green carpet, made of recyclable materials, of course. We're still waiting for our sources (we've hit up six different contacts so far) to deliver two tickets.LiNeBrEaKFour starsLiNeBrEaKThe Google ball, Tuesday night:LiNeBrEaKGoogle has become the de facto tech-industry party host after throwing successful bashes at both national party conventions over the summer. Google is shunning traditional ball etiquette, going for a lounge-like concept. And -- now this would be a first for an inaugural fete -- the company will be serving really good food, says one source. For that reason, we'll be heading here instead of the Western states ball, the official California event, where 11,000 are expected. And we've got tickets.LiNeBrEaKLINK-live Presidential Inaugural Gala, Tuesday night:LiNeBrEaKIt's billed as a party to celebrate technology serving humanity. Steven Chu Lawrence Berkeley's Nobel laureate physicist and Obama's choice for energy secretary, is slated to receive "the nature award." You can attendLiNeBrEaKvirtually via www.linklive.org. And you can join the celebration online using Twitter (name: linklive; address: #linklive2009), ScribbleLive, Ustream and Flickr. We think we've got tickets, and would hate to miss Chu, the Bay Area's hottest -- or is that coolest? -- scientist.LiNeBrEaKThree starsLiNeBrEaKNetroots Nation party, Monday night:LiNeBrEaKLiberal stars of the blogosphere come together to pat themselves on the back for helping Obama get elected. Among the co-hosts are Firedoglake and Fivethirtyeight.com. Guests can hang out in the Guitar Hero Lounge. If the event wasn't in Virginia, we'd consider giving it four stars. If we don't get Green Ball tickets, we'll be heading here.LiNeBrEaKFor San Jose man, family ties aren't enoughLiNeBrEaKRobert Wright, seventh-grade teacher at Morrill Middle School in San Jose, stumbled across a genealogical Web site this past summer that shows he and Obama share a distant ancestor, Obadiah Columbus Wright. He had named his son, 14, Obadiah after the ancestor but had no clue about Obama's connection until he did a routine search of the name. After Obama's victory, Wright figured the connection ought to get him an inauguration ticket. First, he approached the Obama inaugural planners. They sent back an e-mail informing him how to donate to the inaugural committee. U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein sent a form e-mail telling him that he didn't make the cut. She had 60,000 ticket requests. He thought he had the ear of an aide to U.S. Rep Zoe Lofgen and even faxed over the family tree. But, alas, no tickets. "I guess my limb grew too far from the family tree." He'll be watching the inauguration with his students.LiNeBrEaKFeinstein to introduce the Rev. Rick WarrenLiNeBrEaKTune in to the inauguration ceremony and the first speech you will hear from the podium will come from California's own Sen. Dianne Feinstein, who chairs the congressional inaugural committee.LiNeBrEaKWhat will she say in the global spotlight? "It will be very formal and very brief," she told reporters at a preview of the main event. "This is a tightly scripted, very precise schedule."LiNeBrEaKFeinstein will introduce Rick Warren, pastor of Saddleback Church in Lake Forest, to give the invocation. Obama's choice of Warren for that honor drew controversy because of the pastor's support for Proposition 8 in California, which banned same-sex marriages. Obama and Feinstein opposed Proposition 8.LiNeBrEaKBring the noise, toss the broomsLiNeBrEaKPrecision lawn-chair marching? The inaugural parade always features lots of traditional marching bands, but this year a few units stand out for different reasons.LiNeBrEaKThe Redwood Middle School Marching Band from Saratoga enjoys the distinction of being the only middle school band participating in the parade.LiNeBrEaKFor the first time, an openly gay group, The Lesbian and Gay Band Association, will march in an inaugural parade. The association performed at other events during Bill Clinton's two inaugurals.LiNeBrEaKThe World Famous Lawn Rangers from Arcola, Ill., toss unique "show" brooms into the air, and according to the official program, often catch them. Their motto: "You're only young once but you can always be immature."LiNeBrEaKA royal turnoutLiNeBrEaKSeen at U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein's well-attended Saturday night reception at the Library of Congress: Queen Noor of Jordan, Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer and movie star Angela Bassett.LiNeBrEaKObama to be toasted with California wineLiNeBrEaKOregon Pinot take this. A California Pinot Noir from Anderson Valley has been selected to be served at Tuesday's inaugural luncheon, the new president's sit-down lunch with 230 dignitaries following the swearing in.LiNeBrEaKGoldeneye Pinot Noir 2005 will be served with the second course, duck and pheasant served with sour cherry chutney and molasses sweet potatoes. It's produced by Napa Valley's Duckhorn Vineyards whose 2007 Sauvigon blanc will be served with a first course of fish stew.LiNeBrEaKWho came up with the pairings? Obama's first meal as president is similar to the foods Abraham Lincoln would have eaten. And the planners, notably U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein who heads up the congressional committee planning the lunch, insisted on California vintages.LiNeBrEaKWine Spectator and Wine Enthusiast both give the pinot 92 points and it retails for $55 a bottle. And for the champagne toast? Korbel in the Russian River Valley is producing a "special inaugural cuvee." This marks the seventh inauguration for Korbel. But it's Duckhorn's first.LiNeBrEaKAlthough the inaugural lunch committee said they would pay for 10 cases of the wines, Duckhorn was so honored they decided to donate them.LiNeBrEaKThe luncheon menu is the most visited part of the congressional inaugural committee website. To check it out go to: www.inaugural.senate.gov/luncheon/LiNeBrEaKThe Scene is compiled by Mercury News Staff Writers Mary Anne Ostrom and Frank Davies. For more insider notes on Barack Obama's inauguration, go to www.mercurynews.com/obama.-inauguration		OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (87%); NOBEL PRIZES (69%); POLITICAL PARTY CONVENTIONS (68%); GENEALOGY (67%); BLOGS and MESSAGE BOARDS (63%); PRIMARY and SECONDARY SCHOOL TEACHERS (60%); GLOBAL WARMING (56%)  	GOOGLE INC (83%)  		BARACK OBAMA (84%); STEVEN CHU (67%); AL GORE (57%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (79%); SAN JOSE, CA, USA (69%) CALIFORNIA, USA (79%); WEST USA (73%) UNITED STATES (79%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News   	Mary Anne Ostrom and Frank Davies, San Jose Mercury News, Calif.  		GOOG (NASDAQ) (83%) NASDAQ-NMS:GOOG  	NAICS519130 INTERNET PUBLISHING and BROADCASTING and WEB SEARCH PORTALS (83%) Arts  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090118-SJ-The-Scene-Where-techies-want-to-be-seen-in-D-C-0118  	SJ  									
The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL Edition	Ex-49er Jerry Rice catches acting bug  	Pg. N22  	699 words  	Since retiring from football three years ago, Jerry Rice has been busy reinventing himself. He'd seen other former players who didn't know what to do next and became determined that that would not happen to him. So he appeared in commercials for Gatorade, Visa and Zaxby's restaurants.LiNeBrEaKThen he went on "Dancing With the Stars" and surprised everybody by coming in second using moves he didn't learn on a football field. LiNeBrEaK Now comes Rice the actor. He took a small role in "Without a Paddle: Nature's Calling," a direct-to-DVD sequel to the 2004 adventure comedy "Without a Paddle." Oliver James and Kristopher Turner star as friends in their 20s who disappear into the wilderness in search of a beautiful missing woman. In the wilds, they meet up with Hal Gore Rice, former vice president Al's unappreciated younger brother. Hal believes that he discovered Tipper and a solution to global warming first, and that Al's Oscar, Emmy and Nobel Prize rightfully should be his.LiNeBrEaKWe caught up with the world's greatest wide receiver and former San Francisco 49er and Oakland Raider when he was fresh from watching his 17-year-old son, Jerry Rice Jr., play an amateur all-star game. Rice, 46, said he didn't want his son to play football "because I know how vicious the game can be and I didn't want that pressure on him." But the teenager, who plays wide receiver and a little quarterback, appears determined to go into the family business. "I couldn't play quarterback because I couldn't throw the ball," Rice said.LiNeBrEaKNow the question is: Can he play Hal Gore or other parts that might come his way?LiNeBrEaKQ:How serious are you about this acting business?LiNeBrEaKA: I'm not looking to be the next Denzel Washington or Will Smith. But I like the challenge of acting. I think so many people are afraid of stepping out of their boundary and opening themselves up to criticism. I am a risk taker. If there is something I want to do, I am going to go for it and deal with the critics.LiNeBrEaKQ:What was the biggest challenge in making the movie?LiNeBrEaKA: I had to learn my lines in one day because it sort of fell into my lap. They wanted former quarterback great Terry Bradshaw, but he probably looked at it and said, "I'm not going to do this." There was no prompter or anything. You had to remember your lines and the other actors' lines, too, so you knew when to come in. The hardest part for me is right before the director says, "Action!" You are running lines over and over in your head, and suddenly he says "action" and I go, "Say, what is my line?"LiNeBrEaKQ:You appear in a floor-length fur coat that has clearly seen better days. How did you feel about wearing it?LiNeBrEaKA: When I first looked at it, I didn't want to put it on. I'm used to having my uniform be nice and neat and not having stuff dangling from the bottom. Then all of a sudden I had to wear this thing, which I found out was made of squirrel.LiNeBrEaKQ:I'm wondering if you know Al Gore and how you feel about playing his "brother."LiNeBrEaKA: I don't know him personally. But I thought it was hilarious that Hal Gore would think he had found the cure to global warming in the wilderness. To me, I had a chance to go crazy with it.LiNeBrEaKQ:When you were on "Dancing With the Stars," you approached it with the same vigor and strong work ethic that you had during your football career. Are you also giving acting your all?LiNeBrEaKA: Yes. When I commit to something, I feel I have to do it well because of my reputation and what I have built for myself. Once I had committed to "Dancing With the Stars," if I had gone on and was a bust I would have had to deal with the criticism. But I worked my butt off. I don't like coming in second place. We athletes are very competitive.LiNeBrEaKQ:So how do you rate your performance in the "Without a Paddle" sequel?LiNeBrEaKA: I'm going to watch it tonight and critique it the same way I did my "Dancing With the Stars" routines and the way I watched tapes of my games. You look at them and think, "Here is where I could have done better." That keeps you from getting complacent. I think the reason I had so much success in football was because I never got complacent. LiNeBrEaKWithout a Paddle: Nature's Calling PG-13 is available on DVD for $29. 98 discounted online from Paramount Famous Productions.		ATHLETES (89%); FILM (89%); AMERICAN FOOTBALL (89%); SPORTS (89%); SPORTS and RECREATION EVENTS (78%); MISSING PERSONS (74%); ACTION and ADVENTURE FILMS (74%); FAMILY COMPANIES (63%); NOBEL PRIZES (52%); GLOBAL WARMING (52%); AWARDS and PRIZES (52%); ACTORS and ACTRESSES (89%) DATEBOOK; MOVIES; BIOGRAPHY; INTERVIEW  		SAN FRANCISCO 49ERS (59%)  	WILL SMITH (52%) Jerry Rice  	SAN FRANCISCO, CA, USA (91%) CALIFORNIA, USA (91%) UNITED STATES (91%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  	In "Without a Paddle: Nature's Calling," former San Francisco 49ers wide receiver Jerry Rice plays Al Gore's unappreciated brother, Hal Gore. Paramount Famous Productions  		Newspaper  	2009 San Francisco Chronicle All Rights Reserved  	Ruthe Stein  															
The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL Edition	A failed presidency  	Insight; EDITORIALS; Pg. G2  	711 words  	It is hard to imagine that one U.S. presidency could leave more wreckage than George W. Bush's did during his eight years in the White House.LiNeBrEaKBy his own yardsticks, his administration was an abject failure. He was a divider, not a uniter. He was "the decider" who led the country into a war of choice on what proved to be false pretenses. His administration was neither compassionate nor conservative. It ran up record deficits while giving tax breaks to the wealthy and creating a culture of government neglect that left some Americans trapped in a netherworld of neglect after Hurricane Katrina, and continues to keep all of us gripped by the angst of an economic system that remains on the brink of collapse.LiNeBrEaKThis was a president whose election was assured only after the U.S. Supreme Court, in a 5-4 ruling, settled the more than monthlong dispute over the Florida outcome. He immediately began to govern as if he had a ringing mandate. LiNeBrEaKThe defining event of the Bush presidency came on Sept. 11, 2001, when al Qaeda terrorists hijacked four commercial airliners and turned them into missiles against the icons of U.S. financial and military might. More than 3,000 died that day, and the world was transformed. For a fleeting moment, the American people - and global sentiment - rallied around Bush. But that opportunity would soon be squandered.LiNeBrEaKFor the neocon factions within the Bush administration, the 9/11 attacks opened the opportunity for two goals it brought into office: To force a regime change in Iraq, and to expand the power of the executive branch. Bush and Vice President Dick Cheney went on the stump in 2002 to sell the notion that Iraq possessed weapons of mass destruction and had a connection to al Qaeda. Neither proved to be true. Still, America went to war, and American troops remain in battle to this day, many billions of dollars and more than 4,000 U.S. lives later.LiNeBrEaKThe threat of terrorism became the rationale for other Bush administration assaults on American values. The Bush White House pushed the limits of the law to establish warrantless wiretapping, military tribunals, indefinite detentions of suspected "enemy combatants," torture techniques on detainees and a legal no-man's land at Guantanamo Bay. Bush expanded and redefined the use of "signing statements" to effectively declare that he - as president - can pick and choose which laws he will enforce or ignore.LiNeBrEaKJust don't call Bush a conservative. The last Clinton administration budget had a surplus of more than $100 billion; the fiscal 2009 deficit could approach $700 billion.LiNeBrEaKBush was a disaster on the environment in many ways, but in none more critical than in his belated acknowledgment that climate change was real and was a serious threat to the planet. This nation essentially lost eight years in addressing the most profound issue of our time. In the final weeks of his presidency, Bush moved to undermine the Endangered Species Act. The Bush administration also let politics trump science in other ways, such as its resistance to stem cell research and myriad family-planning programs.LiNeBrEaKPolitics also pervaded this administration's oversight of the Department of Justice. Its attempt to fire nine U.S. attorneys appeared targeted at those who were not regarded as conservative enough.LiNeBrEaKWhen strong hurricanes struck the Gulf Coast in 2005, what seemed to be a slow and disorganized response reflected badly on the Bush White House. The public relations damage was compounded when Bush toured Louisiana right after Katrina and commended Federal Emergency Management Agency director Michael Brown for a "heckuva job." The awful hurricane aftermath, in which we saw hungry and frantic Americans scrambling through the chaos, became an indictment on the competence of the Bush administration.LiNeBrEaK"He kept us safe" is the mantra of the Bush loyalists. Indeed, terrorists did not strike again after 9/11. But the Bush policies did, leading us into war, depriving our liberties, exploiting our natural resources and allowing the construction of financial houses of cards - while seizing new executive powers at every turn. This nation is deeper in debt, gloomier in outlook and weaker in global stature than when George W. Bush took office.LiNeBrEaKThis has been a disastrous eight years.		TERRORISM (90%); SEPTEMBER 11 ATTACK (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); US PRESIDENTS (91%); TERRORIST ORGANIZATIONS (87%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (79%); IRAQ WAR (78%); HIJACKING (71%); WEAPONS OF MASS DESTRUCTION (71%); HURRICANE KATRINA (70%); HURRICANES (70%); CLIMATE CHANGE (69%); SUPREME COURTS (68%); LAW COURTS and TRIBUNALS (68%); COMMERCIAL and GENERAL AVIATION AIRCRAFT (66%); ARMED FORCES (66%); AIRLINES (52%); WIRETAPPING (50%); ECONOMIC CRISIS (76%); MILITARY COURTS (73%) INSIGHT; EDITORIAL; PRESIDENCY; PRESIDENT; END; SEPTEMBER 11 TERRORIST ATTACK; WAR WITH IRAQ 2003  		AL-QAEDA (55%); SUPREME COURT OF THE UNITED STATES (56%)  	GEORGE W BUSH (96%); DICK CHENEY (53%) George W. Bush  	CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (98%); IRAQ (93%); CUBA (66%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Francisco Chronicle All Rights Reserved  																
The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   FINAL Edition	The world;  THE INAUGURATION OF BARACK OBAMA;  Global crises: Obama inherits more dire and serious troubles than any incoming U.S. president in decades, but the world seems to trust that he has the personal wherewithal to meet all challenges	Main News; Pg. W6  	1498 words  	President Barack Hussein Obama will arrive at the White House on Tuesday and inherit a world of troubles weighty enough to make Atlas groan.LiNeBrEaK"This is the toughest foreign policy in-box that any president has faced in 55 years," said Jessica Mathews, president of the Carnegie Endowment for International Peace. "We are in a deep hole on a whole lot of issues where he's going to have to climb out of before he can even start to achieve."LiNeBrEaKImmediate crises such as the violence in Gaza, first-term priorities such as the wars in Iraq and Afghanistan, long-term endeavors such as the American relationship with China and Russia, and epochal concerns such as globalization and global warming - Obama will face them all.LiNeBrEaKAt the same time, the new president's supporters in this country and around the world are expecting a new era of effective multilateral diplomacy as radical and revolutionary, in its way, as the era of unilateral militarism it is replacing - at a time when an extraordinary financial crisis has sharply limited the new administration's ability to pay for new initiatives. LiNeBrEaKMore dire challengesLiNeBrEaK"I certainly don't know of any president who has come to the White House with more challenges - dire, serious, strategically threatening challenges - as Obama," said Abbas Milani, director of the Iranian Studies Program at Stanford University. LiNeBrEaKCriticized in the presidential campaign for a thin international dossier, the president-elect's Web site now promises to "renew America's security and standing in the world through a new era of American leadership," with goals including fighting global poverty, seeking Middle East peace, a comprehensive settlement with Iran, and a nuclear-free world.LiNeBrEaKBut in the real world of international affairs, setting goals is easy - a democratic Iraq, a Palestinian state, a halt to the killing in Darfur. Achieving them is hard. LiNeBrEaKObama outlined some of his foreign policy ideas in "The Audacity of Hope." He embraces multilateralism when possible and unilateralism when necessary; democratization and liberalization as goals but not as impositions; reforming inefficient international organizations, but setting a model through domestic reform.LiNeBrEaKSome foreign policy experts see in his moderate philosophy an exciting departure from the policies of past administrations.LiNeBrEaK"The Obama team is much more realist and - it seems paradoxical - much more idealist at the same time," Milani said. "That combination, I think, is a very potent combination."LiNeBrEaKAt the same time, the people Obama has selected to implement his policies - Hillary Rodham Clinton as secretary of state, Robert Gates as secretary of defense, Gen. Jim Jones as national security adviser - are not seen as revolutionaries, said George Friedman, founder of Stratfor, a geopolitical intelligence company.LiNeBrEaK"These are not radical thinkers," Friedman said. "Literally, he has positioned himself in the heart of the foreign policy establishment."LiNeBrEaKLess stick, more carrotLiNeBrEaKMany other foreign policy experts do expect changes - even dramatic ones - under Obama, who they say will use less stick and more carrot in dealing with allies and rivals alike.LiNeBrEaK"Obama has to say that the United States is the most important player in the world system, but we are going to cooperate with every other player," said Geoffrey Wiseman, director of the USC Center on Public Diplomacy. "The U.S. has more hard power than anybody else, and in some ways it has more soft power than anybody else. ... I think he is trying to strike a reasonable balance in the middle."LiNeBrEaKAs evidence of intent, many foreign policy experts point to Obama's retention of Gates, Bush's secretary of defense, who in the past year gave a series of speeches calling for a dramatic increase in American soft power.LiNeBrEaKThomas Barnett, author of the forthcoming "Great Powers: America and the World After Bush," said that by keeping Gates, Obama sent a message that he will rebalance American hard and soft power.LiNeBrEaK"By keeping Gates in there you have a guy who's really pushing for, 'Hey, let's get off this next-war-itis crap,' " said Barnett, using the term Gates coined to describe the defense establishment's obsession with a hypothetical war against some future superpower. LiNeBrEaKThe challenge for Obama, Barnett said, is not just to rebalance America's policy, but to move it away from a 20th century concept that views the world as a jumble of individual nations that require discrete policies and toward a 21st century perspective that sees the world as an interconnected network.LiNeBrEaKIn "Great Powers," Barnett uses this example: In the old model, placing economic sanctions on Iran while boosting trade with China made sense. The new model recognizes that by boosting China's economy through trade, the United States boosts China's energy needs. That sends China shopping for oil in Iran, meaning U.S. actions indirectly strengthen the Tehran regime.LiNeBrEaKRubik's Cube of issuesLiNeBrEaK"Hopefully Obama comes in with a sense of the horizontal connectivity between these issues," Barnett said. "He is very much looking at a Rubik's Cube - an interconnected puzzle, where how he deals with one situation is going to send early signals on a host of issues."LiNeBrEaKObama faces a thick package of interconnected issues. They range from the way the economic collapse may affect China's willingness to help tackle human rights issues in Africa to the manner in which tensions between India and Pakistan are causing Pakistan to shift military assets away from the Khyber Pass - America's route to Afghanistan. LiNeBrEaKSome analysts are skeptical about how a philosophy that embraces complexity and multilateralism will translate into speedy progress in the real world.LiNeBrEaK"At the level of rhetoric and diplomacy, it's going to be a much better environment than we've seen recently," said Ted Galen Carpenter, vice president for defense and foreign policy studies at the Cato Institute. "He is not Bush. That gives him a certain amount of time, a certain advantage going in. But nasty, substantive issues have a knack of intruding."LiNeBrEaKFew analysts expect or encourage Obama to resolve - or even to tackle - some of the biggest global issues right away. Instead, some say, Obama should seek out contained, nonideological issues where America shares interests with allies and rivals.LiNeBrEaKSuch issues offer the United States an opportunity to connect with friends and foes through familiar organizations - NATO, the United Nations - through existing organizations that the United States does not connect with as regularly - the Shanghai Cooperation Organization, the League of Arab States - and through currently nonexistent organizations that the United States can help create to address specific issues, such as piracy in the Gulf of Aden or violence in East Congo, and then nurture as long-term diplomatic forums.LiNeBrEaKObama is a fan of small-scale cooperations - his chapter on foreign policy in "The Audacity of Hope" ends by spotlighting two such examples: the U.S.-led effort to secure nuclear materials set adrift by the collapse of the Soviet Union, and American participation in the global response to the 2004 East Asian tsunami.LiNeBrEaKThe world is chockablock with opportunities like those, analysts say - the challenge Obama faces is picking the right ones.LiNeBrEaKIronically, among the ripest opportunities Obama may inherit is what is broadly seen as his predecessor's greatest failure: Iraq.LiNeBrEaK"Almost all of the neighbors have an interest in what Iraq is going to be like going forward," Carpenter said. "That clearly means talking to countries like Turkey and Saudi Arabia, but it also means probably at some point bringing Iran and Syria into the process. I think Obama will be receptive to that sort of thing."LiNeBrEaKSkeptics note that while diplomacy has been unpopular in recent years, it's not like it hasn't been tried. But even some of them say Obama may have what it takes to break through the gridlock.LiNeBrEaKHe understands powerLiNeBrEaK"I think that Obama may well be a great president. Because I see him as a rather ruthless, calculating, unsentimental man who will sell you your own hat if you leave it on the table," said Friedman, admiringly. "He is a man who understands power."LiNeBrEaKOther, more optimistic analysts say that Obama's arrival might be a game-changer for a less Machiavellian reason: his name.LiNeBrEaK" 'Barack' is Arabic for 'grace of God,' 'Hussein' is the name of the Shiites' third imam, the symbol of their faith," said Milani. "The idea that someone can come from this background - a child of an African father and a single mother, a poor person who earns a scholarship, goes to Harvard, becomes the president of the United States - is so unlike every stereotypical conspiracy-tainted image of the United States, it does a great deal to undermine that false premise."LiNeBrEaKOther analysts agreed, saying Obama's personal story suggests he will have a longer global honeymoon than past presidents.LiNeBrEaK"This is a massive public diplomacy gift that the United States has been given - or the United States has given itself," Wiseman said. 		INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (91%); FOREIGN RELATIONS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); US PRESIDENTS (91%); IRAQ WAR (90%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (90%); FOREIGN POLICY (89%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (79%); PUBLIC POLICY (78%); NATIONAL SECURITY (77%); GLOBALIZATION (77%); WAR and CONFLICT (74%); 