The Sunday Oregonian (Portland, Oregon) 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   Sunrise Edition	Will recession kill green plans? Critics in industry say limits proposed in West Coast states can easily push employment lower and power rates higher  	Local News  	1146 words  	"The governor is not going to approve a proposal that's going to damage the Oregon economy."LiNeBrEaKBrian Shipley,LiNeBrEaKdeputy chief of staff for energy, climate change and natural resourcesLiNeBrEaKWill recession kill green plans?LiNeBrEaKCritics in industry say limits proposed in West Coast statesLiNeBrEaKcan easily push employment lower and power rates higher Governor asks LiNeBrEaKfor tighter lidLiNeBrEaKon emissionsLiNeBrEaKSCOTT LEARNLiNeBrEaKOregon's economy is putting at risk Gov. Ted Kulongoski's aggressive plans for tackling global warming.LiNeBrEaKThe governor's bid to limit Oregon's greenhouse gas emissions arrives before the 2009 Legislature at an awkward time.LiNeBrEaKManufacturing jobs are dropping. Electricity bills are rising. Powerful economic interests, including heavy industry and the state's biggest electric utilities, argue that Kulongoski's strategy could boost both of those trends.LiNeBrEaKIn Oregon's global warming debate, in other words, prepare for Stella the Steelworker.LiNeBrEaKThanks to limits on the release of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases, she'll pay higher utility bills at home. Her mill will pay more for electricity, too, and buy either expensive pollution controls or expensive pollution allowances. Meantime, some dirtier mill in Indonesia or Idaho will spew greenhouse gases at will.LiNeBrEaKKulongoski, along with other West Coast governors, wants to ratchet down the amounts of carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases that industry, power plants and, eventually, cars and trucks, can send to the sky.LiNeBrEaKEnvironmentalists expect a fight and a test of how the environment fares when the economy takes center stage.LiNeBrEaKThe governor says capping emissions and gradually tightening the caps is the best way to ensure that Oregon reaches its goal --one of the most aggressive in the nation --to cut greenhouse gas emissions by 10 percent below 1990 levels by 2020.LiNeBrEaKKulongoski says he'll insulate the economy from rate increases by boosting energy efficiency projects to reduce fossil fuel use and encourage alternatives.LiNeBrEaKStella's mill will get an expanded tax credit if it invests in energy efficiency, for example. And Stella would have a better shot at financial help with insulating her house or installing energy efficient windows.LiNeBrEaKThe governor proposes subsidies for electric cars, incentives for solar energy, tougher building codes, help for residential and commercial energy efficiency projects and other measures designed to reduce emissions.LiNeBrEaKThat would give industry and power plants more breathing room, Kulongoski says, particularly since the caps don't take effect until 2012.LiNeBrEaKThe whole package would cement Oregon's standing as a green leader, the thinking goes, and give Oregon companies a jump-start if the U.S. Congress passes a national cap.LiNeBrEaK"The governor is not going to approve a proposal that's going to damage the Oregon economy," said Brian Shipley, Kulongoski's deputy chief of staff for energy, climate change and natural resources.LiNeBrEaKEnvironmentalists warn that political pressure from business could lead to a looser cap that doesn't end up reducing emissions. That appears to be what happened the past few years in Europe.LiNeBrEaKOn the other hand, if the emissions cap stays tight, critics are skeptical that energy efficiency improvements can nab enough emissions savings to prevent a big economic hit.LiNeBrEaKThe Northwest's population is expected to grow. So are the numbers of electronic gizmos.LiNeBrEaKMark Nelson, a high-profile Salem lobbyist, is leading Oregonians for Balanced Climate Policy, which questions Kulongoski's approach. Its members include groups representing Realtors, paper mills, loggers, industry, cattlemen, dairy owners, farmers, metals industries, food processors and builders.LiNeBrEaKThe group agrees emissions need to come down, Nelson says, and strongly supports other measures to boost energy efficiency and reduce greenhouse gases. It also isn't absolutely opposed to an emissions cap, Nelson says.LiNeBrEaKBut he doesn't sound too enthused.LiNeBrEaK"We'd almost prefer a carbon tax, which we think is a hell of a lot more straightforward," he said. "The economic damage is so incredible (to reach the state's emissions reduction targets). You only do it by shutting down industry."LiNeBrEaKLabor, a big supporter of the Democrats in the Democratic-controlled Legislature, is shaky on the proposal. If a plan included protections for workers affected by the cap, says Elana Guiney of the Oregon AFL-CIO, "We definitely would consider supporting it."LiNeBrEaKMany of Oregon's public and private electric utilities, including PGE and PacifiCorp, say any carbon caps or carbon taxes should be adopted at the federal level, not by states.LiNeBrEaKA state system prompts manufacturers to move to states without regulation and lower their costs by doing so, said Scott Bolton, PacifiCorp's West Coast lobbyist.LiNeBrEaKBut environmental groups aren't ceding the economic high ground.LiNeBrEaKPutting a gradually tightening cap on emissions is the smartest way to wean the economy off fossil fuel that is volatile in price, questionable in source and diminishing in quantity, said Eric de Place, senior researcher with the Sightline Institute, a Seattle-based environmental think tank.LiNeBrEaK"It is not a winning strategy to need huge amounts of energy to generate a buck," de Place said. "If an Oregon steel plant uses a ton of power, the best strategy to protect those jobs is to make it the cleanest, meanest, most efficient steel plant there is."LiNeBrEaKEnergy price hikesLiNeBrEaKThe Western Climate Initiative, which last year designed a cap system for Oregon and other Western states, predicts residential electricity rates would rise 13 percent over base levels by 2020 if the cap focused on industry and utilities.LiNeBrEaKIndustrial electricity prices would rise by more than a third, the group predicts, though the number would drop dramatically if emissions from cars, trucks and building heating get capped, too. A broader system would boost gasoline prices from 7 percent to 17 percent, the WCI says.LiNeBrEaKThe Electric Power Research Institute says West Coast electricity price hikes could be more dramatic in the early years of a cap --in the range of 40 percent --because utilities couldn't just flip to less carbon-intensive sources.LiNeBrEaKThe only Oregon-specific estimate so far comes from Portland's Cascade Policy Institute, which opposes a cap.LiNeBrEaKAbsent an alternative energy breakthrough, a cap system based on Oregon's greenhouse gas reduction goals would chop economic growth to 2020 in half, the study projected.LiNeBrEaKKulongoski has commissioned an Oregon-specific study. David Van't Hof, the governor's sustainability and renewable energy adviser, said initial results don't show a big hit to industrial jobs.LiNeBrEaKIf global warming predictions pan out, Oregon could be short of water in the summer, get more damaging storms and endure more extreme temperatures, driving electricity use up.LiNeBrEaK"The broader issue," Van't Hof said, "is what's the cost of not taking action."LiNeBrEaKScott Learn: 503-294-7657; scottlearn@news.oregonian.com		NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (92%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (91%); UTILITY RATES (91%); EMISSIONS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (90%); GOVERNORS (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); RECESSION (90%); ECONOMIC NEWS (90%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (89%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (89%); APPROVALS (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (89%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (89%)