The Times Leader (Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania)  	January 18, 2009 Sunday 	OPINION: We should allow time, history to decide who compares best to President Lincoln Richard L. Connor Opinion  	COMMENTARY  	1041 words  	Jan. 18--IT'S EASY TO make comparisons between President-elect Barack Obama and former President Abraham Lincoln. We have the Illinois connections and then the hovering, dark clouds of war, a nation divided and in crisis, and other similarities that provide a historic link. Drawing a line between the two men -- Obama as an African American and Lincoln with his legacy of ending slavery -- is as emotionally charged as it is inspirational.LiNeBrEaKBut as we await the historic inauguration of Obama on Tuesday, there is another parallel with Lincoln and perhaps even one with Sir Winston Churchill. That parallel is awaiting the historic analysis of President George W. Bush. LiNeBrEaKBush leaves office with approval ratings lower than the prices you hear some auto dealers offering to hesitant buyers.LiNeBrEaKI can find only one person on record still devoted to Bush, and she denies her loyalty has anything to do with the baby gift she received from him when her daughter was born.LiNeBrEaKNevertheless -- and this may knock me off some Christmas card lists -- I can see a case for history being kinder to Bush than might seem imaginable now.LiNeBrEaKYes, there are any number of better decisions he could have made. Foremost among them would have been to bring a quick and decisive end to the war in Iraq shortly after it began.LiNeBrEaKAnd yes, he appears to have been soft on big business, especially the oil and energy sector. He has not broken new ground in one of the most vital areas of government policy -- the environment, climate change, and the entire green movement. The handling of some war prisoners has been questionable. His administration failed in response to the crisis in New Orleans and Mississippi following Hurricane Katrina. He fired the people who made the blunders but his personal culpability is that the disaster and accompanying problems happened on his watch.LiNeBrEaKThe dismissal of seven U.S. attorney generals appears to have had a political agenda and resulted in the resignation of many senior staff from the department of justice. The controversy continues to be a black mark for the White House.LiNeBrEaKThere are areas, though, where Bush has excelled.LiNeBrEaKHe has faced a number of crises that few if any presidents have had to confront. First, he was President when the United States was attacked on Sept. 11, 2001. He was decisive in his response and showed admirable leadership both at home and abroad. His establishment of the Office of Homeland Security and creation of a cabinet post is historic and shows vision to the changing world order and the danger that now exists on our shores.LiNeBrEaKThe nation now appears headed for disastrous financial calamity, the worst since the Great Depression. The Bush administration has been forceful in trying to bring calm and to allocate money to industries fighting to survive.LiNeBrEaKAnd the economic woes of this country -- just like other monumental, sea-change problems -- did not simply appear one day. Nor will they go away the next. Sure, this happened under his watch but the seeds for our mortgage, home loan crisis and those of the domestic automobile industry collapse were sown long before Bush took office.LiNeBrEaKHis administration rid a nation, region and the world of Saddam Hussein, a despot whose sordid, tortuous crimes against humanity are well documented.LiNeBrEaKHe paved the way for democracy in Iraq and other countries. It is still too early to tell if democracy will stick in any of those countries, but people who have never voted are voting and among others, women, have new found rights to education and liberation.LiNeBrEaKIf we begin to expect that a chief executive of anything -- be it a country or a Fortune 500 company -- cannot make a mistake or two among the hundreds, perhaps, thousands of decisions they make, then our standards have reached the point of ridiculousness.LiNeBrEaKLooking at Lincoln and Churchill and how they were viewed both in and out of office indicates how difficult it is to pre-judge history's final assessment of a leader.LiNeBrEaKBoth men were criticized for making quick and sometimes impulsive decisions against the advice of advisers. At times both were pilloried for decisions regarding war.LiNeBrEaKLincoln bore the brunt of criticism for war casualties. More soldiers died at the Civil War battle at Antietam in one day -- more than 7,000 -- than the number of American soldiers who have been killed in the war in Iraq. That number is about 4,500 which is not to imply those deaths are inconsequential or without great heartaches to their families.LiNeBrEaKLincoln was criticized, as Bush has been, for running afoul of the Constitution and civil liberties. Lincoln suspended the writ of habeas corpus, which allows imprisoned persons to challenge the legality of their arrests. And there were more than 10,000 "arbitrary arrests" while Lincoln was in office.LiNeBrEaKBush lacks the eloquence of both men.LiNeBrEaKChurchill was not only a galvanizing and witty speaker, he also wrote "The History of the Second World War," a book which won the Nobel Prize for Literature in 1953. Lincoln earned immortality with his address at Gettysburg.LiNeBrEaKWe know for virtual certainty that Bush's speeches will not go down in history. He will not be known for a public display of intellectual depth. What we do not know, however, is how he will be ultimately judged. We know there has not been a foreign attack on our land since 9/11. Is it because of Bush's policies?LiNeBrEaKIf it is proven he kept our nation safe, we will begin to see him differently as a leader.LiNeBrEaKIn fact, only time will tell if he will be viewed as a failure or if, like Lincoln and Churchill, his legacy will grow and expand and shine in the reflected light of history. In the end, it may be Bush -- and not Obama -- who will be found to have more in common with the great President Lincoln.LiNeBrEaKRichard L. Connor is editor and publisher of The Times Leader. Reach him at rconnor@timesleader.com		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (86%); US PRESIDENTS (91%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (77%); IRAQ WAR (77%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (76%); ENERGY and UTILITY TRADE (74%); GREEN MARKET (73%); NATIONAL SECURITY (72%); GREAT DEPRESSION (72%); CLIMATE CHANGE (69%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (69%); HURRICANE KATRINA (68%); CHRISTMAS (67%); ATTORNEYS GENERAL (66%); SEPTEMBER 11 ATTACK (65%); JUSTICE DEPARTMENTS (64%); HURRICANES (63%); ECONOMIC DEPRESSION (62%); LAW ENFORCEMENT (61%); NEW CAR DEALERS (54%); SPECIAL INVESTIGATIVE FORCES (50%)  			BARACK OBAMA (94%); GEORGE W BUSH (56%)  	NEW ORLEANS, LA, USA (79%) ILLINOIS, USA (92%); PENNSYLVANIA, USA (79%); MISSISSIPPI, USA (79%); LOUISIANA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%); IRAQ (79%)  	January 18, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Times Leader   	Richard L. Connor, The Times Leader, Wilkes-Barre, Pa.  			Lifestyle  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090118-WB-OPINION-We-should-allow-time-history-to-decide-who-compares-best-to-President-Lincoln-Richard-L-Connor-Opinion-0118  	WB  									
The Washington Post 	January 18, 2009 Sunday   Met 1 Edition	Study: Electricity Usage Is Down;  Weather, Rates May Be Factors In 2% Drop in '08 	METRO; Pg. C01  	896 words  	Last year, as gas prices broke $4 a gallon and the U.S. economy put a wheel in the ditch, the Washington region did something improbable.LiNeBrEaKIt became slightly friendlier toward the climate.LiNeBrEaKSlightly.LiNeBrEaKA new Washington Post analysis shows that local homes and businesses used about 2 percent less electricity in the first nine months of 2008 than they did in 2007. That's a small drop, but for Washington, any drop is significant: Electric power is the region's largest single source of greenhouse gas emissions, and in recent years power use has grown rapidly.LiNeBrEaKThe news cheered local officials, many of whom have promised to cut emissions sharply. LiNeBrEaKBut it also illuminates the work they still have, cajoling or forcing residents to change old behaviors. Last year, a spike in fuel prices, a spell of mild weather and a historic recession barely dented the region's problem.LiNeBrEaK"Things may get worse before they get better," Montgomery County Executive Isiah Leggett (D) said earlier this week at a news conference announcing new proposals to shrink the county's carbon footprint. "But someone has to start."LiNeBrEaKThe Washington Post estimated recent trends in the region's carbon dioxide emissions using sales data from electric utilities and government figures for miles driven on local roads. Together, these two sources account for about 70 percent of local emissions, leaving out things such as methane from local cows, airplanes and oil-burning furnaces.LiNeBrEaKThe analysis, using methods from the U.S. Energy Information Administration, appears to offer the first glimpse of regional emissions since 2005.LiNeBrEaKIt shows that for two years -- even as local governments promised to reduce greenhouse gases -- the region was pumping out more and more of them. Emissions from the two sources grew 1. 2 percent per year on average in 2006 and 2007.LiNeBrEaKThat was slower than the growth of the region's emissions in the booming first years of this decade. But it was still about 50 percent higher than the national rate for 2005 to 2007. Local emissions still appear to have been borne upward by bad traffic, centers for computer servers, extensively wired suburban houses and a steady, government-centered economy.LiNeBrEaKThen came 2008, and a glimmer of good news about electricity. Vehicle-travel figures from last year are not available yet.LiNeBrEaKLocal leaders said the drop in power usage last year might be a sign that their save-the-climate efforts are working.LiNeBrEaKAlready, they said, Montgomery's commercial buildings are using less power. Dominion has sold 2 million energy-efficient light bulbs. And more than 20,000 people have logged on for energy-saving tips at the Pepco Web site.LiNeBrEaK"I'm certainly encouraged by it," said Stan Edwards, who oversees climate programs in Montgomery. "And I hope it's something we're doing."LiNeBrEaKBut those who sell the electricity saw other possible reasons. At Pepco, which serves the District and Maryland suburbs, officials also blamed a rate hike that increased customers' bills, by about $2 a month on average in Maryland and about $21 a month on average in the District.LiNeBrEaK"There is no way to really identify how much of it is ethically motivated and how much of it is budget-motivated," said Kemm Farney, an analyst at Pepco Holdings, the utility's parent company.LiNeBrEaKAnd in Virginia, Dominion officials said the change was probably just related to the weather. Last year was milder, and customers needed less power to heat and cool their homes. Power usage decreased all along the East Coast last year, and utility experts believe the weather and the economy were largely behind it.LiNeBrEaKWhen you filter out the effects of weather, Dominion spokesman Chet Wade said, "we're still seeing growth in Virginia."LiNeBrEaKSo this good news is also bad news, a warning about how hard it is to slash emissions. Will the decline in power use vanish if this summer is hotter, or if the region booms again?LiNeBrEaK"We know that the task is huge," said John Morrill, Arlington County's energy manager.LiNeBrEaKMontgomery, Arlington and Fairfax counties have committed to stopping the growth of overall emissions by next year. The District has set a target of reducing emissions 7 percent below 1990 levels by 2012.LiNeBrEaKBut local governments don't have the federal government's power over such major emissions sources as autos and power plants. And now their options are diminished by tight budgets.LiNeBrEaKOn Thursday, a panel in Montgomery proposed measures including solar panels on county buildings, bike paths for carbon-free commutes and interest-free loans for homeowners who want to give their houses a green overhaul.LiNeBrEaKBut Leggett, the county executive, said he had not yet decided which ideas the cash-strapped government would take on.LiNeBrEaKIn Arlington, the government had begun funding energy audits of county homes. The county paid an expert about $300 to examine Andrew D'Uva's Clarendon townhome for energy-leaking drafts; the expert recommended that he buy a more efficient heating and cooling system.LiNeBrEaKBut the county didn't make D'Uva buy the system. And it didn't buy it for him.LiNeBrEaK"Really, I didn't want to waste any more energy than I needed to," D'Uva said. But his purchase of a new system won't pay for itself for years: "I had to invest $8,000 to save $700 a year" on lower utility bills, D'Uva said.LiNeBrEaKNow, even the audits have stopped, halted last summer when the budget ran out. The county had audited about 40 households.LiNeBrEaKIt has about 89,000.		EMISSIONS (91%); OIL and GAS PRICES (90%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (89%); METHANE (78%); RECESSION (78%); ECONOMIC NEWS (78%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%);