nd to shy away from math and science, and that ought not to be."LiNeBrEaKEwers said sponsors are crucial to the continued growth of LEGO League since robotics kits cost between $500 and $600. The teams raise a lot of their own money, but they're assisted by groups like 4-H (Ewers' specialty), the Idaho Robotics Opportunities for K-12 Students (Idaho ROKS), the NASA Idaho Space Grant Consortium, the Idaho National Laboratory and private donors, he said.LiNeBrEaKOnce the teams have their kits, they set about building their robot and programming it to perform a set list of tasks, which generally consists of moving various LEGO pieces around the game table.LiNeBrEaKDuring the first round of competition Saturday afternoon, the Moscow team of the Circuit Breakers scored 215 out of 405 possible points, good enough to put them in first place for a while. Robot operators and siblings David Bowman, 15, and Martha Bowman, 11, said robotics is the perfect way to get them hooked on technology.LiNeBrEaK"It's actually really great for the scientific and technical stuff," David Bowman said. "It teaches us about computers and computer engineering, and the physical side of the robot."LiNeBrEaKMartha Bowman said the fun of the experience made her more curious about subjects like math. "The way they do it, I get more interested."LiNeBrEaKHer brother was even more enthusiastic.LiNeBrEaK"It's a blast," David Bowman said. "Give us LEGOs and we're just set. We'll do anything."LiNeBrEaKMills may be contacted at jmills@lmtribune.com or (208) 883-0564.		CHILDREN (90%); COLLEGES and UNIVERSITIES (90%); ROBOTICS (89%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (89%); EDUCATION SYSTEMS and INSTITUTIONS (76%); EDUCATION (76%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (76%); MATHEMATICS (67%); EDUCATION ADMINISTRATION (65%); CLIMATE CHANGE (55%)  	SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY EQUIPMENT LLC (57%)  	UNIVERSITY OF IDAHO (57%)  		IDAHO, USA (94%); UTAH, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	20