The Boston Globe 	January 17, 2009 Saturday   THIRD EDITION	`RECYCLING' AT THE DUMP  	LETTERS TO THE EDITOR; Pg. A10  	735 words  	Landfills holdLiNeBrEaKpotential for powerLiNeBrEaKRE "FINDING a sustainable future at the dump" (Op-ed, Jan. 12): Jeffrey Surma totally ignored the remarkable progress that has been made in turning landfill gas into low-cost, renewable energy, and misrepresented as fact that America's landfills are "close to capacity." The country currently has about 20 years of landfill disposal capacity overall. LiNeBrEaKUS waste-based energy projects provide enough clean, lower-cost, renewable energy to light and heat more than 3 million homes. Major firms such as Dell and BMW are using power generated from landfill gas to run offices and manufacturing sites. And the University of New Hampshire at Durham recently installed a pipeline from a neighboring landfill that is expected to provide the school with as much as 80 to 85 percent of its energy needs. LiNeBrEaKThe use of landfill gas reduces global warming because it captures methane. The EPA estimates that using methane as renewable, "green" energy has the annual environmental and energy benefits equivalent to preventing the use of almost 271 million barrels of oil.LiNeBrEaKThe promise of existing and emerging technologies is essential for advancing the beneficial use of waste products. However, these facilities are still in the pilot stage. What the general public needs to know is that solid waste companies using existing technology are converting landfill gas into clean, renewable energy, helping reduce our dependence on foreign oil and reducing greenhouse gas emissions.LiNeBrEaKBruce J. ParkerLiNeBrEaKWashington, D.C.LiNeBrEaKThe writer is president and CEO of the National Solid Wastes Management Association.LiNeBrEaKRecycling is stillLiNeBrEaKour best optionLiNeBrEaKJEFFREY SURMA uses terms like "recycling" and "sustainable" to describe a process that is anything but. Once our wastes are turned into energy, they are gone, up in smoke, not able to be renewed or recycled. His column reflects a lack of understanding of these terms and of environmental principles, and is a prime example of greenwashing.LiNeBrEaKContrary to Surma's claims, genuine recycling is the environmentally preferable, sustainable way to manage waste. It precludes the need to mine new resources, reduces pollution, and uses less water and energy to make new products. According to a recent study by the Tellus Institute that was commissioned by the state, recycling saves much more energy than is generated by turning waste into energy, and creates fewer greenhouse gas emissions and particulates. Plus, it employs many more people.LiNeBrEaKMarkets for recyclables are depressed because of the economy. So are all commodities. Commodity markets are cyclical and will rebound - likely well before a plasma-enhanced melter plant is built.LiNeBrEaKThe only thing renewable about garbage is that we keep making it. Some components may be renewable (paper, food) but others are not (metals, plastics, glass). To claim that turning these materials into energy is renewable, recycling, environmental, or sustainable is, well, rubbish.LiNeBrEaKAmy PerlmutterLiNeBrEaKCambridgeLiNeBrEaKMarkets will recoverLiNeBrEaKREADERS OF Jeffery Surma's op-ed might be misled into believing that plasma gasification provides the ideal solution to the problem of how to find value in the 6 million tons of waste Massachusetts generates every year, but recycling is still the better solution. Though the current financial crisis has had a negative effect on recycling markets, when the economy recovers, so will these markets.LiNeBrEaKThe highest use for what Surma describes as "familiar solid-waste products" is still recycling. There is no need to find an alternative disposal option for materials such as paper - which six months ago was the country's leading export by volume - soda bottles, milk jugs, tin cans, scrap metal, etc. Demand for these products historically has been very strong and will undoubtedly recover before too long.LiNeBrEaKThe most important benefit of recycling is that it decreases the demand for natural resources used to manufacture new products. Recycling paper saves trees, water, and energy. Recycling aluminum reduces the need to extract aluminum from the earth and uses 95 percent less energy than creating a can from virgin materials.LiNeBrEaKThe state needs to stay true to its commitment to capture the recyclables in its waste stream. Only once we have diverted as much as we can for true recycling should we consider alternative disposal options for what is left over.LiNeBrEaKAnn DorfmanLiNeBrEaKNewtonLiNeBrEaKThe writer is on the executive board of MassRecycle.		LETTERS and COMMENTS (92%); LANDFILLS (91%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); METHANE (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); EMISSIONS (89%); WASTE MANAGEMENT and REMEDIATION SERVICES (89%); SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (79%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (78%); ENERGY DEMAND (78%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (78%); COMMODITIES TRADING (77%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (77%); FUEL MARKETS (77%); MANUFACTURING FACILITIES (74%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (73%); PARTICULATE MATTER (72%); ECONOMIC NEWS (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); CHEMICALS and RUBBER MARKETS (63%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (58%); PLANT CONSTRUCTION (54%); BUSINESS and PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATIONS (65%)  		UNIVERSITY OF NEW HAMPSHIRE (56%)  		DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (79%); NEW HAMPSHIRE, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Jim Meehan Illustration  		Newspaper  	2009 Globe Newspaper Company All Rights Reserved  																
The Denver Post 	January 17, 2009 Saturday   FINAL EDITION	EDITORIAL With one move, Bush an environmental champion  	Pg. A-30  	217 words  	President George W. Bush is not likely to be accused of being overly friendly to the environment, but his decision creating three new marine national monuments in the Pacific Ocean near Hawaii deserves praise. LiNeBrEaKHis move means 195,274 square miles of marine environment, which includes some of the more pristine coral reef ecosystems in the world, will be protected.LiNeBrEaKIt's a surprising move from a president who has dragged his heels on global warming issues and declared open season on large tracts of public land in the West for oil and gas drillers.LiNeBrEaKWith the designation, Bush will have protected more ocean than anyone in history. The cynical view is that it's a last-minute effort at legacy building - but we'll take it.LiNeBrEaKThe protected areas include the Marianas Trench, undersea volcanoes and thermal vents, and a series of atolls that are home to a variety of seabirds, endangered turtles and hundreds of species of fish.LiNeBrEaKIn 2006, Bush created what was then the largest marine sanctuary by designating 140,000 square miles of ocean and islands near Hawaii as protected.LiNeBrEaKWe're glad to see the president making an effort to save what are unique and fragile parts of the ocean ecosystem.LiNeBrEaKIt's just too bad he didn't see fit to extend that laudable sentiment to more policy areas during his eight years in office.		NATIONAL PARKS (91%); ISLANDS and REEFS (90%); OCEANS (90%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); SALTWATER ECOSYSTEMS (90%); US PRESIDENTS (78%); MARINE RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (78%); ENDANGERED SPECIES (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (56%)  			GEORGE W BUSH (94%)  	HAWAII, USA (93%); PACIFIC OCEAN (92%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 19, 2009  	ENGLISH  		Editorial  	Newspaper  	2009 The Denver Post All Rights Reserved  																
The Hartford Courant (Connecticut)  	January 17, 2009 Saturday 	Despite The Cold, The Heat's Still On  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	371 words  	Jan. 17--So what ever happened to global warming?LiNeBrEaKThe question might pop up as we try to insulate ourselves from this week's chill.LiNeBrEaKThe short answer is, it's January at 42 degrees latitude. Arctic temperatures -- in the teens with a wind chill down to zero to 5 below -- will be around at least through tonight, the National Weather Service says. LiNeBrEaKThe longer answer: Weather is not the same as climate. The short-term fluctuations of temperature and precipitation we're used to in New England are just part of a long-term picture of averages and means.LiNeBrEaKWeather: An early frost kills off the last of your tomatoes.LiNeBrEaKClimate: Since 1990, the Connecticut shoreline has shifted from Plant Hardiness Zone 6 to the warmer Zone 7.LiNeBrEaKClimate is driven by many fluctuations, ranging from decades-long shifts in ocean currents to changes in the Earth's orbit over hundreds of thousands of years (hence, the ice ages). But within the typical climate shifts of our own era, all of our fossil-fuel burning seems to be having an impact.LiNeBrEaKAnd while it's cold right now, 2008 ranked worldwide as the eighth warmest year on record, tied with 2001, according to a report by the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration. That's based on land and ocean surface temperatures going back to 1880.LiNeBrEaKHalf the globe has warmed at least one-half of one degree Fahrenheit in the past 30 years, and a quarter of the planet has warmed at least a full degree, the Earth System Science Center at the University of Alabama in Huntsville reported last month.LiNeBrEaKThat doesn't seem like much. But signs of spring come earlier; snow cover is shrinking.LiNeBrEaKSea levels are inching up from the expansion of warmer water and melting glaciers and ice caps.LiNeBrEaKStill feeling cold? At least you're not in Minnesota, where the temperature this week dropped to 37 below zero.		GLOBAL WARMING (90%); WEATHER (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (89%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (89%); OCEANS (88%); OCEANOGRAPHY (78%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (63%)  	NATIONAL OCEANIC and ATMOSPHERIC ADMINISTRATION (54%)  		EARTH (92%); CONNECTICUT, USA (90%); ALABAMA, USA (79%); MINNESOTA, USA (79%); NORTHEAST USA (79%) UNITED STATES (90%)  	January 17, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Hartford Courant   	David Funkhouser, The Hartford Courant, Conn.  			Science  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090117-HC-Despite-The-Cold-The-Heat-s-Still-On-0117  	HC  									
The Houston Chronicle (Texas)  	January 17, 2009 Saturday 	GREENHOUSE GASES: Debate flares over how to cut greenhouse gases  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	1499 words  	Jan. 17--Attacking climate change through a complex greenhouse gas trading system is a centerpiece of the incoming Obama administration's energy policy.LiNeBrEaKBut economists and energy analysts of all ideological stripes are saying a better approach to getting a cleaner atmosphere might involve a political dirty word -- tax.LiNeBrEaKA cap-and-trade system for carbon dioxide, already operating in Europe and contained in some proposed U.S. energy legislation, would aim to reduce greenhouse gases by setting a cap on carbon dioxide emissions, issuing emissions permits and allowing companies to trade them in an open market. Over time, the number of permits would drop, forcing companies to lower emissions.LiNeBrEaKA tax, on the other hand, would simply impose a fee for every ton of CO2 produced by users of fossil fuels, like power plants and refineries. Over time the tax would increase, again encouraging companies to find alternatives. Both options give companies incentives to lower emissions, and both would result in higher energy prices for consumers. LiNeBrEaKBut proponents of a tax on CO2 emissions say it would be less complicated and less expensive to administer and monitor. And the cost would be more predictable to businesses and consumers than a trading system, in which prices can fluctuate greatly.LiNeBrEaKGregory Mankiw, the former head of the Bush administration's Council of Economic Advisers, and the Congressional Budget Office, among others, have touted a CO2 tax as a better path. Energy industry executives have too, including former Duke Energy Chief Executive Paul Anderson, Dynegy CEO Bruce Williamson and Exxon Mobil Corp. CEO Rex Tillerson, who said this month that a tax would be "a more direct and transparent approach."LiNeBrEaK"There seems to be a pretty good consensus among economists in support of a tax, which is surprising given the admiration most have for the strength of markets," said Amy Myers Jaffe, an energy fellow at Rice University's Baker Institute for Public Policy.LiNeBrEaKBut getting a new tax passed could be a long shot, despite growing public support for climate change legislation and a Democratic administration and Congress that are more inclined to support taxes on industry than Republican predecessors.LiNeBrEaK"So even if a tax is better, can a tax actually get passed by Congress?" asked Francisco Padua, a trader at Amerex Brokers in Sugar Land, which is active in existing emissions markets. "Why even talk about it?"LiNeBrEaKMomentum buildsLiNeBrEaKThe momentum for a cap-and-trade program continued to build last week, as a coalition of business and environmental groups ranging from ConocoPhillips and General Electric Co. to the Natural Resources Defense Council provided a detailed plan to Congress.LiNeBrEaKNo matter how CO2 is regulated in the U.S., it will have a large effect on Texas, and Houston in particular.LiNeBrEaKHarris County ranks No. 1 in the country for tons of CO2 emitted per year at 18. 6 million tons, according to a Purdue University study released last spring. That's because of the concentration of refineries in the area, combined with more than 3 million cars and trucks. CO2 legislation likely would raise costs for local industry.LiNeBrEaKBut a cap-and-trade system also could also create a business opportunity. CO2 trading could top $3. 1 trillion by 2020, double the size of the current global commodities derivatives market, according to Point Carbon, an emissions market advisory firm. A U.S. market would be the largest, worth about $2. 3 trillion.LiNeBrEaKHouston is home to many large commodity trading operations, so it would be a natural place to locate CO2 traders.LiNeBrEaKCap-and-trade programs enjoy strong support for many reasons.LiNeBrEaKSuch a program has been used for more than a decade to cut acid rain in the U.S. by reducing the amount of sulfur dioxide power plants produce. The program assigned a cap on emissions from coal-fired power plants and then created a trading system for allowances that lets companies decide whether it's more cost effective to reduce emissions or buy allowances to pollute.LiNeBrEaKOver time, the number of available allowances was lowered. This made it more expensive to buy emission allowances than to install cleaner technologies at the power plants -- so plants installed more equipment to clean emissions.LiNeBrEaKThe acid rain program cut sulfur dioxide emissions more than 30 percent below 1990 levels, according to the Environmental Protection Agency, in a way that was predictable and cost-effective to businesses. A similar program aimed at reducing nitrogen oxides, a key component of smog, helped cut those emissions 74 percent below 1990 levels in 20 Eastern states.LiNeBrEaKMuch more complexLiNeBrEaKHow much CO2 might decline under a U.S. cap-and-trade program would depend upon how it was structured, what caps were set and other factors.LiNeBrEaKBut success with sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides trading won't necessarily translate to CO2.LiNeBrEaKThose trading schemes were applied only to a segment of one industry -- certain coal-fired power plants. CO2 trading would apply to all power plants and many other industries, so it would be more complex and require more oversight.LiNeBrEaKPower plants also have several relatively easy options for sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides reductions, such as switching the type of fuels burned or adding smokestack scrubbers. For CO2, there are currently few easy options, highlighting a need for new methods.LiNeBrEaKAnd the early results for Europe's CO2 cap-and-trade system -- which is many times larger than the U.S. sulfur dioxide and nitrogen oxides programs -- are seen by some as less than stellar.LiNeBrEaKThe first round of emission credits were free, allowing some emitters to sell permits at big profits without actually lowering their CO2 output.LiNeBrEaKAnd too many credits were issued, leading to a steep crash in carbon credit prices in 2006.LiNeBrEaKAnother component of the system that has raised questions is a United Nations-run market that issues tradable carbon credits from projects that trap or destroy carbon emissions, such as restoring carbon dioxide absorbing forests. Stanford University researchers found some Chinese chemical companies actually increased their output of a refrigerant because destroying a byproduct of the process creates a carbon credit they could then sell.LiNeBrEaKBrice Lalonde, France's special ambassador in charge of climate change, defends the European Union's trading scheme, saying early problems will resolve themselves as the market develops.LiNeBrEaK"I don't see that many missteps," Lalonde said. "We had an experimental phase to start with, and we are trying to learn by doing. The main outcome is that the cap-and-trade system works."LiNeBrEaKSpecial interestsLiNeBrEaKThe Baker Institute's Jaffe has misgivings because a cap-and-trade system creates a large commodity market designed by the U.S. Congress under the influence of competing special interests.LiNeBrEaK"The lobbying over the design will be intense, and there are a lot of aberrations that can be created when you design a market through the political process," she said.LiNeBrEaKAnd just like any large commodity market, CO2 prices could be highly volatile, said Craig Pirrong, a finance professor at the University of Houston who is co-teaching a graduate-level carbon trading class this semester.LiNeBrEaK"Banks like the volatility and complexity, because the more volatile and complex, the more money they could make," Pirrong said. "But volatility may make companies put off investing in cleaner technology because they can't get an accurate estimate on the costs."LiNeBrEaKSome resistance to cap and trade also stems from the current economic downturn, triggered in part by failures on the part of market participants and regulators.LiNeBrEaK"I think cap-and-trade is unpoliceable," said S. David Freeman, a former executive with several large utilities around the country, including Texas' Lower Colorado River Authority. He now spends much of his time crusading against nuclear power.LiNeBrEaK"You could plant a bunch of trees for a credit, but someone has to make sure you don't cut them down five years later," Freeman said. "There seems like a lot of chances to manipulate."LiNeBrEaKStill, some leading environmental groups prefer cap-and-trade. The Environmental Defense Fund has favored trading, in part because it sets limits on carbon emissions and a tax sets only a price.LiNeBrEaKAnd many are skeptical that the government would make good use of tax proceeds. Various proposals call for the money to go directly back to consumers or to pay for research in low-carbon energy technology, but some worry that the money could just be used for other, un-related projects.LiNeBrEaK"The private sector would do a better job using that value," Amerex's Padua said.LiNeBrEaKtom.fowler@chron.com		EMISSIONS (94%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (91%); ENERGY REGULATION (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (90%); PUBLIC POLICY (90%); COMPUTER TRADING SYSTEMS (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); ECONOMIC NEWS (89%); LEGISLATION (89%); ECONOMIC POLICY (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (78%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (78%); OIL and GAS PRICES (78%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY TRADE (78%); STOCK EXCHANGES (78%); GOVERNMENT BUDGETS (77%); INDUSTRY ANALYSTS (77%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (76%); POWER PLANTS (73%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (70%)  	DUKE ENERGY CORP (90%); EXXON MOBIL CORP (84%); CONOCOPHILLIPS (84%); GENERAL ELECTRIC CO (61%); DYNEGY INC (58%); TELENT LTD (50%)  	COUNCIL OF ECONOMIC ADVISERS (54%); CONGRESSIONAL BUDGET OFFICE (54%)  	BARACK OBAMA (91%); R