San Jose Mercury News (California) 	January 17, 2009 Saturday 	Who's Hot, Who's Not at the Inauguration  	NEWS  	1283 words  	ROYAL TURNOUTLiNeBrEaKSeen at U.S. Senator Dianne Feinstein's well-attended Saturday night reception at the Library of Congress: Queen Noor of Jordan, Supreme Court Justice Stephen Breyer and movie star Angela Bassett. Also making the rounds among the numerous California congressional delegation members was Obama's pick for Labor Secretary, Rep. Hilda Solis.LiNeBrEaKWHERE TECHIES WANT TO BE SEENLiNeBrEaKHollywood may have it's A-list parties, but so does the tech crowd. Here's where the digital glitterati want to be seen. Ratings are purely unscientific based on buzz and how hard Mercury News reporters had to work to get into the party. LiNeBrEaKFive stars.LiNeBrEaKThe Green Ball, Monday night.LiNeBrEaKThis enviro-star studded party for foes of global warming is the hottest ticket in town for the green-tech crowd. Al Gore is the star attraction and attendees will walk down a green carpet, from made of recyclable materials, of course. We're still waiting for our sources (we've hit up six different contacts so far) to deliver two tickets.LiNeBrEaKFour stars.LiNeBrEaKThe Google ball, Tuesday night.LiNeBrEaKGoogle has become the de facto tech-industry party host after throwing successful bashes at both national party conventions over the summer. Google is shunning traditional ball etiquette, going for a lounge-like concept. And, this would be a first for an inaugural fete, they will be serving really good food, says one source. For that reason, we'll be heading here instead of the western states ball - the official California inauguration night event - where 11,000 are expected. And we've got our Google tickets.LiNeBrEaKFour stars.LiNeBrEaKLINK-live Presidential Inaugural Gala, Tuesday nightLiNeBrEaKIt's billed as a party to celebrate technology serving humanity. Steven Chu, Lawrence Berkeley's Nobel laureate physicist and Obama's choice for energy secretary, is slated to receive "the nature award". You can attend virtually via www.linklive.org . And you can join the celebration online using Twitter (name: linklive; address: #linklive2009), ScribbleLive, USTREAM and Flickr. We think we've got tickets, would hate to miss Chu, the Bay Area's hottest --or is that coolest -- scientist.LiNeBrEaKThree stars.LiNeBrEaKNetroots Nation party, Monday nightLiNeBrEaKLiberal stars of the blogosphere come together to pat themselves on the back for helping Obama get elected. Among the co-hosts are Firedoglake and Fivethirtyeight.com . Guests can hang out in the Guitar Hero Lounge. If the event wasn't in Virginia, we'd probably give it four stars. If we don't get Green Ball tickets, we'll be across the Potomac.LiNeBrEaKThree stars.LiNeBrEaKCalifornia "Fly me to the Moon" party, Sunday nightLiNeBrEaKA retro title, but can you think of a better place for Californians to convene than the Smithsonian's air and space museum? The state Democratic Party-sponsored bash is not really a tech event. But hey, in their day, the Kitty Hawk and Spirit of St. Louis were the cat's meow. We're going.LiNeBrEaKThree starsLiNeBrEaKBytes and Books Inaugural Ball, Tuesday nightLiNeBrEaKStar Wars meets Hamlet. George Lucas will be honored at the Bytes and Books Inaugural Ball in a bid to raise the profile of technology in the classroom. Sponsors include Apple and Intel. We're sure the Bard is thrilled the Folger Shakespeare Library is the site of the party.LiNeBrEaKOBAMA TO BE TOASTED WITH CALIFORNIA VINTAGESLiNeBrEaKOregon Pinot take this. A California Pinot Noir from Anderson Valley has been selected to be served at Tuesday's inaugural luncheon, the new president's sit-down lunch with 230 dignitaries following the swearing in.LiNeBrEaKGoldeneye Pinot Noir 2005 will be served with the second course, duck and pheasant served with sour cherry chutney and molasses sweet potatoes. It's produced by Napa Valley's Duckhorn Vineyards whose 2007 Sauvigon blanc will be served with a first course of fish stew.LiNeBrEaKWho came up with the pairings? Obama's first meal as president is similar to the foods Abraham Lincoln would have eaten. And the planners, notably U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein who heads up the congressional committee planning the lunch, insisted on California vintages.LiNeBrEaKWine Spectator and Wine Enthusiast both give the pinot 92 points and it retails for $55 a bottle. And for the champagne toast? Korbel in the Russian River Valley is producing a "special inaugural cuvee.'' This marks the seventh inauguration for Korbel. But it's Duckhorn's first.LiNeBrEaKAlthough the inaugural lunch committee said they would pay for 10 cases of the wines, Duckhorn was so honored they decided to donate them.LiNeBrEaKThe luncheon menu is the most visited part of the congressional inaugural committee website. To check it out go to: www.inaugural.senate.gov/luncheon/LiNeBrEaKSAN JOSE OBAMA RELATIVE LEFT OUT IN THE COLDLiNeBrEaKRobert Wright, seventh grade teacher at Morrill Middle School in San Jose, stumbled across a genealogical website last summer that shows he and Barack Obama share a distant ancestor, Obadiah Columbus Wright, on Obama's mother's side. He had named his son, 14, Obadiah after the ancestor but had no clue about Obama's connection until he did a routine search of the name. After Obama's victory, Wright figured the connection ought to get him an inauguration ticket.LiNeBrEaKFirst, he approached the Obama inaugural planners. They sent back an email informing him how to donate to the inaugural committee. U.S. Sen. Dianne Feinstein sent a form email that he didn't make the cut. She had 60,000 ticket requests. He thought he had the ear of an aide to U.S. Rep Zoe Lofgen and even faxed over the family tree. But, alas, no tickets. "I guess my limb grew too far from the family tree,'' said Wright. So he'll be watching the inauguration with his students.LiNeBrEaKFEINSTEIN RESPECTS CHOICE OF WARRENLiNeBrEaKTune in to the inauguration ceremony and the first speech you will hear from the podium will come from Dianne Feinstein, who chairs the congressional inaugural committee.LiNeBrEaKWhat will she say in the global spotlight? "It will be very formal and very brief," she told reporters at a preview of the main event. "This is a tightly scripted, very precise schedule."LiNeBrEaKFeinstein will introduce Rick Warren, pastor of Saddleback Church in Lake Forest, Cal., to give the invocation. Barack Obama's choice of Warren for that honor was controversial because of the pastor's support for Proposition 8 in California, which banned same-sex marriages. Obama and Feinstein opposed Prop 8.LiNeBrEaK"I respect the president-elect's choice, because he wants to bring people together," Feinstein said. "I don't know Pastor Warren, but I believe the American people will be very respectful because of the specific nature of this event. It's not political."LiNeBrEaKBRING THE FUNK, TOSS THE BROOMSLiNeBrEaKPrecision lawn-chair marching? The inaugural parade always features lots of traditional marching bands, but this year a few units stand out for different reasons.LiNeBrEaKThe Redwood Middle School Marching Band from Saratoga enjoys the distinction of being the only middle school band participating in the parade. Sure hope they make that midnight bus to D.C. The young musicians are staying in a hotel three hours from the Capitol.LiNeBrEaKFor the first time, an openly gay group, San Francisco-based Lesbian and Gay Band Association, with members nationwide, will march in an inaugural parade. The association performed at others events during Bill Clinton's two inaugurals, but never in the official parade.LiNeBrEaKThe World Famous Lawn Rangers from Arcola, Ill., toss unique "show" brooms into the air, and according to the official program, often catch them. Their motto: "You're only young once but you can always be immature."LiNeBrEaKAnd look for the Get a Life Marching Band (102 participants from age 29 to 71) of Portland, Ore., performing their popular medley of traditional inaugural fare - Grand Funk Railroad tunes and "Louie Louie."LiNeBrEaKContact Mary Anne Ostrom at mostrom@mercurynews.com or (415) 477-3794.		LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); CELEBRITIES (90%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (78%); LEGISLATORS (78%); NATIONAL LIBRARIES (78%); INTERNET SOCIAL NETWORKING (77%); OBAMA'S FIRST 100 DAYS (77%); LAW COURTS and TRIBUNALS (77%); SUPREME COURTS (72%); LABOR DEPARTMENTS (71%); NOBEL PRIZES (67%); POLITICAL PARTY CONVENTIONS (65%); BLOGS and MESSAGE BOARDS (61%); GLOBAL WARMING (54%); ACTORS and ACTRESSES (90%)  	GOOGLE INC (91%)  	LIBRARY OF CONGRESS (84%)  	DIANNE FEINSTEIN (91%); STEPHEN BREYER (91%); BARACK OBAMA (85%); HILDA L SOLIS (57%); AL GORE (56%); STEVEN CHU (53%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (79%) CALIFORNIA, USA (94%); WEST USA (79%); VIRGINIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%); JORDAN (90%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 San Jose Mercury News All Rights Reserved  	By Mary Anne Ostrom and Frank Davies Mercury News  		GOOG (NASDAQ) (91%)  	NAICS519130 INTERNET PUBLISHING and BROADCASTING and WEB SEARCH PORTALS (91%)  												
The State (Columbia, South Carolina)  	January 17, 2009 Saturday 	Wildlife officals opposes coal plant: Opposition mounts to proposed Santee Cooper facility  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	395 words  	Jan. 17--The chief of the National Wildlife Federation is criticizing Santee Cooper's plan to build a coal-fired power plant near Florence.LiNeBrEaKPresident Larry Schweiger said the state-owned utility's plan is increasingly at odds with many power companies, which are dropping plans to build traditional coal plants. Schweiger, in South Carolina on Friday, said Santee Cooper should do the same in Florence County. LiNeBrEaKSchweiger is the third national conservation leader to visit the state in the past two weeks to speak against the $2. 2 billion project along the Great Pee Dee River.LiNeBrEaK"We can avoid this choice and avoid spending a lot of money wrongly,'' Schweiger said in a conference call with reporters. "It seems to me your best opportunity is to go in a new direction.''LiNeBrEaKCoal-fired power plants are a major concern for wildlife, he said.LiNeBrEaKChief among the concerns is mercury, a highly toxic metal released into the air from coal plants. Because of mercury pollution, some fish in the Great Pee Dee and other Lowcountry rivers are tainted by mercury. The state has issued health advisories against routinely eating some types of fish.LiNeBrEaKSantee Cooper spokeswoman Laura Varn said the company needs the plant to supply power, but she also said the facility will "be built in a way that is protective of the environment.''LiNeBrEaKSchweiger said South Carolina should concentrate more on using alternative sources of energy to provide power. He noted the Santee Cooper plant also would contribute greenhouse gases, a major source of global warming. President-elect Barack Obama is likely to take a harder line against coal plants. New taxes on carbon emissions are expected, he said.LiNeBrEaKLast week, the head of the national Sierra Club's coal campaign and a representative of Physicians for Social Responsibility also spoke in South Carolina against the facility. Schweiger was in South Carolina to attend a meeting of the state Wildlife Federation today in Columbia.LiNeBrEaKReach Fretwell at (803) 771-8537.		COAL FIRED PLANTS (91%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (91%); COAL INDUSTRY (91%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (91%); HEAVY METALS and TOXIC MINERALS (90%); POWER PLANTS (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (90%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (90%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (90%); WILDLIFE (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (90%); EMISSIONS (89%); TALKS and MEETINGS (77%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (77%); WATER POLLUTION (75%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (72%); STATE OWNED BUSINESSES (72%); CLIMATE CHANGE (69%); TOXIC and HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (64%); PHYSICIANS and SURGEONS (50%); US PRESIDENTS (77%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (63%)  	NATIONAL WILDLIFE FEDERATION (84%)  	BARACK OBAMA (54%)  	COLUMBIA, SC, USA (90%) SOUTH CAROLINA, USA (95%) UNITED STATES (95%)  	January 17, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The State   	Sammy Fretwell, The State, Columbia, S.C.  			Disasters  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090117-CS-Wildlife-officals-opposes-coal-plant-0117  	CS  									
Ventura County Star (California)  	January 17, 2009 Saturday 	New rules made for Channel boaters: First plan since '83 tackles issues  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	793 words  	Jan. 17--Much has changed in the natural world since the Channel Islands National Marine Sanctuary last drafted a management plan in 1983.LiNeBrEaKInvasive species that can alter the environment are more of an issue. Whales dying from ship strikes in the Santa Barbara Channel have became a huge concern. And then there are global warming, aquaculture, sewage discharge and myriad other challenges that have come up in the 26 years since the last plan was drafted.LiNeBrEaKA new plan, released Friday, addresses those issues and others that may pop up in the oversight of the 1,470 square miles of protected area that circle the Channel Islands. LiNeBrEaK"It's a blueprint for how we manage the sanctuary for the foreseeable future," said Sanctuary Manager Chis Mobley. "Since it hadn't been done since 1983, a lot of effort went into engaging the public about what we want to do in the future."LiNeBrEaKThough much of the document offers loose guidelines on future management -- such as expanding education, restoring ecosystems and promoting more science -- there are some concrete changes that affect boaters motoring or sailing through the channel.LiNeBrEaKA new regulation clarifies that any discharge of untreated sewage in the sanctuary is prohibited. Mobley said a number of boats that can carry up to 30 people only have sewage storage, not treatment capabilities, onboard.LiNeBrEaKUntreated sewage can cause marine mammals to become ill and lead to algal blooms in the ocean, which can decrease oxygen levels in the sea.LiNeBrEaKAnother new regulation doesn't allow large ships to dump gray water stored in the ballast into the sanctuary for fear it could contain exotic species such as zebra mussels.LiNeBrEaKOne thing not addressed in the report is if the sanctuary could expand its boundaries in the future. But Mobley said given current financial issues, it's a challenge to manage the existing sanctuary.LiNeBrEaK"Given that reality, we are not in a big hurry to change our boundaries," he said.LiNeBrEaKThe document also details plans for a new headquarters, which will be built in about a year on the UC Santa Barbara campus. The university also is constructing a new building, the Outreach Center for Teaching Ocean Science, which will be next to the sanctuary's new headquarters.LiNeBrEaKOn the NetLiNeBrEaKhttp://channelislands.noaa.govLiNeBrEaKCommentsLiNeBrEaKPosted by janusjuris on January 17, 2009 at 5: 17 a.m. (Suggest removal)LiNeBrEaKWhat a load! Global warming is a MYTH perpetuated by uneducated people who can't read: they only accept the pablum spoon fed in sound bites by those who stand to gain from green technology. In 10 years anyone who claims 'global warming' will be laughed out of town like the clowns they are...we are heading into an ice age!LiNeBrEaKPosted by handyhood on January 17, 2009 at 6: 46 a.m. (Suggest removal)LiNeBrEaKJanisjuris- While I don't agree with you about the ice age thing, I do agree with you on global warming. It is a known fact that for thousands of years the earth has been going, and continues to go through cycles of warm and cold. All the screaming of global warming is the same as chicken Little's,"the sky is falling!".LiNeBrEaKPosted by luv2sail on January 17, 2009 at 6: 54 a.m. (Suggest removal)LiNeBrEaKhandyhood, couldn't agree with you more. Wondering where Al Gore is hiding now that temps in the Northern States are at record lows?LiNeBrEaKPosted by nojustice_justus on January 17, 2009 at 9: 51 a.m. (Suggest removal)LiNeBrEaKSo if I got it straight its actually Global Freezing?LiNeBrEaKArticle discussions on this site are to support community debates of issues related to our stories and editorials.LiNeBrEaKDiscussions should not stray from the subject of the story or editorial.LiNeBrEaKWe do not allow the following:LiNeBrEaK* Posts t