The Virginian-Pilot(Norfolk, VA.) 	January 17, 2009 Saturday    The Virginian-Pilot Edition	Rebirth for right-wing radio Rebirth for right-wing radio  	LOCAL; Pg. B7  	546 words  	BRACE YOURSELF . The right-wing radio barkers are about to enter a golden era. Not to hear them tell it, of course.LiNeBrEaKWith the dire paranoia in which they revel, and by which they keep their listeners in a turmoil of anxiety, the goofy right's mouthpieces have been shouting for months that with a Democratic president and Congress, Washington will shut down their fulminations. LiNeBrEaKThe mechanism would be a restoration of the Fairness Doctrine, by which, back in the bad days before Reagan, the Federal Communications Commission required that broadcast commentary actually be fair and balanced -- rather than just saying it is.LiNeBrEaKThe broadcasters' mock grumbling at the time aside, the rule provided them with the cover they wanted to avoid any profitless political programming.LiNeBrEaKBut talk radio, all but universally right wing, salvaged AM radio from technology's trash heap, and now a powerful business lobby backs its reign of madness.LiNeBrEaKThe pitchmen and pitchwomen of the right have been deterred not one whit from their frisson of self-fright by the fact that President-elect Barack Obama has said he doesn't favor reviving the doctrine or that no legislation to do so shows any breath of life in Congress.LiNeBrEaKThe radio talkers, poor babies, have suffered cruelly through the last eight years. George W. Bush was never their drink of choice, but they have had to gag it down on the premise that anything Bush did was better than anything any Democrat would do.LiNeBrEaKThe talkers have had to swallow historic budget deficits, federal involvement in public education, help for African AIDS victims, all offensive to rightist dogma. They have been reduced to taking refuge in situational ethics.LiNeBrEaKNow the wraps are off and you can already hear the joy abounding. Two pop outrages of the moment herald the future.LiNeBrEaKThe trumpets of the right have it that Al Franken has stolen the U.S. Senate seat in Minnesota from incumbent Norm Coleman in a crooked recount.LiNeBrEaKShocking premise indeed, but no evidence backs it up. Independent observers have praised the recount for its transparency and care.LiNeBrEaKThe five-member recount board, which was bipartisan and included top jurists, found a 225-vote lead for Franken. Coleman is suing, so it's wait and see, but all the board's key rulings were unanimous and its deliberations were public.LiNeBrEaKAnd it turns out that Obama's pick as his chief adviser on global warming, Carol Browner, President Clinton's EPA director, was recently listed on the Web site of the Socialist International as one of 14 members of its Commission for a Sustainable World Society.LiNeBrEaKThe international is an umbrella for democratic socialist parties. Israel's and Britain's Labor Parties are members. So is Canada's New Democratic Party. It is a center for the same sort of reformist impulses to which we owe workers' compensation, child labor laws and other progressive policies.LiNeBrEaKBut maybe we better keep an eye on the Browner person after all. Next thing you know, like the people of Western Europe, we, too, might be borne down under the soul-sapping burden of universal health coverage and really good public transit.LiNeBrEaKCarry on, talk radio. But for you, Lenin's Tomb would be moved to Washington.LiNeBrEaKTom Teepen is a columnist for Cox Newspapers. He is based in Atlanta. E-mail him at teepencolumn@ earthlink.net.		RADIO BROADCAST INDUSTRY (78%); COMMUNICATIONS REGULATION and POLICY (78%); ETHICS (78%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (76%); VOTERS and VOTING (76%); LOBBYING (76%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (76%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (76%); POLITICAL PARTIES (76%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (75%); US PRESIDENTS (71%); BUDGET (70%); ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (70%); US SENATE ELECTIONS (66%); PUBLIC SCHOOLS (64%); AIDS an