Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News 	January 17, 2009 Saturday 	Manure-to-energy plant faces red tape  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	675 words  	Jan. 17--Mount Vernon company needs state to relax solid-waste rulesLiNeBrEaKMOUNT VERNON -- A local business looking to create renewable energy from cow manure has broken ground on a power-generation plant southwest of here but may be derailed by what dairy farmers say is unnecessary government regulation.LiNeBrEaKFarm Power Northwest's manure digester at the end of Beaver Marsh Road will be viable only if the state Department of Ecology is willing to exempt the facility from existing solid-waste rules, company co-owner Kevin Maas said. Once completed, the digester will convert a mixture of manure and food waste into enough electricity to light the town of La Conner. LiNeBrEaKMaas, who owns Farm Power along with his brother Daryl, said he needs to be optimistic that Ecology will not require a solid-waste permit.LiNeBrEaKThose in the manure digesting business have been meeting with Ecology for more than a year, looking for a way to create a permit exemption for digesters. Farmers don't need a solid-waste permit simply for storing manure, but digesters aren't effective unless a relatively small amount of food waste -- about 5 or 10 percent of the total -- is mixed in.LiNeBrEaKIf a digester runs on manure alone it produces about half the electricity it would with the right mixture of food waste, Maas said. Investors aren't willing to buy into his $3. 5 million project if it yields that kind of result, he said.LiNeBrEaK"In effect, we're betting the company that this will be resolved," Maas said.LiNeBrEaKIt doesn't make sense to dairy farmer Jason Vander Kooy, who will supply manure to Farm Power, that the state would want to make it more difficult to produce something as popular as renewable energy. Another regulation would be redundant, he added, because manure and feed on dairy farms are already tightly regulated.LiNeBrEaK"To add another layer of rules and regulations on us, for renewable energy, ... we're just doubling up," Vander Kooy said.LiNeBrEaKLaurie Davies, Ecology's solid-waste program manager, told a senate agriculture committee on Thursday she remained optimistic that a new permit rule could be written by June.LiNeBrEaKBut the Maas brothers also testified Thursday before the senate Agriculture and Rural Economic Development Committee, seeking legislation to create the exemption, because there is concern that negotiations with Ecology aren't going anywhere.LiNeBrEaK"There are people in the digester community who are losing hope. ... In meetings where we thought we made progress, it was clear we hadn't," Maas said.LiNeBrEaKDavies told the committee she sees the value of manure digesters as both a renewable energy source and as a way to reduce global warming. The digesters eliminate methane, an especially potent greenhouse gas.LiNeBrEaK"I think we're all in agreement that there are incredible benefits that can be happening," Davies told the committee.LiNeBrEaKHowever, two main hurdles must be overcome before Ecology can relax permit requirements, Davies said. For one, the department wants to make sure all digesters, not just those operating on farms, are given the same exemption.LiNeBrEaKThere's also a public health issue, Davies said. As in any solid-waste facility, Ecology would expect manure digesters to protect ground water and control odor and vermin.LiNeBrEaK"It isn't just a pound of solid waste that they want to bring in. It's a huge amount of waste they want to bring in," Davies said.LiNeBrEaKFarm Power will begin operations in early August, Daryl Maas said, with or without the cooperation of the state government.LiNeBrEaK"By the time we're done (with construction), either we'll have a rule or we'll just operate," he said.		POWER PLANTS (91%); AGRICULTURAL WASTES (91%); SOLID WASTE REGULATION (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL PERMITS (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (9