The Bradenton Herald (Florida)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	FPL wants zoning changes  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	502 words  	Jan. 16--PARRISH -- They want to grow mirror-like reflectors instead of tomatoes on land adjacent to the Florida Power and Light Co. plant in east Manatee. LiNeBrEaKThe company, which operates an existing power plant near Parrish that burns natural gas to generate electricity, is proposing to add a solar thermal facility that collects energy from the sun.LiNeBrEaKFPL has asked the county to re-zone 620 acres of land adjacent to its existing power plant from an agricultural classification to one designated "planned development/public interest," said Rae Dowling, FPL's area manager for external affairs.LiNeBrEaKOfficials told visitors at a neighborhood meeting Thursday about the possibility that the company would add solar generating capacity to the plant.LiNeBrEaKIf the project comes to fruition, the site where rows of mirror-like reflectors would be installed to trap the sun's heat would be spread across what is now a tomato field, said Paul Rutledge, a retired equipment operator who lives near the property.LiNeBrEaK"I might get sunburn," he joked.LiNeBrEaKStill, he was OK with the idea, he said, adding, "I guess it would be a big help."LiNeBrEaKThe company is considering a number of sites, but re-zoning is the first step, said Dowling, adding, "Without that, we can't go any further."LiNeBrEaKA preview meeting with county commissioners is slated for 1: 30 p.m. Tuesday, where the company will explain its proposal, said Laurie E. Suess, principal planner for the county planning department.LiNeBrEaKIt is slated to go before the Planning Commission for formal approval in March, she said. If FPL decides to build the project here, it would be the first large-scale solar generating facility ever built in Manatee County, she said.LiNeBrEaKThe proposal calls for a hybrid system in which concave reflectors gather heat from the sun's rays, which would be converted to steam that would produce electricity in existing turbines, said John C. Gnecco IV, FPL's manager for project development. "With free energy from the sun, we consume less fossil fuel," he said.LiNeBrEaKThe solar thermal system would produce no greenhouse gases, he noted.LiNeBrEaK"It's absolutely incredible," said Joan Hodges, vice president of the Parrish Civic Association. "We would be so fortunate to have it in our area. It's a win-win. What would be the negative?"LiNeBrEaKNeil Spirtas, representing the Manatee Chamber of Commerce, was impressed with the plan's environmental virtues and hoped it would bring jobs, too.LiNeBrEaK"We've been working with a green business initiative, working with companies to become aware what it means to improve the environmental effects in their businesses," he said.LiNeBrEaK"This is a perfect example."		ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (91%); POWER PLANTS (90%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (90%); ZONING (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); SOLAR POWER PLANTS (89%); COUNTY GOVERNMENT (89%); SOLAR ENERGY (89%); COUNTIES (89%); LAND USE PLANNING (78%); EMISSIONS (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (77%); TALKS and MEETINGS (74%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (71%); BUSINESS and PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATIONS (72%)  	FLORIDA POWER and LIGHT CO (91%)  			FLORIDA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Bradenton Herald   	Sara Kennedy, The Bradenton Herald, Fla.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090116-BR-FPL-wants-zoning-changes-0116  	BR  									
Buffalo News (New York) 	January 16, 2009 Friday   CENTRAL EDITION	EandE 'looks good' for fiscal 2009  	BUSINESS; Pg. D7  	477 words  	Kevin Neumaier isn't sure how the financial crisis will affect Ecology and Environment six months from now, but he's pretty confident the Lancaster environmental services firm will be in good shape two years from now. LiNeBrEaK"Usually you have good vision for six months, and you can't see so well out two years," said Neumaier, EandE's president and chief executive officer. "Now, it's the opposite."LiNeBrEaKThe recession and a severe credit crunch that is making it harder for many of EandE's clients to obtain financing for their environmental projects is adding "uncertainty" to the company's outlook, Neumaier said.LiNeBrEaKBut Neumaier said he takes heart that many of EandE's government projects already are funded and he expressed optimism that the financing difficulties wouldn't significantly delay the advance work, such as environmental impact statements and permitting assistance, that the company does for many projects.LiNeBrEaK"This quarter is going good, and from what we can see, it looks good [for the rest of the fiscal year], he said Tuesday, following the company's annual shareholder's meeting. "We just don't know for sure."LiNeBrEaKBehind Neumaier's optimism is the ongoing push to reduce carbon dioxide emissions and increase the use of renewable energy.LiNeBrEaK"Climate change and energy independence are major drivers for our markets going forward," Neumaier said. "If we don't do something about it, . . . we're in for something a whole lot worse than the financial crisis."LiNeBrEaKPresident-elect Barack Obama's goal of reducing carbon dioxide emissions by 80 percent by 2050 could spur renewable energy projects, from wind and solar energy to hydroelectric and advanced coal projects, like the one proposed for Jamestown, he said.LiNeBrEaKObama's economic stimulus plan, released Thursday by House Democrats, includes more than $20 billion in renewable energy tax cuts and a tax credit for research and development on energy conservation, energy efficiency and renewable energy. It also includes a multiyear extension of the renewable energy production tax credit for wind, hydropower, geothermal and bioenergy.LiNeBrEaKIn the long run, the efforts to combat climate change and global warming should lead to more work on renewable energy projects and other initiatives, Neumaier said, even if the short-term outlook is less certain.LiNeBrEaKNeumaier said the company's conservative financial position also should help EandE weather the economic crisis. The company has $14 million in cash and only a little more than $2 million in debt.LiNeBrEaKThe company got even stronger in the first quarter, with profits almost tripling. The company also bought back 197,000 shares of its stock from a free-falling hedge fund, Tontine Associates, that needed to sell its shares in August, a move that is expected to add to EandE's earnings per share.LiNeBrEaK"We've been operating pretty well in this financial crisis," Neumaier said.LiNeBrEaKe-mail: drobinson@buffnews.com		ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL INDUSTRY (90%); EMISSIONS (89%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (89%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (86%); SOLAR ENERGY (86%); TAXES and TAXATION (86%); CLIMATOLOGY (86%); TAX LAW (85%); WIND ENERGY (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL ENGINEERING and CONSULTING (78%); BIOMASS (78%); CREDIT CRISIS (78%); RECESSION (78%); ECONOMIC NEWS (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (75%); ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ASSESSMENT (73%); LEGISLATORS (73%); POLITICAL PARTIES (73%); GLOBAL WARMING (70%); HYDROELECTRIC POWER (70%); SHAREHOLDER MEETINGS (69%); ENERGY RESEARCH (65%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (63%); COAL INDUSTRY (50%); CORPORATE TAX (50%); HEDGE 