The Charlotte Observer (North Carolina)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	Duke joins plan to lower emissions  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	813 words  	Jan. 16--Duke Energy was among a rare group of household-name corporations and environmental groups that rolled out a plan Thursday to sharply lower greenhouse gas emissions as President-elect Obama assumes office.LiNeBrEaKThe plan, developed over two years, was an attempt to present the new president with a consensus of leading players in the debate over regulation of carbon dioxide. The gas is linked to climate change.LiNeBrEaKTheir recommendations would place national limits, dropping over time, on how much carbon dioxide may be released. Emitters like Duke could trade "allowances" -- permission slips to release carbon -- to stay under that cap. LiNeBrEaKBut the industry plan differs from Obama's, who also supports carbon caps, on a key starting point. The U.S. Climate Action Partnership, which crafted the plan, says companies like Duke should initially get allowances free. Obama has said he wants the companies to buy them at auction.LiNeBrEaKIt's a critical difference, because the value of the allowances is expected to soar into the trillions of dollars by 2050. The industry plan envisions reducing carbon releases 80 percent, compared to 2005, by that date. Interim targets were set for 2012, 2020 and 2030.LiNeBrEaK"If (free allowances) were removed from the mix entirely, I would say that it was one of the cards that could make the (plan) fall down very quickly," said Keith Trent, Duke's chief strategy and policy officer.LiNeBrEaKTrent said the costs of buying auctioned allowances would pass to customers, estimating that Duke's customers would see a 25 percent to 30 percent rate increase. He had no comparable estimate for free allowances, but said they would put money directly to work cleaning up plants.LiNeBrEaKIt's too much to make customers pay for auctioned allowances in addition to the costs of "decarbonizing" power plants, Trent said.LiNeBrEaKElectric utilities emit 40 percent of the nation's greenhouse gases. Duke Energy, one of the largest U.S. utilities, with 4 million electric customers, releases 100 million tons of carbon dioxide a year, third-highest among U.S. utilities.LiNeBrEaKEnvironmental groups not involved with the partnership slammed free allowances and said the plan wasn't aggressive enough in calling for a 14 percent to 20 percent reduction in carbon emissions by 2020.LiNeBrEaK"Giving away too many allowances for free would distort the market and could result in windfall profits for polluters," said Alden Meyer of the Union of Concerned Scientists.LiNeBrEaKInvesting in technologyLiNeBrEaKThe partnership includes 26 corporations -- among them DuPont, GE, PepsiCo and the Big Three automakers -- and high-profile advocates such as the Environmental Defense Fund and the Natural Resources Defense Council.LiNeBrEaKThe group cast its recommendations as a politically palatable stimulus to investment in low-carbon technologies and a way to start ratcheting down carbon emissions at the lowest cost to consumers.LiNeBrEaK"The health of our economy and the safety of our climate are inextricably linked, except nature doesn't do bail-outs," said Jonathan Lash, president of the World Resources Institute, a partnership member. "If the diverse membership of (the partnership) can find common ground, Congress can agree on effective legislation."LiNeBrEaKIt's uncertain how rapidly legislation could be passed, given Obama's focus on the crumbling economy and two wars. The longer the wait for climate action, the partnership said, the higher the costs.LiNeBrEaKDuke CEO Jim Rogers, testifying Thursday before the House Energy and Commerce committee, said that "by starting now we have a better chance to smooth out and minimize the inevitable cost increases that will be imposed on U.S. consumers."LiNeBrEaKThe committee chairman, Rep. Henry Waxman, D-Calif., said he will move "quickly and decisively" to push greenhouse-gas legislation out of his committee before Memorial Day. Waxman said inaction will make it harder for the economy to pull out of recession.LiNeBrEaK"U.S. industries want to invest in a clean energy future," he said, "but uncertainties about whether, when and how greenhouse gas emissions will be reduced is deterring these vital investments."LiNeBrEaKBut Illinois Republican Rep. John Shimkus warned his committee colleagues to "be prepared for battle." He called the partnership plan "a shell game" to hide the cost from taxpayers.LiNeBrEaK"Let's develop a trading floor for U.S. emissions, and let's let the big-money folks at Goldman Sachs control it," Shimkus joked. "Is that a good idea?"LiNeBrEaKThe Associated Press and Bloomberg News contributed.		EMISSIONS (91%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (89%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (89%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); POWER PLANTS (78%); SCIENCE NEWS (76%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (76%); CHEMICALS (76%); CLIMATOLOGY (76%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (74%); AUTOMOTIVE MFG (68%); AUTOMOBILE MFG (63%); AUTOMAKERS (60%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  	DUKE ENERGY CORP (92%); PEPSICO INC (50%)  		BARACK OBAMA (94%)  	UNITED STATES (79%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Charlotte Observer   	Bruce Henderson, The Charlotte Observer, N.C.  		DUK (NYSE) (92%); PEP (NYSE) (50%) DUK, DD, GE, PEP  	SIC4911 ELECTRIC SERVICES (92%); NAICS312111 SOFT DRINK MANUFACTURING (50%); NAICS311919 OTHER SNACK FOOD MANUFACTURING (50%); SIC2096 POTATO CHIPS, CORN CHIPS, and SIMILAR SNACKS (50%); SIC2086 BOTTLED and CANNED SOFT DRINKS and CARBONATED WATER (50%) Environment/Recycling/Waste  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090116-CH-HLT-EMISSIONS-CUTBACKS-20090116  	CH  									
Chattanooga Times and Free Press (Tennessee)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	City receives suggestions toward sustainability  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	577 words  	Jan. 16--A 123-page report released Thursday by the Chattanooga Green Committee includes 47 initiatives the city could take to make itself more green, including creating an Office of Sustainability in city government.LiNeBrEaKThe report acts as a road map for Chattanooga on how to become more sustainable and sets benchmarks for the years 2012, 2020 and 2050 on how to decrease greenhouse gas emissions.LiNeBrEaKKaren Hundt, director of Planning and Design at the Chattanooga-Hamilton County Regional Planning Agency, said some of the ideas had monetary costs, some did not. LiNeBrEaK"Some could be implemented right away," she said. "Some are long term."LiNeBrEaKCommittee officials said they did not have a dollar figure on how much enacting the potential items could cost. But they said they would be moving almost immediately to implement some items, such as the Office of Sustainability.LiNeBrEaKMayor Ron Littlefield, who attended the report's release, held at the green/spaces building on East Main Street, said afterward he thought the city could afford to open the Office of Sustainability. Several people inside his organization already have expressed interest in the job and could be shifted into the position, he said.LiNeBrEaK"I'm very much in favor of it," Mr. Littlefield said. "I already know how to do it."LiNeBrEaKBut Mr. Littlefield said he would not start implementing the new office until after the March 3 city election. He's running for re-election against Rob Healy and Joe Lance.LiNeBrEaKSome of the green report's suggestions include making it easier for residents to recycle, making Chattanooga a leader in sustainable industry and also making sustainable building mainstream in the city.LiNeBrEaKThe report also made recommendations on reducing community waste, creating more alternative transportation and setting sights on a comprehensive public education campaign.LiNeBrEaKMs. Hundt said the committee used data from the Mayor's Climate Protection Agreement in 2006 and found the city's overall greenhouse gases had increased by 25 percent. City government's carbon footprint had increased 10 percent, she said.LiNeBrEaKCity Forester Gene Hyde, chairman of the green committee, said it would take more than just government pulling together to decrease those levels.LiNeBrEaK"Is this going to be an easy or a difficult journey?" he asked. "It's going to be difficult."LiNeBrEaKCommittee members worked on the report for a year, hosting a public forum and holding more than 160 meetings. Committee member Jim Frierson said the report is meant to provide a way to educate and focus the public, businesses and government.LiNeBrEaK"It's not about regulations; it's not about casting blame," he said.LiNeBrEaKMs. Hundt said many of the ideas that cost money still can be done while the nation is in a recession because, in the long term, many of the suggestions can save money.LiNeBrEaK"It is a cost up front," she said.LiNeBrEaKRick Gehrke, an environmental and sustainability consultant who lent his expertise to the committee, said now is the time to enact some of these ideas.LiNeBrEaK"There's no better time," he said. "These are all efficiency measures."		CITY GOVERNMENT (91%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (90%); CITIES (90%); SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); ELECTIONS (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (78%); GREEN BUILDING (78%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (76%)  				TENNESSEE, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (79%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Chattanooga Times and Free Press   	Cliff Hightower, Chattanooga Times Free Press, Tenn.  			Environment/Recycling/Waste  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090116-TN-City-receives-suggestions-toward-sustainability-0116  	TN  									
Contra Costa Times (California) 	January 16, 2009 Friday 	Green Scene: Going green from clothes to meat  	ENVIRONMENT; News; Business; Lifestyle; Home and Garden  	576 words  	Last week, I wrote about some of the many small things we can do to hop aboard the Green Scene train. With so much info out there about global warming, eco-friendly this and that, it can be a bit much. But it can also be easy and rewarding to help out Mother Earth. Here are a few more tips to get you on track.LiNeBrEaKEverything old is new again LiNeBrEaKVintage (yep, I mean secondhand) clothing is ecologically sound. By buying a piece of used clothing, you avoid the energy used in producing and shopping for a new one.LiNeBrEaKEvery item of clothing you own has an impact on the environment. So, hit the thrift and consignment shops; buy new clothing you really need (not just want); try a closet swap with some pals or donate your no-longer worn duds. In these economic times, this is not only eco-friendly but wallet-friendly.LiNeBrEaKReach for the starLiNeBrEaKBefore you buy that next big appliance, check out its Energy Star rating, a system devised by the Environmental Protection Agency. Approved products can be pricier but cost less to use. By using Energy Star appliances, you can reduce a utility bill by as much as 30 percent.LiNeBrEaKSteak outLiNeBrEaKWeird but true   a burger actually contributes to global warming. Who knew something so tasty could be bad for the Earth?LiNeBrEaKThe international meat industry generates about 18 percent of the world's greenhouse-gas emissions   even more than transportation   according to a U.N. Food and Agriculture Organization report. If you can't bear to say adios to your steak forever, simply cut back.LiNeBrEaKCozy upLiNeBrEaKImproving your home's efficiency can be as simple as giving your hardworking water heater a warm hug via an insulated blanket (about $10-$20).LiNeBrEaKMost water heaters older than five years are constantly losing heat, thus wasting energy. If the surface feels warm to the touch, get your heater an extra blankie.LiNeBrEaKFarm aidLiNeBrEaKFruit, veggies, meat and milk produced closer to home rack up fewer petroleum miles than those trucked cross-country. Search www.localharvest.org by ZIP code for farmers markets, green grocers and food co-ops in your area.LiNeBrEaKThink inside and out of the boxLiNeBrEaKAll those foam peanuts and plastic CD cases cost energy to manufacture and deliver. Reduce the amount of excess packaging by buying in bulk and pass up packages within packages.LiNeBrEaKFor example, buy a big bag of chips, instead of a box containing 6 little bags. Avoid grabbing a handful of napkins at a restaurant when you really just need a couple. Take your own reusable cup when visiting a favorite coffeehouse (some even give you credit).LiNeBrEaKWear greenLiNeBrEaKGreen makeup may only be for the Wicked Witch but eco-green beauty products are becoming quite fashionable. Ask for organic or natural products at your favorite cosmetics counter. The choices available are quite eco-beautiful.LiNeBrEaKGood 'car-ma'LiNeBrEaKYes, I know, the hybrid is in your future, just not the near future. Still, your old-school auto doesn't have to be evil. Just giving your ride a tuneup and keeping tires properly inflated or replacing a clogged air filter can improve gas mileage and efficiency.LiNeBrEaKIf you can boost your car performance from 20 to 24 mpg, Old Reliable will put 200 fewer pounds of CO2 into the atmosphere each year.LiNeBrEaKLast, but so not leastLiNeBrEaKI culled much of this info from the Time magazine/CNN online report "The Global Warming Survivor Kit." While I've given you just a few eco-kick starts, the story listed 51 things. For more, go to www.time.com/time/specials/2007/environment .LiNeBrEaKReach Trine Gallegos at trinemitch@comcast.net		ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); GREEN MARKET (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (90%); EMISSIONS (77%); ENVIRON