Florida Times-Union (Jacksonville) 	January 16, 2009 Friday 	ENERGY;  Balanced solution 	Pg. B-6  	549 words  	Oil companies were taking a beating when gas prices were at $4 a gallon.LiNeBrEaKWhere is the applause now that prices have dropped below $2 a gallon?LiNeBrEaKThe reason: They are scapegoats. LiNeBrEaKInvestor-owned oil companies don't control oil prices.LiNeBrEaKLet that sink in.LiNeBrEaKInvestor-owned oil companies like ConocoPhillips and Exxon only control about 7 percent of the world's oil supply. Nationalized oil companies control most of the supplies, like those in Venezuela or Saudi Arabia.LiNeBrEaKOil prices surged to $4 due in large part to huge worldwide demand, especially from the booming economies of the world's two most populous countries, China and India.LiNeBrEaKOil prices have plunged in large part due to the worldwide recession, said Luc Messier, senior vice president of project development and procurement for ConocoPhillips.LiNeBrEaKHe recently visited the Times-Union to share his energy company's perspectives.LiNeBrEaKAmong his points:LiNeBrEaKGlobal warming is fact: ConocoPhillips was the first energy company to join the U.S. Climate Action Partnership, a group of about 30 major corporations that have called on the federal government to enact significant action to reduce greenhouse gases. Other members include Shell, Duke Energy and PGandE Corp.LiNeBrEaKThose companies want firm, consistent direction from the federal government so they can justify the billion-dollar investments required for the next generation of energy technology.LiNeBrEaKCarbon taxes or a cap and trade program must be high enough to justify action, but not so high to make it difficult for companies to invest. That fine balance is difficult, but key to a successful transition to a green energy sector.LiNeBrEaKMessier's keys to a new energy future:LiNeBrEaKDiversify sources. No single source of energy is a panacea. All will be needed.LiNeBrEaKEfficiency. Conservation will help stabilize energy prices and buy time for the new sources to come on line.LiNeBrEaKNew technology. There are all kinds of developments in the works, from breakthroughs in batteries; to converting coal to a gas; to even extracting oil from ice. But there has to be a market for it.LiNeBrEaKProtecting environment. Oil drilling can be done without harming the environment, for instance. That must remain a key consideration of any new energy source.LiNeBrEaKNational security is the elephant in the room of the oil industry, however. When oil is the dominant revenue source of a nation, it seems to lead to tyrannical or unstable behavior of its leaders. Venezuela, for instance, has expropriated the investor-owned oil assets.LiNeBrEaKOnly a comprehensive energy strategy that gives businesses the assurance that they won't be left in the lurch can change this nation's addiction to oil.LiNeBrEaKLet's hope the new administration and Congress are pragmatic. Our nation's economic future depends on it.LiNeBrEaKON GLOBAL WARMINGLiNeBrEaKAn energy company's position: ConocoPhillips recognizes that human activity, including the burning of fossil fuels, is contributing to increased concentrations of greenhouse gases in the atmosphere that can lead to adverse changes in global climate."LiNeBrEaKDual challenges: "Meeting the twin challenges of taking action on climate change and providing adequate and reliable supplies of energy will require technical innovation, resource commitments and responsible stewardship by energy producers and consumers alike."LiNeBrEaKSource: Climate Change Position on www.conocophillips.com		OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (93%); OIL and GAS PRICES (92%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (90%); PRICE CHANGES (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY SECTOR PERFORMANCE (89%); CRUDE OIL and NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (89%); OIL and GAS EXTRACTION (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (88%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (88%); EMISSIONS (79%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (79%