lower.LiNeBrEaK"Kansas workers are the backbone of our economy, so an agreement that puts our contractors to work will benefit all Kansans," said Rich Taylor, business manager for the council.LiNeBrEaKThe council collectively represents about 10,000 members in central and western Kansas. During construction, the expansion project is set to create more than 2,400 Kansas jobs, earning more than $78 million per year and generating more than $9 million a year in taxes.LiNeBrEaKThe memorandum expires July 1 unless the Kansas Legislature passes legislation in the 2009 session "that provides directly or indirectly for the issuance of a construction air permit for the project" by KDHE, according to Sunflower.LiNeBrEaK"Sunflower and the council share a common desire to put Kansans to work and to utilize the expertise of Kansas contractors," Sunflower CEO and President Earl Watkins said. "This agreement fits with our desire to not only provide reliable, affordable power to central and western Kansans but also to ensure that Kansas workers have access to the jobs available during the project construction."		AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); CONSTRUCTION (90%); CONSTRUCTION CONTRACTING (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL PERMITS (89%); COLLECTIVE BARGAINING AGREEMENTS (89%); LABOR UNIONS (89%); AIR QUALITY (89%); POWER PLANTS (78%); EMISSIONS (78%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (78%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (76%); LEGISLATORS (76%); SUPREME COURTS (74%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (73%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (73%); GLOBAL WARMING (67%); AGENCY ADJUDICATION (66%); PLANT CONSTRUCTION (58%); LEGISLATION (50%)  	SUNFLOWER ELECTRIC POWER CORP (91%)  	KANSAS SUPREME COURT (56%)  	BEN NELSON (51%)  	KANSAS, USA (97%) UNITED STATES (97%)  	January 17, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Stephanie Farley, The Garden City Telegram, Kan.  			Construction  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090116-GM-Sunflower-pla