Grunion Gazette (Long Beach, California)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	Port Air Quality Efforts Make Significant Gains  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	580 words  	Jan. 16--Air quality has shown signs of overall improvement around the Port of Long Beach, according to a new study.LiNeBrEaKThe port's latest Air Emissions Inventory has reported that ships, trains, trucks and other goods-movement machinery produced less pollution in 2007 than in previous years, following the port's passage of a Clean Air Action Plan. Nick Sramek, vice president of the Long Beach Board of Harbor Commissioners, said that pollution from several types of sources had dropped to 2004 and earlier levels in the yearLiNeBrEaKA 2008 report for air quality is slated for release midyear. LiNeBrEaK"We thought it was very promising for the first year of the program," he said.LiNeBrEaK"I was surprised that some of the numbers were down as much as they were."LiNeBrEaKAccording to the report, major pollutants were reduced due to fewer ships visiting the port; those that did visit usually were larger in size. Such toxins, including particulate matter from diesel exhaust, have been linked to environmental damage and public health problems.LiNeBrEaK"In recent years, it's become clearer that diesel pollution poses a serious health threat throughout the region," Assistant Director of Communications Art Wong said. "Diesel equipment at the port has been a major source, so we've taken initiatives to significantly reduce that. Ongoing inventories will show the extent of that progress."LiNeBrEaKThe drop in pollution also was attributed to compliance with a California Air Resources Board regulation on the use of low-sulfur fuels as well as participation in such efforts as the Green Flag Vessel Speed Reduction Program, where ships slow down voluntarily to cut pollutants. In addition, harbor craft, locomotives and heavy-duty trucks began operating off of ultra-low-sulfur diesel fuel.LiNeBrEaK"It's the ships, the trucks, the trains -- all of the equipment working within the port," Wong said.LiNeBrEaKMeanwhile, the PierPASS program reduced heavy-duty truck idling time from about 3. 8 million idling hours to 2. 5 million. Cargo-handling equipment that would otherwise emit more pollution has been replaced with cleaner alternatives.LiNeBrEaKStill, Wong said, the port has more work to do in terms of reducing carbon dioxide and other greenhouse gases. Those pollutants saw slight increases from 2005 to 2007. The Clean Air Action Plan does not include greenhouse gas reduction measures, but port officials said they have begun work on solutions.LiNeBrEaK"Things that will have to continue are the replacement of some older fuel so that we can see even more improvements," Wong said.LiNeBrEaKThe port produced the study as part of its Clean Air Action Plan, approved by the Long Beach Board of Harbor Commissioners in November 2006, following the enactment of its environmental protection Green Port Policy.LiNeBrEaKDespite economic challenges, port officials said they are looking to implement more sustainable measures. Shipping companies, Wong said, have provided much of the funding for such upgrades.LiNeBrEaK"We're going to do everything we can," Sramek said. "We're not going to let funding get in our way."LiNeBrEaKFor more information, visit www.polb.com/emissions.		EMISSIONS (90%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); AIR QUALITY (90%); DIESEL FUEL (89%); HARBORS and PORTS (89%); HARBOR and PORT OPERATIONS (89%); RESEARCH REPORTS (89%); PORT AUTHORITIES (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (78%); PARTICULATE MATTER (78%); MARINE CARGO HANDLING (78%); MARINE SHIPPING (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); MOTOR VEHICLES (77%); SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT (72%); APPROVALS (71%); TRANSPORTATION SUPPORT SERVICES (68%)  	CALIFORNIA AIR RESOURCES BOARD (54%)  			CALIFORNIA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Kelly Garrison, Grunion Gazette, Long Beach, Calif.  			Disasters  