nvest in new, cleaner technologies until they know what Congress is going to require," Waxman said.LiNeBrEaKUnder the cap-and-trade program envisioned by the consortium, a new Carbon Market Board would be tasked with setting annual limits on the amount of emissions allowances companies could use.LiNeBrEaKHigher costs seenLiNeBrEaKThe plan drew criticism from conservatives, who said it would lead to slower economic growth and higher energy costs.LiNeBrEaKRep. Joe Barton, R-Ennis, predicted that any move to clamp down on emissions during a recession would lead to further economic declines.LiNeBrEaKAnd Houston Democratic Rep. Gene Green said he has concerns that the prices for emissions allowances would be too volatile under a cap-and-trade program.LiNeBrEaKMeanwhile, some environmentalists said the proposed greenhouse gas limits would be undermined by the USCAP's proposal for a "safety valve" that would kick in whenever the price for emission allowances spiked. Then, under the coalition's plan, the government could allow companies to use more offsets to meet the emissions limits.LiNeBrEaKComing sunday: Some say a tax would work better than a cap- and-trade system.		EMISSIONS (95%); ENERGY REGULATION (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (79%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (78%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (78%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); LEGISLATION (78%); ECONOMIC GROWTH (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY TRADE (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (78%); AIR POLLUTION (78%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (78%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (78%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (78%); LEGISLATORS (78%); RECESSION (78%); ECONOMIC NEWS (78%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (78%); POLITICAL PARTIES (78%); POWER PLANTS (73%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); ECONOMIC DEVELOPMENT (73%); PETROLEUM REFINERIES (72%) Ecology Air Pollution  	DUK