rgy, trying to forecast carbon prices is almost as bad as throwing darts at a board.LiNeBrEaKWhat's more, the carbon trading market is unlike any other -- governments define both the supply and demand, panelists said. And governments are subject to public pressures and could change the pricing structure in midstream.LiNeBrEaKSteve Fine of ICF International pointed out that an earlier cap-and-trade system, to remove sulfur dioxide from the air, had worked very well and became a model for the system now used in Europe. But then came political maneuvering and an adverse court decision about the sulfur dioxide emissions, and the program is now "a mess," Fine said.LiNeBrEaKEven with all the negative comments, many panelists said progress was being made. The Regional Greenhouse Gas Initiative (RGGI) in the Northeast, where states have created a carbon trading market, has had considerable start-up problems, "but RGGI is real, RGGI is alive," said Franz Litz of the World Resources Institute.LiNeBrEaKThe process is started, and that is the most important fact, Litz said.LiNeBrEaKWhile the economic downturn has slowed the environmental movement worldwide, it has also caused many factories to cut back production, and people are using less electricity. "So there are going to be fewer emissions for a while," said Graham Cooper of Environmental Finance Publications, which sponsored the meeting.		EMISSIONS (90%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); ENTREPRENEURSHIP (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); GLOBAL WARMING (89%); VENTURE CAPITAL (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (77%); PRICE MANAGEMENT (77%); FINES and PENALTIES (77%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (73%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (73%); CONSULTING SERVICES (71%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (70%); PRICE CHANGES (69%); LAW COURTS and TRIBUNALS (50%); LITIGATION (50%)  	AMERICAN ELECTRIC POWER CO INC (55%)  			UNITED STATES (94%); EUROPE (92%); NORTH AMERICA (79%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The 