Redlands Daily Facts (California)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	Local environmentally concerned citizens meet  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	863 words  	Jan. 16--REDLANDS -- A diverse group of environmentally concerned citizens met this week to plan how the city and its residents can reduce their impact on the environment.LiNeBrEaKThe first meeting of Redlands' Climate Action Task Force was Jan. 14 at the city's council chambers. The 21 members of the task force sat at a long table headed by Mayor Jon Harrison, Quality of Life director Gary Van Dorst and task force chairman Jan Hudson.LiNeBrEaKHarrison, who invited members to join the new task force, has made green development and sustainability a city priority. LiNeBrEaKThe task force will develop a list of actions to recommend to the city to reduce greenhouse gas emissions in Redlands, looking at possibilities in both the public and private sectors.LiNeBrEaKHarrison told the task force that globally, urban areas contribute a majority of the earth's greenhouse gases, but cover only a small percentage of the Earth's surface.LiNeBrEaK"What can we do with our 37 square miles to make a difference?" Harrison said.LiNeBrEaKThe members are:LiNeBrEaKTim Krantz, associate professor of environmental studies at the University of RedlandsLiNeBrEaKRenea Wickman, Redlands residentLiNeBrEaKGlenna Wiseman, director of marketing for HelioPowerLiNeBrEaKMarvin Hudson, owner of Viewpoint Financial Development Co.LiNeBrEaKLee Young, retired engineerLiNeBrEaKBill Jury, professor of environmental science at University of California, RiversideLiNeBrEaKMichael TenEyck, municipal utility managerLiNeBrEaKfor the city of Rancho CucamongaLiNeBrEaKDan Rendler, regional director for Southern California EdisonLiNeBrEaKGregg Schneider, vice president of CaseworksLiNeBrEaKPaul Foster, assistant medical group administrator for Kaiser Permanente in the Inland Empire counties, past president of the Redlands Chamber of Commerce and the incoming president for