, green building, waste reduction and recycling, and land use and community design.LiNeBrEaKThe task force will split into subcommittees to study what could be done in certain environmentally minded areas. The group will focus on five categories for the next few months, with the committees reporting to the group at their monthly meetings.LiNeBrEaKThe task force also talked about what expertise the Climate Action Task Force could draw upon.LiNeBrEaK"What are our strengths as a community that we can build on?" Glenna Wiseman asked.LiNeBrEaKRedlands already has a strong recycling program through the waste management department. The task force agreed that Redlands also has strong intellectual expertise with the University of Redlands, ESRI and other companies and organizations.LiNeBrEaKTim Krantz introduced a group of University of Redlands students who could function as a research group for the task force and work with subcommittees.LiNeBrEaKThe next meeting of the Climate Action Task Force is 6 p.m. Wednesday, Jan. 28, in the A.K. Smiley Public Library's Assembly Room. The group is slated to finish organizing subcommittees and begin research.LiNeBrEaKE-Mail Staff Writer Megan McClain at mmcclain@redlandsdailyfacts.com		CITIES (90%); COUNTIES (89%); TALKS and MEETINGS (89%); LAND USE PLANNING (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL RESEARCH (89%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (89%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (78%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (78%); CITY GOVERNMENT (78%); GREEN BUILDING (78%); EMISSIONS (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); EDUCATION SYSTEMS and INSTITUTIONS (74%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (74%); NONPROFIT ORGANIZATIONS (72%); SANITATION DISTRICTS (72%); COLLEGES and UNIVERSITIES (71%); ARCHITECTURAL SERVICES (70%); EDUCATION ADMINISTRATION (69%); SCHOOL DISTRICTS (69%); BUSINESS DEVELOPMENT (66%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (66%); WASTE MANAGEMENT and REMEDIATION SERVICES (61%); CLERGY and RELIGIOUS (60%); BUSINESS and PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATIONS (78%)  	KAISER PE