mpacts of widening this freeway," Davis said. "The most efficient way to mitigate those impacts is to improve transit service along the same corridor."LiNeBrEaKRT executive Mike Wiley said the tentative deal would allow the agency to cut seven minutes off run times for some trains into downtown.LiNeBrEaKThe agreement, however, does not fully comply with a court ruling issued last year.LiNeBrEaKJudge Timothy Frawley ordered Caltrans to study carpool lanes' potential impacts on greenhouse gas emissions, which have been linked to global warming.LiNeBrEaKCall The Bee's Tony Bizjak, (916) 321-1059.		GOVERNMENT BUDGETS (90%); SUITS and CLAIMS (90%); SETTLEMENT and COMPROMISE (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (89%); PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION (88%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); JUDGES (78%); DECISIONS and RULINGS (78%); SETTLEMENTS and DECISIONS (78%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (78%); LEGISLATORS (78%); POLITICAL PARTIES (78%); BUDGET (75%); EMISSIONS (73%); RAIL TRANSPORTATION (72%); URBAN RAIL SYSTEMS (72%); RAIL CROSSINGS (72%); LAW COURTS and TRIBUNALS (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (60%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (74%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (61%)  		ARNOLD SCHWARZENEGGER (57%)  	SACRAMENTO, CA, USA (94%) CALIFORNIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Sacramento Bee   	Tony Bizjak, The Sacramento Bee, Calif.  			Crime/law  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090116-SA-Possible-deal-in-Hwy-50-suit-could-remove-one-barrier-in-budget-battle-0116  	SA  									
The Salt Lake Tribune (Utah)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	Mayan Nobel laureate calls racism a 'disease': U. of U. ? She lectured as part of Martin Luther King Jr. Day events.  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	605 words  	Jan. 16--When 1992 Nobel Peace Prize winner Rigoberta Menchu Tum gets a day off from advocating for peace and human rights worldwide, she likes to sleep in.LiNeBrEaKMenchu said the changes in climate and time zones wear on her during her travels. Once rested, she spends time with her husband of 17 years, Angel Canil; her 14-year-old son, Mash; and their three dogs. She also likes making jewelry, sewing, cooking and taking care of her plants.LiNeBrEaK"My house is a small jungle," she told The Salt Lake Tribune . "I like to be an ordinary person." LiNeBrEaKBut some folks who attended Menchu's hourlong lecture Thursday at the University of Utah said she was inspirational and down-to-earth.LiNeBrEaKIt was her first time in Utah, and more than 1,000 people showed up for the event, nearly filling Kingsbury Hall. Her keynote address -- it began and ended with a standing ovation, and had some laughs in between -- was one of several events this week at the U. in honor of Martin Luther King Jr. Day on Monday.LiNeBrEaKMenchu, 50, is a Mayan Indian from Guatemala who has spent her life fighting social injustice. She also ran unsuccessfully in 2007 for president of her Central American country. She has had her share controversy. For example, she has acknowledged that when she wrote a book about her life, she mixed her own testimony with experiences of other people during Guatemala's civil war that lasted from 1960 to 1996.LiNeBrEaKDuring her talk --LiNeBrEaKin Spanish and with an interpreter -- she told "young people" that there is no excuse for them not to be involved in challenging injustices. She encouraged them to initiate change in their communities because it doesn't happen on its own.LiNeBrEaK"Don't wait until you become a victim; you have your rights," she said.LiNeBrEaKMenchu said racism is a "disease" that affects people spiritually and emotionally when they are not content with themselves.LiNeBrEaKShe said it still exists in her homeland --but she has hopes that it will improve over time.LiNeBrEaK"Why can someone be against a brother who doesn't have the same skin color?" she said. "Prejudice has brought us apart."LiNeBrEaKShe said humans need to interact with humans who are different from them to experience various cultures. And if all people "respected" each other, they would be able to understand one another, despite their differences.LiNeBrEaK"The power of guns can never solve the problems of humanity," she said.LiNeBrEaKMenchu also said, "Human beings have abandoned our basic relationship with mother earth." She called on people to take responsibility for taking care of the environment.LiNeBrEaKAfter the event, Hanah Kim, a 22-year-old community college student, said Menchu "inspired me" to get more involved in human-rights issues.LiNeBrEaKFarah Melendez, a U. international studies sophomore, said Menchu's talk about fighting injustice reminded her of why she walked in Utah's historic immigrants rights march in 2006.LiNeBrEaK"It's an endless fight to making [things] better," she said.LiNeBrEaKjsanchez@sltrib.comLiNeBrEaKDid you know?LiNeBrEaKThe names of Menchu's dogs are Sotz (bat), K'oi (monkey), Char (a type of bird).LiNeBrEaKAlthough she has experienced snow worldwide, Menchu has never tried any snow sports.LiNeBrEaKShe likes to visit cities' mercados (markets) when she travels.LiNeBrEaKMLK eventsLiNeBrEaKFor information about other MLK Jr. events, go to www.sltrib.com.		NOBEL PRIZES (91%); AWARDS and PRIZES (91%); AFRICAN AMERICANS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); RACE and RACISM (89%); CIVIL RIGHTS (89%); SOCIAL JUSTICE (78%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (76%); COMMUNITY COLLEGES (74%); DOGS (73%); COLLEGES and UNIVERSITIES (69%); NATIVE AMERICANS (66%)  		UNIVERSITY OF UTAH (56%)  		UTAH, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (