THE SEATTLE POST-INTELLIGENCER 	January 16, 2009 Friday 	CLIMATE THE LOSER IN TUNNEL CHOICE  	EDITORIAL; Pg. A13  	598 words  	We believe Gov. Chris Gregoire, Seattle Mayor Greg Nickels and King County Executive Sims made the wrong choice in selecting the deep-bore tunnel to replace the Alaskan Way Viaduct.LiNeBrEaKOur commitment to real climate solutions is the loser in this decision.LiNeBrEaKYou don't have to be a climate change expert to understand the role transportation investments play in shaping travel habits, energy consumption and growth patterns. We had an opportunity to press forward with a package of new transit, street improvements and a better Interstate 5 that would have met our future transportation needs. LiNeBrEaKThe Surface/Transit/I-5 solution, vetted in the recent planning process, tested beautifully in the computer models. Modeling showed that we already have plenty of pavement if we use it more efficiently. This solution represents an approach that has proven effective repeatedly in other cities: London, San Francisco, Seoul, Paris, Copenhagen, New York, Vancouver.LiNeBrEaKReorienting priorities around transit, compact growth, street connectivity, and providing people real alternatives to driving works for urban mobility, freight mobility and economic development. Spending $2 billion or more on tailpipe capacity with deep-bore tunnel - the most expensive option - is not a step toward a better future.LiNeBrEaKThe tunnel being planned by the state will be the largest diameter bored tunnel in the world. With only 1 percent of the design work complete and the funding plan unfinished, there are many unanswered questions about its feasibility. Details on the full cost, constructability, schedule and funding will likely swipe the bloom right off the rose. We anticipate another chance to reevaluate its cost/benefit in the near future.LiNeBrEaKAs Washington State Department of Transportation is figuring that out, where do the rest of us go from here?LiNeBrEaK- The viaduct is unsafe, and the promise to close and remove it in 2012 should be kept. The citizens of Seattle are bearing the risk, and the city should hold the governor accountable to this commitment.LiNeBrEaK- With the separation of project responsibilities, the city and county are now free to pursue the smart investments that actually will increase our local alternatives to driving: new transit, a First Avenue streetcar, a parking tax, transit incentives, as well as local street improvements. These projects are the critical path to closure of the viaduct in 2012. Elected leaders should finalize the funding plan and propose the new taxes immediately, and we should all work together to get these under way.LiNeBrEaK- With the state ceding authority for the waterfront back to Seattle, we can get started now envisioning the best use of this valuable public land. The opportunity to create a civic heart for our city - with parks, event spaces, a four lane urban street and active edges integrated into a functional shore ecology - is safely back in our collective (local) hands.LiNeBrEaK- It's time to embrace tolling - it's the best strategy available to reduce congestion and maximize the efficiency of our existing roads and highways. Tolls can also be an important revenue source to address our region's backlog of maintenance needs and to provide additional transit service.LiNeBrEaKOur elected officials missed an opportunity to make a cost-effective decision to move us toward a lower carbon and economically resilient future. There are still many decisions to be made, and future generations are counting on us to act boldly for the long-term health of the region.LiNeBrEaKCary Moon is director of the People's Waterfront Coalition. Mike O'Brien is chair of the Cascade Chapter of the Sierra Club.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); HIGHWAY FUNDING (89%); ROAD and BRIDGE CONSTRUCTION (89%); COUNTY GOVERNMENT (89%); CITY GOVERNMENT (89%); COUNTIES (89%); GOVERNORS (78%); CIT