St. Louis Post-Dispatch (Missouri) 	January 16, 2009 Friday   SECOND EDITION	LETTERS FROM READERS YOUR VIEWS  	EDITORIAL; Pg. C8  	1454 words  	Let Legislature figure out how to pay for new plantsLiNeBrEaKThe editorial "Short circuit" (Jan. 11), regarding proposed legislation that would allow Missouri utilities an alternative way to finance power plant construction, was shortsighted. It nitpicked on technicalities and overlooked the real issues.LiNeBrEaKThe paper might be right that the bill's sponsor overreached in calling his bill a "job creation tool." Building a nuclear plant in Callaway County will produce the same number of jobs whether it is financed by Ameren's shareholders or by its customers.LiNeBrEaKBut the editorial's snarky approach to the legislative proposal ignored current realities. Because of Environmental Protection Agency regulations, America has not built a coal-fired plant in 20 years. Coal is under increasing pressure as a fuel for electric power because of global warming and because of accidents such as the one in Kingston, Tenn., several weeks ago. We may be at the point at which we either build a new nuclear plant or risk limited distribution of electricity in the future. LiNeBrEaKIn theory, the shareholders of Ameren could borrow the money and build a new nuclear power plant. But from whom would they borrow the money? With the collapse of the credit markets, it may be unrealistic to think that Ameren can just shop for a loan to build a nuclear plant. LiNeBrEaKIf we need a new plant to provide us with electricity in the future, and a utility can't borrow the money to build it, what should we do? I don't look forward to reading the Post-Dispatch in the dark. Personally, I'd be willing to pay a little extra on my bill each month rather than risk not having enough electricity for my family in the years ahead.LiNeBrEaKHow big is that risk? I'm not sure; it is a matter to investigate and debate. And where better than in a legislative arena? With all due respect to the Public Service Commission, it can't change the law it enforces. That's the Legislature's job. I'm not afraid to see our legislators revisit standards established in the 1970s. Let's keep the lights on.LiNeBrEaKJames F. Dowd III | Webster GrovesLiNeBrEaKOther heroesLiNeBrEaKThe Post-Dispatch unveiled John F. McDonnell as the Citizen of the Year in the story "Leaving corporate life, not the community" (Jan. 11). The winner was selected by a group of former winners. There is no question that Mr. McDonnell has earned his place among them.LiNeBrEaKThe paper's Talk of the Day blog ran an informal survey for readers to vote on their nominees for "St. Louis-area person of the year." More than 7,000 votes were cast, yet no mention was made in the print version of the paper. The majority of the votes went to Ryan Hummert, the firefighter killed in Maplewood, and to Randy Grim of Stray Rescue. Both men were cited as heroes by voters. In true hero fashion, Mr. Grim tipped his hat to Mr. Hummert, who made the ultimate sacrifice when he was killed in the line of duty.LiNeBrEaKHomage should have been paid to the efforts of both Mr. Hummert and Mr. Grim and attention brought to the number of votes each man received from what was not a select committee but the citizenry at large.LiNeBrEaKRachelle L'Ecuyer | Maplewood Maplewood Community Development DirectorLiNeBrEaKWaiting to see Obama's Middle East policyLiNeBrEaKFor Palestinians, it is a struggle for survival. For Israelis, it is an undertaking to break Hamas's back. But the battle in Gaza is of no less significance to the United States. What is at stake is the America's ability to reclaim its sovereignty in making foreign policy decisions based on its values and self-interests, including mending its strained relations with the Arab and Muslim worlds.LiNeBrEaKWhile the current administration lacked the will to alter the dynamics that produced the current conflict, the upcoming administration is determined to get engaged. President-elect Barack Obama kept his cards close to his chest while the onslaught in Gaza went on. If he delivers a fair resolution to the crisis, Arabs and Muslims will pardon his cautions posture while hundreds lost their lives under Israeli fire. If, on the other hand, he maintains the "Israel is our strongest ally" policy, then all bets are off.LiNeBrEaKRami Saffarini | Platte City, Mo.LiNeBrEaKCost of a wage hikeLiNeBrEaKWell, you just knew it was going to happen. The people who convinced voters to raise the minimum wage to unheard-of levels have reaped what they sowed. In her column "Minimum-wage jobs outsourced to Mexico" (Jan. 9), Susan Weich explained that 78 full-time jobs and 150 piece workers are history because the rising minimum wage has forced the owner of a factory to move the jobs to Mexico.LiNeBrEaKNo longer will these Missouri workers have a wage, health care and a 401(k), which the employer provided. Now they have unemployment benefits for 26 weeks. We were told this was going to be the result if this law passed, and it has come to pass. I hope the people who supported this law are satisfied.LiNeBrEaKI suspect that this is just the beginning. They got their higher minimum wage, and now they get the unemployment that goes right along with unconscionable increases in that wage. Did these workers benefit from the rise in the minimum wage? You make the call.LiNeBrEaKMarc Schoenfeld | ChesterfieldLiNeBrEaKWho's next in line?LiNeBrEaKWho are we trying to bail out with billions of tax dollars? The theory is that the federal government gives money to business, and business allows us to keep our jobs and keep paying for our houses and cars. Banks and credit card companies will relax their death grips, and we'll all breathe more easier at the cash register.LiNeBrEaKSounds a lot like the discredited "trickle down" economic theory, wherein "what's good for business is good for the consumer." We gave tax breaks and incentives to bankers and CEOs with the idea that the benefits would trickle down to ordinary mortgage-paying, car-buying, grocery-shopping Americans. Instead, corporate profits went up, CEOs got huge bonuses and more dividends were declared for people wealthy enough to own stock.LiNeBrEaKI don't foresee any trickle-down effect happening with the bailout either. Bankers and executives will get the bailouts, businesses will hold onto the cash to ease their liquidity and credit issues, and the job cuts, wage freezes and "cost containments" will continue.LiNeBrEaKThe business community is about profits and growth, not about beneficence toward consumers or employees. From a business perspective, passing the government's largesse down to ordinary workers is counterproductive, not in the best interests of the business.LiNeBrEaKI'm tired of "fixes" for which I get to pay taxes but from which I never see any benefit. Who are we bailing out next? How many governors now have their hands out? How many mayors? What other industry will my taxes rescue?LiNeBrEaKJ. L. Hickman | Fairview HeightsLiNeBrEaKBail out inmates, tooLiNeBrEaKMisosuri's inmates could use some of the bailout money. If we got a bailout, Missouri could let go of some 11,000 employees and save $650 million a year. (I don't know what the Department of Corrections spends that money on, but it's not food. The food is awful. And the medical care is almost nonexistent.)LiNeBrEaKThere are too many young men here, taking up space. They will have a tough time getting and keeping jobs. The courts should have an alternative plan.LiNeBrEaKBut maybe we are too small to save, not like the big banks that were "too big to fail."LiNeBrEaKJames "Tony" Shivers | Bowling Green, Mo.LiNeBrEaKThe untouchablesLiNeBrEaKThe rush by the Democratic Party and the media to immediately and off-handedly exonerate Timothy Geithner, President-elect Barack Obama's nomination for Treasury secretary, for his tax evasions is incredible, in the literal sense of the word, and astoundingly offensive to the sensibilities of the average American.LiNeBrEaKThis purportedly is a man of immense financial intellect. Are we to believe that he "honestly" made these mistakes - not once but over the course of several years? If he can make mistakes of such a simple nature regarding basic tax policy, can he even remotely be qualified to be our Treasury secretary, called upon to make policy decisions of enormous complexity, especially given the current economic crisis? The answer has to be a resounding "no." You simply can't have it both ways. The reality is that if Timothy Geithner were a Republican, nominated by a Republican president, the Democrats and the media would go nuts - and rightly so. But, because he is Mr. Obama's man, he appears untouchable.LiNeBrEaKMike Macauley | BallwinLiNeBrEaKThat's politicsLiNeBrEaKA recent letter claimed that Alaska Gov. Sarah Palin is no Caroline Kennedy, who is seeking an appointment to the U.S. Senate from the New York governor. The letter writer was correct.LiNeBrEaKMs. Palin has been elected to public offic three times by a majority of her constituents; Caroline Kennedy hasn't seen fit to even vote about half of the time.LiNeBrEaKKerry Recker | South St. Louis County		POWER PLANTS (92%); NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS (92%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (91%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (90%); LEGISLATION (90%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (90%); LETTERS and COMMENTS (90%); POWER and COMMUNICATION SYSTEM CONSTRUCTION (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); LEGISLATORS (89%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (78%); PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSIONS (78%); JOB CREATION (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (77%); INVESTIGATIONS (77%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (77%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (76%); SHAREHOLDERS (75%); CIVIL SERVICES (75%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (74%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (74%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (69%); 