St. Petersburg Times (Florida) 	January 16, 2009 Friday   4 State / Suncoast Edition	IT'S EASY BEING GREEN  	SPORTS; Pg. 8C  	722 words  	Brian Brawdy's motto is "Wonder. Explore. Believe."LiNeBrEaKOver the past year, the 47-year-old Tampa resident logged more than 50,000 miles in his green recreational vehicle and has hiked, biked and paddled in every one of the Lower 48 states. This weekend he will have his Wonder machine at the Florida RV Supershow at the Florida State Fairgrounds.LiNeBrEaK"I wanted to do more than just recycle old newspapers and tin cans," said Brawdy, a former police officer from upstate New York. "So I decided to do what I can to get more people outdoors. I believe that the more people we have who go out and enjoy nature, the more people will want to protect it." LiNeBrEaKBrawdy began his journey more than 20 years ago, after his father's suicide.LiNeBrEaK"I had a hard time dealing with my father's death," he said. "The only solace I could find was when I was by myself out in the middle of nowhere."LiNeBrEaKThe road warriorLiNeBrEaKSo Brawdy quit his job and traveled the country, eventually ending up in Colorado, where he worked as a meditation instructor, helping people focus through this timeless Eastern discipline.LiNeBrEaK"I discovered pretty quickly that the mind was a powerful thing," he said. That led to a similar post in Chicago, where he picked up a part-time position at an outdoors outfitter.LiNeBrEaK"I wanted to go camping," he said.LiNeBrEaKThen, in 2000, a local TV station called the shop looking for a survival expert. "I showed them how to build an igloo," he said. "That was the beginning of my television career."LiNeBrEaKIn the years that followed, Brawdy eventually became a traveling outdoors survival expert, filming more than 1,500 segments, including appearances on Good Morning America and the Today Show.LiNeBrEaKThe eco-RVLiNeBrEaKIn 2007, Brawdy found himself in Tampa, recovering from surgery to remove skin cancer (the bypr