Times-Standard (Eureka, California)  	January 16, 2009 Friday 	Governor calls for unity in crisis  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	1034 words  	Jan. 16--The crux of Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger's State of the State address Thursday was simple: The state is on the verge of insolvency, it's the Legislature's fault and it's now up to those same lawmakers to work together to fix the situation.LiNeBrEaKWith the state's budget deficit expected to reach $42 billion in the next 18 months, Schwarzenegger delivered a terse, 12-minute speech in front of the state Legislature imploring lawmakers to set aside partisan ideologies to broker a deal to bring the state's massive budget into balance. The speech was a far cry from the norm, as the State of the State is generally seen as an opportunity for governors to laud their accomplishments and outline grandiose visions for the future. LiNeBrEaKThose in attendance saw none of that Thursday.LiNeBrEaK"It doesn't make any sense for me to ... stand in front of you and talk about education or infrastructure or water or health care reform and all of those things when we have this huge budget deficit," Schwarzenegger said. "I will talk to you about my vision for all those things and much more as soon as we get the budget done."LiNeBrEaKNorth Coast representatives Assemblyman Wesley Chesbro and Sen. Patricia Wiggins had slightly differing views on the governor's address, with Wiggins applauding the address and Chesbro taking a more cautious approach.LiNeBrEaK"It was not a bad speech as far as it went," Chesbro said from Sacramento, "but I'm waiting to try to determine which Gov. Schwarzenegger we're going to be dealing with: the governor who negotiated landmark global warming legislation with us and negotiated bipartisan support for infrastructure bonds for transportation and education, or the governor that just last week vetoed our $18 billion budget package."LiNeBrEaKThe $18 billion budget deal Chesbro referred to was a Democrat-backed proposal that combined cuts and tax increases.LiNeBrEaKWiggins said Schwarzenegger's address said little she could disagree with.LiNeBrEaK"His remarks were measured, respectful, complimentary but prodding -- and they were delivered in a tone that was cautionary and firm, but not alarming," Wiggins said in a statement. "We are in the midst of a fiscal crisis, which we have yet to resolve after months of negotiations. I agree with him that each and every one of us must reach across the aisle now to avoid a fiscal disaster, a disaster we may face if we don't get this budget dilemma resolved soon."LiNeBrEaKIn his address, the governor didn't seem to hesitate to lay responsibility for the current fiscal crisis squarely on the shoulders of legislators, who Schwarzenegger said have let rigid partisan ideology dominate state government, rather than the best interests of Californians. The governor even invoked imagery from one of his movies to make the point.LiNeBrEaK"It is not that California is ungovernable: it is that for too long we have been split by ideology," he said. "Conan's sword could not have cleaved our political system in two as cleanly as our own political parties have done."LiNeBrEaKSchwarzenegger went on to say that the Legislature has at times engaged in civil war, and that the needs of its constituents sometimes become secondary.LiNeBrEaKWiggins and Chesbro strongly disagreed with that statement.LiNeBrEaK"This is simply not true," Wiggins said. "Each of us does have the people's interest in mind. But, let's not forget, we all represent different constituencies. What people want in Sonoma County is not always the same as what people want in Tulare County."LiNeBrEaKChesbro had a similar take, saying the governor seems to be very good at blaming the Legislature, but not so good at turning that critical eye inward.LiNeBrEaK"He's not assuming his share of the responsibility for his failure to act," Chesbro said. "Every time the Democrats have negotiated or responded to a budget compromise from him, he's failed to deliver support. As a Republican governor, I think it's really his responsibility to get the Republican legislators to compromise, and he's really shown no ability to do that."LiNeBrEaKThe sticking point in budget negotiations so far has been raising taxes. Schwarzenegger and Democrats have proposed raising a variety of taxes, but have not agreed on the form those should take. Meanwhile, Republicans have reportedly refused to budge on their pledge to oppose any state tax increases.LiNeBrEaKThe governor's latest budget plan, released on New Year's Eve, proposes $17. 4 billion in spending cuts, $14. 3 billion in tax increases and $10 billion in borrowing to close the deficit through June 2010.LiNeBrEaKThe proposal has already drawn fire from the California Federation of Teachers and the American Federation of Teachers, which claim the proposal cuts education funding by more than $7 billion. This comes on the heels of the California Teachers Association's announcement earlier in the week that California has slipped to 47th in the nation in per-pupil funding.LiNeBrEaKMoving forward, Wiggins said she believes the situation is truly dire, but is confident the problem will be addressed before the end of the month.LiNeBrEaKChesbro said he's also hopeful a compromise can be reached quickly, but reiterated his intent to protect public education from cuts and to make sure health care funding isn't reduced any more than necessary.LiNeBrEaKSchwarzenegger ended his address by complimenting California's firefighters, who earlier this year managed to extinguish more than 2,000 fires that were burning at once. He called on the Legislature to show the same courage, and to act quickly to strike a budget deal.LiNeBrEaK"Addressing this emergency is the first and most important and greatest thing that we must do for the people of California," he said. "The $42 billion deficit is a rock upon our chest and we cannot breathe until we get it off."LiNeBrEaKThe Associated Press contributed to this report.		BUDGET (91%); GOVERNMENT BUDGETS (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); GOVERNORS (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); LEGISLATORS (90%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (78%); VETO (78%); HEALTH CARE POLICY (72%); TAX LAW (72%); TAXES and TAXATION (66%); GLOBAL WARMING (63%); HEALTH CARE REFORM (52%); INSOLVENCY and BANKRUPTCY (77%)  			ARNOLD SCHWARZENEGGER (94%)  	SACRAMENTO, CA, USA (79%) CALIFORNIA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Times - Standard   	Thadeus Greenson, Times-Standard, Eureka, Calif.  			Government  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090116-VJ-GOVERNOR-ADDRESS-20090116  	VJ  									
