he region can support sustainable large-scale fisheries.LiNeBrEaKBOTTOM LINE: Federal managers are getting ahead of any problems by saying "no" to industrial fishing in the Arctic right now.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); COMMERCIAL FISHING (91%); FISHERIES (91%); FISHERIES ADMINISTRATION (90%); SUSTAINABLE FISHERIES (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (89%); MARINE RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (89%); SPORTS and RECREATION (79%); SPORTS (79%); BULK SHIPPING (78%); SALTWATER ECOSYSTEMS (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (77%); TRENDS (77%); SUSTAINABLE DEVELOPMENT (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (76%); SPORTS and RECREATION EVENTS (74%); CLOSINGS (74%); WEATHER (72%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (63%)  	PACIFIC FISHERY MANAGEMENT COUNCIL (57%)  	TED STEVENS (67%)  	JUNEAU, AK, USA (79%) ALASKA, USA (94%); PACIFIC OCEAN (93%); ARCTIC OCEAN (79%) ARCTIC (99%); UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Anchorage Daily News   	Anchorage Daily News, Alaska  			Sports (sports events/team news)  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090115-AC-EDITORIAL-ARCTIC-FISHING-20090115  	AC  									
Appeal-Democrat (Marysville, California)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	EDITORIAL: Green push hypocrisy tarnishes Golden State  	COMMENTARY  	670 words  	Jan. 15--Even before Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger, California staked its claim as an environmental darling. No regulation seemed beyond reach of the Golden State in search of a green legacy.LiNeBrEaKThe state's environmental regulations already compounded U.S. EPA requirements. Faddish alternative-energy mandates were imposed for years, to the envy of environmentalists elsewhere. Then the governor proudly pushed the so-called Global Warming Solution Act in 2006, raising the bar further with unparalleled environmental mandates.LiNeBrEaKAlas, reality is catching up. Gov. Schwarzenegger must be uncomfortable now, calling for waivers of environmental review for 10 huge highway projects he says are urgently needed to stimulate a sinking economy. Bypassing reviews could speed a $1. 2 billion economic infusion and create 22,000 jobs, he says. LiNeBrEaK"This is a stunning turnaround by the governor, and I am baffled by it," California League of Conservation Voters President Tom Adams told the Los Angeles Times.LiNeBrEaKStunning, perhaps. But not baffling. Shortly after the Legislature's approval of the Global Warming Solutions Act, we observed that these additional heavy-handed regulations only would add to an already devastating economic burden.LiNeBrEaKThe much-touted 2006 law seeks to reduce CO2 emissions on the theory that will reduce global warming, despite temperatures having declined even while emissions dramatically increased over the past decade. Of course, highway construction consumes vast amounts of cement, which produces great quantities of CO2 when manufactured, and also requires much heavy machinery, which gives off great amounts of genuine pollutants, as well as harmless CO2.LiNeBrEaKWe say harmless because CO2 is natural gas essential to life, even though it has greenhouse-gas properties. Until a misguided U.S. Supreme Court decision last spring, CO2 wasn't considered a pollutant. As a former director of the federal Office of Energy Research, physicist William Happer, puts it: "Every time you exhale, you exhale air that has 4 percent carbon dioxide. To say that that's a pollutant just boggles my mind. What used to be science has turned into a cult."LiNeBrEaKCult or not, California's environmental crusades have been more image than substance.LiNeBrEaK"A dirty secret about California's energy economy is that it imports lots of energy from neighboring states to make up for the shortfall caused by having too few power plants," Max Schulz, director of the Manhattan Institute's Center for Energy Policy and the Environment, wrote in an Orange County Register op-ed column last week.LiNeBrEaKA substantial portion of the state's power is imported from coal-burning plants in five other states, and from large-scale hydropower in three others. Schulz quoted James Lucier of Capital Alpha Partners, a Washington, D.C.-area investment group: "California practices a sort of energy colonialism. They rely on Western states to supply them with power generation they are unwilling to build for themselves." As Schulz noted, that leaves other "states to deal with the resulting pollution."LiNeBrEaKNot coincidentally, California energy prices are among the nation's highest, aggravated by regulations requiring expensive renewable power sources. Consequently, heavy manufacturing and other energy-intensive industries have been fleeing.LiNeBrEaKNow Gov. Schwarzenegger wants to selectively waive some costly environmental reviews, making this state of laws instead a state of arbitrary men, where some are favored and others not. He also insists to do so won't ruin the environment. If that's the case, why were those laws necessary in the first place?		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); EMISSIONS (90%); GOVERNORS (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (8