Chicago Tribune (Illinois)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Interior nominee vows `balanced approach' to energy and land-use policy  	WASHINGTON DATELINE  	739 words  	WASHINGTON _ It was a classic Western script, with a Cabinet nominee taking the Gary Cooper role: a low-talking, boots-and-bolo-tie wearing former lawman pledging to clean up a federal agency gone amok.LiNeBrEaKNominated by President-elect Barack Obama to lead the Interior Department, Sen. Ken Salazar, D-Colo., appeared on Thursday before a Senate committee that still technically counts him as a member _ and treated him more than sympathetically. LiNeBrEaKThe Interior Department has drawn criticism from lawmakers and environmentalists in recent years over a sex and drugs scandal in one of its bureaus and an auditors' report saying employees manipulated endangered species decisions to advance a political agenda.LiNeBrEaK"I want to clean up the mess," Salazar said in his opening statement.LiNeBrEaKBut he offered only a few details on his plans and sidestepped several hot subjects, including federal protection for gray wolves, the relationship between global warming and the Endangered Species Act, and whether he would continue to allow guns and snowmobiles in national parks.LiNeBrEaKIn some areas he was more direct, promising to reform the nation's signature mining law and to consider a full plate of options for energy independence, including offshore oil drilling and, under the right conditions, oil-shale development.LiNeBrEaKHe pledged support for renewable energy development _ a cause he championed as senator _ and promised a "balanced approach" to energy and land-use policy. He emphasized his rural roots, having grown up on a ranch in Colorado's San Luis Valley. And he called for a new national youth conservation program putting young people to work in parks and public spaces.LiNeBrEaKRepublicans and Democrats on the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee repeatedly told Salazar how much they admire his integrity and how they will miss him when he leaves the Senate. They called him brother, invited him to visit their states and, in the case of Sen. Mel Martinez of Florida, offered to arrange for him to wrestle alligators in the Everglades.LiNeBrEaK"This is on its way to being a full-fledged bouquet-tossing contest," Sen. Ron Wyden, D-Ore., joked.LiNeBrEaKMany environmental groups support the nomination, but some continue to voice their displeasure.LiNeBrEaKIn a press release, Nicole Rosmarino of WildEarth Guardians said Salazar "will not take strong stances on behalf of science and environmental protection and is not up to the task of undoing the enormous damage the Bush administration has done to public lands, endangered species, and the credibility of the Department of the Interior over the last eight years."LiNeBrEaKSalazar repeatedly promised to put science first in the agency's decision-making. But asked if he believed the government should consider global warming in endangered species protection _ a position environmentalists favor but the Bush administration rejects _ he gave only a hint of an opinion.LiNeBrEaK"There is no doubt that climate change and global warming is having an impact on a whole host of natural features of this world, including endangered species that we have," Salazar said. "It is something that we will take a look at."LiNeBrEaKSalazar left himself open to compromise over a pair of domestic oil initiatives: drilling on the Outer Continental Shelf, which he said could make sense in some areas but not others, and leasing federal land for oil-shale development _ a particularly hot issue in his home state, where most shale efforts are located. He pledged to pursue research into so-called "clean coal" technology that seeks to capture and store carbon dioxide emissions from coal to curb global warming.LiNeBrEaKEven initially skeptical Republicans declared themselves pleased. Sen. Jim DeMint, R-S.C, had said he was concerned that Salazar's energy approach was "to cut off American energy supply." But, after speaking with him this week, he told Salazar at the hearing, he came to believe "we're pretty much on the same page."		LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); ENDANGERED SPECIES (90%); LAND USE PLANNING (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); WILDLIFE (89%); NATIONAL PARKS (89%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (89%); POLITICAL PARTIES (89%); WILDLIFE CONSERVATION (88%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (79%); LEGISLATORS (77%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (77%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (77%); PLATFORMS and ISSUES (77%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (75%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (75%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (75%); CLIMATE CHANGE (75%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (75%); MAMMALS (74%); GLOBAL WARMING (73%); MINES and MINING (71%); OIL EXTRACTION (71%); MINING REGULATION and POLICY (67%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (66%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (66%); MOTOR VEHICLES (52%)  			KEN SALAZAR (85%); BARACK OBAMA (58%); MEL MARTINEZ (53%); RON WYDEN (52%)  	CHICAGO, IL, USA (71%) COLORADO, USA (93%); ILLINOIS, USA (79%); FLORIDA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (95%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  	ARCHIVE PHOTOS on MCT Direct (from MCT Photo Service, 202-383-6099): Ken SalazarLiNeBrEaKARCHIVE GRAPHIC on MCT Direct (from MCT Graphics, 202-383-6064): 20081217 Salazar OBAMA		Newspaper  	2009 Chicago Tribune   	By Jim Tankersley, Chicago Tribune  	WASHINGTON   			Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune News Service  	20090115-BC-OBAMA-SALAZAR  	TB  									
Contra Costa Times (California) 	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	My Word: Linda Sheehan - Communities beginning to recognize importance of environment  	MY TOWN; Alameda; Letters; News; Local  	596 words  	TWO JAN. 11 articles, "Climate change may be stoking stronger winds, altered oceans," and "Food crisis due to warming world trumps all other worries, say scientists," discuss how science is demonstrating that we are altering, perhaps irrevocably, the Earth's systems. LiNeBrEaKOngoing resistance to this science occurs in part because it humbles us to our actual place on the planet   as one piece of a larger whole, rather than the dominant entity. LiNeBrEaKIt is reminiscent of reactions to the then-radical proposal that the Earth revolves around the sun, rather than the other way around; or that humans developed over countless millennia through evolution, rather than springing to Earth fully formed.LiNeBrEaKThough it is before our eyes every day, we continue to resist the knowledge that we cannot keep consuming the Earth and expect that it will not respond in ways that we simply can't control.LiNeBrEaKIf we accept the science that we coexist as one piece of a larger system, we can take action to improve our own lives and prevent the dire predictions scientists are making for our future family members.LiNeBrEaKOne of the first steps is to rework our legal system to reflect our actual place in the world.LiNeBrEaKOur laws currently allow   indeed, encourage   the accelerating devastation that scientists predict will arrive. Similar to a legal system premised on the sun revolving around the Earth, our laws are based on myth, not science   in this case, the myth that we can control the planet.LiNeBrEaKThe science doesn't work that way, and neither will the laws.LiNeBrEaKEffective laws allow and constrain behavior to promote desired relationships.LiNeBrEaKThey work in two directions, to reflect each party's respective rights; for example, I can't take your car and you can't take mine.LiNeBrEaKClimate change and other failures result from laws that ignore the two-way relationships that exist between us and the water, air, land and life around us.LiNeBrEaKOur legal system focuses on the rights and needs of people, but ignores the same rights and needs of the other members of the ecological community. The laws encourage us to take from the environment, only regulating how much   but barely doing even that.LiNeBrEaKFortunately, models are cropping up for legal systems that can steer us in the right direction, based on science.LiNeBrEaKIn September, Ecuadorians adopted a new constitution that, for the first time, endows the environment with inalienable rights to "exist, persist, maintain and regenerate its vital cycles, structure, functions and its processes in evolution."LiNeBrEaKThe constitution further grants individuals the legal authority to defend these rights on behalf of the environment.LiNeBrEaKEcuadorians have taken the lead in reflecting science in law by acknowledging the interdependence between us and our environment and respecting both sides of that relationship.LiNeBrEaKCommunities around the United States also are starting to create their own rights-based environmental laws. States such as in Pennsylvania and New Hampshire have recognized in ordinance the "enforceable right of natural communities and ecosystems to exist and flourish" within their boundaries.LiNeBrEaKEcuador's constitution, and a growing body of environmental ordinances in the United States, has set the stage for an evolution of law that recognizes the inherent, inalienable rights of all occupants of this Earth to exist and thrive for the benefit of each of us and our descendants.LiNeBrEaKLet's make that evolution a reality.LiNeBrEaKLinda Sheehan is an attorney and the executive director of the California Coastkeeper Alliance, representing 12 Waterkeeper organizations coast-wide. She lives and works in Fremont.		SCIENCE NEWS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%);