The Eagle (Bryan, Texas)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Texas AandM offers some fun new courses  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	874 words  	Jan. 15--Yes, you can get class credit for learning about Big Foot and for becoming more environmentally conscience.LiNeBrEaKThe list of courses to choose from at Texas AandM, like at most other universities, keeps expanding, much to the pleasure of students looking for a class that might just make homework fun.LiNeBrEaKClasses recently approved to be added to the course guide include Ecotourism: Principles and Practices; Science,Pseudoscience and Critical Thinking in Anthropology; Polar Regions of the Earth: Science, Society and Discovery; and, a personal favorite, Festivals, Fairs and events. LiNeBrEaKYou might have already taken an off-the-beaten-path class that sucks you in by the very title, so shoot us an e-mail if you have a favorite you want to mention: spotlight@theeagle.comLiNeBrEaKHere's a sampling of some of the new ones up for discussion.LiNeBrEaKPolar Regions of the Earth: Science, Society and DiscoveryLiNeBrEaKIn the past two years, the number of majors within geosciences has doubled. With much attention faced on global warming and being environmentally conscious, it's no wonder.LiNeBrEaK"The poles are very distant to us here in Texas," said Andrew Millington, professor in geosciences. "What students will realize, is that we're all connected."LiNeBrEaKAccording to the syllabus, one of the objectives of this class is to show that the earth is a co-dependent system of systems.LiNeBrEaK"Clearly they should get an appreciation that even though they live in Texas... what we do in Texas affects the polar regions. What's happening in the world's polar regions is relevant here," Millington said.LiNeBrEaKLast semester, classes in the department experienced record enrollment, he said.LiNeBrEaKEcotourism: Principles and PracticesLiNeBrEaKBeing eco-friendly is a new trend in most aspects of daily life.LiNeBrEaKThis class aims to show how those same ideas can be applied to leisurely travel. According to the International Ecotourisn Society, ecotourism is "responsible travel to natural areas that conserves the environment and improves the well-being of local people."LiNeBrEaKIn this class, students will have the opportunity to see how ecotourism affects the cultures tourists come into contact with, governmental agencies and also the private sector. The class will be taught as a seminar and emphasizes class participation and discussion.LiNeBrEaKScience, Pseudoscience and Critical Thinking in AnthropologyLiNeBrEaKFor those curious about Big Foot, aliens and other such claims, this class is worth considering. According to the syllabus the class focuses on "closely scrutinizing some of the fantastic claims that have been made regarding the fields of biological anthropology and archaeology."LiNeBrEaKCoursework will include evaluating the legitimacy of various documentaries, and writing a review of a pseudoscientific book.LiNeBrEaKFestivals, Fairs and EventsLiNeBrEaKTo successfully host most events, there are several areas that need attention.LiNeBrEaKThere's advertising, budgeting, recruiting help, and much more. This class has been developed as a spin off from a highly successful event leadership program.LiNeBrEaK"We submitted a major curriculum overhaul of our undergraduate classes," said Gary Ellis, department head for Recreation, Parks and Tourism Sciences. "I think a reason for that was responsiveness to changes and evolution in the knowledge base, and also being mindful of emerging career opportunities for our students."LiNeBrEaKThis class incorporates several appearances by guest speakers who have been successful in the event planning industry.LiNeBrEaK"In addition to the knowledge we provide, experience is the best way to improve in this particular field," said Harrison Pickney, an instructor for the class. "That's why we try to get so many professionals from the field to talk to students about their experiences."LiNeBrEaKLong processLiNeBrEaKFor those skeptical of the actual value of some of these classes, rest assured. It generally takes a minimum of five months before a class can be approved and added to the course guide.LiNeBrEaK"The faculty wants to make sure the curriculum of the university is substantive and meets the needs of the university and the students," said Doug Slack, regents professor in wildlife and fisheries sciences, and former head of the core curriculum committee.LiNeBrEaKFaculty members ensure the value of each proposed class by sending it through a five-step process.LiNeBrEaK"If everything goes right, it takes about a month for each step of the process," he said.LiNeBrEaKThe class must first be approved through the department, then by the college. From there it is sent for approval by the university curriculum committee and then to the executive committee of the faculty senate. The last step in the process is getting the green light from the office of the president.LiNeBrEaKAnd of course, there are some classes that don't make the cut.LiNeBrEaK"One time we had a course that made it sound like a fly fishing course," Slack said. "We later found out it wasn't, it was just an unfortunate title for the class."		ECOTOURISM (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); ANTHROPOLOGY and ARCHAEOLOGY (89%); FESTIVALS (89%); CURRICULA (89%); TRENDS (77%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (77%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (76%); APPROVALS (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (71%); ARCHAEOLOGY (60%)  				TEXAS, USA (95%); EARTH (92%) UNITED STATES (95%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Eagle   	Michelle Casady, The Eagle, Bryan, Texas  			Entertainment  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090115-EG-Texas-A-M-offers-some-fun-new-courses-0115  	EG  									
The Hartford Courant (Connecticut)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Many expect better U.S. science policy under Obama  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	814 words  	Jan. 15--In the past eight years, scientists upset with President George W. Bush have tried a number of ways to show their displeasure: Nobel Prize winners have taken to YouTube to criticize his science policies; scientific organizations have circulated petitions.LiNeBrEaKIn Connecticut, 100 scientists marched in their academic robes outside the U.S. Coast Guard Academy when Bush came to speak in 2007. The organizer of that protest, Connecticut College chemistry Professor Marc Zimmer, said it was Bush's lack of action on global warming and his acceptance of intelligent design as science that particularly vexed him. LiNeBrEaKHe expects Barack Obama to restore the country's position in science.LiNeBrEaK"It's really early on and what he's done is he's got a superstar team of scientists, and they're real scientists," Zimmer says.LiNeBrEaKNot all scientists were unhappy with the Bush years, but a large number were, and they grew increasingly vocal in their criticism of the president's policies on stem cell research, health care, and alternative fuel sources.LiNeBrEaKIn an online video in October, Martin Chalfie, winner of 2008 Nobel prize for chemistry, charged that Bush's policies have "excluded reasoned research and documented scientific information, and substituted ideology and false science. This change is destroying our scientific integrity."LiNeBrEaKChalfie, who was one of 76 Nobel laureates who signed a letter endorsing Obama, said this week that Obama's science appointments show that the president-elect is on the right track.LiNeBrEaK"At the moment, the people he's selected seem to be quite wonderful," he said. "The other thing is, he's moved rather quickly to name these people, and that's a very important aspect to this."LiNeBrEaKObama scored points among scientists when, during his campaign, he released an 11-page science plan that included doubling the funding for the National Institutes of Health over the next 10 years. He has also said that he recognizes the potential for stem cell research to treat several disorders and that he would reverse current restrictions on federal funding for stem cell research.LiNeBrEaKIn a radio address last month, he said science "holds the key to our survival as a planet, and our security and prosperity as a nation." His science appointments, including John P. Holdren of Harvard as White House science adviser, have been well received.LiNeBrEaK"The last eight years have had their ups and downs; we have not made progress in areas we should have," says Suman Singha, vice president for research at the University of Connecticut. "I think as a scientist, I am more hopeful about the next eight years."LiNeBrEaKSince a federal act in 1862 fostered the teaching of agriculture and engineering in universities, Singha says, "those have been the areas that have kept the United States as a world leader."LiNeBrEaKThe country has stayed at the forefront of science, he says, but its lead has slipped in the past eight years. He hopes the next four years will see the country refocus on science.LiNeBrEaK"To compete with China and India, I think that's what we need to do," says Singha.LiNeBrEaKNot all scientists have been so enthusiastic.LiNeBrEaKMichael Monce, who teaches physics at Connecticut College, says he is wary of Obama's appointment of Carol M. Browner for global warming czar. She has been adamant that CO{-2} emissions are the cause of global warming; Monce says evidence is building that contradicts that position.LiNeBrEaKRegarding claims that funding for scientific research has decreased during the Bush administration, Monce says the past eight years have only been a continuation of a pattern that began during the Clinton administration. If anything, he says, the decrease leveled off during the Bush years.LiNeBrEaKHaifan Lin, who teaches cell biology at Yale, is looking forward to the change in administration. He criticizes Bush's prohibition on using federal funds for research on human embryonic stem cell lines that were created after Aug. 9, 2001, or on using federally funded facilities for such research. He says the older stem cell lines have less research value because they are aged.LiNeBrEaKHe noted that Connecticut researchers have been less affected by the restrictions because the state is one of the few in the country to provide its own stem cell funding. Despite Obama's vow to overturn the funding restriction, Lin says U.S. researchers will continue to feel the effects of Bush's policy. Even if Obama reverses the restrictions early on, he says, federal funding would not likely be available for two more years.		SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (92%); NOBEL PRIZES (91%); SCIENCE NEWS (91%); AWARDS and PRIZES (91%); SCIENCE POLICY (91%); GOVERNMENT RESEARCH FUNDING (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); PUBLIC POLICY (89%); BIOTECHNOLOGY and GENETIC SCIENCE (89%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); STEM CELL RESEARCH (87%); CHEMISTRY (78%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (78%); ENGINEERING (78%); PETITIONS (77%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (76%); MILITARY SCHOOLS and ACADEMIES (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (70%); HEALTH DEPARTMENTS (67%); INTERNET SOCIAL NETWORKING (77%)  		US COAST GUARD (58%)  	BARACK OBAMA (95%); GEORGE W BUSH (94%)  	CONNECTICUT, USA (93%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Hartford Courant   	William Weir, The Hartford Courant, Conn.  			Science  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090115-HC-SCIENCE-POLICY-20090115  	HC  									
