News and Observer (Raleigh, North Carolina)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Storing sun's energy key to energy independence  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	782 words  	Jan. 15--It's widely accepted that our future energy needs will be met by experimental and theoretical technologies. Possibilities include "clean" coal, advanced "breeder" nuclear reactors, hydrogen fuel cells, and batteries with enough storage capacity to back up power plants.LiNeBrEaKNathan Lewis, a chemistry professor at the California Institute of Technology, has spent three decades researching another option: harnessing solar power to create fuels that can replace oil and gasoline. LiNeBrEaKLewis will give the keynote speech tonight in Chapel Hill to kick off a two-day conference at UNC exploring the future of solar energy. The conference marks the creation of the Solar Energy Research Center, a joint effort between UNC, Duke, N.C. Central, N.C. State and the University of Florida, which have are combining research in chemistry and polymers and other scientific disciplines. To fuel its research ambitions, the center has applied for a $25 million grant from the U.S. Department of Energy.LiNeBrEaKLewis's address is open to the public tonight at 7 p.m. at the Stone Center Theater. The conference continues Friday but requires registration and has sold out.LiNeBrEaKHere are excerpts from Lewis's phone interview with NandO business reporter John Murawski.LiNeBrEaKNandO: Tell us what you'll be talking about.LiNeBrEaKLewis: I'm going to talk about where our energy comes from now. That gets at the scale of the energy problem. It's not fixing a few light bulbs in Fresno. It's not building 50 nuclear power plants. Even if you conserved energy at twice the level you need [it wouldn't be enough].LiNeBrEaKNandO: What would it take?LiNeBrEaKLewis: Something like 10,000 nuclear power plants within the next 50 years somewhere in the world. That's a pretty stunning number to most people, but it's in fact the scale of energy.LiNeBrEaKNandO: What else will you discuss?LiNeBrEaKLewis: I'll look at the resource base and tell you how much wind is there on our planet, and how much can be extracted, and how much can you get out of advanced biofuels, and how much can you get out of all the tides and coal-fired power plants and solar, and I'll look at the resource base to decide where the answers lie and where they don't.LiNeBrEaKNandO: How are we going to offset 10,000 nuclear power plants?LiNeBrEaKLewis: If you care about greenhouse gas emissions and climate change, if energy demand is going to double, and if you have to cut emissions by 80 percent, then basically you have to save as much energy as all the energy we use today combined, and you have to make as much clean energy as we use today combined, and you have to do that within our lifetime. It's possible. We can't do it by talking about it. We have to do it by getting serious about doing it.LiNeBrEaKNandO: How does the sun fit into this picture?LiNeBrEaKLewis: More energy from the sun hits the earth in one hour than all the energy consumed on our planet in an entire year. We just can't run all our factories for one hour at full bore and then shut them down for the rest of the year. To exploit the sun and to have a technical energy systems solution you have to capture, convert and store it. We still don't have a way to store electricity on a massive scale. If you can't store it, you can't do much with it, and it's especially pronounced when you have intermittent resources, like wind and solar. In principle, you could rely on them [solar and wind power] exclusively.LiNeBrEaKNandO: Describe your research.LiNeBrEaKLewis: I work in technologies to capture, convert and store sunlight. Solar paint: stuff you can paint on your roof, and maybe ultimately make fuel directly. Artificial photosynthesis: How do you build a leaf? Nature built it. We know it works. We just gotta figure out a way to do it ourselves better.LiNeBrEaKI've been working on the fundamentals in wet solar cells for about 30 years. They can directly make fuel -- unlike the ones we're used to thinking about now that only make electricity. We would like to make a liquid fuel because it would be easier to put in cars. We have hints that it works but we don't have any product yet.LiNeBrEaKNandO: How long do you think it'll take us to get there?LiNeBrEaKLewis: How long does it take a chicken to hatch a golden egg?LiNeBrEaKNandO: That's never happened, has it?LiNeBrEaKLewis: Well, there's one way: Buy more chickens. If we had more research, we'd have greater odds of actually getting something out quicker.		CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (90%); ENERGY DEMAND (90%); SOLAR ENERGY (90%); CHEMISTRY (90%); FUEL CELL TECHNOLOGY (90%); POWER PLANTS (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (89%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (89%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (89%); NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS (89%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); CHEMICALS RESEARCH (78%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (78%); ENERGY RESEARCH (78%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (78%); HYDROGEN ENERGY (78%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (78%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (78%); BIOMASS (78%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (73%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (73%); BIOFUELS (72%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (72%); TALKS and MEETINGS (70%); GRANTS and GIFTS (68%); INTERVIEWS (66%)  		CALIFORNIA INSTITUTE OF TECHNOLOGY (58%); US DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY (56%); UNIVERSITY OF FLORIDA (56%)  		NORTH CAROLINA, USA (92%); CALIFORNIA, USA (90%); FLORIDA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 News and Observer   	John Murawski, The News and Observer, Raleigh, N.C.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090115-RA-Storing-sun-s-energy-key-to-energy-independence-0115  	RA  									
North Adams Transcript (Massachusetts)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Local farmers concerned about EPA's rumored 'cow tax'  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	707 words  	Jan. 15--Despite continuing reports that the U.S. Environmental Protection Agency is considering a tax on livestock as part of efforts to begin regulating greenhouse gas emissions, officials at the government agency maintain the "cow tax" is a misunderstanding.LiNeBrEaKBut even the thought of such an idea concerns local farmers. LiNeBrEaK"It wouldn't help us, that is for sure," said James Hoellerich, whose brother Roy co-owns Hales Hill Farm LLC in Adams. "I don't think it 's necessary. Farmers are not doing that great and never have."LiNeBrEaKVictor Ziemba, owner of Ziemba Farm in Adams, and John Gwozdz, co-owner of Hales Hill Farm, said taxing farms for each of their cows would be devastating to the family-run businesses barely able to make ends meet.LiNeBrEaK"I think it would put everybody out of business. It would be too expensive to compete," said Gwozdz, whose farm has about 100 cows.LiNeBrEaKA news release from the New York Farm Bureau in November 2008 stated that the tax could be as high as $175 per animal -- a figure often cited in news articles since, even after the EPA tried to dispel the rumor.LiNeBrEaK"If it was $5 a cow, we could handle it, but even $100 a cow is too much," Gwozdz said.LiNeBrEaKZiemba, who has about 175 cows on his farm, said he disagrees with a tax on the animals, and there is no reason for it.LiNeBrEaK"I'd say it would put most farmers out of business, and they can't stay in business now with the price of milk goingLiNeBrEaKdown," he said.LiNeBrEaKHe said another tax would put his farm out of business, and it can barely afford to stay in business now.LiNeBrEaK"We're working seven days a week, and we still lose money," he said.LiNeBrEaKZiemba, Gwozdz and Hoellerich agreed there are other ways to combat greenhouse gas emissions besides taxing livestock.LiNeBrEaK"They should put people first, and then get to the animals," Hoellerich said.LiNeBrEaKJonathan Schradar, spokesman for the EPA, said Tuesday the agency is a long way from addressing global climate change by taxing the country's livestock population.LiNeBrEaK"There is a lot to do with human-created issues before we talk about volcanos and livestock," Schradar said.LiNeBrEaKHe said the whole misunderstanding of the EPA's intentions began when the agency put out an Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking last year, asking the public whether emissions from automobiles should be regulated under the Clean Air Act. For the EPA to take action against auto emissions, it would have to declare all greenhouse gas emissions dangerous to public health and classify them as pollutants -- that would include carbon dioxide, nitrous oxide and methane.LiNeBrEaKThe Department of Agriculture then submitted comments against any regulation because it would mean methane, which is a natural byproduct of livestock, would have to be regulated.LiNeBrEaK"From that, our friends at the farm bureau then decided to make it an issue that the EPA wanted to institute a cow tax," Schradar said.LiNeBrEaKThe Advance Notice of Proposed Rulemaking for the control of greenhouse gases was signed by EPA Administrator Stephen Johnson in June 2008, and the public comment period on the document ended in November 2008.LiNeBrEaKAccording to the document, in 2006, the agricultural sector contributed 8 percent of greenhouse gas emissions, compared to 34 percent from electrical generation, 28 percent from transportation, 19 percent from industry, 6 percent from commercial and 5 percent from the residential sector.LiNeBrEaKSchradar said the EPA has yet to do anything about regulating greenhouse gases.LiNeBrEaK"There is no such thing as a cow tax. The EPA is not proposing one. It's all rumor," he said.LiNeBrEaKCheryl Lekstrom, director of member relations with the Massachusetts Farm Bureau, said Tuesday the EPA was looking for a way to address emissions being produced from farms, but nothing had been proposed.LiNeBrEaK"We just know of it by rumor," she said of the cow tax.LiNeBrEaKTo reach Meghan Foley, e-mail mfoley@thetranscript.com		ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (91%); FARMERS and RANCHERS (91%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); EMISSIONS (90%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); MAMMALS (90%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS (89%); AGRICULTURE DEPARTMENTS (89%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (89%); AGRICULTURAL COMMODITY REGULATION (78%); AGENCY RULEMAKING (78%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (78%); FOOD SAFETY REGULATION (78%); METHANE (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); ADMINISTRATIVE PROCEDURE (78%); FAMILY COMPANIES (68%)  		US ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (84%); NEW YORK FARM BUREAU (55%)  		UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Meghan Foley, North Adams Transcript, Mass.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090115-QN-Local-farmers-concerned-about-EPA-s-rumored-cow-tax-0115  	QN  									
