Plain Dealer (Cleveland) 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   Final Edition; All Editions	A disturbing drop in migrating birds  	INSIDE and OUT; Pg. E6  	834 words  	AERIAL VIEWLiNeBrEaKBird walksLiNeBrEaKAt 9: 30 a.m today, naturalist Jen Brumfield will lead a walk through the woods at the West Creek Reservation. Entrance is on West Ridgewood Drive in Parma. For additional information call 216-341-9225.LiNeBrEaKAt 9 a.m. Sunday, the Blackbrook Audubon club will embark on a field trip to the Geauga County Amish areas, focusing on Best Lake, Hayes Road, Swine Creek, and Headwaters Park. Target birds include snow buntings, Lapland longspurs, Wilson's snipe and rough-legged hawks. Meet at the Best Lake parking lot just south of Chardon on the right-hand side of Ohio 44. For additional information call 440-257-2507. LiNeBrEaKBirds descending from the vast boreal forests that cover a billion acres of Canada have brightened up the past several winters in Northeast Ohio.LiNeBrEaKCommon redpolls, evening grosbeaks, white-winged crossbills and pine grosbeaks have invaded our area in extraordinary numbers, joining the annual waves of boreal visitors such as tree and white-throated sparrows, dark-eyed juncoes, saw-whet owls and Bonaparte's gulls.LiNeBrEaKBut as Obi-Wan Kenobi says, there is a "great disturbance in the force."LiNeBrEaKThe vast incubator for up to 5 billion birds is under siege by mining, oil and timber interests that threaten to alter forever the natural world as we know it.LiNeBrEaKAlready, surveys have documented disturbing drops in the numbers of familiar birds that we welcome to our yards, parks and lakes each year.LiNeBrEaKSome of the population losses are noticeable only anecdotally. For instance, birds we consider common here, such as chestnut-sided and blackpoll warblers, least flycatchers and Swainson's thrushes, are experiencing significant drops, according to research conducted by the Canadian Boreal Initiative.LiNeBrEaKCommon nighthawks, winter wrens, kinglets and barn and bank swallows are also showing troubling trends.LiNeBrEaKEven some of our favorite winter visitors are exhibiting the ill effects of habitat loss and climate change. Birds such as Northern harriers, pine siskins, Northern flickers, purple finches and sparrows: white-throated, white-crowned, song, vesper, and juncoes.LiNeBrEaKI previously wrote about the bird suffering the most precipitous decline - the rusty blackbird - which has lost 11 percent to 16 percent of its numbers on its boreal breeding grounds.LiNeBrEaKWhat can we do?LiNeBrEaKIncreasing our awareness of this crisis is one thing. Several Web sites documenting the problem are listed below.LiNeBrEaKSupporting organizations such as the National Audubon Society, the Nature Conservancy and the Sierra Club are other ways to help.LiNeBrEaKThe latest Audubon magazine chronicles the impact that human and natural forces are having on the boreal forest. The article places much of the onus on the timber industry, with 65 percent of its produce going to pulp and paper manufacturing.LiNeBrEaKCiting the mailing of 20 billion unsolicited catalogs a year, there is a groundswell of grass roots support for a Do Not Mail system similar to the Do Not Call registry. To learn more about this proposal, go to www.catalogcutdown.org.LiNeBrEaKThe province of Ontario has taken the lead in preventive actions, moving to protect more than half of its remaining northern boreal forests - 55 million acres of wilderness - from commercial logging, drilling and mining. Other actions have been taken to preserve more than 36 million acres of the Northwest Territory and much of Quebec's forests.LiNeBrEaKLet's hope the rest of Canada follows suit. If not for us, then for the generations of birders to come.LiNeBrEaKFor details, go to www.LiNeBrEaKsaveourborealbirds.org, www.LiNeBrEaKborealbirds.org and www.LiNeBrEaKborealcanada.ca.LiNeBrEaKSightingsLiNeBrEaKIce on the lake and huge floes of fish are making for fabulous gull-watching at the East 72nd Street warm-water release site in Cleveland's Gordon State Park. Jen Brumfield led a Local Patch birding tour group to the site on Friday and hit a home run with nine gull species, including a black-headed. Unfortunately, they don't have black heads in winter; Brumfield suggests scanning the Bonaparte's gulls for dark black flashes under the wings' primary feathers. The numbers of white-winged gulls are staggering, the lesser black-backed gulls have returned after several weeks absent, and the Bonaparte's gulls are so numerous they look like giant shape-shifting clouds when the fly. The prospects for rarities are only going to increase as the ice fills in the open spots on the lake.LiNeBrEaKA possible black-legged kittiwake showed up at East 72nd Street on Sunday.LiNeBrEaKA rough-legged hawk and a Northern shrike were highlights of a morning walk through Inga Schmidt's Geauga County neighborhood. She also has pine siskins at her feeders.LiNeBrEaKEvan Schlanser, 14, was thrilled by the arrival of about six white-winged crossbills in the pines outside his home in South Russell Township. Jeanne Hrenko spotted several crossbills at the North Chagrin Reservation.LiNeBrEaKSherrill Parle was surprised by a predawn sighting of what first appeared like a small snow man on her front lawn in Hinckley. It was a male snowy owl.LiNeBrEaKTo reach this Plain Dealer reporter: jmccarty@plaind.com, 216-999-4153		BIRDS (93%); FORESTRY and LOGGING (89%); FORESTS and WOODLANDS (89%); LOGGING INDUSTRY (78%); TRENDS (73%); CLIMATE CHANGE (73%); ECOSYSTEMS and HABITATS (69%); PAPER MILLS (60%); PAPER and PACKAGING (60%); POPULATION DECLINE (58%); PULP MILLS (50%); PAPER MFG (50%); FORESTRY and LOGGING SECTOR PERFORMANCE (74%)  				OHIO, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  	SPECIAL TO THE PLAIN DEALER Some woodland birds that we take for granted during the spring and fall migrations - such as this Swainson's thrush - are becoming less common as the