ented the essay opportunity to her students.LiNeBrEaK"I am French and a big proponent of the European Union," Worthington said.LiNeBrEaKWINNERSLiNeBrEaK"I focused on the European Union's efforts with global warming and humanitarian efforts in Africa," Wemette said.LiNeBrEaKShe will be visiting France for about a week in July.LiNeBrEaK"It was a confidence booster," she said. "And I got to learn about the European Union."LiNeBrEaKPlus, ever since she started taking French in seventh grade, Wemette has wanted to visit France.LiNeBrEaK"I can't wait for the trip."LiNeBrEaKBaldwin, for his essay, delved into unity and how diverse cultures and religions come together for prosperity and peace.LiNeBrEaKHis essay finished in the Top 50, earning him a gift basket of French products.LiNeBrEaKBaldwin lived in France for four months during an exchange program and hopes to one day work in corporate and international law. He's also fluent in Spanish and said the languages he has learned will be beneficial to his career.LiNeBrEaKWorthington was not surprised by their success.LiNeBrEaK"They are top students," she said.LiNeBrEaKShe's proud of them and boasted that because of the award, Wemette got a call from Smith College in Massachusetts inquiring about her future plans.LiNeBrEaK"They will go far in life," Worthington said.LiNeBrEaK"And they put AuSable Valley on the map."LiNeBrEaKE-mail Stephen Bartlett at: sbartlett@pressrepublican.com		AWARDS and PRIZES (90%); LANGUAGE and LANGUAGES (90%); PRIMARY and SECONDARY SCHOOL TEACHERS (78%); EMBASSIES and CONSULATES (73%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%); RELIGION (50%); HIGH SCHOOLS (89%)  		EUROPEAN UNION (93%)  		PARIS, FRANCE (92%); NEW YORK, NY, USA (79%) NEW YORK, USA (93%); NEW JERSEY, USA (92%); CONNECTICUT, USA (91%) FRANCE (96%); EUROPE (95%); EUROPEAN UNION (94%); UNITED STATES (93%); AFRICA (79%); EUROPEAN UNION MEMBER STATES (94%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Stephen Bartlett, The Press-Republican, Plattsburgh,