The Record (Bergen County, NJ) 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   All Editions	Jackson vows resolve at EPA helm;  Says she won't let politics sway policy 	NEWS; Pg. A01  	901 words  	Former state environmental commissioner Lisa P. Jackson pledged aggressive action to combat pollution and global warming if confirmed as administrator of the federal Environmental Protection Agency.LiNeBrEaKTestifying before a Senate Committee on Wednesday, Jackson acknowledged a daunting agenda that would reduce greenhouse-gas emissions and other air pollution, clean up hazardous waste sites, reduce toxic chemicals and protect the nation's waters. "These five problems are tough, but so is our resolve to conquer them," Jackson said.LiNeBrEaKSeated directly behind Jackson at her confirmation hearing were Upper Ringwood residents Vivian Milligan, Jay Van Dunk, Wayne Mann and Veronica Van Dunk. Personal guests of Jackson and first-time visitors to the Capitol, they sat calmly as photographers hovered. LiNeBrEaKAs commissioner of the state Department of Environmental Protection, Jackson called for faster cleanup of the site in Ringwood where Ford Motor Co. dumped tons of toxic waste more than 40 years ago from its former Mahwah plant. Now in its fifth EPA-supervised cleanup, the tainted area was the only one in the nation to be relisted as a Superfund site.LiNeBrEaKFor decades, residents, many of them members of the Ramapough tribe, have complained that Ford's paint sludge caused elevated rates of cancer, asthma in nearly every household, unexplained rashes and premature death. After an EPA cleanup, residents took officials on a tour of their neighborhood where chunks of gray, wrinkled sludge tainted the community.LiNeBrEaK"They and too many other Ramapoughs have lived on top of a Superfund site for decades," Jackson said during the hearing. "They are vivid reminders to me of how EPA can be a force for good if it does its job well and what can go wrong if EPA falls short."LiNeBrEaK"Now we have a strong voice in the EPA," Mann said before the hearing began. "I am honored to be Lisa's guest."LiNeBrEaKSen. Barbara Boxer, D-Calif., chairwoman of the Senate Committee on Environment and Public Works, hailed Jackson's nomination as a course correction from the Bush administration.LiNeBrEaK"We have seen the agency move in a direction diametrically opposed to the mission it was established to achieve," she said.LiNeBrEaKOverall, Jackson was met with enthusiasm from many committee members, particularly the Democrats. Although there was mention of the DEP's handling of a toxic site in South Jersey where children were allowed to attend a day care center, the issue passed quickly.LiNeBrEaKJackson's hearing went so smoothly, in fact, that the committee has decided to release her nomination for a full vote by the Senate in the coming days.LiNeBrEaKJackson, who once served as Governor Corzine's chief of staff, was accompanied by her husband and appeared at ease, having testified several times before Congress in the past. She was introduced by New Jersey Sens. Frank R. Lautenberg and Bob Menendez. Jackson had met with several committee members in recent days to discuss her record and plans for the EPA, where she had worked for 15 years before joining the DEP in 2002.LiNeBrEaKIf confirmed by the Senate, Jackson would join President-elect Barack Obama's so-called Green Dream Team, charged with developing energy independence and creating green jobs, key components of Obama's economic recovery plan.LiNeBrEaKRepublican committee members expressed concerns not with Jackson as much as with Obama's policies, particularly about the economic impact of addressing global warming, which they say will drive up energy costs. The Democrats, however, believe the search for solutions will create jobs that bolster the economy.LiNeBrEaKJackson testified that she would stress "scientific integrity" and the "rule of law" in making policy at the agency. In a poll of members of the Union of Concerned Scientists, a national organization, 60 percent said their research had been subjected to political interference during the Bush administration.LiNeBrEaKLautenberg and Menendez praised Jackson's tenure in New Jersey, where she wrote the state's climate-change laws, developed the energy master plan and enjoyed support from both sides of the political aisle.LiNeBrEaK"Lisa Jackson has the energy, expertise and experience we need to revitalize the EPA," Lautenberg said.LiNeBrEaKThe EPA has to take a more muscular role in Superfund cleanups, he said. During the 1990s the agency averaged more than 80 Superfund cleanups per year compared with just 30 last year, he said.LiNeBrEaKJackson, 46, a Princeton-educated engineer, would become the first African-American to lead the agency of 20,000 employees.LiNeBrEaKSeveral community and environmental groups have backed her nomination, including the Sierra Club's New Jersey Chapter and New Jersey Audubon Society.LiNeBrEaKSince her nomination, a handful of environmental groups have lobbied against her appointment, including the national Public Employees for Environmental Responsibility (PEER) and Edison Wetlands Association. Critics have charged that Jackson's leadership of the DEP was flawed, especially in the site remediation program. But Jackson's supporters say the program was already under duress before she took office. In 1994 there were 270 case managers and 12,000 contaminated sites. There are now 150 cases managers and 20,000 sites.LiNeBrEaKOn a personal note, Jackson said she understands concerns with air pollution and its role in creating asthma in the population, especially in children. One of Jackson's two sons suffers from asthma and was hospitalized over Christmas.LiNeBrEaKE-mail: layton@northjersey.com		ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (94%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); WATER POLLUTION (90%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP (90%); HAZARDOU