Richmond Times Dispatch (Virginia) 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   Final Edition	Put a Price On Carbon  	EDITORIAL; Pg. A-11  	708 words  	All of us who recognize that man-made emissions are creating the climate crisis also realize that the surest way to reduce and, ultimately, eliminate the problem is to put a price on fossil carbon itself. For the past eight years the only solution deemed politically viable was a cap-and-trade system because Americans aren't thought to be mature enough to use the term "taxes" in debates about public policy. Well, much has changed since Nov. 3, 2008.LiNeBrEaK What hasn't changed is the need for speed. We are already above what many now consider the safe level of atmospheric CO2 - 350 PPM. LiNeBrEaK This week Gov. Tim Kaine announced four new incentives "to promote green jobs as part of his Renew Virginia initiative." Each one of these initiatives, however, will fail unless there is a sure and rising price for carbon. If Virginians want to see a new green economy that creates energy security and new jobs, and begins to slow climate-killing carbon emissions, we must be concerned about the carbon pricing mechanism itself.LiNeBrEaK If speed matters then we should realize that cap-and-trade is a formula for delay. For starters, there is no consensus on how CO2 allocations (the key to capping carbon emissions) will be distributed: free to big polluters, auctioned freely, or some sort of hybrid system? What doesn't even exist today is a working U.S. market for these carbon allocations - and who thinks that, from the ashes of the financial markets, a new dependable system will soon arise? The much smaller carbon trading system recently inaugurated in New England has taken years to work out. The one in the EU also took years to work out and a recent GAO report says that it has failed: CO2 emissions are worse now than they were in 1990.LiNeBrEaK ANY FORM OF carbon pricing will provide incentives to develop alternative energy, even prices set on carbon by a cap-and-trade system. The real incentive, however, for such Innovation-creating investment is the long-term assurance of a stable premium on fossil fuels. Look at the dampening effect on fuel-saving investments the current swing in gasoline prices is having. Supporters of cap-and-trade point to the successful effort to reduce SO2 and NOx through such a mechanism. Yet price volatility - on average 17 percent a month - was a hallmark of that very limited system. Prices swings in the European Union's system are equally volatile.LiNeBrEaK Cap-and trade suffers from many other defects as well, but since speed in responding is the goal, our leaders should be urging a national, if not global, direct tax on carbon. Administered far upstream, at the refinery, mine head, natural gas processor, or port of entry, the tax is transparent, can be collected with no additional bureaucracy, and can be implemented in six months.LiNeBrEaK Economists who have studied this subject believe that, since virtually all the products that will be covered by a carbon tax are already being taxed in one way or another, a national tax could easily cover 90 percent of the sources of carbon emissions. Just last week, Rex Tillerson, the CEO of Exxon, called for carbon taxes as a "more direct, more transparent, and more effective approach" than cap-and trade.LiNeBrEaK A BIG PROBLEM with cap-and-trade is that no one wants to discuss openly what happens to the revenues derived from that system: Do they reward existing polluters, do they become another government (albeit greatly diminished because of middle-man profits) revenue stream, or is there some other way that these funds will be used?LiNeBrEaK Carbon taxes can be structured to be revenue neutral if that is what the politics demand, but whatever happens to the revenue stream will be a decision by our elected leaders and not by shadowy, unregulated financial markets.LiNeBrEaK Thomas Friedman, in Hot, Flat and Crowded, when comparing cap-and-trade to carbon taxes, opts for the latter, saying: "We have to go from 'this is the best we can do' to 'this is how we are going to do it best.' "LiNeBrEaK That is the formula for creating jobs, reducing carbon emissions, and restoring America's leadership role as we seek to save our planet in peril.LiNeBrEaKAl Weed is the chairman of Public Policy Virginia, a Charlottesville-based think tank working on climate change issues. Contact him at (434) 970-2232 or aweed@ppvir.org		EMISSIONS (91%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (78%); OIL and GAS PRICES (77%); PUBLIC POLICY (76%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (76%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (74%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (72%); GASOLINE PRICES (72%); TAXES and TAXATION (72%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (72%); PRICE INCREASES (72%); GASOLINE MARKETS (71%); BANKING and FINANCE (71%); COMPUTER TRADING SYSTEMS (69%); INTERNATIONAL ECONOMIC ORGANIZATIONS (61%); NATURAL GAS PROCESSING (50%) OPINION; ENVIRONMENT; POLLUTION; WEATHER; ENERGY  			TIM KAINE (56%)  	VIRGINIA, USA (92%); NORTHEAST USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%); EUROPE (79%); EUROPEAN UNION (68%); EUROPEAN UNION MEMBER STATES (68%)  	January 20, 2009  	ENGLISH  	PHOTO  		Newspaper  	2009 Richmond Newspapers, Inc. All Rights Reserved  	AL WEED  															
The Santa Fe New Mexican (New Mexico)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Bills would resolve water claims, create preserves  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	676 words  	Jan. 15--Resolution to a major tribal water-rights case, a new wilderness area and a new preserve in an area containing fossilized footprints are among the New Mexico projects included in a massive package of water and public lands bills the U.S. Senate is scheduled to vote on this afternoon.LiNeBrEaKThe Omnibus Public Lands Management Act is sponsored by Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M. It contains 160 bills, of which 15 directly impact New Mexico. The Senate voted 68-24 Wednesday morning to end debate on the act and take it to a vote. If the Senate approves the act, it will go to the House. LiNeBrEaKAmong the bills are two that settle water-rights claims of the Navajo Nation, the state's largest tribe, to the San Juan River. The bill calls for approval of a 2005 settlement between New Mexico and the tribe, guaranteeing the Navajos the rights to 600,000 acre-feet of water per year for farming, cities, households and industrial uses. The bill authorizes federal funding over the next two decades for a pipeline to serve portions of the Navajo Nation and the city of Gallup. The bill authorizes $870 million to build the pipeline, with some of the cost paid by the state and the communities served.LiNeBrEaKA group of irrigators along the San Juan have protested against the settlement, saying it cedes too much water to the tribe and will harm other water-rights holders in the basin. Bingaman said, however, it will end decades of litigation and the potential for more litigation over water rights in the Four Corners area and will protect other water-rights holders.LiNeBrEaKThe omnibus bill does not include approval or funding for two other New Mexico Pueblo water-rights settlements -- the Aamodt case, which involves four pueblos in the Pojoaque Valley, and another one concerning Taos Pueblo -- according to Bingaman's spokeswoman Jude McCartin.LiNeBrEaKOne portion of the omnibus bill establishes a nationwide conservation system within the U.S. Bureau of Land Management, and another portion, the Secure Water Act promoted by Bingaman, calls for a nationwide effort to quantify water resources and increase water efficiency.LiNeBrEaKThe act recognizes eight "major reclamation basins" that are included for study under the bill, including the Rio Grande. Under the bill, the U.S. Geologic Survey, the National Oceanic and Atmospheric Administration and other agencies would coordinate efforts to determine the impact of climate change on water supplies in the basins and how that would affect available water for cities, wildlife and energy production.LiNeBrEaKThe omnibus bill also:LiNeBrEaKu Designates 16,030 acres of BLM land in northeastern New Mexico as the Sabinoso Wilderness, a bill U.S. Sen. Tom Udall, D-N.M. championed when he was a U.S. representative.LiNeBrEaKu Establishes the Prehistoric Trackways National Monument to protect a major deposit of Paleozoic Era fossilized footprints of amphibians, reptiles and insects in the Robledo Mountains in Southern New Mexico.LiNeBrEaKu Creates the Fort Stanton-Snowy River Cave National Conservation Area near Fort Stanton to protect a series of newly explored underground caves.LiNeBrEaKu Reauthorizes the Rio Puerco Watershed Management Program, which Bingaman first wrote into law in 1996 and which has helped restore much of the 7,000-square-mile degraded watershed.LiNeBrEaKu Creates a preservation program for the historic Route 66 Corridor, which crosses through New Mexico.LiNeBrEaKu Authorizes the Eastern New Mexico Rural Water System project to build a pipeline from Ute Lake to Eastern New Mexico communities.LiNeBrEaKu Funds the restoration of irrigation projects along the Rio Grande for several pueblos.LiNeBrEaKContact Staci Matlock at 470-9843 or smatlock@sfnewmexican.com		WATER RIGHTS (91%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); LEGISLATION (90%); US FEDERAL G