The Salt Lake Tribune (Utah)  	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	The Salt Lake Tribune Rebecca Walsh column: Walsh: How to work the media  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	580 words  	Jan. 15--You have to give the Congress of Racial Equality credit: They know how to throw a dog-and-pony show.LiNeBrEaKParachuting into town yesterday, CORE spokesman Niger Innis and a gaggle of pastors staged a "protest press conference," rapping Robert Redford for opposing the Bush administration's sale of oil and gas leases on some of the most spectacular public land in Utah. They claim Redford's environmental ethic hurts "grandmothers on a fixed income and single mothers dependent upon public assistance in South Chicago."LiNeBrEaKYou see what they did there? They slapped down the race card in front of a Sundance movie theater. It was brilliant. Movie star plus lots of Hollywood in town for the film festival plus middle-class white guilt equals exponential increase in media coverage. LiNeBrEaKI didn't go -- just on principle. But The Salt Lake Tribune sent reporter Patty Henetz. You probably noticed the headline.LiNeBrEaK"They've got the celebrity name. They've got the location right. And they're going to draw media attention," says Laurie Wilson, a Brigham Young University communications professor.LiNeBrEaKPredictably, the loyal opposition howled. Crossroads Urban Center Director Glenn Bailey knows his response to CORE's shaky facts creates a phony debate for reporters to chew on. Still, he and former city mayor Rocky Anderson issued a press release.LiNeBrEaK"Somebody has to question their facts at this point. They keep getting trotted into town by various conservativeLiNeBrEaKcauses," says Bailey. "It's irritating to those of us who are actually doing the work on poverty issues."LiNeBrEaKTurns out the 77-parcel sale to which Redford objected would amount to two days worth of U.S. consumption. But facts are beside the point. This is theater, media manipulation, politics -- or all three.LiNeBrEaK"If facts made politics, we'd actually have a better society than we do," says Sutherland Institute Director Paul Mero, who recruited Innis' father for a 2008 Earth Day seminar meant to debunk global warming. "They're taking advantage of an opportunity to make a point. It doesn't have to be a fact. It doesn't have to be a compelling argument. All it has to do is project the broader argument" of environmental racism.LiNeBrEaKOriginally a reputable civil rights organization, CORE has become the willing tool of energy companies, conservative think tanks and white politicians. Kanab Republican Rep. Mike Noel and former legislator Aaron Tilton, in particular, love to use the Innis family -- Niger testified on Capitol Hill a year ago. The Tribune covered that gig. And I wrote about Sutherland's green day party.LiNeBrEaKI don't know if all the editors who sent reporters to Wednesday's press conference think Innis raises legitimate issues or were just afraid to be the only ones without a Redford headline. The scrum was almost -- but not quite -- inevitable.LiNeBrEaK"As a media outlet, why are you covering it? What's the substantive news here?" asks Wilson. "If there's not a substantive story without Robert Redford, then you shouldn't be telling the story."LiNeBrEaKCan't argue with that.LiNeBrEaKRebecca Walsh is a columnist. Reach her at walsh@sltrib.com		CELEBRITIES (90%); FILM (90%); RACE and RACISM (89%); POLITICS (87%); LEGISLATORS (78%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); PRESS CONFERENCES (77%); NEWS REPORTING (77%); EARTH DAY (76%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (76%); ETHICS (76%); MOVIE INDUSTRY (74%); HUMAN RIGHTS ORGANIZATIONS (73%); CIVIL RIGHTS (73%); MAYORS (72%); FESTIVALS (72%); OIL and GAS LEASES (71%); SINGLE PARENTS (70%); ARTS FESTIVALS and EXHIBITIONS (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (66%); THEATER (57%); ACTORS and ACTRESSES (74%)  	BRIGHAM YOUNG UNIVERSITY (55%)  	BRIGHAM YOUNG UNIVERSITY (55%)  		UTAH, USA (96%) 