The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   FINAL Edition	Politics makes strange new allies;  Former foes form consulting group for state campaigns 	Main News; Pg. A11  	530 words  	In what may be evidence that America really is ushering in a more conciliatory era in politics, a group of leading strategists who have battled each other for years are now joining forces in a Sacramento consulting group. LiNeBrEaK LFM Campaigns will be led by top GOP and Democratic consultants who have been murderously competitive on leading campaigns, but who now say they aim to concentrate on government reform, ballot issues and initiatives. LiNeBrEaKThe principals are:LiNeBrEaK-- Steve Schmidt, chief strategist for Gov. Arnold Schwarzenegger's re-election campaign who was also the senior GOP strategist for John McCain's 2008 presidential campaign and for President Bush's 2004 re-election campaign. LiNeBrEaK-- Democrat Chris Lehane, the former spokesman for both the Clinton White House and for Al Gore's presidential campaign in 2000.LiNeBrEaK-- Adam Mendelsohn, a leading GOP spokesman and the former communications director for Schwarzenegger.LiNeBrEaK-- Democrat Averell "Ace" Smith, who has worked against both Schwarzenegger and McCain as one of the nation's most formidable opposition researchers.LiNeBrEaK-- Democrat Mark Fabiani, the former special counsel to President Bill Clinton and a deputy campaign manager for Gore and running mate Joe Lieberman in 2000.LiNeBrEaK Brian Jones, a former communications director for the Republican National Committee and communications director for McCain last year, will also move from Washington to California to take a role in the venture. LiNeBrEaK The initials of the new firm stand for Lehane Fabiani Mercury, the latter a reference to Mercury LLC, the consulting firm founded by Schmidt and Mendelsohn that includes former Democratic Assembly Speaker Fabian N&uacute;&ntilde;ez as a partner. LiNeBrEaK "This firm, coming together, is a byproduct or a reflection of the times we're in," said Lehane, an oft-quoted personality thanks to his frequently well-honed barbs against GOP candidates, including McCain and Schwarzenegger. "These are folks who have been on the other side of the aisle, who have gone toe-to-toe and blow-to-blow."LiNeBrEaK "And the fact that these folks were able to come together really does reflect that people are putting down their swords and picking up the plowshares," he said. LiNeBrEaKBut the formation of the bipartisan firm may also reflect a changing economic and political landscape in California, which has seen an increasing number of initiatives and ballot measures, creating potentially lucrative work for consultants who normally represent very different campaign interests.LiNeBrEaKInitiatives and referendums "are unique, because they're issue-based and not partisan-based," said Mendelsohn, who served as a strategist for Proposition 11, the California redistricting measure passed by voters in November. LiNeBrEaKOn issues such as high-speed rail, clean water and global warming, "The ballot approach makes tremendous sense in this atmosphere," and on such matters, "we've worked with each other, and we have tremendous respect for each other," he said.LiNeBrEaKIt may not mean a truce in verbal warfare when it comes to campaigns, however. LiNeBrEaK"We all do partisan politics," Mendelsohn said. "And we'll continue to do it." LiNeBrEaK "I will have my plowshare in my right hand - and my sword will continue to be in the left," Lehane said.		CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (91%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (90%); POLITICS (90%); CONSULTING SERVICES (90%); ELECTIONS (90%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (90%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (90%); BALLOTS (89%); REFERENDUMS (89%); VOTERS and VOTING (89%); POLITICAL CANDIDATES (78%); POLITICAL PARTIES (78%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (77%); REDISTRICTING (74%); CLIMATOLOG