St. Petersburg Times (Florida) 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   4 State / Suncoast Edition	510 CAMPAIGN PROMISES AND WE'RE WATCHING  	NATIONAL; POLITIFACT; Pg. 1A  	1275 words  	Barack Obama made 510 promises when he was running for president, a list that is stunning in its scope and leaves almost no part of the executive branch untouched, according to a new analysis by PolitiFact.LiNeBrEaKThe analysis found that Obama made more than twice as many promises as George W. Bush and Bill Clinton, whose campaign pledges were examined by other news organizations. Bush made 177 promises in 2000 and Clinton made 204 in 1992, as reported by the Knight Ridder Washington Bureau (now McClatchy).LiNeBrEaKObama made sweeping promises like ending the Iraq war and cutting taxes on the middle class, and narrow ones like establishing programs to help animals survive global warming, weatherizing 1-million low-income homes per year and increasing tax deductions for artists.LiNeBrEaKThe promises reflect a philosophy that government can, and perhaps should, play a role in solving problems at all levels. LiNeBrEaK"I would describe him as an activist realist," said Bill Galston, a former policy adviser to President Clinton and a senior fellow for governance study at the nonpartisan Brookings Institution. "On the one hand, he does not share the reflexive antigovernment position that has dominated the last 30 years of American politics."LiNeBrEaKOn the other hand, Galston said, it would not be fair to call Obama a "gung-ho intervener or spender." Obama is grounded by a sense of what is economically and politically feasible, he said.LiNeBrEaKPolitiFact, the St. Petersburg Times' fact-checking Web site, compiled the 510 promises by examining Obama's campaign Web site, position papers, interviews and speeches. PolitiFact staffers will be tracking each one on the Web site's Obameter, which will show whether they are "In the Works" or "Stalled," and will ultimately indicate whether the promise was "Kept" or "Broken." The ratings will be tallied on a chart on PolitiFact's home page that will show the overall progress of the Obama presidency.LiNeBrEaKAmong PolitiFact's findings:LiNeBrEaK- Obama calls for more regulation, new agencies and at least 11 new groups that would have "corps" in their name, including: an America's Voice Corps to foster international diplomacy; an Artists Corps to work in low-income schools and communities; and a Health Corps to improve public health.LiNeBrEaK- Of the 510 promises, most deal with foreign policy (87), followed by health (76), the environment (59) and energy (51). He's also fond of transparency (33) and government efficiency (32). Only one deals with canines - a promise to buy his daughters a dog.LiNeBrEaK- He likes advice. We found he wants to create at least 10 new advisers such as a director of urban policy, a special adviser on violence against women, the nation's first chief technology officer and an American Indian policy adviser.LiNeBrEaK- Even before the need arose for a major economic stimulus bill, Obama proposed hundreds of billions in new spending. His ideas include $150-billion over 10 years on green initiatives, $60-billion for roads and bridges, $50-billion for the global fight against AIDS and $25-billion more in foreign aid. He also promised billions in cost savings by ending the war in Iraq, reducing earmarks and reforming federal contracting, to name a few.LiNeBrEaK- He likes green. Overall, Obama hopes to create 5-million "green" jobs as part of a more energy-efficient economy. He wants to retrofit federal buildings to save energy and spur a "Green Revolution" in Africa.LiNeBrEaKObama's high level of detail - and the large number of promises - reflects the need for a newcomer to establish his credibility.LiNeBrEaK"Obama was relatively unknown at the national level," said Martha Joynt Kumar, a professor of political science at Towson University, "so he had to have a greater degree of specificity about what his plans were. You've got to let people know who you are."LiNeBrEaKAlthough at times ridiculed by opponents as little more than a gifted speaker who emphasized abstract platitudes like "change," Obama and his policy team laid out an extremely detailed agenda for America. He was well-known for his pledge to end the war in Iraq, but his position paper on the issue details eight other promises, including a specific pledge to provide at least $2-billion to assist Iraqi refugees. Likewise, his broad health care plan includes a pledge to name a coordinator to oversee all federal efforts to combat autism.LiNeBrEaKSome promises are wrapped in nearly indecipherable jargon. "Institutionalize the Proliferation Security Initiative (PSI)." (It's actually a global security program launched in 2003 to stop the buying and selling of weapons of mass destruction.)LiNeBrEaKOthers are just plain obscure: "Fight to protect roadless areas on Forest Service lands from all new road construction" and to implement "cooperative projects to remove brush, small trees and other overgrown vegetation that serve as fuel for wildfires."LiNeBrEaKKumar and other political scientists said Obama's presidency should not be judged solely on the success of his campaign promises.LiNeBrEaKThey noted some promises are more weighty than others. And circumstances change.LiNeBrEaK"In some senses, the world has changed a lot," said Bob Williams of the Tax Policy Center. "When a lot of those promises were made, we were in a different situation than we are now. It would be wrong to go blindly forward without re-evaluating."LiNeBrEaKNevertheless, Obama's campaign promises form a road map for his presidency. Obama's supporters will certainly expect him to keep many promises, while his opponents try to maintain the status quo.LiNeBrEaKGary Kalman, the legislative director for the nonpartisan U.S. Public Interest Research Group, is monitoring Obama's initiatives on health care, energy and education. He said he expects Obama's economic recovery package to include several goals Obama outlined during the campaign, such as funding for electronic health records and green energy.LiNeBrEaK"Campaign promises matter, not only in the context in which they were made," Kalman said, "but also looking at the events we're currently facing."LiNeBrEaKGalston, the former adviser to Clinton, agreed.LiNeBrEaK"Campaign promises don't just drop into a void," Galston said. "They represent transactions with people. They represent promissory notes that people accept at face value and expect to redeem at some point, maybe not right away."LiNeBrEaKIn other words, he said, "You'd better not say it if you don't mean it."LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKPROMISE KEPTLiNeBrEaKNo. 503: Appoint at least one Republican to the Cabinet.On Dec. 19, President-elect Obama nominated Ray LaHood, a former GOP congressman from Illinois, to serve as his secretary of transportation.LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKIN THE WORKSLiNeBrEaKNo. 502: Get his daughters a puppy.The Obama family has narrowed the choice to two: labradoodle or Portuguese water hound.LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKNO ACTIONLiNeBrEaKNo. 468: Require hybrid fleet at the White House.It's too early to evaluate progress.LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKPROMISE KEPTLiNeBrEaKNo. 13: Require taxpayers to report more detail on capital gains taxes. Congress passed this as part of emergency economic legislation in October. The rule is expected to deter underreporting of capital gains taxes.LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKIN THE WORKSLiNeBrEaKNo. 405:Create White House performance team and chief performance officer. Obama named Nancy Killefer as the nation's first chief performance officer on Jan. 7, but the performance team has yet to be named.LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKPROMISE KEPTLiNeBrEaKNo. 32: Create a tax credit of $500 for workers. Obama said the credit would be part of the economic stimulus package that he wants passed as soon as possible. Congress has yet to act, though.LiNeBrEaKOBAMETERLiNeBrEaKIN THE WORKSLiNeBrEaK"I want you to hold our government accountable. I want you to hold me accountable." Barack Obama on Sept. 9, 2008		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); PUBLIC POLICY (89%); US PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); POLITICS (78%); INTERVIEWS (78%); TAXES and TAXATION (76%); WOMEN (76%); PERSONAL FINANCE (75%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (75%); LOW COST HOUSING SCHEMES (74%); US PRESIDENTS (89%); IRAQ WAR (72%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (72%); FOREIGN POLICY (72%); TAX DEDUCTIONS (70%); WEB SITES (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (69%); URBAN DEVELOPMENT (50%); ECONOMIC NEWS (50%); LOW INCOME PERSONS (74%)  		BROOKINGS INSTITUTION (55%)  	BARACK OBAMA (95%); BILL CLINTON (92%); GEORGE W BUSH (58%); HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (55%)  	UNITED STATES (93%); IRAQ (79%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  	LiNeBrEaKPHOTO (3)  		Newspaper  	2009 Times Publishing Company All Rights Reserved  	ROBERT FARLEY, ANGIE DROBNIC HOLAN, PolitiFact.com Staff Writers  															
USA TODAY 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   FIRST EDITION	Proposal to cut greenhouse gases set for release  	MONEY; Pg. 8A  	356 words  	A coalition of leading corporations and environmental groups plans to call today for aggressive reductions in U.S. greenhouse gas emissions, an initiative that eventually would raise electricity and gasoline prices. LiNeBrEaKThe group -- which includes General Electric, ConocoPhillips, DuPont, Duke Energy and the Natural Resources Defense Council -- will urge Congress to pass a law requiring emissions to be cut 80% by 2050, two people with direct knowledge of the plan say. They declined to be identified because the proposal won't be made public until today.LiNeBrEaKThe cuts are in line with targets advocated by President-elect Barack Obama.LiNeBrEaKWhen it formed two years ago, the U.S. Climate Action Partnership, which includes some of the USA's top industrial polluters, called for emissions reductions of 60% to 80% by 2050. The coalition today will lay out a far more detailed blueprint, seeking a 42% cut in emissions by 2030.LiNeBrEaKThe proposal comes despite the recession, which could make it difficult to pass costly climate-change legislation this year. But Kyle Danish, a partner in law and policy firm Van Ness Feldman, notes that caps on emissions likely would not begin for several years, after the economy recovers. Meanwhile, he says, businesses want to put their imprint on legislation that's likely to be passed by 2010.LiNeBrEaK"They want to get in the game,"  Danish says.LiNeBrEaKUnder the group's proposed cap-and-trade system, utilities, oil companies and other manufacturers would have to acquire an allowance for every ton of greenhouse gases, primarily carbon dioxide, that they emit. New power plants would have to buy their permits, while existing ones initially would get much of their allowances free.LiNeBrEaKOver time, the cap would grow more stringent and allowances prices would rise, forcing utilities, for instance, to replace coal plants with wind farms.  The costs are likely to be passed to consumers in higher electric bills or gasoline prices, for example.LiNeBrEaKThe proposal recommends a $10-a-ton minimum for a permit. To prevent CO{-2} permit prices from soaring, it calls for a store of credits to be generated by preserving forests; trees absorb CO{-2}. 		EMISSIONS (91%); LEGISLATION (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); CHEMICALS (89%); GASOLINE PRICES (89%); OIL and GAS PRICES (89%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (89%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (78%); POWER PLANTS (78%); FORESTS and WOODLANDS (78%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); WIND ENERGY (78%); PRICE INCREASES (78%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (78%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (77%); ECONOMIC RECOVERY (77%); GASOLINE MARKETS (77%); RECESSION (76%); ECONOMIC NEWS (76%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (73%); WIND POWER PLANTS (64%); COAL INDUSTRY (63%)  	CONOCOPHILLIPS (84%); DUKE ENERGY CORP (58%); GENERAL ELECTRIC CO (58%); VAN NESS FELDMAN PC (55%)  	NATURAL RESOURCES DEFENSE COUNCIL (58%)  	BARACK OBAMA (57%)  	UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			NEWSPAPER  	2009 Gannett Company, Inc. All Rights Reserved  	Paul Davidson  		COP (NYSE) (84%); DUK (NYSE) (58%); GNE (PAR) (58%); GEC (LSE) (58%); GEB (BRU) (58%); GE (NYSE) (58%)  	SIC4911 ELECTRIC SERVICES (58%); NAICS336412 AIRCRAFT ENGINE and ENGINE PARTS MANUFACTURING (58%); NAICS335222 HOUSEHOLD REFRIGERATOR and HOME FREEZER MANUFACTURING (58%); NAICS335211 ELECTRIC HOUSEWARES and HOUSEHOLD FAN MANUFACTURING (58%)  												
