The Washington Post 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   Suburban Edition	Economic Recovery A Priority For Kaine;  Governor Pushes For Green Jobs as Legislature Opens 	METRO; Pg. B01  	941 words  	Gov. Timothy M. Kaine told the General Assembly on Wednesday that he will use his final year in office to cultivate a major expansion in environmentally oriented jobs and try to work through partisan barriers to steer Virginia through severe financial turbulence.LiNeBrEaKDelivering his  State of the Commonwealth Address on the opening day of the 2009 legislative session, Kaine (D) said he has worked hard over the past three years to make the state a better place to start a business, buy a home and raise a child. LiNeBrEaKBut Kaine told lawmakers that navigating "a time of national economic distress" will represent one of the biggest challenges of their political careers.LiNeBrEaK"I don't have to tell you we are serving in one of the most difficult times in our nation's recent history," Kaine said. "But we must be mindful that our pressures are no greater than those that our citizens are facing every day. . . . It is my hope that the size of the challenge . . . will inspire our best efforts to cooperate in finding the best solutions."LiNeBrEaKHours before Kaine delivered his address in the House chamber, Senate Majority Leader Richard L. Saslaw (D-Fairfax) outlined the magnitude of the fiscal turmoil that awaits legislators.LiNeBrEaKSaslaw said he thinks lawmakers will have to close a two-year shortfall of at least $4 billion -- earlier estimates had placed the gap at $2. 9 billion. If confirmed when the administration recalculates revenues this month, legislators will have 45 days to find $1 billion in cuts beyond those proposed by Kaine in December.LiNeBrEaKEfforts to balance the budget will probably be complicated by squabbling between the House, which is controlled by Republicans, and the Senate, which the Democrats control.LiNeBrEaKKaine, the new chairman of the Democratic National Committee, sought to rise above the partisanship by focusing his speech on how he plans to navigate the state through the recession.LiNeBrEaKHe vowed to speed up construction of previously approved state projects and said he is working with President-elect Barack Obama to make sure Virginia gets its fair share of the economic stimulus package pending before Congress.LiNeBrEaKKaine is also proposing a big effort to lure to the state companies that focus on the manufacture or sale of environmentally friendly products. Beside helping to slow climate change, Kaine said, the state could add thousands of "green jobs."LiNeBrEaK"The development of new energy sources presents dramatic new opportunities for the commonwealth," Kaine said during his 42-minute speech.LiNeBrEaKIn the GOP response to Kaine's address, Del. David B. Albo (Fairfax) indicated that his party is willing to work with the governor on environmental initiatives.LiNeBrEaKHouse and Senate Republicans want to set aside more than 25,000 acres of state land for renewable energy and work with the tobacco commission to allocate $100 million for the research and development of alternative energy sources. The commission oversees Virginia's share of the 1997 tobacco settlement.LiNeBrEaK"When it comes to energy, Republicans want to work with Democrats to keep the cost of heating oil, gasoline and electricity down," Albo said.LiNeBrEaKMore contentious will be Kaine's proposal for a 30-cent increase in the tobacco tax, which has generated opposition from Republican leaders. Legislators will also debate election law changes, the prospect of drilling off the coastline, driver safety initiatives and regulation of companies that offer vehicle title loans.LiNeBrEaKAnd they will consider a handful of perennial hot-button issues, including a ban on smoking in restaurants and bars and a requirement that gun sellers conduct background checks on people who buy firearms at gun shows.LiNeBrEaKKaine gave no indication Wednesday that he plans to push for a new transportation funding plan after failing last year to forge a compromise on a proposal to raise money for new roads. That means he will probably leave office without fulfilling a key promise from his 2005 campaign.LiNeBrEaKDespite calls for bipartisanship, the day began with a fierce showdown between House Republicans and Democrats that has left Alexandria residents without representation in the House.LiNeBrEaKWith Democrat Charniele Herring clinging to a 16-vote lead over her GOP opponent in Tuesday's special election to replace former delegate Brian Moran, the GOP majority voted to block her from being seated pending a recount.LiNeBrEaK"It's a bad start," Del. Robert H. Brink (D-Arlington) said.LiNeBrEaKLater in the day, House Republicans attempted to scuttle Democrats' plans to attend Monday's Virginia Inaugural Ball, which is a fundraiser for the state party. Republicans say Kaine and Democratic lawmakers are skirting the prohibition against raising money during the session by attending.LiNeBrEaKThe tension will probably continue as lawmakers gear up for another campaign season that will generate national attention.LiNeBrEaKWith the first contested Democratic primary for governor in two decades, lawmakers in that party are being forced to choose sides in the nomination fight among Moran, Terry McAuliffe and Sen. R. Creigh Deeds (Bath). Although recent legislative sessions have been marred by Republican infighting, the Democrats were the ones divided this year over who should succeed Moran as chairman of the House Democratic caucus.LiNeBrEaKAfter deadlocking in three consecutive ballots, House Democrats chose Del. Kenneth R. Plum (Fairfax) over Del. Kristen J. Amundson (Fairfax) as caucus chairman.LiNeBrEaKThe winner of the June Democratic gubernatorial primary will take on Attorney General Robert F. McDonnell (R) in the general election. Democrats will also be looking to pick up the six seats needed to gain control of the House.LiNeBrEaKStaff writer Fredrick Kunkle contributed to this report.		LEGISLATIVE BODIES (91%); GOVERNORS (90%); LEGISLATORS (90%); ECONOMIC RECOVERY (90%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (89%); POLITICAL PARTIES (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); GOVERNMENT BUDGETS (78%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (78%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (78%); ENTREPRENEURSHIP (77%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (76%); BUDGET (72%); CLIMATE CHANGE (67%); EXECUTIVE MOVES (65%); RESEARCH and DEVELOPMENT (65%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (60%)  	DEMOCRATIC NATIONAL COMMITTEE (53%)  		TIM KAINE (94%); BARACK OBAMA (52%)  	RICHMOND, VA, USA (79%) VIRGINIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  	IMAGE; By Bob Brown -- Richmond Times-dispatch Via Associated Press; Virginia Gov. Timothy M. Kaine waits for technicians to adjust equipment before a run-through of the speech he gave at the opening of the General Assembly. In the address, Kaine shared his priorities for the last year of his term.  		Newspaper  	2009 The Washington Post All Rights Reserved  	Tim Craig and Anita Kumar; Washington Post Staff Writers  	RICHMOND, Jan. 14  									Maryland  					
The Washington Post 	January 15, 2009 Thursday   Suburban Edition	Nominee Signals Big Changes For EPA;  Confirmation Hearing Held 	FOREIGN; Pg. A08  	730 words  	At the outset of Lisa P. Jackson's confirmation hearing yesterday to be Environmental Protection Agency administrator, Sen. John Barrasso (R-Wyo.) said many of his constituents fear that the incoming Obama administration will use existing laws to enact broad environmental rules.LiNeBrEaK"All fear for their economic future in today's political environment," he told Jackson and Nancy Helen Sutley, who is in line to chair the White House Council on Environmental Quality. "Ranchers and miners know that addressing climate change through the Clean Air Act is a disaster waiting to happen. That's something Congress never intended." LiNeBrEaKIn her response a couple of hours later, Jackson agreed she would consider applying existing laws to issues that were not on the agenda 30 years ago when Congress passed them. The laws, she told Barrasso, "were meant to address not only the issues of today, but the issues of tomorrow."LiNeBrEaKThe 4  1/2  -hour hearing before the Senate Environment and Public Works Committee underscored the dramatic shifts that could occur at the EPA and CEQ if Jackson and Sutley, as expected, are confirmed. While Jackson shied away from specifying what steps she would take upon beginning the job, the former head of New Jersey's Department of Environmental Protection said she would consider regulating coal ash waste from power plants in the aftermath of recent spills and take a more active approach toward other environmental concerns.LiNeBrEaK"Science must be the backbone of what EPA does," she said, adding that she aims to serve Americans who have suffered from "environmental negligence" such as the effects from untended Superfund sites or the government's botched response to Hurricane Katrina. "They are my conscience."LiNeBrEaKSen. Barbara Boxer (D-Calif.), who chairs the panel, pressed Jackson on whether she would back measures to start regulating carbon dioxide, such as a finding that  CO2 emissions endanger public health and welfare and a waiver allowing California and other states to impose their own regulations on greenhouse gas emissions from automobiles. Boxer's staff even prepared a "Report on the Tools Available Under the Clean Air Act to Immediately Reduce Global Warming Pollution" outlining how Jackson could do so.LiNeBrEaKIt would take time to finalize either of these measures, both of which outgoing EPA Administrator Stephen L. Johnson rejected, because the agency would have to conduct a rule-making process on each. But David Doniger, policy director for the Natural Resources Defense Council's climate center, said that both could be concluded within months, and that the private sector would feel the impact immediately.LiNeBrEaKBoxer told Jackson she might end up angering senators such as Barrasso, but that just meant she was tackling a pressing issue. "You're not going to make everybody happy," Boxer said. "That's for sure, because if you do, that means you're doing nothing."LiNeBrEaKThat sort of activism, however, alarms business leaders such as U.S. Chamber of Commerce President Thomas J. Donohue, who told reporters last week that his group wants Congress to take the lead on climate regulation.LiNeBrEaK"We're better off with the Congress making those decisions rather than the independent regulators who have just arrived in town on a white horse and want to do good things," he said.LiNeBrEaKBut Frank O'Donnell, who heads the advocacy group Clean Air Watch, said he is optimistic that "an Obama administration will send a signal that it intends to use every power available to make progress on this critical issue until -- and even beyond when -- Congress takes action."LiNeBrEaKThe waiver allowing California's tailpipe emissions law to go forward would affect half the U.S. auto market, Doniger said, adding that while a rule-making may take two to three months, "in political form, it's done the day it's announced."LiNeBrEaKJeffrey Holmstead, who heads the environmental strategy section at the Bracewell and Giuliani law firm and is a former assistant EPA administrator for air and radiation, said making a finding that  CO2 endangers public health could take a year or longer to finalize.LiNeBrEaKEven more daunting, he said, is the question of how EPA will apply a provision of the Clean Air Act that labels any emitter of 250 tons of a pollutant a year as a "major source" of pollution. When you apply that standard to carbon dioxide, he said, "any building in downtown Washington could be a major source."		ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (92%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (91%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (91%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (90%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); EMISSIONS (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (89%); SUPERFUND (78%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (78%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); ADMINISTRATIVE PROCEDURE (78%); AGENCY RULEMAKING (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (78%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (77%); ENERGY REGULATION (77%); HURRICANE KATRINA (75%); HURRICANES (73%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (72%); GLOBAL WARMING (70%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (70%); HAZARDOUS WASTE (66%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (65%); POWER PLANTS (65%); INFRASTRUCTURE (54%)  		US ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (84%); COUNCIL ON ENVIRONMENTAL QUALITY (57%)  	LISA P JACKSON (94%); BARACK OBAMA (58%); BARBARA BOXER (53%)  	CALIFORNIA, USA (92%); WYOMING, USA (92%); NEW JERSEY, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 23, 2009  	ENGLISH  	IMAGE; By Lauren Victoria Burke -- Associated Press; Lisa P. Jackson, flanked by Sen. Robert Menendez and Nancy Helen Sutley, attends her confirmation hearing.  		Newspaper  	2009 The Washington Post All Rights Reserved  	Juliet Eilperin; Washington Post Staff Writer  										Maryland  					
