Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News 	January 15, 2009 Thursday 	Whales' migrations evoke curiosity  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	919 words  	Jan. 15--Climate change is a real consequence facing the planet, and its affects now are beginning to manifest on a more local scale with the migration patterns of various whale species, many which are seen off the coast of Point Vicente in Rancho Palos Verdes.LiNeBrEaKIn fact, studies show that the Pacific gray whale's southbound migration to its Baja California winter breeding and calving grounds has become more lengthy, according to Michele Sousa, the Aquarium of the Pacific's senior marine mammal biologist. LiNeBrEaK"What we're seeing is that a lot of the animals are having to go further north to get their food ... [and they] go up further because it's not in their normal places," Sousa said. "Then, when they make the trip back, that's why we think we're seeing some increases in births en route, instead of waiting to get to Baja."LiNeBrEaKObservations also indicate slight abnormalities in the migratory patterns of the fin whale -- the second largest mammal on Earth, next to the blue whale.LiNeBrEaKDan Salas, an RPV resident and captain of Harbor Breeze Cruises, said he started spotting the fin whales in July 2008, and they've been in local waters ever since.LiNeBrEaK"They're just making themselves at home ... It's kind of unusual to have fin whales feeding this time of year right off our coast," he said. "Something has definitely changed here with the ocean current and the climate for these whales to stay so late ... For some reason, there's quite a bit of food here."LiNeBrEaKFin whales are similar to the blue variety in that they're a "cosmopolitan" species found in all oceans. The 50- to 70-ton animals usually remain off the coast through early September, but Salas said there have been about 15 to 18 whales "actively" feeding on krill, a shrimp-like plankton, spread out in a 20-mile area from Long Beach to Santa Monica Bay.LiNeBrEaKAs of Wednesday morning, census takers from the Los Angeles chapter of the American Cetacean Society stationed at the Point Vicente Interpretive Center in RPV counted 138 gray whales and 10 calves heading south since Dec. 1. The previous day, the group reported seeing fin whales, and one pair came within a mile of the shoreline. Blue whales were last seen off of Point Vicente on Dec. 16 and humpbacks haven't made an appearance since Dec. 28.LiNeBrEaKWhile viewing the massive sea creatures from afar on land may be exhilarating, a newly formed joint venture allows those curious about cetaceans to view them up close.LiNeBrEaKHarbor Breeze Cruises, in partnership with the Aquarium of the Pacific, now offers the public an "educational whale adventure" that includes a whale-watching trip on "The Christopher," Salas' high-speed catamaran built specifically for chasing ocean life, plus a visit to the aquarium.LiNeBrEaKOn these journeys -- available seven days a week -- the aquarium's experts stress the importance of what people can do to keep the marine mammals' habitat clean.LiNeBrEaK"A lot of people don't realize we have this diversity right off of our coast, and what they do on land affects all of these animals," said Alicia Archer, the aquarium's biologist and boat program coordinator. "A lot of our trash [flows from] the storm drains directly into the ocean. Now, these animals are filter feeders. You can imagine that what goes in the ocean also can get stuck in their baleen, [furry plates on either side of their mouth that trap the food source, while allowing water to leave]."LiNeBrEaKIt's about respect, Archer and Salas both said -- not only for the ocean, but also for the cetaceans, such as fin whales, that are listed as endangered under the Endangered Species Act and protected by the Marine Mammal Protection Act.LiNeBrEaK"We're just out here to enjoy them. A lot of the whales know -- I mean, these whales are so smart," Salas said. "They actually know we're here. Sometimes they'll come out and check us out, see how we're doing ... I think they're more intelligent than humans. Could be, huh?"LiNeBrEaKACS-LA volunteers Cynthia Woo and Palos Verdes resident Natalie Massie, who belong to the same group of census takers conducting daily counts at the PVIC, last Thursday, Jan. 8, boarded "The Christopher," applying their expertise to help spot the whales on a special voyage. That day, about seven to eight miles off the coast of Long Beach, the group encountered three playful fin whales who came within close range of the 75-foot boat.LiNeBrEaKSightings of these giants of the deep sea strike a winsome sense of awe in even the most seasoned of whale watchers.LiNeBrEaK"They're spectacular -- they're huge," Woo said.LiNeBrEaK"The biggest excitement I get now is being able to take people out who don't get to see these animals. I still get excited when I see them," added Salas, who has more than 20 years of boating experience.LiNeBrEaKTo keep track of the whale migrations, stop by the Interpretive Center, 31501 Palos Verdes Drive West in RPV, or log onto the local ACS branch's Web site at www.acs-la.org. For more information about the Aquarium of the Pacific-Harbor Breeze Cruises' daily whale excursions, call (562) 590-3100 or visit www.aquariumofpacific.org.LiNeBrEaKTo comment on this story, go to www.pvnews.com.LiNeBrEaKaratcliff@pvnews.com		MARINE MAMMALS (97%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); MAMMALS (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (89%); COASTAL AREAS (89%); ZOOS and AQUARIUMS (89%); BIOLOGY (77%); CENSUS (64%); OCEANS (64%)  				LOS ANGELES, CA, USA (77%) EARTH (79%); CALIFORNIA, USA (77%) UNITED STATES (77%)  	January 16, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Ashley Ratcliff, Palos Verdes Peninsula News, Calif.  			General  		20090115-VT-Whales-migrations-evoke-curiosity-0115  	VT  									
Albuquerque Journal (New Mexico)  	January 14, 2009 Wednesday 	Chu May Push Labs To Evolve: Panel Questions DOE Nominee  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	642 words  	Jan. 14--WASHINGTON -- Steven Chu, a Nobel laureate physicist and national laboratory director chosen by Presidentelect Barack Obama to lead the Department of Energy, told Congress on Tuesday that he would combat climate change and aggressively promote clean energy and conservation if confirmed for the Cabinet post.LiNeBrEaKChu, director of the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory in California since 2004, also endorsed nuclear power and said coal can remain a key energy source, provided that new science mitigates its negative effect on the environment. Chu had previously described coal use as an envir on ment a l "nightmare," p r o mp t i n g s o m e wor -- ried questions from senators who represent coal-producing states. LiNeBrEaKDespite those concerns, Chu, 60, received near-unanimous praise from members of the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee.LiNeBrEaKSen. Jeff Bingaman of New Mexico, Democratic chairman of the committee, said he expects Chu to win confirmation. The panel could move the nomination to the full Senate later this week, Bingaman said.LiNeBrEaKBingaman said the nominee's experience as a national laboratory director is a good sign for Los Alamos and Sandia national laboratories, with more than 20,000 employees in New Mexico.LiNeBrEaK"Obviously he's very familiar with our national laboratories ... and he knows the lab directors and the issues that the labs contend with," Bingaman said in an interview after the hearing.LiNeBrEaKChu told senators he would push the national laboratories -- with Los Alamos and some of the others focused on nuclear weapons -- to evolve their missions. "I have challenged some of the best scientists at Berkeley lab to turn their attention to the energy and climate change problem," Chu said. "I want to extend this approach to an even greater extent throughout the department's network of national laboratories."LiNeBrEaKThe hearing contained almost no discussion of weapons budgets at the labs. The Carnegie Endowment for International Peace issued a report this week that said at least 67 percent of DOE's budget goes to nuclear weapons and weapons-related programs.LiNeBrEaKDanielle Brian, executive director of the Project on Government Oversight, said that spending should have been examined at the hearing.LiNeBrEaK"How can the Senate confirm Dr. Chu without having heard a single thing about how he plans to run the vast majority of the Department of Energy?" Brian asked in a statement. "This is a case where the Senate has left some pretty important questions unanswered."LiNeBrEaKMeanwhile, Chu told senators that although he would push for more use of renewable energy, such as wind and solar power, simply using less energy makes more sense in the short-term.LiNeBrEaK"More efficient use of energy in the United States is the one big factor that can (quickly) reduce our dependence on foreign oil," Chu said.LiNeBrEaKHe also said climate change, which some key Republicans in Congress believe isn't caused by humans, threatens world security if carbon dioxide emissions aren't curbed.LiNeBrEaK"It is now clear that if we continue on our current path, we run the risk of dramatic disruptive changes to our climate system in the lifetimes of our children and grandchildren," Chu said.LiNeBrEaKHe said science eventually will provide a way to help capture and contain carbon dioxide emissions from burning coal, a leading energy source in the U.S.LiNeBrEaK"Coal resources in the U.S. are immense, and I'm optimistic we can begin to use those resources in a clean way," Chu said.		NOBEL PRIZES (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); AWARDS and PRIZES (90%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (89%); SOLAR ENERGY (89%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); SCIENCE NEWS (78%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (78%)