Anchorage Daily News (Alaska)  	January 14, 2009 Wednesday 	EDITORIAL: Alaska should prepare for this important shift in national policy: A change is coming  	COMMENTARY  	628 words  	Jan. 14--Monday, the Anchorage Chamber of Commerce got a briefing that might be listed under the heading of "What a difference an election makes." Local attorney Heather Grahame told the business group's weekly luncheon that the new Congress and the new president will push major new laws to reduce greenhouse gas pollution. She urged Alaska businesses to think about getting ready for the coming change.LiNeBrEaKThere is "extraordinary political momentum" for action on greenhouse gases, said Grahame, who specializes in energy legislation at the law firm Dorsey and Whitney. LiNeBrEaK"Obama promised to make us a worldwide leader on climate change," she noted, and he is appointing people who will make good on that promise. In Congress, key committee positions are now held by members who are eager to move greenhouse gas legislation.LiNeBrEaKFixing the economy is still the top priority in Washington D.C., but climate change is right behind on the "to-do" list.LiNeBrEaKThe days of "inaction by the federal government" on global warming are over, according to Grahame.LiNeBrEaKAnd isn't that a welcome change?LiNeBrEaKAt last, the nation has a leader who realizes what's at stake. No longer will the president deny what the best available science shows -- that man-made greenhouse gases are pushing the earth toward a potentially catastrophic tipping point with climate change.LiNeBrEaKGrahame said there will be plenty of debate about exactly how best to control greenhouse gases. Old style command-and-control regulation -- the government sets limits on the pollution and then tries to enforces those limits with fines -- has fallen out of favor. Market-based approaches are getting more attention.LiNeBrEaKOne market-based option is a tax on greenhouse gas emissions -- charging industries (or maybe even consumers) for the right to pollute. The less you pollute, the lower the taxes.LiNeBrEaKAnother market approach is called cap-and-trade. Government sets an overall limit on greenhouse gas pollution and gives (or sells) pollution "allowances" to various industries or businesses. An industry that can easily reduce greenhouse gas pollution will have allowances it doesn't need. Those extra allowances can be traded or sold to businesses that have a harder time reduces greenhouse gases. Over time, the cap can be lowered to ensure pollution levels actually go down.LiNeBrEaKIt will be a challenge to get a market-based pollution control system right. Set a carbon tax too high, and you hurt the economy, which is already in a world of hurt. Set it too low, and you don't cut pollution enough.LiNeBrEaKThe same is true for cap-and-trade. Choosing where to set the cap will be controversial. So will deciding how to allocate pollution rights among businesses, industries and consumers.LiNeBrEaKReducing greenhouse gases requires complicated choices, without knowing exactly how well the rules and market incentives will pay off. But success is possible, as Grahame pointed out to the chamber of commerce audience. Cap and trade controls placed on sulfur dioxide years ago have efficiently and effectively cut emissions and helped control acid rain, an environmental scourge of the 1970s and '80s.LiNeBrEaKThe country won't see similar progress on greenhouse gas pollution overnight -- but at least the hard work in Washington, D.C., is finally getting underway.LiNeBrEaKBOTTOM LINE: On global warming, the recent election made a big difference -- and that's a good thing.		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (91%); PUBLIC POLICY (90%); EMISSIONS (90%); LEGISLATION (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); LAWYERS (90%); EMISSIONS CREDITS (89%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (77%); MAJOR US LAW FIRMS (77%); ENERGY REGULATION (76%); TAXES and TAXATION (76%); GLOBAL WARMING (71%); BUSINESS and PROFESSIONAL ASSOCIATIONS (89%)  	DORSEY a