The Boston Globe 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   THIRD EDITION	Clinton says she would embrace climate, arms treaties Lays out vision to revitalize US leadership  	NATIONAL; Pg. A9  	998 words  	A NEW PRESIDENTLiNeBrEaKWASHINGTON - Senator Hillary Clinton pledged yesterday that as secretary of state she would revitalize US leadership by embracing a host of treaties on arms control and climate change that the Bush administration has been reluctant to endorse.LiNeBrEaKIn five hours of testimony before the Senate Foreign Relations Committee, she said she would revive attempts to ratify or renegotiate several international accords, including the Comprehensive Test Ban Treaty, which bans nuclear weapons testing; the Fissile Material Cutoff Treaty, which stops the production of fuel for nuclear weapons; and the START agreement between the United States and Russia, which expires in December. The treaty reduces stockpiles of nuclear weapons and their delivery systems. LiNeBrEaKIn addition, Clinton said during her confirmation hearing that President-elect Barack Obama would appoint a negotiator to international efforts to halt global climate change.LiNeBrEaK"The best way to advance America's interests in reducing global threats and seizing global opportunities is to design and implement global solutions," Clinton said in her opening remarks. "That isn't a philosophical point. This is our reality." LiNeBrEaKHer statements marked a drastic departure from the Bush administration's broad skepticism toward treaties, and were greeted enthusiastically by Democrats and many Republicans on the committee, as well as by specialists on arms control and the environment.LiNeBrEaK"The Obama administration recognizes that to deal with international challenges like nuclear proliferation and nuclear weapons, we need greater cooperation," said Daryl Kimball of the Arms Control Association, a Washington-based nonproliferation think tank. "If we are going to improve the global system, the United States is going to have to lead by example, and these three initiatives have been something that other countries expect the United states to take action on."LiNeBrEaKHowever, some conservatives have already begun to campaign against the treaties, which need a two-thirds majority in the Senate to pass, saying that they bring the United States closer to world government and unwisely tie US hands.LiNeBrEaK"More senators should be educated about the sovereignty implications of these treaties," said Steven Groves of the conservative Heritage Foundation, although he acknowledged that "it could still be a tough fight to block them."LiNeBrEaKMassachusetts Democrat John Kerry, who made his debut yesterday as chair of the committee - a position recently relinquished by Vice President-elect Joe Biden - warmly welcomed Clinton's pledges to take climate change seriously and made his own impassioned plea for US participation in international efforts.LiNeBrEaK"Many today do not see climate change as a national security threat, but it is," Kerry said in his opening remarks.LiNeBrEaKThroughout the hearing, Clinton commented with confidence on a wide range of foreign policy questions - from meat-and-potatoes issues, like Iraq, to arcane topics, like the need to map the continental shelf.LiNeBrEaKOn Iran, Clinton declined to say whether she would soon meet with Iranian officials, but said the new administration would use both sanctions and diplomacy to dissuade Tehran from continuing uranium enrichment.LiNeBrEaK"We are not taking any option off the table at all, but we will pursue a new, perhaps different approach that will become a cornerstone of what the Obama administration believes is an attitude toward engagement that might bear fruit," she said.LiNeBrEaKOn the Israel-Palestinian crisis, she pledged stepped-up US engagement in building the capacity of a Palestinian government, saying "We cannot give up on peace."LiNeBrEaKStill, the issue of foreign donations to a foundation run by her husband, former president Bill Clinton, came up several times in the hearing as members implored her to take additional measures to ensure there was no appearance of a conflict of interest.LiNeBrEaK"The bottom line is that even well-intentioned foreign donations carry risk for US foreign policy," Richard Lugar, the ranking Republican from Indiana, told her, adding that the foundation was a "temptation" for foreign governments who might see it as a way to curry favor.LiNeBrEaKLugar applauded both Clinton's credentials and her foreign policy vision, and pledged to support her nomination, but called on the Clintons to either decline new foreign donations or at the very least make them public as soon as possible. Senator Clinton has agreed to allow vetting of donations to the foundation by foreign governments - not individuals - through the State Department ethics office and to make all donations public once a year.LiNeBrEaKSenator David Vitter, a Louisiana Republican, and Senator Bob Corker, a Tennessee Republican, also urged her to ask her husband to curtail acceptance of foreign donations. Corker said that the Clinton Foundation, which operates a number of global anti-poverty and HIV efforts, is a "speck" compared with the "huge magnitude of efforts" that Clinton herself can now enact on behalf of the US government.LiNeBrEaKClinton made no promises to amend the agreement that she struck with the committee, saying that she is already going beyond what ethics rules requires, and that the foundation pays for lifesaving drugs for 1. 4 million people in the developing world.LiNeBrEaK"My husband doesn't take a salary. He has no financial interest in any of this," she said, expressing pride in the foundation's work. "I don't take a salary. I don't have any financial interest."LiNeBrEaKThe Associated Press reported yesterday that Senator Clinton intervened at least six times on issues affecting companies or individuals that later contributed to her husband's foundation. For example, the AP said she had written to the Federal Communications Commission in 2004, expressing concern that changes to competitive local exchange carrier access rates could hurt carriers such as New York-based PAETEC Communications. PAETEC's chief executive is Arunas Chesonis, whose family and charity later contributed to the Clinton Foundation, the report said.		ARMS CONTROL and DISARMAMENT (94%); MILITARY WEAPONS (94%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (93%); NUCLEAR WEAPONS (91%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); FOREIGN RELATIONS (89%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (89%); FOREIGN POLICY (89%); POLITICAL PARTIES (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); TALKS and MEETINGS (78%); COMPREHENSIVE TEST BAN TREATY (76%); NATIONAL SECURITY (73%); TESTIMONY (73%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (72%); US PRESIDENTS (90%)  			HILLARY RODHAM CLINTON (94%); BARACK OBAMA (91%); JOHN KERRY (52%); JOE BIDEN (51%)  	MASSACHUSETTS, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (97%); IRAN (79%); IRAQ (79%); RUSSIA (72%)  	January 14, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Vow of global engagementSenator Hillary Clinton testified yesterday that as secretary of state she would embrace arms and climate treaties that the Bush administration has been reluctant to endorse. A9.Alex Wong/Getty Images (PHOTO RAN ON PAGE A1.) Hillary Clinton, with daughter Chelsea Clinton behind her, gave five hours of testimony during her confirmation hearing.  		Newspaper  	2009 Globe Newspaper Company All Rights Reserved  	Farah Stockman Globe Staff  															
Buffalo News (New York) 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   CENTRAL EDITION	Deep freeze grips WNY;  Record cold temperatures feared in next few days 	NEWS; Pg. A1  	1153 words  	We were buffeted by record-setting, hurricane-force winds.LiNeBrEaKWe were blasted by record-setting snowfall in a couple of blizzardlike snowstorms.LiNeBrEaKNow comes the deep freeze.LiNeBrEaKAn Arctic front moved into Western New York overnight, bringing bone-chilling temperatures -- and the outside chance of a record low -- for the next few days.LiNeBrEaKGlobal warming?LiNeBrEaKNot here. Temperatures won't climb very far out of the single digits until the weekend, and Thursday night's low will hit a numbing minus-5 degrees. LiNeBrEaK"It's been a couple years since we've been this cold," said Joseph Pace, a meteorologist with the National Weather Service at Buffalo Niagara International Airport.LiNeBrEaKTuesday's blustery winds and steady snow are giving way to uncommonly frigid temperatures that will linger here for several days and make Buffalo feel more like Siberia.LiNeBrEaKThe icy temperatures may come close to the record low for Thursday's date -- minus-12 in 1957. And, combined with the wind chill, it will make it utterly unpleasant outside for two- and four-legged creatures.LiNeBrEaKBuffalonians tend to think of themselves as hardy folk who won't let winter weather disrupt our routines.LiNeBrEaKBut with the cold front moving in, experts are offering a range of tips to help people stay safe as they try to warm their homes, commute to work and get their children ready for school.LiNeBrEaK"I would think it's a great thing to be prepared, especially with the subzero temperatures that are being forecast," said Shaun D. Seufert of the AAA of Western and Central New York.LiNeBrEaK* Most calls to AAA at this time of year involve battery and lock-out problems, and the agency is bracing for more of the same the next few days, said Seufert.LiNeBrEaKThe AAA that covers the metro Buffalo, Rochester and Syracuse areas received nearly 16,000 calls for vehicle assistance over one five-day period in late December -- double the typical number, he said.LiNeBrEaK* It's important when the temperatures fall to such dangerous levels to try to be there for neighbors and others who need a little extra help, said Dr. Karthik Puppala, a resident in family medicine at Millard Fillmore Suburban Hospital, Amherst.LiNeBrEaKMany of those admitted to the hospital with weather-related problems -- frostbite, injuries from falls on ice -- were vulnerable because of their age or medical condition or because they lived alone, he said.LiNeBrEaK* Cats and dogs need special attention as well, said Gina Browning, a spokeswoman for the Erie County SPCA.LiNeBrEaK"They can't tell us when they're too cold," Browning said. "We have to be really in tune with our pets and what they're trying to tell us with their behavior."LiNeBrEaK* With the deep freeze coming, hardware stores in the area have noticed some people trying to better prepare their homes for the cold.LiNeBrEaK"I recommend you keep your water on just a little bit, so it's dripping out and it doesn't sit in [the pipes] and freeze," said Frank DiMaria, owner of Mr. Plumber in the Town of Tonawanda.LiNeBrEaKIf your pipes do freeze, DiMaria said, call a professional.LiNeBrEaKAlso, if a plumber does come out to the house to thaw the pipes, make sure he also determines what the problem is so the pipes don't freeze again several hours later.LiNeBrEaK"Don't do it yourself," he said. "A lot of fires happen when there are people trying to thaw out their pipes. They try to use a torch, then you have insulation burning, drywall burning."LiNeBrEaK* With temperatures dropping so severely, area schools will be keeping an eye on the weather.LiNeBrEaKDistricts decide whether to cancel classes early, with superintendents up by about 4 a.m. to get the latest conditions from the National Weather Service, police and highway crews.LiNeBrEaK"We've had 12 days in the last 14 years when we closed for cold," said John Fahey, assistant superintendent for transportation for the Buffalo Public Schools. "The threshold seems to be minus-20 degrees, with the wind chill."LiNeBrEaKIf school is not closed on these frigid days, parents may want to accompany their children to the bus stop or at least make sure they know what to do if the bus doesn't show up, Fahey said.LiNeBrEaKParents also have the option of driving their children, car pooling or keeping them home.LiNeBrEaKAs thousands of children around Erie County go to sleep this week dreaming of a day off from school, the rest of us will have to wait until the weekend for relief from the cold.LiNeBrEaKIt will be cold, but not as cold as it was in parts of the Great Plains and upper Midwest, where temperatures hit lows of minus-40 degrees.LiNeBrEaKAs another Arctic front moves into the area, temperatures Thursday will be bone-chilling, with a high near 5 degrees in the afternoon and winds that could gust to 28 mph.LiNeBrEaKThis region hasn't had a day where the high temperature didn't break 5 degrees since January 1994, meteorologist Jon Hitchcock said.LiNeBrEaKThe low Thursday night will drop to minus-5 degrees at the airport, and it will likely be much colder farther inland.LiNeBrEaKTemperatures should hit the mid-20s Sunday.LiNeBrEaKe-mail: swatson@buffnews.com and jrey@buffnews.comLiNeBrEaK&gt;Tips to get through the deep freezeLiNeBrEaKFor youLiNeBrEaK* Try not to leave any skin exposed to the elements.LiNeBrEaK* Dress in layers. Keep your extremities warm. Wear boots, hats and gloves, though mittens are better.LiNeBrEaK* If you know a family member or neighbor who lives alone and needs extra assistance, check in on them to make sure they have adequate heat and food.LiNeBrEaKFor your childrenLiNeBrEaK* If you are worried about your kids waiting at the bus stop, accompany them, drive them to school, find a car pool or keep them home.LiNeBrEaK* Check children playing outside for frostbite or hypothermia.LiNeBrEaK* For more tips, visit this page at the Buffalo Public Schools Web site: www.buffaloschools.org/news.cfm?story=1369LiNeBrEaKFor your vehicleLiNeBrEaK* Make sure your vehicle's battery is in good condition and keep the terminal connections clean and tight.LiNeBrEaK* To keep your gas line from freezing, keep the tank at least half full. Using dry gas or a fuel system anti-freeze can help, but consult your owner's manual before doing that.LiNeBrEaK* Warm up your car for five or 10 minutes before driving it.LiNeBrEaK* Check your oil, anti-freeze and windshield wiper fluid levels.LiNeBrEaKFor your petLiNeBrEaK* Don't leave your pet outside unsupervised for any length of time.LiNeBrEaK* Because snow can pile up and pets can scamper over fences, make sure your pet is wearing evident identification tags.LiNeBrEaK* Keep foot pads of cats and dogs free of snow and ice.LiNeBrEaK* Give your car a tap, or a kick, before you start it in case a cat climbed under the hood to find warmth.LiNeBrEaKFor your homeLiNeBrEaK* Keep faucets open to a drip so pipes don't freeze.LiNeBrEaK* Don't try to thaw out pipes by yourself -- call a plumber.LiNeBrEaK* Know where the main water shut-off valve is, and how to turn it off should pipes burst.LiNeBrEaK* Be careful using space heaters; inspect cords on electric heaters.LiNeBrEaK* Keep flammable materials away from heating appliances.LiNeBrEaKSources: Buffalo Public Schools; Williamsville Central School District; Mr. Plumber; AAA of Western and Central New York; City of Buffalo; SPCA; National Weather Service; Millard Fillmore Suburban Hospital.		WEATHER (91%); HURRICANES (89%); METEOROLOGY (78%); GLOBAL WARMING (77%); DISEASES and DISORDERS (77%); CHILDREN (69%); FAMILY PRACTICE (64%); CATS (62%); DOGS (60%); AIRPORTS (54%); HARDWARE STORES (50%); COLD INJURIES (73%) WEATHER WINTER TEMPERATURES  				BUFFALO, NY, USA (93%); ROCHESTER, NY, USA (79%) NEW YORK, USA (93%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 14, 2009