The New York Times 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   Late Edition - Final	A Stimulus Plan That Values Learning  	Section A; Column 0; Editorial Desk; LETTERS; Pg. 32  	663 words  	To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Re ''Tax Cuts for Teachers,'' by Thomas L. Friedman (column, Jan. 11):LiNeBrEaK  Mr. Friedman is right. America must invest in its people.LiNeBrEaK  If President-elect Barack Obama hopes for technology and innovation to jump-start our nation's economy, he will have to expand federal financing for scientific research through agencies like the National Science Foundation and the National Institutes of Health.LiNeBrEaK  In particular need of increased federal assistance are fellowships to support graduate studies, like the graduate research fellowship awarded by the N.S.F. The program's alumni have included more than 20 Nobel laureates, as well as a co-founder of Google, Sergey Brin. LiNeBrEaK  As research institutions across the country slash their budgets, the nation's ability to maintain its scientific edge is tied ever more closely to government financing. Federal support is necessary to spur American innovation, train the next generation of American scientists, and combat climate change and disease.LiNeBrEaK  Let's start investing in our people -- it's one investment that is sure to outperform the stock market.LiNeBrEaK  Andrew L. ChangLiNeBrEaK  Stanford, Calif., Jan. 11, 2009LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Thomas L. Friedman's proposal to eliminate federal income taxes for all public schoolteachers is a refreshingly creative and workable idea. It's relatively easy to put into effect, shows teachers that we appreciate them in a tangible way and has broad appeal, including for conservative tax-cutters.LiNeBrEaK   Fred Haag LiNeBrEaK  Burnt Hills, N.Y., Jan. 11, 2009LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Eliminating federal income taxes for public schoolteachers, as Thomas L. Friedman proposes, would do nothing to increase the perceived value of teachers or address their strategic position. LiNeBrEaK  If such a proposal were put into effect with no defined minimum salary, market pressures would give municipalities the opportunity to cut teacher salaries until their take-home pay was the same as before the income taxes were eliminated, with the savings most likely going into reduced local taxes. LiNeBrEaK  The net result would be a further corrupted tax system.  John Hutson LiNeBrEaK  Santa Clara, Calif., Jan. 11, 2009LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Thomas L. Friedman wants to ''double the salaries of all highly qualified math and science teachers'' to encourage more people to become teachers and help make the United States more innovative. LiNeBrEaK  But without highly qualified language arts teachers to teach students to read and comprehend increasingly complex material and how to communicate it clearly to others (and, preferably, in more than just the English language), and without highly qualified social studies teachers to teach students about the global economy and the diverse societies around the world with whom we must interact, knowledge of math, science and technology in and of themselves will not increase American competitiveness. LiNeBrEaK  To accomplish that, the salaries of all teachers should be raised, since all subjects are equally vital in stimulating students' minds.  Susan L. Schwartz LiNeBrEaK  Haverhill, Mass., Jan. 11, 2009LiNeBrEaK  The writer is a public schoolteacher in Methuen, Mass.LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Here is a math problem. Subtract the number of hours that a typical math teacher spends outside of school grading student work, tutoring and preparing for class from those spent by a typical English teacher. LiNeBrEaK  As the wife of an English teacher and a teacher myself, I can tell you that the number of hours that an exemplary English teacher must volunteer of his or her own time in order to teach the essential skills of literacy and writing far exceeds that which we ask other teachers to contribute.LiNeBrEaK  As someone who is not opposed to the idea of merit pay, I would suggest that exemplary math and science teachers be rewarded for their work. But to pay people differently based on their title or perceived value at a given political moment, and not based on their work, effort or skill at teaching, is blatantly unfair.  Lauren Friend LiNeBrEaK  Santa Cruz, Calif., Jan. 11, 2009	http://www.nytimes.com  	SCIENCE NEWS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); PRIMARY and SECONDARY SCHOOL TEACHERS (90%); RESEARCH (90%); LETTERS and COMMENTS (90%); SCIENCE FUNDING (90%); TAX RELIEF (90%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); TAX LAW (90%); TEACHING and TEACHERS (90%); TEACHER COMPENSATION (89%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (89%); HUMANITIES and SOCIAL SCIENCE (89%); INCOME TAX (89%); WAGES and SALARIES (89%); MATH and SCIENCE EDUCATION (78%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (76%); HEALTH DEPARTMENTS (76%); ALUMNI (70%); NOBEL PRIZES (70%); CLIMATE CHANGE (67%); GLOBALIZATION (60%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (59%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (90%); GRADUATE and PROFESSIONAL SCHOOLS (75%)  	GOOGLE INC (58%)  	NATIONAL SCIENCE FOUNDATION (57%); NATIONAL INSTITUTES OF HEALTH (57%)  	THOMAS L FRIEDMAN (96%); BARACK OBAMA (58%); SERGEY BRIN (56%)  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (77%) CALIFORNIA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (95%)  	January 14, 2009  	ENGLISH  	DRAWING (DRAWING BY MICHAEL KLEIN)                                            	Letter  	Newspaper  	2009 The New York Times Company   			GOOG (NASDAQ) (58%)  	NAICS519130 INTERNET PUBLISHING and BROADCASTING and WEB SEARCH PORTALS (58%)  												
Patriot News (Harrisburg, Pennsylvania) 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL EDITION	Keep conserving  	LETTERS; Pg. A12  	248 words  	Yes, lower gas prices are a blessing in these tough economic times. Yes, lower gasoline prices will help Detroit sell cars. Yes, lower prices are a welcome blow to the petrodictators that control much of the world's oil. But will lower gas prices make you stupid? LiNeBrEaKThe problem is, lower prices result in increased demand. We know where that leads. Prices go back up again. It's not rocket science. Its simple supply and demand economics. Unfortunately, lower energy prices result in a decreased collective effort to use less oil and gasoline. Using more oil and gas takes badly needed money out of our economy and sends billions to countries that are not our friends: Saudi Arabia, Iran, Russia, Venezuela, etc. This is a serious problem for our economy and disastrous in any effort to reverse global warming.LiNeBrEaKTom Friedman's Jan. 2 column recommends a gas tax or carbon tax with offset relief in other areas such as decreased payroll taxes. This makes sense to me. I will leave the specifics of how to do this to economists, accountants and responsible politicians with the common sense and guts to do the right thing.LiNeBrEaKFor the rest of us: Don't let temporary cheap gas make you stupid. Drive as if gas is $5 a gallon and going higher. Carpool if you can. Batch your shopping trips. Support public transportation. And please, make your next car as fuel-efficient as possible.LiNeBrEaKI believe it is time for our generation to make sacrifices. Please be part of the solution.LiNeBrEaKMARIO SANGILLO Lower Paxton Twp.		OIL and GAS PRICES (94%); LETTERS and COMMENTS (92%); GASOLINE PRICES (91%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); FUEL TAX (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); GASOLINE MARKETS (73%); GLOBAL WARMING (71%); PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION (50%)  			THOMAS L FRIEDMAN (56%)  	PENNSYLVANIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (79%); IRAN (79%); SAUD