Pioneer Press (St. Paul, Minnesota)  	January 14, 2009 Wednesday 	Big Stone II pushes clean-energy alternative  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	614 words  	Jan. 14--Can an offer of clean-energy technology seal the deal for Big Stone II?LiNeBrEaKA group of rural utilities hoping to gain approval for high-voltage power lines from the proposed coal-fired power plant in South Dakota on Tuesday offered to equip the plant with such technology at a hearing before the Minnesota Public Utilities Commission.LiNeBrEaKThe offer was the latest effort by utilities led by Otter Tail Power of Fergus Falls, Minn., to support the proposed Big Stone II power plant in Milbank, S.D. The matter has been before the PUC for more than three years. LiNeBrEaKA St. Paul hearing room packed with attorneys, environmentalists and building and construction union officials listened to what essentially were the closing arguments in a long-running trial. The plant now is estimated to cost between $1. 4 billion and $1. 5 billion if it is built by 2015 and would provide 650 construction jobs, though most of them would go to South Dakota.LiNeBrEaKThe commission is scheduled to vote Thursday on whether to allow high-voltage transmission lines to be built from the South Dakota plant to central Minnesota, where nearly half of its proposed 500 megawatts to 580 megawatts of electricity would be consumed.LiNeBrEaKAlthough the project has been approved in South Dakota, it would die if the Minnesota PUC votes down the transmission lines. The utilities say they need the coal-fired plant to satisfy the region's demand for electricity, which they say will exceed regional capacity beginning in 2013.LiNeBrEaKButLiNeBrEaKenvironmentalists worry that carbon dioxide emissions from the plant will contribute to global warming. That could cost ratepayers a lot more than renewable energy like wind power if, as expected, the incoming Obama administration levies a cost on carbon emissions to discourage the use of fossil fuels in energy production.LiNeBrEaKUnder the latest proposal by the utilities, however, Big Stone II could be built as an "ultra-supercritical coal plant," meaning it would burn hotter and more efficiently than a conventional supercritical plant, using less coal and emitting fewer emissions, said Mark Rolfes, the plant's project manager.LiNeBrEaKThe plant also could be built with extra space for "clean coal technology" that could be installed later, proponents said. Such equipment could trap carbon dioxide and send it in a pipe to oil fields in North Dakota or Canada. It could then be pumped underground and used to push up trapped oil, Otter Tail Power CEO Chuck McFarland said.LiNeBrEaK"It would be the hybrid car of power plants," Big Stone II attorney Todd Guerrero told the five commissioners.LiNeBrEaKBut environmentalists dismissed the claims, saying ultra-supercritical technology wouldn't dent the 4 million tons of CO2 the plant is expected to produce annually.LiNeBrEaKThe proposal to capture carbon dioxide is meaningless since Big Stone II backers don't know when that technology might be feasible, said attorney Beth Goodpaster, of the Minnesota Center for Environmental Advocacy.LiNeBrEaKCommissioners expressed concern about how to minimize the risk of later rate hikes related to the cost of building and operating Big Stone II. They asked for the Office of Energy Security to present new ideas Thursday on how to divide the risk between consumers and the utilities.		UTILITIES INDUSTRY (92%); POWER PLANTS (90%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (90%); CONSTRUCTION (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); APPROVALS (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSIONS (90%); EMISSIONS (89%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (89%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (89%); COAL INDUSTRY (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (88%); 