San Antonio Express-News 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   METRO Edition	The whiff of a new 'gas' tax is in the air  	A SECTION; Pg. 1A  	612 words  	Could the secret to containing global warming lie in controlling the, to put it delicately, "emissions" from cows and pigs?LiNeBrEaKThe seemingly comical idea is being taken dead seriously by some of the 5,350 farmers and ranchers gathered in San Antonio this week for the American Farm Bureau Federation's annual meeting.LiNeBrEaKMany are worried that an idea floated by the Environmental Protection Agency to regulate greenhouse gas emissions as a pollutant through the Clean Air Act could act as a de facto tax on livestock. The cost, according to the American Farm Bureau, could be $175 a year for each dairy cow, $87. 50 for each head of beef cattle and $20 for each hog. LiNeBrEaK"It is just outrageous," said cattle farmer Brad Hargett, who made the trip from Monroe, N.C. "A small producer such as myself, it would put us out of business."LiNeBrEaKThe issue is garnering significant attention in the agriculture community. The Farm Bureau's national and Texas publications recently carried stories about it, and EPA spokesman Jonathan Shradar said he's had several calls a day on the "cow tax" for the past three months. Ultimately though, Shradar characterized the "cow tax" as a scare tactic used by the by the Farm Bureau to fight global warming regulation.LiNeBrEaK"Any time you get people who are opposed to climate change regulation or climate change science, you always hear the cows coming up," he said. "No one has anything to worry about. Our friends at the Farm Bureau have suggested wrongly that the EPA is proposing to regulate cows, and that is inaccurate."LiNeBrEaKRick Krause, the Farm Bureau's director of regulatory regulations, disagrees with the EPA's attempts to dismiss the "cow tax" and makes no apology for making such a fuss over the issue.LiNeBrEaK"It wouldn't have been in the federal register if the EPA wasn't serious about floating the idea," he said. "I know we've got the EPA's attention."LiNeBrEaKThe idea stems from a notice the EPA issued in July seeking comment on its proposal to regulate greenhouse gas emissions under the Clean Air Act.LiNeBrEaKShradar said the proposal is focused on carbon dioxide regulation, but the Department of Agriculture, in its comments, said that the way the proposed rule is written, it would likely include the regulation of the greenhouse gas methane. The Farm Bureau worries that the regulations would be extended to any livestock operation that emitted more than 100 tons of greenhouse gas a year. That would hit virtually every livestock operation in the country, Krause said.LiNeBrEaKThat's because cows, pigs, goats and all manner of livestock emit methane from the manure they leave and, as Krause puts it, "the gas coming out of both ends."LiNeBrEaKThat gas can be potent when it comes to global warming. Methane is thought to be some 20 times more powerful at causing climate change than carbon dioxide.LiNeBrEaKShradar acknowledges that all sources of greenhouse gases are being discussed as the EPA formulates climate change plans, but he insists farmers and ranchers have little to worry about.LiNeBrEaK"Even if we regulate methane, we would most likely waive agriculture activities," said Shradar. "There is no cow tax."LiNeBrEaKCharles Nunu of Element Markets, a Houston-based alternative energy and carbon management firm, said much of the anxiety over the issue can be attributed to uncertainty over climate change policy. In an effort to fight global warming, the administration of President-elect Barack Obama is expected to push climate change regulation this year that will affect some or all sectors of the economy.LiNeBrEaK"We all know it's coming," he said. "But I think there is a lot up in the air right now."LiNeBrEaKPossible 'gas' taxesLiNeBrEaK* $175 for each dairy cowLiNeBrEaK* $87. 50 for each head of beef cattleLiNeBrEaK* $20 for each hog		AIR Q