San Jose Mercury News (California)  	January 14, 2009 Wednesday 	EPA nominee pledges to quickly review California's emissions standard  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	599 words  	Jan. 14--WASHINGTON -- Lisa Jackson, President-elect Barack Obama's choice to head the Environmental Protection Agency, told senators Wednesday that she will move quickly on California's request to enact its own far-reaching vehicle emissions standards.LiNeBrEaK"My commitment is that I will immediately review that," Jackson, New Jersey's top environmental official, told Sen. Barbara Boxer, the California Democrat who chairs the Environment and Public Works Committee. "I will look to science and the law, and rely on the expert advice of the staff." LiNeBrEaKThat was a signal from Jackson, during her confirmation hearing to become EPA director, that she is likely to approve the state's bid -- turned down by the Bush administration a year ago -- for a waiver from the Clean Air Act to enforce its own standards. Obama pledged to grant the waiver during the presidential campaign.LiNeBrEaKStephen Johnson, outgoing EPA director, overruled the unanimous recommendations of his scientific and legal staff when he turned down the California standard, angering Boxer and other Democrats on the committee.LiNeBrEaKNew Jersey and at least 15 other states, with more than 40 percent of the nation's population, are ready to enact the California standard, designed to reduce greenhouse gas emissions by 30 percent in new cars and light trucks by 2016.LiNeBrEaK"Granting the waiver is the single greatest thing we could do for fuel efficiency," Boxer said Monday during a briefing with CaliforniaLiNeBrEaKreporters.LiNeBrEaKJackson, a 46-year-old chemical engineer who heads the New Jersey Department of Environmental Protection, received a warm reception from the committee. So did Nancy Sutley, deputy mayor of Los Angeles, who is nominated to head the White House Council for Environmental Quality.LiNeBrEaKJackson, who would be the first African-American to head the EPA, pledged to follow "science and the rule of law" and to make sure that "political appointees will not compromise the integrity of EPA's technical expertise."LiNeBrEaKDemocrats complained that the EPA under Johnson too often followed the will of industry, ignoring scientific findings about threats to public health.LiNeBrEaKRepublicans on the committee had kind words for Jackson's record, but warned that any move by the EPA to use the Clean Air Act to deal with climate change could threaten coal industry jobs and consumers who depend on coal and oil.LiNeBrEaK"We can't support East Coast and West Coast plans that would hurt our industries," said Sen. Christopher Bond, R-Mo. "What may be acceptable in San Jose, California, may not be acceptable in Carthage, Missouri."LiNeBrEaKSutley, 46, spent six years in state government in Sacramento, serving as deputy secretary of the state EPA and an adviser to former Gov. Gray Davis. The daughter of immigrants from Argentina, Sutley has been a gay activist and advocate for California's aggressive global-warming regulations.LiNeBrEaKSutley told the committee that she will help coordinate the Obama administration's environmental and energy policies and will focus on global warming and clean technology.LiNeBrEaKBoxer said she expected Jackson and Sutley to be confirmed by the Senate as early as next week.LiNeBrEaKContact Frank Davies at fdavies@mercurynews.com or (202) 662-8921.		AIR QUALITY REGULATION (93%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (92%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS (91%); EMISSIONS (91%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (91%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS STANDARDS (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (89%); POLITICAL PARTIES (89%); APPOINTMENTS (78%); CAMPAIGNS and ELECTIONS (78%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); ENERGY EF