The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL Edition	Torture by any other name  	Op-Ed; LETTERS TO THE EDITOR; Pg. B6  	1187 words  	Editor - I pride myself on being a liberal, which in my mind includes hearing and discussing points of view very different from my own. I'm glad to see Debra J. Saunders' columns because I think we need a healthy discourse of opinions. I am, however, nearly shaking with anger over her Tuesday piece entitled "Flexibility on torture.'"LiNeBrEaKIt sounded like she was regurgitating all the nonsense this outgoing administration has been feeding us for the last eight years, especially touting that horrifying phrase - "enhanced interrogation techniques" - designed to make torture more palatable to the general public. LiNeBrEaKSaunders stated that these "techniques," such as sleep deprivation, exposure to cold and waterboarding "do not scar." She quoted a former CIA official as saying it isn't torture "because we don't torture our own people." That kind of circular thinking and double talk is absurd. These techniques, even if not used regularly, cause enormous distress. If Saunders wants to deny this, I challenge her to experience the simulated drowning of waterboarding.  LiNeBrEaKI've read articles about how prisoners are treated regularly in Guantanamo and things as "simple" as sleep deprivation and exposure to cold have extreme detrimental affects to a person's psyche. People claim that these tactics have saved us from further attacks, but how can you prove a negative? I have extremely mixed emotions about this, because I too want to feel safe in a post 9/11 world, so I can't say that I don't want something done. But to claim we aren't torturing people is absurd and insulting.LiNeBrEaKJENNIFER SMITH LiNeBrEaKSan Francisco LiNeBrEaKCall it what it isLiNeBrEaKEditor - The descent into barbarity is invariably paved by euphemisms. Does the word torture bother you? Just replace it with "enhanced interrogation techniques," as Debra J. Saunders does. Like air freshener in your bathroom, one euphemistic spray makes everything smell so much better.LiNeBrEaKFELIX BRAENDEL LiNeBrEaKSan Rafael LiNeBrEaKWrong, wrong, wrongLiNeBrEaK Editor - How many times can you get it wrong before you are asked to go away? I am speaking about Debra J. Saunders. Over the last eight years we, the readers have been subjected to her being a global warming denier, calling the appalling George W. Bush a giant, claiming that Iraq is not a quagmire, and now she says that waterboarding is not torture and that torture is effective, when it has been proven otherwise.LiNeBrEaKAt what point does never getting it right disqualify you from holding the job of columnist? She has long ago proven that being a ideologue prevents her from at the very least being rational.LiNeBrEaKVERNON BURTON LiNeBrEaKSan Leandro LiNeBrEaKIn praise of SaundersLiNeBrEaKEditor - Thank you for the perceptive column on torture by Debra J. Saunders.LiNeBrEaKDAVID C. HAMILTON LiNeBrEaKSalem, Ore. LiNeBrEaKDon't torture meLiNeBrEaKEditor - I confess! I'm a liberal, I voted for Barack Obama. Now, please make Debra J. Saunders stop torturing me with her "grabbing, shaking, open hand slapping, sleep deprivation, exposure to cold and simulated-drowning" endorsing columns.LiNeBrEaKSaunders wants "flexibility on torture." Is this some form of torture yoga? Interrogators can bend the suspect's limbs, but don't break them. And that's how she wants to treat the "suspect," I prefer not to imagine what rites of the inquisition she might inflict on someone actually convicted.LiNeBrEaKCall me old-fashioned, but when you terrorize the terrorist, you become the terrorist. So stop it, Debra, quit twisting words, slapping our intelligence and putting bad TV shows on the same level as national policy.LiNeBrEaKSTEVE ABNEY San Francisco LiNeBrEaKBART's leadershipLiNeBrEaKEditor - Regarding the article "BART calls meeting on killing, gets flak" Jan. 12, I know that I will be voting at the next election for a different director to represent me. I would advise other voters to do so as well. LiNeBrEaKOscar Grant's homicide and its aftermath have shown me that the BART directors are just one more group of political seat-warmers and benefits-collectors, rather than the responsible and prudent overseers of a huge transit system they purport to be. LiNeBrEaK Ultimately the voters have to show these directors who is the boss. All of these directors should be voted out of office as soon as possible. Better yet, they should resign.LiNeBrEaKJOHN MEHRING LiNeBrEaKSan Francisco LiNeBrEaKAll together now ...LiNeBrEaKEditor - President-elect Barack Obama says we need "skin in the game," meaning that we all must make sacrifices in these troubled times. Does that include members of Congress? They just gave themselves a $4,700 raise.LiNeBrEaKKEITH C. DeFILLIPIS LiNeBrEaKSan Jose LiNeBrEaKSupport police officersLiNeBrEaKEditor - The real crime is that San Francisco city government at all levels fails to acknowledge the cameras will not, do not, and cannot work. LiNeBrEaKWhat does work are solid leaders who manage, schedule, monitor and oversee city agencies. The SFPD can and will reduce crime with leadership: Give the men and woman of the SFPD the tools they need - solid direction daily to prevent crime.LiNeBrEaKTOM DE TORRE LiNeBrEaKLincoln LiNeBrEaKA 16-year-old's viewLiNeBrEaKEditor - Californians vote in draconian sentencing laws for minor offenders. Our prisons begin to overfill. The prison health care system breaks down. To pay for fixing it, we propose slicing the school year by five days. If this goes into place, the achievement gap will widen, and more young people will see petty theft as a way of getting by. These petty offenders will be caught under our draconian sentencing laws, and tossed in for 25-to-life. LiNeBrEaKAm I the only one who sees the pattern?LiNeBrEaKSAM NEFF LiNeBrEaKPalo Alto LiNeBrEaKA true 'Sanctuary City'LiNe