The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL Edition	Chu cruises in energy post hearing;  Obama's pick promises to fight climate change, push renewable energy 	Main News; Pg. A4  	1121 words  	 Steven Chu, President-elect Barack Obama's choice to lead the Energy Department, is known for his scientific prowess as a Nobel laureate physicist and director of the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory. But at his Senate confirmation hearing Tuesday, he showed he knows a few political moves as well.LiNeBrEaKHe appealed to Democrats on the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee with a pledge to forcefully advocate for Obama's plans to fight climate change and speed the nation's transition to renewable energy. But he also soothed Republicans and lawmakers from energy-producing states with his support for new nuclear plants, clean coal technology and some new oil drilling as part of a comprehensive energy bill.LiNeBrEaKThe 60-year-old Chu was cruising toward an easy confirmation even before he set foot in the Senate hearing room, but his steady performance is likely to have assured it. The committee's chairman, Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M., predicted Chu would be confirmed by the panel later this week and by the Senate next Tuesday. LiNeBrEaKChu could have a much harder time satisfying Washington's various energy constituencies when he steps into the job running an agency with a $23. 9 billion budget, 14,000 employees and 193,000 contract workers - a post that includes managing the nation's sprawling nuclear weapons complex.LiNeBrEaKChu, a professor of physics and cellular and molecular biology at UC Berkeley who once chaired Stanford University's physics department, got off to a strong start at the hearing as senators of both parties praised his science credentials. Chu shared a Nobel Prize in 1997 for his work in finding new methods for trapping atoms with laser light.LiNeBrEaKSen. Lisa Murkowski of Alaska, the panel's ranking Republican, said Chu was "uniquely poised" to carry out the agency's science and technology missions. California Democratic Sen. Dianne Feinstein, Chu's home-state senator who introduced him to the panel, said, "In my opinion, there is no one brighter or better equipped than this man to become secretary of energy."LiNeBrEaKAlthough the questioning was mostly gentle, Chu was forced to try to defuse the controversy over several remarks he had made in recent speeches. Sen. Byron Dorgan, D-N.D., pointed to a statement that Chu made in a speech last year in which he called coal "my worst nightmare" because of the heavy greenhouse gas emissions of coal-fired plants. The statement drew fire from conservative bloggers and coal-state lawmakers.LiNeBrEaKChu reiterated his view that "if the world continues to use coal the way it is using it today, not only in the United States but in Russia, India and China, it is a pretty bad dream" because of emissions of not just carbon, but also mercury and sulfur dioxide. He added that he would not back a moratorium on new coal plants, as some environmentalists want, favoring new technologies to limit emissions instead.LiNeBrEaK"There are ... some people in the United States who feel perhaps we should turn off coal," he said. "But even if we do it, China and India will not. And so we are in a position to develop those technologies so that the world can capture the carbon."LiNeBrEaKChu also retreated from comments he made last September favoring much higher gas taxes, when he said, "somehow we have to figure out how to boost the price of gasoline to the levels in Europe" - which at the time were over $8 a gallon. Sen. Jim DeMint, R-S.C., called the idea "a tax on folks who are trying to get to work."LiNeBrEaKChu pointed out that Obama has said raising gas taxes was "off the table" because of the weak economy.LiNeBrEaKHe sidestepped a question by Murkowski about whether he favors reinstating the presidential and congressional bans on offshore drilling. Chu said new offshore leases could be part of a new energy bill, but he suggested that the country can't drill its way to energy independence with less than 3 percent of the world's proven oil reserves.LiNeBrEaK"More efficient use of energy in the United States is the one big factor that can most help us decrease our dependency on foreign oil," he said.LiNeBrEaKChu was chosen by Obama for his expertise on renewable energy, and he was at his best Tuesday describing the pioneering work being done at the Lawrence Berkeley Lab. He spoke of the lab's Helios Project, which seeks to harness solar energy and gene-altered bacteria to create new biofuels that could substitute for gasoline, diesel and jet fuel.LiNeBrEaKChu said the rapid, commercial-scale development of new technologies is the best way to address the twin issues of climate change and America's dependence on foreign oil. He said he supports Obama's plan for a cap-and-trade system that sets tough targets for emissions reductions and allows major emitters to buy and sell credits to release greenhouse gases.LiNeBrEaK"It's an aggressive plan, but one I think is achievable," he said.LiNeBrEaKChu also made comments favoring an expansion of nuclear power. He explained that nuclear power now accounts for 20 percent of the country's energy supply, but 70 percent of its carbon-free electricity.LiNeBrEaK"The point here is that nuclear power ... is going to be an important part of our energy mix," he said.LiNeBrEaKLawmakers praised his testimony, but some on Capitol Hill predict that energy policy will be driven not by Chu, but by Carol Browner, President Bill Clinton's secretary of the Environmental Protection Agency, whom Obama picked as his new energy and climate czar. Sen. Bob Corker, R-Tenn., questioned whether Browner should appear before the committee about her role, although her post does not require Senate confirmation.LiNeBrEaKChu brushed off the idea of a fight for clout between the Energy Department and the White House, saying he's already had cordial talks with Browner.LiNeBrEaK"She has a difficult task ahead of her in trying to coordinate people" from various agencies, he said. "I think it will be a collaborative and close cooperation."LiNeBrEaKHeard at the hearing LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK"It is now clear that if we continue on our current path, we run the risk of dramatic, disruptive changes to our climate in the lifetimes of our children and our grandchildren."LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK - Steven Chu, energy secretary-designateLiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK"The coal resources in the United States are immense. And I am very hopeful and optimistic that we can figure out a way to use those resources in a clean way." LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK - ChuLiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK"Any man who can work both at Cal Berkeley and Stanford has to be adept at forging consensus."LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK - Sen. Evan Bayh, D-Ind.LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK"Dr. Chu is persistent, persuasive and passionate about science. And I think you'll find that his determination is infectious." LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK - Sen. Dianne Feinstein, D-Calif.LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK"Will you take a lead, not just to talk about it, not just to opine about it as we often do, but actually do the things necessary to see if we can't restart a nuclear industry in America?"LiNeBrEaK&bull;LiNeBrEaK - Sen. Jeff Sessions, R-Ala. 		PHYSICS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (90%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); AWARDS and PRIZES (90%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (90%); LEGISLATORS (89%); NOBEL PRIZES (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (89%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (89%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); POLITICAL PARTIES (89%); POWER PLANTS (78%); ENERGY REGULATION (78%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (78%); BIOLOGY (78%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (78%); POLITICS (78%); NUCLEAR WEAPO