St. Louis Post-Dispatch (Missouri) 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   THIRD EDITION	Coal ash disposal rules vary from state to state Tennessee's toxic spill spurs concern about power plant wastes stored in ponds.  	NEWS; Pg. A1  	944 words  	When a storage pond with more than a billion gallons of toxic coal ash sludge broke in Tennessee last month, alarms sounded over the lack of federal regulation of coal combustion waste piling up at power plants around the nation.LiNeBrEaKMore than 700,000 tons of coal combustion waste are estimated stored in ponds in Missouri and more than 600,000 tons in Illinois, according to U.S. Department of Energy data. LiNeBrEaKAnd while state environmental regulators say it's unlikely a similar collapse would occur here, some worry about the fact that many ponds are near rivers that supply drinking water.LiNeBrEaK"Coal ash is toxic and the last place in the world it should be is next to water," said Kathy Andria, director of the American Bottom Conservancy, an Illinois-based environmental group. "When you factor in climate change - and the increased potential for greater rainfall events - you raise the risk that these dam walls become weakened and we're looking at a serious problem."LiNeBrEaKDespite growing concerns about the risk from coal combustion waste, there are no national standards for its storage and disposal. The U.S. Environmental Protection Agency does not consider the waste "hazardous" even though it contains harmful metals such as lead and arsenic.LiNeBrEaKStill, industry groups insist that coal combustion waste does not fall into a regulatory black hole as many environmental groups have suggested since the Tennessee catastrophe.LiNeBrEaK"What's been interesting to me is this fiction that since coal ash is not regulated by EPA as hazardous waste, there's no regulation at all," said Jim Roewer, executive director of the Utility Solid Waste Activities Group. "That's simply not true. Many states have very tough programs."LiNeBrEaKRegulations governing coal combustion waste disposal vary wildly from state to state - some do little other than require companies to obtain discharge permits while others establish rigorous water monitoring rules.LiNeBrEaKBoth Missouri and Illinois scrutinize the ponds and landfills where coal ash waste is stored, but many older structures lack liners that would protect pollution from leaching into groundwater and migrating into drinking water sources.LiNeBrEaKIn Missouri, companies that generate coal combustion waste have been moving away from ash ponds in recent years, state environmental regulators say.LiNeBrEaKInstead, those companies are disposing of coal combustion waste in on-site landfills, which are regulated similar to municipal trash dumps. Nine landfills in Missouri have permits to accept coal combustion waste, as do two in Illinois, state environmental regulators confirmed this week.LiNeBrEaKDespite the trend toward "dry" disposal in landfills, most older coal-fired power plants do have several man-made lagoons on site where both fly and bottom ash - the byproducts of burning coal - are stored. Fly ash is captured at the top of the furnace while the coarser bottom ash particles settle out at the base.LiNeBrEaKMissouri environmental regulators say that in general, those ponds are not constructed like the one that burst in Tennessee. That pond covered about 40 acres and sat about 60 feet above the nearby river.LiNeBrEaK"Historically these fly ash impoundments are relatively flat, bowls in the ground," said Chris Nagel, with the Missouri Department of Natural Resources' solid waste management program. "There's not much in the way of elevation."LiNeBrEaKMany environmentalists, however, believe the biggest danger posed by coal ash ponds is leakage, not a catastrophic collapse like what occurred in Tennessee.LiNeBrEaKThey point to cases where unlined coal ash ponds have been linked to water pollution.LiNeBrEaK"I look at a lot of numbers and I'm not particularly phobic, but some of the monitoring we've reviewed has yielded some particularly astounding levels (of pollution)," said Eric Schaeffer, a former top EPA official and now the director of the Environmental Integrity Project.LiNeBrEaKIllinois did not require ponds to be lined until 1989, after state environmental regulators discovered pollution seeping from the Havana, Hennepin and Wood River plants, which were owned by Illinois Power at the time.LiNeBrEaK"Havana and Hennepin leaked as much as they held I think," said Darin LeCrone, a manager in Illinois EPA's bureau of water permit section. "Once we became aware of those problems we changed our regulations."LiNeBrEaKDespite the requirements, there are no regulations in Illinois for how frequently groundwater near the old, unlined ash ponds must be monitored. Each site is monitored on a "case by case" basis, LeCrone said.LiNeBrEaKAmeren officials say they test groundwater near their ash ponds on a weekly basis.LiNeBrEaKSimilarly, the company routinely monitors the structural integrity of the impoundments. Those efforts were beefed up after the company implemented its dam safety program following the collapse of the Taum Sauk reservoir.LiNeBrEaK"We feel like we have a very robust system in place for checks," said Michael Menne, Ameren's vice president for environmental safety and health."LiNeBrEaKMenne said that while the company disposes much of its coal combustion waste on site, it also recycles much of it, saving valuable landfill space.LiNeBrEaKAccording to the American Coal Ash Association, about 43 percent of the coal combustion waste generated each year, or 70 million tons, is recycled.LiNeBrEaKIn 2006, Ameren's Labadie Power Plant opened an on-site concrete packaging facility where it mixes about 10,000 tons of fly ash and 60,000 tons of bottom ash annually into about 2 million bags of concrete.LiNeBrEaKIn addition, fly ash from Ameren plants is used in road construction projects in both Missouri and Illinois.LiNeBrEaK"Over 50 to 60 percent of our ash is recycled," Menne said. "That's a pretty significant amount and we're always looking to recycle more."		POWER PLANTS (90%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (90%); ENERGY REGULATION (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (90%); CHEMICAL ACCIDENTS (90%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL ACCIDENTS and DISASTERS (90%); TOXIC and HAZARDOUS SUBSTANCES (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (89%); PARTICULATE MATTER (89%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (89%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (89%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (89%); LANDFILLS (89%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (78%); WATER POLLUTION (78%); SOLID WASTE TREATMENT and DISPOSAL (78%); HAZARDOUS WASTE (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL PERMITS (77%); TRENDS (77%); WASTE MANAGEMENT and REMEDIATION SERVICES (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (76%); RIVERS (75%); WATER QUALITY (71%); DAMS and RESERVOIRS (70%) {DOC SEPARATOR}  		US DEPARTMENT OF ENERGY (57%); US ENVIRONMENTAL PROTECTION AGENCY (55%)  		MISSOURI, USA (97%); ILLINOIS, USA (94%); TENNESSEE, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (97%)  	January 14, 2009  	ENGLISH  	GRAPHIC - COAL WASTE   		Newspaper  	2009 St. Louis Post-Dispatch, Inc. All Rights Reserved  	By Kim McGuire ST. LOUIS POST-DISPATCH The Associated Press contributed to this report.  															
