The Times Leader (Wilkes-Barre, Pennsylvania)  	January 14, 2009 Wednesday 	Nuke energy-policy push picks up: New Pa. advocacy group stresses pluses of nuclear energy, including its cost and environmental impact.  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	562 words  	Jan. 14--Seizing on a shift in the national political scene, a new nuclear-policy advocacy group announced its creation on Tuesday.LiNeBrEaK"Today is our first day," said Karen Walsh, the executive director of the Pennsylvania Energy Alliance for Generating Reliable Electricity for our Energy Needs, during a Tuesday conference call. LiNeBrEaKCiting nuclear energy's nominal greenhouse-gas emissions, reliability and cheap generation costs relative to alternatives, the alliance is urging Pennsylvanians to support new plant construction and relicensing the nine existing plants, all of which either have been relicensed or are applying.LiNeBrEaKPPL Corp., the majority owner of the Susquehanna Steam Electric Station in Salem Township, also is seeking approval for a new reactor at an adjacent site. The alliance received its initial funding, Walsh acknowledged, from Exelon Corp., which already has had two reactors relicensed in the state, and is seeking approval for three others.LiNeBrEaK"We just feel the time is right, and we feel there is a resurgence in nuclear energy," Walsh said.LiNeBrEaKWalsh noted that Pennsylvania ranks among the nation's leaders in emissions of several major greenhouse gases. While nuclear accounts for about a third of the state's electricity, roughly half comes from coal. During his campaign, President-elect Barack Obama called for mandating infrastructure upgrades to coal plants that would drastically reduce their emissions, but increase their production costs.LiNeBrEaKState environmental advocates, however, aren't sold on nuclear's promise. "By far, it is the most expensive form of energy to build. And it's impossible to build a plant without substantial help from the government," said Jan Jarrett, the president and chief executive officer of Citizens for Pennsylvania's Future.LiNeBrEaKThe same amount of money could shift the state's energy portfolio toward renewables, she said, but an even cheaper solution would be simply to use less electricity. "Vigorous energy conservation could replace the need for a nuclear power plant," she said.LiNeBrEaKAs part of its grand opening, the alliance unveiled the results of a poll of 800 Pennsylvanians on their opinions of nuclear energy. Created by pundit, pollster and Franklin and Marshall College professor G. Terry Madonna, the poll found that nearly 60 percent felt to some extent that nuclear energy will increase national security and reduce global warming. It also found favorable opinions of nuclear's reliability, safety and ability to create energy independence.LiNeBrEaKAn important question it didn't address, though, is what's to be done with the radioactive spent fuel. Walsh said the waste created from a reactor running for 50 years could be packed in a two-car garage.LiNeBrEaK"If it was packed into a two-car garage, it would be an extremely radioactive two-car garage," Jarrett countered. "It seems that it's not prudent to move ahead with new nuclear facilities until they figure out what they're going to do with the waste."		EMISSIONS (91%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (90%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL IMPACT ASSESSMENT (90%); POWER PLANTS (89%); CONSTRUCTION (89%); NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS (89%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (86%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); HAZARDOUS WASTE (78%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (77%); ENERGY DEMAND (77%); COAL INDUSTRY (77%); GLOBAL WARMING (76%); CLIMATE CHANGE (76%); MANUFACTURING FACILITIES (75%); APPROVALS (74%); NATIONAL SECURITY (73%); POLLS and SURVEYS (69%); PLANT CONSTRUCTION (58%); COLLEGE and UNIVERSITY PROFESSORS (50%)  	PPL CORP (71%); EXELON CORP (69%)  		BARACK OBAMA (55%)  	PENNSYL