tion prepares to take office next week, Big Oil clearly is seeking a seat at the table. ConocoPhillips "is ready, eager and willing to work with the new administration," Mulva said. He said a comprehensive policy is needed that would embrace the principles of broad diversity of energy supply, greater efficiency, technological innovation and sound environmental stewardship. 		EMISSIONS CREDITS (90%); EMISSIONS (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (90%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (90%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (78%); POLITICS (78%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (78%); JOB CREATION (77%); CONSUMPTION (73%); CARBON OFFSETS (71%); TAXES and TAXATION (68%); PRODUCT INNOVATION (72%) Business  	CONOCOPHILLIPS (95%); EXXON MOBIL CORP (91%)  	NATIONAL PRESS CLUB (57%)  	BARACK OBAMA (92%); JAMES MULVA (84%); REX W TILLERSON (54%)  		January 15, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Tulsa World   	MARCY GORDON Associated Press  		COP (NYSE) (95%); XOM (NYSE) (91%)  	NAICS325110 PETROCHEMICAL MANUFACTURING (91%); NAICS324110 PETROLEUM REFINERIES (91%); NAICS211111 CRUDE PETROLEUM and NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (91%)  									Jim Mulva supports cap-and-trade to cut carbon dioxide emissions.   			
USA TODAY 	January 14, 2009 Wednesday   FINAL EDITION	Chu vows to tackle global warming;  Obama's Energy nominee warmly received on Hill 	NEWS; Pg. 6A  	458 words  	WASHINGTON -- The Nobel Prize winner nominated to head the Energy Department said Tuesday that he would focus the department in part on global warming. The policy would be a sharp departure from the department's priorities during the Bush administration. LiNeBrEaK"If we continue on our current path, we run the risk of dramatic, disruptive changes to our climate," physicist Steven Chu told the Senate Energy and Natural Resources Committee during his confirmation hearing.LiNeBrEaKSince 2004, Chu has headed the Energy Department's Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, which he redirected to focus on renewable energy. President-elect Barack Obama tapped Chu for Energy secretary last month.LiNeBrEaKAt the hearing, Chu, who often rides his bike to work, called for investments in energy efficiency and renewable energy. At the same time, he presented himself as a pragmatist who won't reject taking advantage of energy sources just because they are out of favor with environmentalists.LiNeBrEaKNew nuclear plants, continued reliance on coal-fired power plants and U.S. oil and gas drilling are all necessary, Chu said. Environmental groups such as the Natural Resources Defense Council (NRDC)  have urged Obama to move the United States to 100% renewable electricity from sources such as solar and wind power.LiNeBrEaK"We need all solutions," Chu said. "We need to make them as clean as possible as quickly as possible."LiNeBrEaKThe NRDC declined to comment, but one industry group took heart from Chu's statements. "We were encouraged by what we heard on nuclear and clean coal," said Keith McCoy of the National Association of Manufacturers.LiNeBrEaKChu seemed headed for an easy confirmation as early as next Tuesday, the day Obama will be inaugurated, said committee Chairman Sen. Jeff Bingaman, D-N.M. Chu's qualifications drew praise from committee Democrats and Republicans alike.LiNeBrEaK"It's great to have somebody of Dr. Chu's intelligence running the Energy Department," said Sen. Bob Corker, R-Tenn.LiNeBrEaKOn global warming, Chu said the U.S. should lead the way in cutting greenhouse gases. Chu, the son of Chinese immigrants, said he hopes that China -- the world's largest source of the main greenhouse gas -- will follow.LiNeBrEaKPresident Bush cited inaction by China and India in his opposition to the Kyoto Protocol, a 1997 global-warming treaty adopted by nearly 200 nations but not the United States.LiNeBrEaKThe treaty exempted most developing nations, including China, from having to cut their global-warming emissions.LiNeBrEaK"The United States should take the first step and hopefully the Chinese will immediately, very closely follow," Chu said.LiNeBrEaKThat drew a gentle rebuke from Sen. Evan Bayh, D-Ind.LiNeBrEaK"That approach will not be enacted by the U.S. Congress," Bayh said. A climate treaty would have to be ratified by the Senate. 		NOBEL PRIZES (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); AWARDS and PRIZES (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); SOLAR ENERGY (90%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (90%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); EMISSIONS (89%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (89%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (89%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); POLITICAL PARTIES (89%); POWER PLANTS (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (78%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (78%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (78%); EMERGING MARKETS (78%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (78%); WIND ENERGY (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (78%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (77%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (75%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (73%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (72%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (72%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (72%); NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS (72%);