Wyoming Tribune-Eagle  	January 14, 2009 Wednesday 	60th Wyo. Legislature begins  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	552 words  	Jan. 14--CHEYENNE -- The new speaker of the Wyoming House of Representatives told fellow lawmakers Tuesday they can still offer property tax relief and accomplish important goals, even though money is tight.LiNeBrEaK"The passage of a bill can be torturous and brutal," House Speaker Rep. Colin Simpson, R-Cody, told new lawmakers. "But you will be strengthened by the fight."LiNeBrEaKSimpson also called on the 60th Wyoming Legislature to help create a western states energy task force during the general session that started Tuesday and is scheduled to continue through March 5. LiNeBrEaKThe task force would be a public-private partnership involving 14 western states. It would provide comprehensive analysis of the energy industry and its needs and impacts.LiNeBrEaKSimpson said he hopes the task force will be in place and hold a conference by the fall.LiNeBrEaKKeeping Wyoming's energy economy viable in a world concerned with greenhouse gases and global warming has to be a priority, he said.LiNeBrEaKLawmakers will have to focus on narrowing priorities, Simpson added.LiNeBrEaKState lawmakers learned last week they would have an estimated $259. 2 million -- rather than $909 million -- available for supplemental spending.LiNeBrEaKThat is money available for new spending on top of the budget that runs through fiscal 2010.LiNeBrEaK"We are able to and we should provide property tax relief," Simpson said.LiNeBrEaKThere are a variety of plans being offered by lawmakers, as well as the governor, he said. Lawmakers should be able to craft a property tax relief bill from those.LiNeBrEaKSome areas of the state have experienced skyrocketing property values that also create skyrocketing tax bills for homeowners.LiNeBrEaKThe speaker said he also expects that the Legislature will address health care, community colleges and local government financing.LiNeBrEaKSimpson comes from an extended family that has been engaged in Wyoming politics for about a century.LiNeBrEaKHis father, Alan Simpson, served in the Wyoming House from 1965 to 1977 and as one of the state's U.S. senators from 1979 to 1996.LiNeBrEaK"I served with giants in this Legislature," Alan Simpson told lawmakers.LiNeBrEaKAnd he said the key to success is establishing trust.LiNeBrEaK"That's the only cash you have here is trust," Simpson said. "Break that trust, and you are history.LiNeBrEaK"Don't get all tangled up day after day in social issues," he advised, "because you'll never change a vote."LiNeBrEaKHis son will be a fine House speaker, Alan Simpson added.LiNeBrEaKThe elder Simpson struggled to control his emotions as he said, "I commend him to you with deep pride and much love."LiNeBrEaKIn other business, Wyoming Supreme Court Justice William Hill administered the oath of office to Cheyenne's newest senator, Rick Hunnicutt.LiNeBrEaKHunnicutt was chosen by Laramie County Republicans and the Laramie County Commission to replace Sen. Bob Fecht, who resigned.LiNeBrEaKGov. Dave Freudenthal will present his State of the State speech at 10 a.m. today to a joint session of the Legislature in the House chamber.		LEGISLATORS (91%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); TAX LAW (90%); TAX RELIEF (89%); PROPERTY TAX (89%); COUNTIES (89%); REAL ESTATE (78%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (78%); LEGISLATION (78%); HOMEOWNERS (78%); COUNTY GOVERNMENT (78%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (78%); POLITICS (78%); EMISSIONS (75%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (75%); REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (75%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (69%); PUBLIC PRIVATE PARTNERSHIPS (69%); GLOBAL WARMING (67%); LAW COURTS and TRIBUNALS (60%); COMMUNITY COLLEGES (50%); SUPREME COURTS (50%)  				CHEYENNE, WY, USA (93%) WYOMING, USA (98%); WEST USA (92%) UNITED STATES (98%)  	January 14, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Wyoming Tribune-Eagle   	Bill McCarthy, Wyoming Tribune-Eagle, 