Akron Beacon Journal (Ohio)  	January 13, 2009 Tuesday 	Coalition calls for investment in renewable energy  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	609 words  	Jan. 13--The proposed federal economic stimulus by President-elect Barack Obama should be used to boost renewable energy, energy efficiency and public transportation, a coalition of Akron leaders, businesses and an Ohio eco-group said today.LiNeBrEaKAkron outlined $150 million in environmentally friendly public works, including boosting energy efficiency at several city buildings and investing in bus improvements, Mayor Don Plusquellic said. LiNeBrEaKAkron has proposed $350 million in other projects, including a request for federal funds for a new downtown hotel, Plusquellic said during a morning news conference at the Akron-Summit County Public Library.LiNeBrEaKAkron is seeking $14 million to help attract a partner to build a hotel with 100 to 110 beds. The hotel would be between the Akron Art Museum and the John S. Knight Center and would help Akron attract more conventions, the mayor said.LiNeBrEaKInvestors cannot arrange the needed financing in today's economy, and such a federal grant would provide a big boost for a second downtown hotel in Akron, Plusquellic said.LiNeBrEaKThe 274-room Radisson Hotel's Akron City Centre is the only full-service hotel downtown.LiNeBrEaKIn 2007, the University of Akron purchased the Quaker Square Inn. Half of the 190 rooms there have been converted into student lodging. UA plans to convert the remaining 95 rooms to student use by late this year.LiNeBrEaKAkron has a major need for more downtown hotel rooms, Plusquellic said.LiNeBrEaK"To be successful, the economic stimulus package must provide a sound investment in our future," Plusquellic said. "This means that funding for projects that conserve energy, promote alternative fuels and clean our environment must be a priority. 'Green' jobs can't be outsourced, and Ohio can be a leader in this area."LiNeBrEaKSaid Michele Fisher of Environment Ohio, "Clean energy can protect our environment and rev our economic engine to generate a brighter future for Ohio."LiNeBrEaKHer statewide eco-group also released a new report, Clean Energy, Bright Future. It said that the economic stimulus program's investments in environmentally friendly projects would reduce global warming pollution, cut oil consumption and create or sustain 3 million jobs in the United States.LiNeBrEaKInvesting $150 billion in non-polluting wind and solar power, energy efficiency and improved mass transit could reduce carbon dioxide emissions by 670 million tons a year across the country, the report said.LiNeBrEaKThe report calls for weatherizing homes and businesses, training workers for new, clean-energy industries and expanding public transit.LiNeBrEaKThere is strong support in Ohio for such a green component to the federal stimulus effort, she said.LiNeBrEaKState Sen. Tom Sawyer, D-Akron, called for major investments to upgrade the nation's overloaded electric system. As much as 20 percent of the electricity produced is lost through inefficiency and overcrowding on the electric grid, he said.LiNeBrEaKAkron businessman Mike Foraker praised the plan to invest in renewable energy, energy efficiency and public transportation.LiNeBrEaK"I'm just so excited by this plan," said Foraker, chief executive of Jennings Heating and the Energy Factory. "I'm extremely impressed by this plan. This plan does the job."		ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (90%); CITY GOVERNMENT (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (90%); URBAN TRANSIT SYSTEMS (89%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (89%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); SOLAR ENERGY (89%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (89%); CITY LIFE (89%); EMISSIONS (78%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (78%); 2008 ECONOMIC ST