The Dallas Morning News (Texas)  	January 13, 2009 Tuesday 	Texas Legislature to revive clean coal debate  	BUSINESS AND FINANCIAL NEWS  	543 words  	Jan. 13--The clean coal debate lives.LiNeBrEaKThis session, the Texas Legislature will revive the issue of whether to give tax breaks to companies building cleaner, coal-fired power plants that capture greenhouse gases. LiNeBrEaKThe bill, filed by Rep. Phil King, R-Weatherford, is designed to make integrated gasification combined cycle power plants, or IGCC, economically viable by waiving up to $100 million in franchise taxes per plant, along with other incentives. The incentives are only for IGCC plants that capture and store at least 60 percent of their carbon dioxide emissions.LiNeBrEaK"People are afraid, the industry's afraid, to go and try to build a clean coal plant. I call it the prototype penalty," King said.LiNeBrEaKNew, prototype technology often costs more than older technology, so some developers shy away from the risk and cost of innovating. IGCC with carbon capture can cost as much as 50 percent more than traditional coal-fired plants.LiNeBrEaKSen. Kel Seliger, R-Amarillo, will sponsor the bill in the Senate. His district includes Odessa, one of the sites proposed to host the now-defunct federal clean coal project called FutureGen.LiNeBrEaKThe bill targets an IGCC plant proposed by Summit Power, which hired former Dallas Mayor Laura Miller to help get it built. Summit wants to build at the Odessa site, but Miller said the company needs government incentives to make a business case for the plant.LiNeBrEaK"The reason there are legislators that are interested in this kind of plant is that Texas has the opportunity to be ground zero in the country for carbon capture and sequestration," Miller said. She will appear at a news conference in support of the bill Thursday in Austin.LiNeBrEaKOther companies with IGCC proposals could also apply for the tax credit.LiNeBrEaKNRG Energy has applied for an air permit for an IGCC plant in South Texas. The company has said it needs government incentives to make the plant profitable.LiNeBrEaKAnd Energy Future Holdings' Luminant generation business has said it is considering building an IGCC facility, but it hasn't offered any proposals.LiNeBrEaK"This type of policy proposal is a solid first step by the Legislature," said Phil Wilson, Luminant's senior vice president of public affairs.LiNeBrEaKThe bill offers three incentives. First, the plant developer gets up to $100 million in franchise tax credit.LiNeBrEaKSecond, the University of Texas' Bureau of Economic Geology will monitor the sites where the carbon dioxide is stored to ensure that the greenhouse gas remains underground.LiNeBrEaKThird, any oil company that will take the carbon dioxide from the plant and use it for enhanced oil recovery gets a tax incentive.LiNeBrEaKA number of oil companies around Texas buy naturally occurring carbon dioxide produced out of state. The carbon dioxide is piped in and injected into aging wells to bring up more oil.LiNeBrEaKIGCC plants are called clean coal because the plant turns the fuel into a gas.		CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (94%); POWER PLANTS (91%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (91%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (91%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (91%); EMISSIONS (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (90%); COAL GASIFICATION (90%); LEGISLATORS (90%); COAL INDUSTRY (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); TAX LAW (90%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (89%); TAX INCENTIVES (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (89%); OIL and GAS INCENTIVES (78%); HOLDING COMPANIES (78%); COAL MINING (78%); PUBLIC POLICY (78%); POWER COGENERATION (77%); OIL EXTRACTION (63%); PLANT CONSTRUCTION (57%)  	ENERGY FUTURE HOLDINGS CORP (52%)  			AUSTIN, TX, USA (79%); DALLAS, TX, USA (58%) TEXAS, USA (97%) UNITED STATES (97%)  	January 13, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Dallas Morning News   	Elizabeth Souder, The Dallas Morning News  		Dhaka:SUMITPOWE, NYSE:NRG  	General  	Distributed by McC