e Dave Agema's letter ("Don't raise taxes in a recession," Pulse, Jan. 5): Whether or not one endorses the concept of a raised gas tax, does anyone really believe that we in the United States can simply "drill our way out" of our energy problems?LiNeBrEaKEven if attainable, would it not already have been achieved, using the millions of acres where drilling is allowed? Mr. Agema seems to believe we are addicted only to "foreign oil," so that if we merely removed the word "foreign," there would somehow be no more addiction, and therefore no problem. One might agree, were it not for the messy little problem of global warming (yes, it's real) -- a subject he conveniently does not address. "Drill Now" may sound good and marginally address energy supply, but it works against confronting the deeper problem that we are abusing our planet (God's creation, remember?). Rather than whining about raised gas taxes, Mr. Agema would be more useful and true as a conservative by championing the benefits of conservation of energy. We just witnessed the power of conservation following last summer's $4 gasoline spike. How about it, Mr. Agema?LiNeBrEaKEDWARD BOLT/Grand RapidsLiNeBrEaKAid to other countriesLiNeBrEaKI can see giving aid to a country that needs it, but let's not give aid to countries that don't need it. Israel is a country that the United States gives aid to, some $3 billion, and Israel would use that money to buy weaponsLiNeBrEaKFirst of all I didn't know that Israel was a country in need of welfare, and why are we giving money to other countries that could be used at home? Are we still going to be giving money to other countries when we are in a Depression? We need to get our own house in order first!LiNeBrEaKMARCIA BOELENS/Rockford		EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (90%); EMPLOYMENT (73%); SMALL BUSINESS (73%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (72%); LEGISLATORS (67%); WAGES and SALARIES (66%); TAXES and TAXATION (64%); FUEL TAX (50%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%) Opinion  	ASSOCIATED PRESS (54%)  			