The Houston Chronicle 	January 13, 2009 Tuesday   3 STAR R.O. EDITION	Bush zeroed in on energy like few other presidents;  Experts clash on assessments of his policies 	BUSINESS; Pg. 1  	1121 words  	WASHINGTON - George W. Bush leaves his mark on the nation's energy policy like no president in a generation.LiNeBrEaKAn unabashed champion of the oil industry, Bush swept aside regulatory impediments to domestic oil and natural gas drilling.LiNeBrEaKBut this same one-time Midland oilman also declared the nation "addicted" to oil and signed bills requiring greater use of renewable fuels and raising vehicle mileage requirements. LiNeBrEaKWhile a steadfast, at times even lone, advocate for building up the nation's emergency oil stockpile, Bush largely punted on what may be the most pressing environmental issue of our age: addressing climate change.LiNeBrEaKAs polarizing a figure on energy as any other issue, Bush sparks assessments that suggest a mix of strategic vision and shortsightedness.LiNeBrEaKKevin Book, an oil analyst with FBR Capital Markets, credits Bush for saving consumers last summer from even worse problems than $4-a-gallon gasoline when supplies of high-quality oil became tight, thanks to a "bold" policy promoting ethanol and other renewable fuels.LiNeBrEaKBut David Doniger, a climate policy expert at the Natural Resources Defense Council, calls Bush's energy legacy "a wasteland," while Mark Cooper, director of research for the Consumer Federation of America, considers Bush's energy policy as disastrous as the government's response when New Orleans was drowning.LiNeBrEaK"The Katrina analysis fits perfectly," Cooper said.LiNeBrEaKPolicy shortcomingsLiNeBrEaKCertainly, Bush fell short on several major energy policy fronts.LiNeBrEaKHe was unable, for instance, to marshal the political support to open up drilling in the Arctic National Wildlife Refuge, believed to hold the largest untapped onshore oil deposit left in the U.S.LiNeBrEaKNo new nuclear power plants have been built on his watch, although utilities have filed a number of new permit requests. And a proposal to encourage refineries to build plants on old military bases has gone nowhere.LiNeBrEaKAn energy focusLiNeBrEaKBut the Bush White House has focused on energy like no administration since Jimmy Carter's.LiNeBrEaK"You've got to give the president a lot credit for putting energy center stage from, literally, the first week in office," said Spencer Abraham, a former Michigan senator who served as Bush's first energy secretary.LiNeBrEaKHis first day in office, Abraham remembers, he was on the phone with the then-governor of California, trying to keep the lights on.LiNeBrEaKAnd from that day on, the Bush White House had to deal with Enron trading shenanigans, petrochemical makers abandoning the United States because of high natural gas prices and motorists clamoring about the cost of filling up their SUVs.LiNeBrEaKMajor role for CheneyLiNeBrEaKWhen Bush took office, many experts were complaining the nation's energy policy had been left to drift.LiNeBrEaKBush assigned Vice President Dick Cheney, the former head of oil field services giant Halliburton Co., to craft a new energy strategy.LiNeBrEaKThe resulting proposal focused largely on boosting domestic energy supplies. Critics complained it had been written in secret, largely reflecting the views of industry with only token acknowledgment of environmental concerns.LiNeBrEaKAbraham said some argued the energy strategy was too alarmist, "when in fact all the subsequent history has borne out" the need for attention directed toward energy concerns.LiNeBrEaKEasier processLiNeBrEaKUnder Bush, the federal government streamlined the process companies must navigate to drill on federal lands. Indeed, the Bureau of Land Management has approved more than twice the number of drilling permits annually under Bush than during the Clinton administration, agency records show.LiNeBrEaKBush also pushed to open new areas offshore. In July, he lifted a presidential moratorium barring drilling off the East and West coasts. Then he helped his Republican allies strong-arm a Democratic-controlled Congress to allow a similar, congressional drilling ban to lapse for the first time since the early 1980s.LiNeBrEaK"He tried to develop federal resources more aggressively than his predecessors had - including his dad, who started that executive moratorium," said Lee Fuller, vice president of government relations for the Independent Petroleum Association of America, referring to former President George H.W. Bush.LiNeBrEaKOil reserve a priorityLiNeBrEaKThe current president, Abraham said, has been "personally adamant" about building up the nation's Strategic Petroleum Reserve, with the amount of oil in the stockpile rising 24 percent during his time in office.LiNeBrEaKBush repeatedly rebuffed calls to try to use the reserve to provide relief for motorists. Indeed, even as oil prices were soaring toward their record highs last summer, Bush insisted on adding new barrels to the reserve, until Congress finally stepped in and forced him to stop.LiNeBrEaKConsumers also complained loudly about record profits oil companies racked up in recent years. Despite that public anger, Bush tried repeatedly to swat away efforts to hit oil companies up for higher taxes.LiNeBrEaKEventually, he was forced to swallow a tax increase in October, when lawmakers added new taxes for the industry to the financial bailout package.LiNeBrEaKBecause Bush "was viewed as an oilman," the Independent Petroleum Association's Fuller said, "it made policy choices sometimes harder to present" because critics assumed he would side with the industry.LiNeBrEaKThat made it all the more dramatic when Bush declared during his 2006 State of the Union address that "America is addicted to oil."LiNeBrEaK'Bright spot'LiNeBrEaKJim Marston, head of the Texas office of the Environmental Defense Fund, said that was a rare "bright spot" for the administration.LiNeBrEaK"The problem was, we didn't treat the addiction," he said.LiNeBrEaKBush has promoted production of ethanol, made both from corn and from nonfood items such as switchgrass, to help lessen the nation's dependence on foreign oil.LiNeBrEaKIndeed, ethanol now accounts for 7 percent of the nation's gasoline supply, according to the Renewable Fuels Association. And in 2007, Bush signed a landmark energy bill requiring even greater use of renewables. That same legislation requires the nation's fleet of cars and trucks achieve an average 35 miles per gallon by 2020.LiNeBrEaKIn coming years, the Bush White House may be most faulted for not moving more aggressively to curb greenhouse gas emissions and slow the effects of climate change.LiNeBrEaKAbraham said critics don't give the administration enough credit for helping encourage development of technologies to combat global warming.LiNeBrEaKBut environmentalists point to FutureGen, a federal initiative to develop a way to capture carbon dioxide emitted from coal-fired power plants. Bush announced the program in 2003, but after five years his administration announced it was revamping the project.LiNeBrEaKMarston said the program was moving in the right direction.LiNeBrEaK"We got close," he said, "and then they pulled the rug out from under it."		CRUDE OIL and NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (90%); ENERGY REGULATION (90%); BIOFUELS (90%); PUBLIC POLICY (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (90%); OIL and GAS EXTRACTION (90%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (90%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (89%); POWER PLANTS (78%); ENERGY and UTILITY CONSTRUCTION (78%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (78%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (78%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); OIL EXTRACTION (78%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (78%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (78%); OIL and GAS PRICES (78%); OIL SERVICES INDUSTRY (78%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (78%); STRATEGIC PETROLEUM RESERVES (78%); NATURAL GAS EXTRACTION (77%); NATURAL GAS PRICES (77%); CONSUMER LAW (77%); CLIMATE CHANGE (77%); OIL and GAS