Mobile Register (Alabama) 	January 13, 2009 Tuesday   03 EDITION	Alabama Power studying idea of using wood for fuel  	A; Pg. 01  	746 words  	Alabama Power studying idea of using wood for fuelLiNeBrEaKBy SEAN REILLYLiNeBrEaKWashington BureauLiNeBrEaKWASHINGTON - With utilities under growing pressure to turn to renewable energy sources, Alabama Power Co. is exploring the option of making electricity solely by burning wood or other "biomass."LiNeBrEaKUnder a study to be completed in the second half of this year, the state's top power provider is looking into converting a coal-fired generating unit at one of its facilities. LiNeBrEaKAmong the sites under consideration is Barry Steam Plant in north Mobile County.LiNeBrEaKThe amount of power involved would be 70 to 80 megawatts, according to a description of the project recently released by the city of Mobile. That's a fraction of the company's total output but still enough to light thousands of homes.LiNeBrEaKOnce the results are in, "we'll make a decision on what we're going to do going forward," Chris Habig, the company's marketing renewable resources manager, said in an interview last week.LiNeBrEaKWhile Habig described the study as part of "general planning activities," environmentalists see it as recognition that utilities are likely to face a long-term federal push to lessen their dependence on coal as a primary fuel source.LiNeBrEaKWhen burned, coal emits carbon dioxide - a colorless, odorless gas now seen as a key culprit behind global warming.LiNeBrEaKWood combustion also produces carbon dioxide, but because trees and other plants absorb the gas during their life cycles, the overall impact on the climate is a wash, according to scientists.LiNeBrEaK"I think it's more of a pre-emptive effort," Adam Snyder, executive director of Conservation Alabama, said of the Alabama Power study, adding that he considers it "a great move."LiNeBrEaKAlong the same lines, Georgia Power Co., another affiliate of Atlanta-based Southern Company, is seeking regulators' permission to convert a small coal-fired plant to biomass, said Anne Blair of the Southern Alliance for Clean Energy, another advocacy group headquartered in Knoxville, Tenn.LiNeBrEaK"I think they are doing a good job in terms of anticipating what is likely to be coming down the pipeline at the federal level and simply diversifying their energy mix," said Blair, who is the alliance's program manager for diesel and biofuels.LiNeBrEaKAlabama Power and other Southern Company affiliates collectively rank among the nation's largest corporate carbon dioxide polluters.LiNeBrEaKAt the congressional level, Southern has lobbied strenuously against legislation that would push utilities to gradually bolster their use of renewable fuels. Such legislation has so far failed, but congressional Democrats are gearing up for another try this year.LiNeBrEaKAlthough Alabama Power uses wood chips and switchgrass at a Gadsden plant, the company has no generating units that run exclusively on biomass. Building such a unit from scratch is also an option.LiNeBrEaKThe Barry feasibility study came to light when the city of Mobile included the proposed conversion in a wish list of projects to be included in an economic stimulus package that lawmakers will take up this month. That list puts the price tag at $100 million, but Habig indicated that the figure could be lower and said no decision has been made on how to pay for the conversion. Higher costs for coal and other fuels make the venture economically cost-effective for the first time, he added.LiNeBrEaKThe company would like to burn tree limbs and other "waste material" but could also use pulp chips, he said. In all, the plant would need 700,000 to 800,000 tons of biomass annually, according to the city of Mobile's description of the project.LiNeBrEaKThat volume of timber is available in southwest Alabama, said Ruth Seawell, a vice president and forest analyst at Larson and McGowin, Inc., a Mobile-based consulting firm.LiNeBrEaKBut, she added, "Do we have the infrastructure to move the resource?"LiNeBrEaKAlthough the study's completion is still months away, Alabama Power has already broached the potential conversion with the Alabama Public Service Commission, a state regulatory agency.LiNeBrEaKIn an interview last week, Commissioner Susan Parker said the project came up in "informal discussions" between the utility and the PSC before Christmas.LiNeBrEaK"I am aware of it, but they have not made any official filing on it," she said. "It's still in the very preliminary stages."LiNeBrEaK(Press-Register Capital Bureau Reporter Brian Lyman contributed to this report.)LiNeBrEaKMIKE KITTRELL/Staff PhotographerLiNeBrEaKBarry Steam Plant in north Mobile County is among the sites being considered for transition to burning wood or other "biomass."		ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (90%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (90%); BIOFUELS (89%); BIOMASS (89%); POWER PLANTS (89%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (78%); LOBBYING (78%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (78%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (78%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (77%); SCIENCE NEWS (77%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (74%); CLIMATE CHANGE (73%); PROCESS STEAM UTILITIES (73%); LEGISLATION (71%); INTERVIEWS (67%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (66%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%)  	ALABAMA POWER CO (94%); SOUTHERN CO (85%); GEORGIA POWER CO (65%); XIAMEN ANNE CORP LTD (52%)  			ATLANTA, GA, USA (68%) ALABAMA, USA (94%); GEORGIA, USA (79%); TENNESSEE, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 21, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Mobile Press Register Inc. All Rights Reserved  	SEAN REILLY, Washington Bureau  		SO (NYSE) (85%); 002235 (SZSE) (52%)  	NAICS221210 NATURAL GAS DISTRIBUTION (85%); NAICS221122 ELECTRIC POWER DISTRIBUTION (85%); NAICS221121 ELECTRIC BULK POWER TRANSMISSION and CONTROL (85%); NAICS221112 FOSSIL FUEL ELECTRIC POWER