The New York Times 	January 13, 2009 Tuesday   Late Edition - Final	Advice for Obama on the Economy  	Section A; Column 0; Editorial Desk; LETTERS; Pg. 24  	1323 words  	To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Re ''Plan to Jump-Start Economy With No Instruction Manual'' (front page, Jan. 10):LiNeBrEaK  The Obama stimulus plan includes about $150 billion of tax cuts for individuals and families. Despite the fact that our economic problems are due in large part to a $400 billion-a-year decrease in consumer spending, many Congressional Democrats and economists have criticized this part of the stimulus plan because they think that a large portion of the tax cuts will be saved rather than spent. Consequently, they believe that more direct government spending, rather than tax cuts, will provide a better economic stimulus.LiNeBrEaK  But there may be a way to increase consumer spending, without incurring the risk that tax cuts will be saved, not spent. Instead of distributing tax cuts in cash, or lower payroll deductions, the government could distribute the tax cuts in the form of gift or debit cards.LiNeBrEaK  These ''gift cards from Uncle Sam'' would be for a stated dollar amount, would be valid only for consumer purchases and would expire if they aren't used by a certain date. Everyone would use the cards, since they either ''use it or lose it.'' With ''gift cards from Uncle Sam,'' overall spending would increase by the exact amount of the tax cut. LiNeBrEaK  Andy Rush Scarsdale, N.Y., Jan. 10, 2009LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  The plan to jump-start the economy should be based on the nation's true economic condition: poverty.LiNeBrEaK  We are currently a poor nation because we have run ourselves into six deep debts: a federal debt (owed heavily to other nationals); a balance-of-payments debt from buying much more from other nations than we have sold them; personal debt from credit cards and other loans; infrastructure deterioration that must be repaired and replaced; education quality compared with our competitor countries; and most serious, an environmental debt from depleting nature's assets of clean air (without climate-changing gases), clean water, fertile soil, diverse species and a healthy ocean.LiNeBrEaK  We cannot afford a stimulus package aimed at sending people back to the mall. It must aim at repaying our debts, particularly restoring the environment, rebuilding infrastructure and improving our schools.LiNeBrEaK  Bill Shore  Sleepy Hollow, N.Y., Jan. 10, 2009LiNeBrEaK  The writer is executive secretary of the Nature Network. LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  I applaud your Jan. 11 editorial ''The Stimulus Debate,'' in which you oppose proposed tax cuts by the coming Obama administration for people making up to $200,000 a year. You do, however, say tax cuts make ''good sense for low-  and middle-income Americans.''LiNeBrEaK  I am a retired journalist and consider myself a middle-income American. Speaking for myself and my wife, we do not need a tax cut. We live modestly on my pension and our Social Security checks. We own our own home and have few debts. And even though, like so many Americans, we have lost a substantial portion of our retirement I.R.A., we have been frugal and lucky. So far we're doing O.K. LiNeBrEaK  I absolutely agree with you that ''every dollar spent on a politically expedient tax cut is money that is not spent where it could do more good.'' LiNeBrEaK  Do the right thing, Mr. Obama -- and don't worry. We'll support you.LiNeBrEaK  James Houtrides Brooklyn, Jan. 11, 2009LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Your concern with tax cuts in the stimulus package is a distraction. Far more troublesome is the conventional assumption that the recession is a more or less classic business cycle that an infusion of cash through infrastructure projects and tax cuts will turn around. It isn't, and it won't be. LiNeBrEaK  The current recession is not cyclical; it is structural, and it is unprecedented. During the 1930s, thousands of factories closed. But their buildings and equipment remained in place and intact, and they could be reactivated to meet World War II mobilization needs. That model no longer exists. LiNeBrEaK  Most of the thousands of manufacturing facilities that closed since World War II closed for good. Their equipment was crated and shipped overseas; their buildings are boarded up, their workers laid off. These factories didn't close because of a cyclical shortfall in demand but because they lost their markets to imports. LiNeBrEaK  No fiscal stimulus can possibly match the benefits of using low-wage overseas labor for such production. Thus, the hollowed-out manufacturing sector will not be able to create the advertised millions of new jobs. I believe that this structural issue looms larger than who gets what tax cuts.LiNeBrEaK  S. Stanley Katz Sarasota, Fla., Jan. 11, 2009LiNeBrEaK  The writer was deputy assistant secretary of commerce, 1976-78, and is a former vice president of the Asian Development Bank.LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor: LiNeBrEaK  Re ''Obama's Biggest Challenge,'' by Bob Herbert (column, Jan. 10):LiNeBrEaK  Mr. Herbert writes what everyone already knows: ''There is one overriding mission for the incoming Obama administration when it comes to dealing with the economy, and that's putting Americans back to work.''LiNeBrEaK  But the way that Mr. Herbert and Barack Obama plan to put people back to work is an illusion. Building roads and bridges as well as green technology will not have any meaningful effect on immediate job creation. Jobs will continue to be lost until people start buying houses and automobiles again, and that is not going to happen unless the consumer is motivated to buy.LiNeBrEaK  The first order of business is to scrap all the bailouts, which are a nonproductive use of taxpayer money. Instead of bailouts, the government should insist that banks start lending again. This can be accomplished with government guarantee of the loans. Such guarantees would be for both the housing and automobile industries. LiNeBrEaK  In addition, first-time buyers of houses should get a $10,000 rebate from the government, and those buying hybrid vehicles a $5,000 rebate. Nothing less will get the economy back on track quickly. LiNeBrEaK  Paul Schoenbaum Williamsburg, Va., Jan. 10, 2009LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  I applaud Bob Herbert's column. If President-elect Barack Obama fails to achieve an aggressive program to sustain and expand employment, we are headed for a real domestic disaster. As he put it, we have an economic emergency.LiNeBrEaK  Mr. Herbert makes the important point that unemployment (and underemployment) creates a vicious cycle, because those who are unemployed must draw on public benefits, including unemployment insurance, food stamps, Medicaid and public assistance. Since the unemployed generally do not pay taxes, the public coffers become strained and depleted.LiNeBrEaK  One point he did not make, but is very important -- especially since Mr. Obama has already hinted that he may move to curtail Social Security benefits -- is that the unemployed (as well as those who are employed but poorly paid) and their potential employers do not contribute to the Social Security system, thus making that system less secure and providing more excuses for cutting benefits.LiNeBrEaK  What our country needs is a true full-employment policy, supported by government as employer of last resort if needed, where everyone who wants to work can get a decent job at a living wage. Such a pro-active policy would go a long way to fulfilling individuals' and families' lives as well as securing our promise as the one nation that Mr. Obama so eloquently called upon us to be.LiNeBrEaK  Marguerite Rosenthal Jamaica Plain, Mass., Jan. 12, 2009LiNeBrEaK  The writer is a member of the Executive Committee of National Jobs for All Coalition and professor emerita, School of Social Work, at Salem State College.LiNeBrEaK  To the Editor:LiNeBrEaK  Re ''The Confidence Surplus,'' by David Brooks, and ''The Obama Gap,'' by Paul Krugman (columns, Jan. 9):LiNeBrEaK  Yes, the economy is complex and the effects of government actions are unpredictable. But I have carefully read The Times's Op-Ed page and paid attention to events these many years, and the best course of action for President-elect Barack Obama and Congress is very clear: Do what Paul Krugman tells you to do!LiNeBrEaK  Christine Hepburn Madison, N.J., Jan. 10, 2009	http://www.nytimes.com  	ECONOMIC NEWS (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); LETTERS and COMMENTS (90%); TAX LAW (90%); TAX RELIEF (89%); WRITERS and WRITING (78%); BALANCE OF PAYMENTS (78%); PERSONAL DEBT (77%); US DEMOCRATIC PARTY (77%); CONSUMER SPENDING (76%); MIDDLE INCOME PERSONS (76%); PUBLIC DEBT (76%); NATIONAL DEBT (76%); PUBLIC FINANCE (71%); CLIMATE CHANGE (66%); ENVIRONMENTAL CLEANUP (61%); EDITORIALS and OPINIONS (59%); DEBIT CARDS (53%); US ECONOMIC STIMULUS PLAN 2008-2009 (90%); LOW INCOME PERSONS (76%)  			BARACK OBAMA (95%)  	UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 13, 2009  	ENGLISH  	DRAWING (DRAWING BY ANTHONY RUSSO)             	Letter  	Newspaper  	2009 The New York Times Company   																
