Richmond Times - Dispatch (Virginia)  	January 13, 2009 Tuesday 	Green jobs could cost $4 million  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	516 words  	Jan. 13--Gov. Timothy M. Kaine believes that protecting the environment can help protect Virginians from the grim economy.LiNeBrEaK"Creating green jobs and a renewable energy sector of the Virginia economy is one way we can create opportunity from our current economic challenges," Kaine said in a statement. LiNeBrEaKKaine outlined a green-jobs initiative yesterday at the Virginia Beach headquarters of a company that installs solar panels.LiNeBrEaKKaine proposes to offer financial incentives to makers and buyers of equipment that produces power but doesn't produce a lot of greenhouse gases.LiNeBrEaKThe plan could cost more than $4 million a year in spending and lost revenue, depending on how many people use the incentives, Kaine officials said.LiNeBrEaKThe Virginia budget is facing a nearly $3 billion shortfall, but the governor has proposed a balanced spending plan that includes the green-jobs program, Kaine spokesman Gordon Hickey said.LiNeBrEaKThere's a "good chance" the General Assembly will approve the program, Hickey said.LiNeBrEaKState Sen. John Watkins, R-Powhatan, a member of the Finance Committee, said he generally favors efforts to bring jobs to Virginia but needs to see the details of Kaine's plan before taking a position on it.LiNeBrEaKWatkins indicated that new expenditures would be a tough sell. "There is no new money," Watkins said.LiNeBrEaKIn his program, Kaine proposes setting aside $2 million to extend grants to manufacturers of equipment for such energy sources as wind and nuclear power.LiNeBrEaKThe grants would be provided only after the businesses are running, paying taxes and providing new jobs, said Steve Walz, Kaine's senior energy adviser.LiNeBrEaKEventually, the state would recoup the money spent on the grants, Walz said. "We wouldn't give these grants unless it's beneficial to the state."LiNeBrEaKKaine also proposed:LiNeBrEaK--Creating a 10-cents-per gallon grant for producers of biofuels such as ethanol from sources other than food crops. For example, some entrepreneurs are trying to produce fuel from the oil in algae.LiNeBrEaKFuel produced from food crops such as corn would receive less support, 7. 5 cents per gallon. Again, a business would not receive the money until it is providing financial benefits to the state, Walz said. --Creating an income-tax credit for those who install green-energy systems, such as solar power. The credit could total $20,000 for a business and $8,000 for an individual. The cost of the credits would be capped for the state at $1 million a year for individuals and $1 million a year for businesses.LiNeBrEaK--Making purchases of home energy systems such as solar cells and small windmills exempt from the state's 5 percent sales tax.LiNeBrEaKContact Rex Springston at (804) 649-6453 or rspringston@timesdispatch.com		ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); SOLAR ENERGY (90%); ENERGY and UTILITY SECTOR PERFORMANCE (90%); JOB CREATION (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (89%); TAXES and TAXATION (87%); BIOFUELS (85%); BIOMASS (78%); GOVERNORS (78%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (78%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (78%); WIND ENERGY (78%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); TAX INCENTIVES (76%); ENTREPRENEURSHIP (76%); SALES TAX (74%); TAX LAW (73%); ETHANOL (72%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (72%); MANUFACTURING OUTPUT (72%); SEAWEED and ALGAE (71%); ALCOHOLS (70%); APPROVALS (69%); CORN FARMING (61%); INCOME TAX (50%)  			TIM KAINE (94%)  	VIRGINIA BEACH, VA, USA (90%) VIRGINIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 13, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Richmond Times - Dispatch   	Rex Springston, Richmond Times-Dispatch, Va.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090113-RV-Green-jobs-could-cost-4-million-0113  	RV  									
