anford add as many as eight faculty positions and 20 graduate student fellowships. If private donors hadn't come forward, adding that many positions probably would have taken a decade, Hennessy said.LiNeBrEaKLynn Orr, who had been director of the school's global climate project, will head the institute. Stanford will now have more money to devote to such research projects as using nanomaterials to make better solar cells, Orr said. And the school's many alternative energy researchers will be encouraged to collaborate with people outside their own departments. LiNeBrEaK"The energy challenge is a big and important one," Orr said, "but it is just the sort of challenge Stanford students and faculty should tackle with enthusiasm."		RESEARCH INSTITUTES (91%); EMISSIONS (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); ENERGY RESEARCH (90%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); SOLAR ENERGY (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); STUDENTS and STUDENT LIFE (90%); RESEARCH (89%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (89%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (78%); COMPUTING and INFORMATION TECHNOLOGY (78%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); EDUCATION SYSTEMS and INSTITUTIONS (78%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (78%); ENGINEERING (78%); AUTOMOTIVE FUELS (76%); INTERNET and WWW (73%); ENERGY EXPORTS and IMPORTS (73%); OIL SERVICES INDUSTRY (71%); PETROLEUM PRODUCTS (71%); COMPUTER SOFTWARE (62%) BUSINESS; ENERGY; COLLEGES; RESEARCH; SOLAR ENERGY; GLOBAL WARMING  	BP PLC (92%); EXXON MOBIL CORP (90%); GENERAL ELECTRIC CO (54%); TEJAS GAS CORP OF HOUSTON (52%)  	STANFORD UNIVERSITY (94%)  	John Hennessy; Jay Precourt; Kat Taylor; Thomas Steyer  	SAN FRANCISCO BAY AREA, CA, USA (94%) CALIFORNIA, USA (94%) UNITED STATES (94%) USA CALIFORNIA; SANTA CLARA; STANFORD  	January 14, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Stanford President John Hennessy discusses the research institute, flanked by director Lynn Orr. Tony Avelar / Associated Press  		Newspaper  	2