The Star-Ledger (Newark, New Jersey) 	January 13, 2009 Tuesday   MORRIS EDITION	Towns face having no say in power line  	NEW JERSEY; Pg. 017  	490 words  	PSEandG applied to the state Board of Public Utilities yesterday for permission to build a 45-mile, $750 million high-voltage power line that would cut through North Jersey, bypassing a potential process that would require approvals from each of the 15 towns affected by the project. LiNeBrEaKThe company's decision to apply directly to the BPU to build the Susquehanna-Roseland power line, which it says is required to prevent overloads and maintain reliability of the power grid, was criticized by opponents as an attempt to avoid local public scrutiny.LiNeBrEaK"PSEandG is going behind the backs of the communities affected by the power lines," said Jeff Tittel, director of the New Jersey chapter of the Sierra Club. He urged the BPU to reject the plan.LiNeBrEaK"These power lines will not only cut an ugly scar across New Jersey but will bring dirty coal power into our state along with more pollution and undermine our efforts to combat climate change," he argued.LiNeBrEaKBut company officials dismissed that contention, saying there is an obvious need for a better and more reliable power system, with an eye on future needs.LiNeBrEaK"The line is needed because demand for electricity in our area has risen substantially in recent years and is expected to continue to grow over the long term despite the current economic slowdown and conservation efforts," PSEandG President Ralph LaRossa said in a statement last night.LiNeBrEaKBoard of Public Utilities spokesman Doyal Siddell said the application is under initial review by agency staff, and the process will include public hearings, which have not yet been scheduled. BPU has one year to make a decision, he said.LiNeBrEaKIf there is no decision in that time, PSEandG may seek approval from the Federal Energy Regulatory Commission, Siddell added.LiNeBrEaKThe proposed 500-kilovolt line would run from Hardwick in Warren County, through Sussex and Morris counties, to Roseland in Essex County. The company said the line has been mandated by PJM Interconnection, an organization that oversees the regional power grid in 13 states, and will prevent electrical overloads and blackouts in northern New Jersey.LiNeBrEaKThe project includes installing 180- to 190-foot towers, about twice the height of what is along the route now, to accommodate the existing 230-kilovolt line and the new 500-kilovolt one.LiNeBrEaKLocal officials and environmentalists criticized the power-line plan on several fronts, charging it presents health hazards, will hinder renewable energy efforts and harm property values. But PSEandG said no direct link has been established between power lines and health issues, and contends the lines will be designed to "cancel out" magnetic fields between the 230- and 500-kilovolt lines.LiNeBrEaKPSEandG said it applied to the BPU to deal with the process in "one comprehensive proceeding." But some local officials, including East Hanover Mayor Joseph Pannullo and Byram Councilman Scott Olson, charged the company with making it more difficult for opponents to voice concerns.		ENERGY and UTILITY LAW (90%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (90%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (90%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (89%); ENERGY and UTILITY POLICY (89%); ENERGY DEMAND (78%); POWER FAILURES (78%); PUBLIC HEARINGS (78%); CITY GOVERNMENT (78%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (78%); PUBLIC UTILITIES COMMISSIONS (78%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (78%); MAYORS (77%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (74%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (73%); ENERGY REGULATION (73%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (72%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (72%); CLIMATE CHANGE (67%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (67%); ECONOMIC DECLINE (50%); ECONOMIC NEWS (50%)  	BOARD OF PUBLIC UTILITIES OF KANSAS CITY (58%)  	SIERRA CLUB (56%)  		NEW JERSEY, USA (94%) UNI