rEaKFor the past 4 1/2 years, he has headed the Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, an Energy Department research institute that he steered to a new focus on renewable energy. He was also on the UC Berkeley faculty.LiNeBrEaKChu recently began teaching himself economics so he could weigh the consequences of differing options for slowing global warming. He won't rely on the opinion of others, preferring to form his own judgments on everything, says Sally Benson, the head of Stanford's energy research center, who worked with Chu at Lawrence Berkeley.LiNeBrEaK"He's very hands-on. He gets into the nitty-gritty," says Benson, who also says he's "a visionary ... truly committed to solving these problems."LiNeBrEaKChu's zeal about climate and energy also fits with a life-long hunger to succeed on a grand scale. He has a "desire to do something noteworthy and important," says Eugene Commins, Chu's graduate adviser at UC Berkeley.LiNeBrEaKEven friends make a joke of Chu's drive, both in the lab and outside it. On the tennis court, the bike path and the hiking trail, Chu is known for turning every encounter into a contest.LiNeBrEaK"You're a seriously competitive person when you turn whipping cream for dessert into a competition," friend and fellow physics Nobelist Carl Wieman of the University of Colorado said at a 60th birthday celebration for Chu.LiNeBrEaKOthers don't find it a joking matter. Chu is "arrogant" with a "we-know-best attitude," says Ignacio Chapela, a UC Berkeley ecologist who clashed with Chu over Chu's plan for the university and the Lawrence Berkeley lab to take part in a research effort funded by energy giant BP.LiNeBrEaKDoesn't suffer 'fools'LiNeBrEaKChu's ambition and independence have served him well in the laboratory, but it's not clear how those qualities will serve him as Energy secretary. He has shown little interest in politics until now and is a novice at the rough-and-tumble of Washington. He'll have to juggle -- and avoid alienating -- many warring parties, both inside and outside the agency.LiNeBrEaKThat could be tough for an outspoken scientist who, Commins says, "doesn't suffer fools gladly."LiNeBrEaKPast Energy secretaries have often been content to take orders from above, says the University of Texas-Austin's Tad Patzek, a former UC Berkeley colleague.LiNeBrEaK"Chu will ... want to implement his own policies. So there's this potential for conflict," says Patzek, who clashed with Chu over the Nobelist's enthusiasm for biofuels, gasoline substitutes derived from plants. "I actually don't know why he agreed to do this."LiNeBrEaKThose who know him say he's up to the job.LiNeBrEaKChu's ex-wife is confident he will make progress on the intractable problem of how to power the nation without destroying the environment.LiNeBrEaK"I'll be stunned if he doesn't succeed," says Lisa Chu-Thielbar. "He might leave a few bloody corpses behind him, but he won't succumb to pressure. He'll do what he thinks is right." LiNeBrEaKThe Chu fileLiNeBrEaKAge: 60; born Feb. 28, 1948.LiNeBrEaKHometown: Garden City, N.Y.LiNeBrEaKEducation: Undergraduate degrees from University of Rochester in New York state; doctorate in physics from the University of California-Berkeley.LiNeBrEaKProfessional experience: Scientist at ATandT Bell Laboratories, 1978-87; scientist at Stanford University, 1987-2004; director of Lawrence Berkeley National Laboratory, 2004-present.LiNeBrEaKFamily: Wife, Jean Chu, a trained physicist; two adult sons, Geoffrey and Michael, from his previous marriage.LiNeBrEaKHobbies: Bicycling, swimming and running.LiNeBrEaKQuote: "Education in my family was not merely emphasized, it was our raison d'etre." 		NOBEL PRIZES (92%); AWARDS and PRIZES (92%); PHYSICS (91%); SCIENCE NEWS (90%); COLLEGES and UNIVERSITIES (90%); RESEARCH (89%); ENERGY RESEARCH (89%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (89%); ENERGY DEPARTMENTS (89%); CLIMATOLOGY (88%); RESEARCH INSTITUTES (88%); ENERGY DEVELOPMENT PROGRAMS (75%); PROFILES and BIOGRAPHIES (7