nvolved in discussions on the region.LiNeBrEaKMr. Bush's document focuses heavily on science and environmental protections.LiNeBrEaKSen. Lisa Murkowski, Alaska Republican, who was the lone member of Congress to actively participate in the drafting process, said the policy is a needed statement at a time when there is much uncertainty surrounding the Arctic.LiNeBrEaK"This is a significant step forward for the nation and sends a message to the world that the Arctic is important to the United States, and we stand ready to work cooperatively with the international community in this vital region," she said.LiNeBrEaKShe added that Congress and President-elect Barack Obama would have to follow through with manpower and money to help make the recommendations policy.LiNeBrEaKIn his directive, Mr. Bush also called on the Senate to ratify the Law of the Sea treaty, which has been pending for years and has been ratified by all of the other nations that border the Arctic.LiNeBrEaKBut the treaty has been blocked by conservative senators, who argue that the U.S. would cede sovereignty and could end up subject to an international tax. Sen. John McCain, Republicans' presidential nominee last year, came out in opposition to the treaty, which could explain the Bush administration's delay in releasing the directive.		US PRESIDENTIAL CANDIDATES 2008 (89%); TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (89%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (89%); US REPUBLICAN PARTY (89%); INTERNATIONAL LAW (89%); US PRESIDENTS (90%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (78%); PRESIDENTIAL ELECTIONS (78%); GLOBAL WARMING (78%); ECOLOGY and ENVIRONMENTAL SCIENCE (77%); MARINE RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (76%); INTERNATIONAL RELATIONS (76%); ENVIRONMENTAL TREATIES and AGREEMENTS (76%); OCEANS (76%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (76%); POLITICAL PARTIES (73%); CONFERENCES and CONVENTIONS (73%); NATIONAL SECURITY (73%); SCIENCE NEWS (71%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (71%); NATURAL GAS PRODUCTS (70%); OIL and GAS EXPLORATION (70%); OIL EXPLORATION (55%); LAW OF 