r future is going to be defined in the choices we make in the remaining 58 percent," Mr. O'Malley said.LiNeBrEaKThe City of Annapolis, Anne Arundel County and Queen Anne's County governments are working on updating their comprehensive plans. It's a tedious process that involves poring over maps, talking with residents and business owners and determining where growth should be directed.LiNeBrEaKWhile environmentalists were pleased with the bills Mr. O'Malley is putting forth, they said it's only a start.LiNeBrEaKAlan Girard, a policy manager for land use at the Chesapeake Bay Foundation, called the Terrapin Run-inspired bill a "no-brainer."LiNeBrEaKDru Schmidt-Perkins, head of the preservation group 1000 Friends of Maryland, said the bills are only the first step. Comprehensive plans should be required to better tie into state goals, such as those to combat climate change and minimize damage to the Chesapeake Bay, she said.LiNeBrEaK"There's already goals out there that people universally believe," she said.LiNeBrEaKThe governor also hinted at some other environmental issues, including paving the way for watermen to raise oysters in aquaculture.LiNeBrEaKWhen asked whether Program Open Space -- the state's signature land-preservation program -- might be hit by budget cuts, Mr. O'Malley responded: "I don't intend to transfer one dime out of Program Open Space."LiNeBrEaKHe also said he soon might have an announcement on the Global Warming Solutions Act, a bill that would set greenhouse gas reduction goals into state law. The bill has failed in the General Assembly several years in a row.LiNeBrEaKLawmakers go back to work tomorrow with the opening of the 2009 General Assembly.		REGIONAL and LOCAL GOVERNMENTS (92%); REAL ESTATE (90%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (90%); ZONING (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); COUNTY GOVERNMENT (89%); COUNTIES (89%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (88%); LAND USE PLANNING (78%); GOVERNORS (78%); REAL ESTATE DEVELOPMENT (77%); HISTORIC DISTRICTS and