The Boston Globe 	January 12, 2009 Monday   THIRD EDITION	THE GREEN BLOG  	HEALTHSCIENCE; Pg. A8  	496 words  	Excerpts from the Globe's environmental blog.LiNeBrEaKGreenhouse credits for a coal plant? LiNeBrEaKMaybe you've read the headlines about the giant sludge pond of fly ash - a byproduct of burning coal - that swallowed a piece of the Tennessee landscape last month, raising a host of questions about the toxic material. LiNeBrEaKIt turns out Massachusetts has its own fly ash controversy.LiNeBrEaKThe Conservation Law Foundation is outraged that state environmental officials have given conditional approval for the region's largest coal-fired power plant to receive what could be millions of dollars in greenhouse gas allowances for recycling fly ash and using it in the production of cement. Dominion, the owner of the Brayton Point power plant in Somerset, says about a ton of greenhouse gas emissions are avoided for every ton of fly ash used in cement production.LiNeBrEaKThere is irony that a toxic byproduct of burning coal - which releases enormous amounts of greenhouse gases into the atmosphere - would be eligible for greenhouse gas credits at all.LiNeBrEaKBut the foundation's argument centers more on additionality: Whether Brayton Point was going to recycle the fly ash anyway. The environmental group argues that the nation's coal-burning industry already regularly recycles fly ash for cement - and increasing regulation on ash is pushing even more recycling to take place. To give Brayton Point credit for it is like giving a student extra credit for carrying a backpack to school: He is going to carry it whether or not you reward him.LiNeBrEaK"It's absurd," says the foundation's Seth Kaplan. "It fails the additionality test completely." He says it's also impossible to measure how much greenhouse gas is truly displaced by using fly ash.LiNeBrEaKState environmental officials say Dominion decided to build a fly ash recycling plant voluntarily in 2006 - when it wasn't 