ding is up to safety codes."LiNeBrEaKKiely said connecting more solar panels to the electrical grid is a "statewide value" that benefits all Coloradans.LiNeBrEaK"It's going to clean up our air, it's going to clean up our water, it's going to clean up our global-warming pollution," she said.LiNeBrEaKBut state Sen. Shawn Mitchell, R-Broomfield, said there is a point when government reaches too far to promote what politicians think is best.LiNeBrEaK"Just because something is a good thing doesn't mean builders should be forced to offer it," Mitchell said.LiNeBrEaKCalifornia is the only state to have a similar requirement of homebuilders. A spokeswoman for the Colorado Association of Home Builders said the organization has yet to take a position on the proposal because the bill hasn't been formally introduced.LiNeBrEaKMcStain Neighborhoods, a local homebuilder, offers customers an option for solar panels in many of its communities. The option has been popular.LiNeBrEaK"It's the kind of thing the whole industry needs to be thinking of," said company co-founder Caroline Hoyt.LiNeBrEaKJohn Ingold: 303-954-1068LiNeBrEaKor jingold@denverpost.com		SOLAR ENERGY (91%); LEGISLATORS (91%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (91%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (90%); GOVERNORS (90%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (90%); CONSTRUCTION SECTOR PERFORMANCE (89%); RESIDENTIAL CONSTRUCTION (89%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (78%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (78%); ENERGY REGULATION (78%); LEGISLATION (77%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (74%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (68%); GLOBAL WARMING (50%)  			BILL RITTER (92%)  	DENVER, CO, USA (79%) COLORADO, USA (94%); CALIFORNIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 12, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 The Denver Post All Rights Reserved  	John Ingold The Denver Post  															
