The New York Post 	January 12, 2009 Monday 	THE MTA'S MATRIX OF MUSH  	All Editions; Pg. 24  	403 words  	Fare hikes? Service cuts?  LiNeBrEaKWho, us?  LiNeBrEaKSeemingly oblivious to their agency's dire financial straits, top Metropolitan Transportation Authority brass strutted off to Washington last Thursday to unveil recommendations from the MTA's environmental "sustainability" commission - developed by outside consultants at a cost of a cool one million very scarce public dollars.   LiNeBrEaKThe commission proposes, among other nonsense, that the MTA:  LiNeBrEaK* Purchase 80 percent of its energy from "renewable" sources by 2050 - largely by supporting proposed wind farms off the New York City coastline.  LiNeBrEaK* "Flex its market power" to "help drive green production throughout the mid-Atlantic region."  LiNeBrEaK* Develop a "decision matrix" to figure out what to do once global warming raises sea levels (presumably covering Long Island and flooding the subway tunnels, thus rendering the MTA itself somewhat beside the point).  LiNeBrEaK* And give riders the option of paying extra to help fund its "green" initiatives when buying MetroCards, which no doubt they will do with gay abandon.  LiNeBrEaKWe'd rather the million bucks had gone to develop a "decision matrix" for regularly emptying subway-station trash barrels - but that wouldn't have spoken to the real reason for Thursday's jaunt to the capital: begging for federal bucks.  LiNeBrEaKThese days, you see, painting one's tin cup green is an attractive strategy to access the federal kitty.  LiNeBrEaKTo that end, the commission recommends that Congress (what else?) raise gas taxes by 40 cents a gallon and pour the dough into mass transit. (We sure hope the consultants didn't charge too much for that battered chestnut.)  LiNeBrEaKStill, given the head-scratching nature of most of their proposals, MTA chief Lee Sander and his deputies would probably have done better truly conserving energy - by staying home.  LiNeBrEaKIndeed, apart from some common-sensical energy-saving ideas, the report has little to say about actually running a transit system.  LiNeBrEaKThe commission is notably silent, moreover, about what any of this will cost - an important consideration, given that the MTA is eyeing both massive fare hikes and major service cuts.  LiNeBrEaKThat's because the MTA is facing steep upcoming deficits in both its operating and capital budgets that no conceivable federal bailout will ever plug.  LiNeBrEaKBut Washington might find Sander's lamentations easier to take if he spent more time running the trains and less money matrixing decisions.  LiNeBrEaKWe know we would. 		PUBLIC TRANSPORTATION (90%); URBAN TRANSIT SYSTEMS (90%); CAPITAL EXPENDITURES (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (77%); WIND ENERGY (77%); CONSULTING SERVICES (77%); BAILOUTS (73%); US FEDERAL GOVERNMENT (70%); TAXES and TAXATION (67%); WIND POWER PLANTS (55%); GLOBAL WARMING (54%)  				NEW YORK, NY, USA (79%) NEW YORK, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 12, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Lee Sander.   		Newspaper  	2009 N.Y.P. Holdings, Inc. All Rights Reserved  																
The New York Times 	January 12, 2009 Monday   Late Edition - Final	2 Britons Die During Peak Ascent In the Alps  	Section A; Column 0; Foreign Desk; Pg. 7  	568 words  	Even for a country with a long tradition of adventuring in the world's most hazardous terrains and oceans, Rob Gauntlett was a remarkable young man.LiNeBrEaK  Two years ago, at the age of 19, he became the youngest Briton to reach the summit of Mount Everest. Over 14 months beginning in 2007, he and a companion traveled 26,000 miles, from the North Pole  to the South Pole, through North, Central and South America, and then the South Atlantic and Antarctica, on skis, dogsleds, bicycles and an oceangoing sailboat, in a demonstration of what could be accomplished by ''natural'' means of transport, requiring no environmentally damaging engines.LiNeBrEaK  On Saturday, trying a notoriously dangerous ascent of the east face of the 13,937-foot Tacul peak in the Mont Blanc mountain range in the French Alps, Mr. Gauntlett, 21, fell hundreds of feet to his death with another young Briton, James Atkinson, also 21, the police in the French city of Grenoble said. Mr. Gauntlett's mother, Nicola Gauntlett, who traveled to the Alpine town of Chamonix on Sunday with his father, David, said the two young men had been ice-climbing during a two-week trip to the Alps. LiNeBrEaK  ''There was obviously a big fall and they both died,'' she told the Press Association, Britain's national press agency. ''We had spoken about something like this happening only recently. We are all just devastated.LiNeBrEaK  ''He's far too young to die.''LiNeBrEaK  Another 21-year-old, James Hooper, Mr. Gauntlett's companion on his Everest ascent in 2006, and on the journey across the continents and oceans, which ended in 2008, accompanied him on the mountaineering trip to France. LiNeBrEaK  Mr. Hooper, who met Mr. Gauntlett at school in West Sussex, south of London, told the Press Association on Sunday that they had been joined on the trip by two less-experienced British climbers and that they had split up for the Tacul peak ascent so each of them could mentor one of the other climbers.LiNeBrEaK  In a BBC interview last year, Mr. Gauntlett described himself and Mr. Hooper as ''two normal guys'' whose ambition was to show that young people can achieve their ''dreams'' through effort and determination. LiNeBrEaK  ''We've tried to really kind of show that the impossible is nothing; you can actually achieve whatever you want,'' he said. ''And at the same time, we wanted to show how rapidly climate change, whether it be man-related or whatever, is affecting the sensitive areas of the world.''LiNeBrEaK  In a ceremony in November in Washington,  Mr. Gauntlett and Mr. Hooper were named the National Geographic Society's adventurers of the year for their journey between the poles. Mr. Gauntlett came close to death on that journey, falling between Arctic floes while skiing between Canada and Greenland, and suffering severe hypothermia that left him unconscious for three hours.LiNeBrEaK  A passing yacht rescued the two and helped Mr. Gauntlett reach a hospital.LiNeBrEaK  The two men continued on to New York, on a bicycle and sailing journey of thousands of miles to southern Chile.LiNeBrEaK  On Sunday, before the name of the other climber killed in the accident was made known by the French police, Mr. Gauntlett was remembered during a church service in the English country town of Petworth, near the Christ's Hospital School in West Sussex where he and Mr. Hooper met. LiNeBrEaK  ''This is very tragic news, but what a wonderful life he enjoyed, however short it turned out to be,'' said the vicar, the Very Rev. Michael Till.	http://www.nytimes.com  	MOUNTAINS (92%); SKIING (76%); WINTER SPORTS (75%); CLIMATE CHANGE (73%); POLICE FORCES (67%); EXTREME SPORTS (66%); INTERVIEWS (60%)  	NATIONAL GEOGRAPHIC SOCIETY (50%)  			LONDON, ENGLAND (54%) MOUNT EVEREST (94%); HIMALAYAS (94%); ALPS (94%); MONT BLANC (79%); ATLANTIC OCEAN 