The Oregonian (Portland, Oregon) 	January 12, 2009 Monday   Sunrise Edition	Dirty little secret of 'dirty snow effect"  	Local News; Pg. a01  	846 words  	SUMMARY: Soot   | Pollution causes the snowpack to melt faster in spring, Northwest researchers sayLiNeBrEaKNorthwest researchers say 'dirty snow effect' magnifies early snowmelt Pollution erodes Western mountain snowpack sooner than it would have melted otherwise Dirty little secret of 'dirty snow effect" Study amongLiNeBrEaKfirst to look at LiNeBrEaKregional effectLiNeBrEaKMICHAEL MILSTEINLiNeBrEaKYou probably don't notice it, but tiny particles of pollution constantly rain down on mountain snow from diesel engines, power and manufacturing plant smokestacks, and other fossil-fuel-burning elements of modern life.LiNeBrEaKThe soot, almost invisible in the snow, absorbs more sunlight, heating the snow and melting it as much as a month earlier in spring, amplifying the effect of already rising temperatures, according to a new study by scientists at the Pacific Northwest National Laboratory in Richland, Wash.LiNeBrEaKThe warming effect of the soot --known to scientists as the "dirty snow effect" --melts away as much as 2 inches of snow in some parts of the West before it would have melted otherwise, computer modeling showed.LiNeBrEaKThat erodes mountain snowpacks that Western farmers and cities have long relied on as a critical reservoir of water. It leaves less snow to melt and fill rivers later in the spring and early summer, when water is most needed for agriculture and thirsty cities.LiNeBrEaKThe dirty snow effect compounds an already recognized trend of earlier snowmelt that scientists have connected to higher temperatures attributed to global warming.LiNeBrEaKThe study is one of the first to examine the effect on a regional scale. It found that Oregon snow is relatively clean, melting only slightly because of soot, and snow in Washington, British Columbia, Idaho and the central Rocky Mountains is dirtier and melts much more.LiNeBrEaKThe soot initiates a troublesome cycle, by melting snow and exposing darker ground, which also absorbs more sunlight and warms, melting even more snow.LiNeBrEaK"You get a kind of runaway effect," said William Gustafson, an author of the study and an atmospheric scientist at the Richland laboratory, which is part of the Department of Energy. The study will be published in the Journal of Geophysical Research-Atmospheres.LiNeBrEaKHe said the dirty snow effect is still minor compared to the larger acceleration of spring snowmelt caused by warmer temperatures. Average annual temperatures in the Pacific Northwest increased 1. 5 degrees Fahrenheit between 1920 and 2003.LiNeBrEaKBut the influence of soot is large enough to alter streamflows in the Western United States and should be weighed by water managers. It's also worth considering the benefits from controlling pollution.LiNeBrEaK"It's still a small part of the whole puzzle," he said. "It's not going to save us from water shortages, but it's one contributor."LiNeBrEaKPollution responsible for the melting comes from both nearby sources and distant regions such as Asia, said Yun Qian, another atmospheric scientist at the lab and lead author of the study. The amount of soot hasn't changed much in recent years, but that could come.LiNeBrEaK"If we have more in the air, we also have more deposited on the snow," he said.LiNeBrEaKBecause the study is based on computer modeling that calculated the effect of soot, it's not precise, the authors said. Philip Mote, Washington's state climatologist, said that although the report is an interesting attempt to demonstrate the influence from soot, it cannot measure specific consequences.LiNeBrEaK"The emissions of soot and their changes over time are not well known, and consequently, their role in the observed changes in snowpack and streamflow over time cannot be quantitatively determined," said Mote, a key author of an international report on the effects of climate change on global snow and ice.LiNeBrEaKResearchers at the Richland lab used a computer model developed at the National Center for Atmospheric Research in Boulder, Colo., to zero in on the effects of soot-driven heating. They also developed software that predicts the behavior of pollution particles to determine how much soot falls on snow in Western mountain ranges.LiNeBrEaKThey then calculated how much darker soot makes snow and how that would translate into extra melting.LiNeBrEaKThe soot in so-called dirty snow probably would be imperceptible to people unless clean snow was next to it, Gustafson said.LiNeBrEaKThe soot drives an average temperature rise of about 1. 2 degrees Fahrenheit at the snow's surface over most of the snow-covered areas in the Western United States, the researchers found. That drives melting of as much as 2 inches of the water contained in snow, the research found.LiNeBrEaKThe researchers did not include other particles, such as dust or the soot from forest fires, that may also fall into snow and speed melting, Qian said. Mote also said that snow deteriorates over the course of winter, darkening on its own, so the results of the study may overstate the effect of soot alone.LiNeBrEaKResearchers hope to expand on the research by trying to calculate how much of the Northwest's eroding snowpack is caused by soot.LiNeBrEaK"This was just a first step," Qian said.LiNeBrEaKMichael Milstein: 503-294-7689; michaelmilstein@LiNeBrEaKnews.oregonian.com		RESEARCH (90%); SCIENCE NEWS (90%); SCIENCE and TECHNOLOGY (90%); MOUNTAINS (89%); EARTH and ATMOSPHERIC SCIENCE (89%); RESEARCH REPORTS (89%); GLOBAL WARMING (89%); METEOROLOGY (89%); EXPERIMENTATION and RESEARCH (78%); CLIMATOLOGY (78%); WEATHER (78%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (78%); PARTICULATE MATTER (78%); TRENDS (76%); WATER RESOURCES MANAGEMENT (76%); WATER SUPPLY UTILITIES (75%); TEST LABORATORIES (73%); MODELING and SIMULATION (73%); COMPUTER SIMULATION (52%)  				WEST USA (93%); OREGON, USA (93%