Palm Beach Post (Florida) 	January 12, 2009 Monday   FINAL EDITION	LETTERS TO THE EDITOR  	OPINION; Pg. 10A  	599 words  	No truly 'clean' energy, but nuclear comes closerLiNeBrEaKI am responding to your editorial "Nuclear power has benefits; being truly 'clean' isn't one."LiNeBrEaKAs an engineer who has worked in the energy industry for more than 22 years, I can tell you that "clean energy" should be considered an oxymoron similar to "jumbo shrimp." Solar cells require cadmium or arsenic, toxic heavy metals which do not have half-lives (i.e., they last forever). Wind requires more steel per unit energy delivered than nuclear power, and making steel is not environmentally friendly. In addition, for solar and wind to supply baseload power, they would require electric energy storage systems which remain prohibitively expensive. Merely being renewable is not a benefit if the expense of using it is excessive and the higher environmental costs apparent once these sources are scaled up. LiNeBrEaKWhile there are no truly "clean" energy sources, nuclear power represents a baseload source of electric generation with low greenhouse emissions. Though there is still debate on whether to recycle or directly dispose of the spent fuel, it has a very small volume and is safely managed. To limit the percentage of nuclear energy allowed to chase the clean energy chimera only will deny us and our children of a valuable energy technology that can truly generate the large amounts of lower-emission electricity our nation and the globe need.LiNeBrEaKROBERT S. MARGOLISLiNeBrEaKPalm Beach GardensLiNeBrEaKGay marriage supporters laboring under technicalityLiNeBrEaKTo those committed same-sex marriage advocates who have a misunderstanding of the massive objections to their use of the term marriage as defined for millennia, I offer the Campbell Soup Co. solution.LiNeBrEaKMy inquiry to the company as to how it can promote and label V8 juice as "100% Vegetable Juice" when the product's major ingredient is tomato, a pulpy berry, they responded: "The United States Supreme Court designates the tomato as a vegetable for trade purposes, though it is technically a fruit."LiNeBrEaKPerhaps, someday by designation of court, there will be a group advocacy movement to change the U.S. flag's colors from red, white, and blue to green, black, and purple without actually changing the flag's colors.LiNeBrEaKCONRAD C. JANKOWSKILiNeBrEaKJupiterLiNeBrEaKChange will take time; bailouts still Bush's babiesLiNeBrEaKIn regard to the letter "Vote for change leaves us with what's in our pockets," our problem is that people don't take the time to understand the world around them. We voted for change, but the change hasn't taken place yet, a fact that the writer has missed. The AIG, bank and auto industry bailouts are happening on Mr. Bush's watch, not under the changed leadership the country voted for. Perhaps the writer needs a lesson in civics. He certainly needs to be a bit more thoughtful before making such a ridiculous complaint.LiNeBrEaKMICHAEL MERKERLiNeBrEaKLake WorthLiNeBrEaKDid writer forget? Bush still in charge until 1/20LiNeBrEaKThe writer of "Vote for change leaves us with what's in our pockets" (Jan. 7) must be at that "certain age." Has he overlooked that President Bush and his band are still in charge? Change begins on Jan. 20.LiNeBrEaKCHARLES MOSOLFLiNeBrEaKJuno BeachLiNeBrEaKJeb should steer clear until W.'s dust has settledLiNeBrEaKJeb Bush's decision not to vie for a Senate seat was one of his more intelligent ones. With his brother finally leaving the White House, after serving eight disastrous years, the voters need a break from any Bush in or near the nation's Capitol. His only shot at any success in national politics would be if the Democrats really screw up in the next four or eight years. It sure is going to be interesting, don't you think?LiNeBrEaKRICHARD YERZYLiNeBrEaKBoynton Beach		LETTERS and COMMENTS (93%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (90%); ENGINEERING (90%); EM