Pittsburgh Post-Gazette (Pennsylvania) 	January 12, 2009 Monday   SOONER EDITION	REPORT ASKS GREAT CARE BE TAKEN BEFORE STORING CARBON DIOXIDE  	HEALTH, SCIENCE, MEDICINE and TECHNOLOGY; Pg. B-1  	632 words  	The Obama administration should create a new commission with broad powers to regulate carbon dioxide capture and storage by utilities and industries that is needed to rein in climate change, according to a report unveiled last week in Washington, D.C.LiNeBrEaKThe 150-page report by an academic and legal team headed by Carnegie Mellon University's Dr. M. Granger Morgan said a Federal Carbon Sequestration Commission would bring order to new and potentially chaotic regulation of efforts to keep carbon dioxide emissions from entering the atmosphere and, instead, store them deep underground. LiNeBrEaKThe commission could also help resolve legal questions about ownership and use of suitable rock formations more than a half mile below the surface for storing the carbon dioxide.LiNeBrEaKDr. Morgan, who briefed congressional and U.S. Environmental Protection Agency staffers on the report Friday, said if the U.S. is to meet its goal of reducing carbon emissions by 80 percent by the end of the century, it will need to employ carbon capture and storage technologies along with a host of low-carbon solutions, but the process must be efficient, safe and effective.LiNeBrEaK"Let's not try to enact definitive regulation until some of the commercial scale carbon capture operations are up and running," Dr. Morgan said. "The commission should wait to draw lessons from the first handful of carbon capture and sequestration projects so regulations aren't enacted today that turn out to be counterproductive in the long run."LiNeBrEaKCarbon capture and storage, or CCS, is the process of collecting carbon dioxide before it is emitted into the atmosphere, compressing it into a liquid and then pumping it deep underground into depleted oil and gas reservoirs, deep coal seams, salt formations or under the ocean floor, where it will do much less harm.LiNeBrEaKAccording to the report, produced by a team of investigators from Carnegie Mellon, the University of Minnesota, the Vermont Law School and the Washington, D.C.-based energy law firm Van Ness Feldman, geoscientists believe the risks associated with sequestration are modest and can be readily managed. And even if there is some leakage of carbon dioxide back to the surface, risks to humans will be minimal.LiNeBrEaKThe report also said all the technologies required for capture, transport and geologic sequestration of carbon dioxide exist but have not yet been applied to emissions controls.LiNeBrEaKBut a proposed EPA rule for regulating the application of those technologies, developed under the authority of the Safe Drinking Water Act, doesn't address the legal questions surrounding access to and use of the deep geological formations.LiNeBrEaK"EPA's focus has been too narrow," Dr. Morgan said. "We need to resolve access to pore space, where carbon dioxide can be stored, in deep sub-surface formations and also address questions of liability."LiNeBrEaKWorldwide, man-made carbon dioxide emissions, primarily from coal-burning power plants and other fossil-fuel burning sources, have increased from an insignificant amount 200 years ago to more than 33 billion tons a year, with 8. 8 billion tons of that produced by the U.S. Those carbon dioxide emissions have increased the amount of greenhouse gases in the Earth's atmosphere, trapping radiant heat from the sun and causing global warming and potentially unhealthy changes in regional climates.LiNeBrEaK"If we are going to save coral reefs, many national parks and all the world's other valuable ecosystems, we have got to cut CO2 emissions by roughly 80 percent," Dr. Morgan said. "Because of our heavy use of fossil fuels, there's no way to get there without carbon capture and sequestration, but we have to do it right."LiNeBrEaKThe report, funded by a $1. 85 million grant from the New York-based Doris Duke Charitable Foundation, can be viewed at www.ccsreg.org/working_papers.html.		EMISSIONS (90%); CLIMATOLOGY (90%); CLIMATE CHANGE (90%); US ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (89%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (89%); CLEAN COAL TECHNOLOGY (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (89%); ENVIRONMENTAL DEPARTMENTS (89%); GEOLOGY and GEOPHYSICS (89%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (78%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (78%); NATURAL GAS and ELECTRIC UTILITIES (78%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (78%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS STANDARDS (78%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (78%); LAW SCHOOLS (77%); INVESTIGATIONS (77%); WATER QUALITY REGULATION (73%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (72%); OIL and GAS INDUSTRY (68%); COAL INDUSTRY (68%); POWER PLANTS (63%); GRADUATE and PROFESSIONAL SCHOOLS (72%)  	VAN NESS FELDMAN PC (52%)  		BARACK OBAMA (91%)  	DISTRICT OF COLUMBIA, USA (93%); VERMONT, USA (79%); MINNESOTA, USA (79%); PENNSYLVANIA, USA (79%) UNITED STATES (94%)  	January 13, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 P.G. Publishing Co.   	Don Hopey, Pittsburgh Post-Gazette  							Don Hopey can be reached at dhopey@post-gazette.com or 412-263-1983./  								
Richmond Times - Dispatch (Virginia)  	January 12, 2009 Monday 	Kaine to offer green-jobs plan  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	473 words  	Jan. 12--Gov. Timothy M. Kaine will call today for state tax incentives and grants to promote environmentally friendly businesses and jobs.LiNeBrEaKKaine will lay out his proposals, which require General Assembly approval, this morning in Virginia Beach, according to sources who requested anonymity because Kaine had not released the plan. LiNeBrEaKKaine will propose, according to the sources:LiNeBrEaK--Creating a tax credit for those whoLiNeBrEaKinstall green energy systems, such as solar power. The credit could reach $20,000 for a business and would be less than $8,000 for an individual. --Making purchases of home energy systems such as solar cells and some windmills exempt from the state's 5 percent sales tax.LiNeBrEaK--Providing state grants to makers of renewable-power equipment such as that used to tap wind or geothermal energy. (Geothermal energy relies on underground temperatures to heat or cool buildings.) This would expand eligibility for a little-used program that currently offers up to $18 million over six years for manufacturers of solar-power equipment.LiNeBrEaKThe proposals add detail to Kaine's Renew Virginia plan, which he launched in mid-December. The program aims to protect the environment and create so-called "green jobs."LiNeBrEaK"Virginia has the potential to create tens of thousands of green jobs by 2025," Kaine said then.LiNeBrEaKKenneth P. Green, a scholar at the American Enterprise Institute, a Washington think tank, believes it's unwise to use tax money to promote green jobs.LiNeBrEaKThat money would be better spent -- and would create more jobs overall -- if left in the pockets of people and businesses, Green said.LiNeBrEaK"I'd call [green jobs] more of a fad than a good thing," Green said.LiNeBrEaKCale Jaffe, a lawyer for the Southern Environmental Law Center, a conservation group, said he was not aware of Kaine's latest proposals but generally supported the push for green jobs.LiNeBrEaKJaffe said he particularly supported efforts to make homes and businesses more energy-efficient because that reduces emissions, linked to global warming, from coal-burning power plants.LiNeBrEaKKaine officials have said they also consider nuclear power plants to be green, since they don't release greenhouse gases.LiNeBrEaKBut Green and Jaffe said they don't call nuclear power green, largely because the plants create long-lasting radioactive waste.LiNeBrEaK"It really depends on how you define green jobs," Jaffe said.LiNeBrEaKContact Rex Springston at (804) 649-6453 or rspringston@timesdispatch.comLiNeBrEaKPoll		ENVIRONMENTALISM (90%); TAX INCENTIVES (90%); ELECTRICITY TRANSMISSION and DISTRIBUTION (90%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (90%); SOLAR ENERGY (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (90%); TAX LAW (90%); POWER PLANTS (89%); NUCLEAR ENERGY (89%); EMISSIONS (89%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (89%); SALES TAX (78%); EMPLOYMENT GROWTH (78%); ENERGY and ENVIRONMENT (78%); ENERGY EFFICIENCY and CONSERVATION (78%); ENVIRONMENTAL and WILDLIFE ORGANIZATIONS (78%); WIND ENERGY (78%); JOB CREATION (78%); WIND POWER PLANTS (76%); GEOTHERMAL ENERGY (76%); ELECTRIC POWER PLANTS (76%); CLIMATOLOGY (73%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (73%); CLIMATE CHANGE (73%); COAL FIRED PLANTS (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (68%); FOSSIL FUEL POWER PLANTS (65%); NUCLEAR POWER PLANTS (65%); NUCLEAR WASTE (60%); HAZARDOUS WASTE (60%)  	MCCLATCHY-TRIBUNE INFORMATION SERVICES (60%); AMERICAN ENTERPRISE INSTITUTE FOR PUBLIC POLICY RESEARCH (54%)  		TIM KAINE (94%)  	VIRGINIA BEACH, VA, USA (91%) VIRGINIA, USA (93%) UNITED STATES (93%)  	January 12, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Richmond Times - Dispatch   	Rex Springston, Richmond Times-Dispatch, Va.  			General  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090112-RV-Kaine-to-offer-green-jobs-plan-0112  	RV  									
