The San Francisco Chronicle (California) 	January 12, 2009 Monday   FINAL Edition		Datebook; Pg. E2  	504 words  	RATING: ALERT VIEWERSincerity Forever: Drama. By Mac Wellman. Directed by Megan Soto. With Jessica Kitchens, Alanna Coby, Ben Fisher, Khamara Pettus et al. Through Jan. 17. Brava Theater Center, 2781 24th St., San Francisco. 65 minutes. Tickets: $10-$25. Call 415 647-2822 or go to www.brava.org.  LiNeBrEaKSincerity is a much overvalued commodity, a handy excuse for all kinds of acts of ignorance, racism and homophobia. As the teenage Ku Klux Klansmen and women of Mac Wellman's "Sincerity Forever" put it - between sessions of premarital sexual activity straight and not and scoffing at believers of global warming and the Holocaust - "The most important thing is not what you know, but whether you're sincere or not."LiNeBrEaKWellman wrote "Sincerity" in 1990 and dedicated it to Sen. Jesse Helms "for the fine job you are doing of destroying civil liberties" and fundamentalist Donald Wildmon. The Brava Theater Center revival that opened Friday makes it look more timely than ever in the wake not only of Proposition 8, but also the election of Barack Obama. After all, when Jesus H. Christ shows up to excoriate moral blindness, she's black.LiNeBrEaKNot that "Sincerity" makes any kind of straightforward argument. Wellman can be among the most convoluted of playwrights, mixing heady arias of wordplay and esoteric references with cartoon-ish characters in a nonlinear framework. Staging "Sincerity" is no easy task, and it's to Megan Soto's credit that she evokes as much of Wellman's humor, anger and thought as she does in her directorial debut as part of Brava's new Emerging Artist program.LiNeBrEaKSoto's is a bare-bones staging, with a low-budget set and semi-professional cast in Brava's upstairs, converted-classroom second stage. Two modestly upholstered chairs serve as the car seats where most of the action takes place for the usual teen rituals of tentative automotive bonding and courting - though the kids' Klan robes and peaked hats add an eerie subtext to their ramblings.LiNeBrEaKAlanna Coby's somewhat reticent Molly and Jessica Kitchens' delightfully earnest Judy confide their ignorance, religious doubts, crushes and belief in sincerity. Chris McDonald's good old boy Tom and Michael Barrett Austin's bumptious, preacherly Hank mirror the girls' conversation with some more disturbing undertones amid the comedy. Judy and Ben Fisher's distracted George engage in some heavy first-date groping while he describes his father's death.LiNeBrEaKSoto can't always resist trying to layer comic action on top of the humor in the dialogue, sometimes to negative effect. There are times when less moving about would yield more direct impact. For the most part, though, she and her actors capture the heart of the piece, as Wellman creates more distorted fun-house mirrors of those first few scenes, with two scabrous, demonic Furballs Alden Moore and Madeline H.D. Brown contributing hilariously foul-mouthed rants.LiNeBrEaKAnd when Khamara Pettus' sharp and sassy Christ delivers her sermon on the nearest mound, "Sincerity" puts small-mindedness in cosmic perspective.		THEATER (92%); THEATER REVIEWS (91%); RELIGION (89%); DRAMA LITERATURE (78%); THEATER and DRAMA (78%); ARTISTS and PERFORMERS (77%); FUNDAMENTALISM (74%); RACE and RACISM (71%); HOLOCAUST (71%); GLOBAL WARMING (55%); ACTORS and ACTRESSES (78%) DATEBOOK; THEATER; REVIEW  			BARACK OBAMA (55%)  	SAN FRANCISCO, CA, USA (91%) CALIFORNIA, USA (91%) UNITED STATES (91%)  	January 12, 2009  	ENGLISH  	Alanna Coby left plays Molly in Mac Wellman's critique of small-mindedness, "Sincerity Forever." Nathanael Keck  		Newspaper  	2009 San Francisco Chronicle All Rights Reserved  	Robert Hurwitt, Chronicle Theater Critic  															
