St. Petersburg Times (Florida) 	January 12, 2009 Monday   4 State / Suncoast Edition	MILESTONES AND MISSTEPS  	NATIONAL; Pg. 4A  	393 words  	Here are the high and low points in the first half of Gov. Charlie Crist's term:LiNeBrEaK- EVERGLADES: With a last-minute lobbying effort from his honeymoon suite, the governor secured water managers' approval for his $1. 3-billion plan to buy land from U.S. Sugar. Environmentalists hail it as a pivotal step to accelerating restoration of the Everglades, even though financial and legal hurdles remain. LiNeBrEaK- VOTING: He insisted on a switch to paper ballots in early 2007, which boosted public confidence in vote counting and led to a smooth election in '08.LiNeBrEaK- CLEMENCY: He streamlined a clemency process that allows some ex-felons to restore their civil rights more quickly. It took another year, however, to eliminate other hurdles that kept many felons from being able to register to vote.LiNeBrEaK- CLIMATE CHANGE: An aggressive plan to require new cars sold in Florida to comply with strict new emissions standards was approved by environmental regulators after intense lobbying by the governor's staff, but implementation could be delayed because the Legislature must vote. Lawmakers also put the brakes on the governor's ambitious timetable requiring power companies to use renewable energy.LiNeBrEaK- PROPERTY INSURANCE: Neither his promise to reduce the cost of windstorm insurance nor his threat to sue property insurance companies got much traction. The second year without a major hurricane helped ease rates, and 40 private insurers have taken thousands of policies out of Citizens, the state-run insurer. But the market is still unstable, and the state doesn't have the money to cover Citizens' costs if a major hurricane hits.LiNeBrEaK- GAMBLING:A compact to allow slot machines and table games at seven casinos of the Seminole Tribe of Florida led the Legislature to file suit for cutting the deal without them. The state Supreme Court sided with lawmakers, delivering Crist's most conspicuous defeat to date. He'll now seek legislative approval in March, but the state missed out on collecting $100-million from the tribe last year.LiNeBrEaK- TAXES: Property taxes didn't "drop like a rock" as he promised, but property values did; the voter-approved increase in the homestead exemption helped, but nobody got the forecast savings.LiNeBrEaK- TRAVEL: A lavish trade mission to Europe in July produced a torrent of criticism at home, few immediate trade wins, and partisan cries of "Empty Chair Charlie."		GOVERNORS (90%); INSURANCE (90%); PROPERTY and CASUALTY INSURANCE (90%); VOTERS and VOTING (90%); ENVIRONMENTAL LAW (90%); LEGISLATORS (90%); LOBBYING (90%); APPROVALS (89%); LEGISLATIVE BODIES (89%); PROPERTY TAX (89%); US STATE GOVERNMENT (78%); ELECTION AUTHORITIES (76%); ENVIRONMENTALISM (76%); CLIMATE CHANGE (76%); ENVIRONMENT and NATURAL RESOURCES (76%); FELONIES (74%); HURRICANES (74%); VEHICLE EMISSIONS (73%); UTILITIES INDUSTRY (72%); AUTOMOTIVE SALES (72%); BALLOTS (71%); CIVIL RIGHTS (71%); ELECTRIC POWER INDUSTRY (70%); GAMING (68%); EMISSIONS (67%); AIR QUALITY REGULATION (67%); RENEWABLE ENERGY (66%); TAX EXEMPTIONS (65%); SUITS and CLAIMS (64%); LITIGATION (64%); TROPICAL STORMS (64%); TRADE DEVELOPMENT (60%); SUPREME COURTS (50%)  			CHARLIE CRIST (92%)  	FLORIDA, USA (92%) UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 12, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009 Times Publishing Company All Rights Reserved  																
Tonawanda News (North Tonawanda, New York)  	January 12, 2009 Monday 	FISHING: Kenmore native makes profitable living on Alaskan seas  	STATE AND REGIONAL NEWS  	545 words  	Jan. 12--When people in the Tonawandas are complaining about winter weather, Charles Wilkins is braving minus 40 degree weather and 40 mile per hour winds on the Bering Sea.LiNeBrEaKWilkins left Kenmore last year, looking for an adventurous and lucrative job. He found just that on board the Arctic Star, a fishing ship that trolls the chilly waters near the Arctic Circle.LiNeBrEaKWilkins' father, Dan, said his son inquired about the career after seeing the TV show "Deadliest Catch," which features the exploits of similar fishing boats doing the dangerous work. LiNeBrEaK"He applied for the job on-line through Seattle's Icicle Seafoods," Dan said.LiNeBrEaKAfter making his own way to Seattle, the company flew Wilkins to Anchorage and then to the port of Dutch Harbor on the Aleutian island chain.LiNeBrEaK"They had to come in like a corkscrew," Dan said. "He said it was the most terrifying thing he's ever done in a plane."LiNeBrEaKA helicopter carried him out to a processing boat, where he was initially assigned. But before long Wilkins made his way onto a fishing boat, where he operates the boat's crane and helps package the fish and crabs they catch.LiNeBrEaKWork starts at 6 a.m. and stops at 10 p.m., seven days a week. And there's no alcohol allowed on the ship to warm them up.LiNeBrEaK"He'd like to know where the global warming is," Dan joked.LiNeBrEaKThe work is tough, as the boats are tossed around by the high winds on rough seas. Setting and hauling half-ton crab pots as the boat battles the waves is dangerous work, but the pay is good and in such a tough economy few can claim such a secure, well-paying job. Dan said leaving the Buffalo area and all of his friends wasn't an easy decision for his son, just as it wasn't easy for him to travel all over the country during his radio career. But when Wilkins returns in a few years, he'll have enough money to start a life.LiNeBrEaK"You just have to look at what's best for you in the field you pick," Dan said.LiNeBrEaKIn the meantime, Wilkins has taken in plenty of interesting sights and places that few in his hometown will ever experience. The boats take long trips out so far north that he can see the ice cap, in an area where eagles are as plentiful in the sky as sparrows. When the ship finally comes into port at St. Paul Island, Dan said the small population of 500 residents treats the fishermen like celebrities.LiNeBrEaKWilkins' family sends him things Buffalo-centric items he just can't get up there, including sauces from Chiavetta's and Old Man River, where Wilkins once worked.LiNeBrEaKWhen the fishing area freezes in mid-February, Wilkins is planning a trip home to see his family and friends. Until then, it's tough to for him to get phone calls home, but he checks his e-mail as often as he can. His dad said folks who know Charles should feel free to send him an e-mail at beringsea716@yahoo.com since he's still curious about what's going on in his hometown.		WEATHER (90%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (77%); GLOBAL WARMING (77%); COMMERCIAL FISHING (76%); ISLANDS and REEFS (73%); EMPLOYMENT SEARCH (72%)  				SEATTLE, WA, USA (88%); BUFFALO, NY, USA (86%) WASHINGTON, USA (92%); PACIFIC OCEAN (92%); BERING SEA (92%); ALASKA, USA (92%); NEW YORK, USA (86%) ARCTIC (93%); UNITED STATES (92%)  	January 12, 2009  	ENGLISH  			Newspaper  	2009    	Daniel Pye, Tonawanda News, North Tonawanda, N.Y.  			Environment/Recycling/Waste  	Distributed by McClatchy-Tribune Business News  	20090112-TT-FISHING-Kenmore-native-makes-profitable-living-on-Alaskan-seas-0112  	TT  									
