ng Alzheimer's disease. The Alzheimer's Association is committed to helping change health policy to promote prevention as the foundation for good health for all Americans. We are partnering with the CDC on a healthy brain initiative that seeks to convey what research has shown --- that what is good for the heart is good for the brain. Managing risk factors is especially important for African-Americans and Hispanics, who are at higher risks for chronic illnesses such as vascular dementia and diabetes.LiNeBrEaKGINNY HELMSLiNeBrEaKHelms is vice president, chapter services and public policy, Alzheimer's Association, Georgia chapter.LiNeBrEaKGeorgia Power right on nukesLiNeBrEaKJay Bookman's column ("Nuke revival puts all risk on customers," @issue, Jan. 4) ignores U.S. political influence. Is there not one political party that has opposed nuclear energy for 40-plus years? Is that party not in full ascendency and appointing those who do not support nuclear renewal?LiNeBrEaKBookman also associates "lucrative federal subsidies" with nuclear energy, an intellectually dishonest accusation especially in light of the fact that wind and solar energy technologies are allowed by federal law to reap huge tax credits and receive direct cash incentives from utilities that must use their power despite low-capacity factors, huge maintenance and repair costs and great unreliability of electricity supply. Bookman said nothing about these consumer-financed technologies, which makes his opinion all the more suspect.LiNeBrEaKGeorgia Power is doing the right thing. But in doing the right thing with such entrenched opposition, legal and finance experts would advise minimizing corporate risk, especially in light of possible Sarbanes-Oxley Act consequences.LiNeBrEaKCHARLES W. PENNINGTONLiNeBrEaKAlpharetta		AUTOMOTIVE SALES (91%); FUEL TAX (91%); GASOLINE (90%); TAXES and TAXATION (90%); GLOBAL WARMING (89%); CLIMATE CHANGE (78%); LETTERS and COMMENTS (77%); GLACIERS and ICEBERGS (69%); NUCLEAR